<HEADLINE>
YOUTH IS TRULY KING IN WISCONSIN SECONDARY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM BARRERO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's no secret that Wisconsin's defense has been a
key ingredient in the Badgers reaching the Rose Bowl and posting a
10-1 record.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive strength has been a staple for coach Barry Alvarez in
his best years since arriving at Wisconsin in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   This season, the emergence of two redshirt-freshman cornerbacks
and a sophomore free safety has allowed the Badgers even more
latitude on that side of the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Freshmen Mike Echols and Jamar Fletcher, along with sophomore
Jason Doering have helped Wisconsin hold opponents to a NCAA-best
10.2 points per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That has been the difference for us,'' Alvarez said. ``They
have allowed us to do some things that we hadn't been able to do in
the past. We've always been pretty good against the run, but we
were just average, at best, in the secondary. These guys have
really come on.''
</P>
<P>
   Doering and Echols each have three interceptions, while Fletcher
leads the team with six picks, including two returned for
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Alvarez said he knows UCLA's diverse offense will present
a stiff challenge to the entire defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``UCLA is so balanced that I don't know if we can overplay the
run or the pass,'' Alvarez said. ``They don't have the type of
tendencies we've been able to see and zero in on against some other
people. We're going to have to play them honest.''
</P>
<P>
   Paint it black: Junior running back Ron Dayne wore a black
practice jersey, normally reserved for injured players and those
who are off-limits from contact, for the second consecutive
Coliseum practice.
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez said Saturday he is not concerned about Dayne's status
for the game and he reiterated that point Sunday, saying Dayne
would wear the jersey all week and would not be involved in
contact.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to try and see if UCLA will cooperate with us on
that,'' Alvarez said, drawing laughs. ``Really, there's no reason
to hit Ron. It would be kind of foolish to hit him this week.''
</P>
<P>
   Dayne injured his clavicle in the Badgers' regular-season finale
against Penn State and missed the season opener against San Diego
State because of an ankle injury.
</P>
<P>
   Stunt double: Freshman Brooks Bollinger has been playing the
role of Cade McNown during practices, but Alvarez realizes the
difficulty in trying to imitate UCLA's All-American.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't simulate what they're going to see in that game with
NcNown, although Brooks does move around pretty well and I think he
gives us good looks sprinting out of the pocket and running
bootlegs,'' Alvarez said. ``But you really can't simulate it with
the accuracy they're going to see on Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
