<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 00:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7988 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBA-HNS &LR;      12-28 1201
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
In what he called ``an attempt to salvage the season,'' NBA
commissioner David Stern met with Billy Hunter, executive director
of the National Basketball Players Association, on Sunday in
Denver. Stern delivered what a league official labeled ``our final
offer'' during a five-hour meeting, the latest effort to end the
180-day lockout.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But with the NBA's Jan. 7 deadline for a settlement approaching,
Hunter deemed the owners' offer not good enough, increasing the
likelihood that the 1998-99 season will be canceled.
</P>
<P>
   The owners made concessions on five key points of their previous
proposal, specifically addressing union concerns about the
shrinking NBA middle class. It was believed by the league that the
proposal would break the negotiating stalemate and put the two
sides on the road to an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Not so.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can say we're done _ we've gone as far as we can go,''
said Jeffrey Mishkin, the league's chief legal officer. ``There
will be no more offers. I have been personally part of NBA
negotiations for 20 years, and I have never seen this kind of
intransigence from the union.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that (breaking the stalemate) was certainly our hope.
We've gone as far as we can go. We've made our final offer, and
we've given them everything we have. And it was rejected.
</P>
<P>
   ``That leaves us with virtually no hope for the season.''
</P>
<P>
   The owners' proposal addressed several union concerns,
including:
</P>
<P>
   An increase in the percentage of basketball-related income
devoted to player salaries. The owners' proposal Stern mailed to
every NBA player Dec. 17 contained a projection of BRI to be
devoted to salaries, offering 57 percent in the first year of the
deal, 57.1 percent in the second, 55.8 percent in the third, 52
percent in the fourth, 52.5 percent in the fifth and 53 percent in
the sixth. The owners went up to 53 percent in the fourth year,
53.5 percent in the fifth and 54 percent in the final year.
</P>
<P>
   An increased minimum salary. Their previous proposal offered a
$250,000 minimum contract for players with zero to two years of
experience, $350,000 for players with three to five years of
experience, an additional $50,000 per year for players with six to
nine years of experience and a $1 million minimum for players who
have been in the league for 10 or more years. The owners are now
offering a $275,000 minimum for a first-year free agent, $300,000
for a player with two years of experience, $350,000 for a
third-year player and an additional $50,000 for every year
thereafter. The $1 million minimum for players with 10 or more
years of experience remained intact.
</P>
<P>
   Concessions on the rookie scale. The owners have asked for a
three-year rookie-scale contract, with a team option for a fourth
year. The new proposal contains a clause that offers a 25-percent
salary increase for players who have their option picked up for the
fourth year.
</P>
<P>
   An additional exception to the salary cap, designed to increase
the middle class. The previous proposal included a ``middle-class
exception'' that would be available every year of the deal, worth
$1.5 million in the first year, $1.75 million in the second year,
$2 million in the third year and an amount equal to the average
player salary in the final three years of the deal. The owners
agreed to keep the current $1 million exception as well, which can
be used once every two years and allows a team to exceed the salary
cap to sign a player.
</P>
<P>
   Accepting the union's 10-percent limitation on contributions to
the escrow fund, designed as a hedge against salary overspending.
The owners were initially asking for the players to contribute an
unlimited percentage but dropped that demand to 15 percent in
subsequent offers. The players have been insisting on no more than
10 percent, and the owners conceded this point.
</P>
<P>
   But Hunter and the players, who reportedly conceded unspecified
salary restrictions on players with up to nine years of experience,
apparently still want more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, this was not enough for the union,'' said Stern
of the owners' proposal. ``We advised the union that no further
offers from the NBA would be made.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter feels otherwise, apparently hoping for more negotiations.
However, no talks have been scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We offered a comprehensive proposal to the NBA,'' Hunter said.
``The NBA countered our proposal, and we indicated to them that we
were willing to negotiate further, which unfortunately they were
unwilling to do at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   But the NBA assures there will be no further concessions. The
union's response left many in the league office shaking their
heads.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot explain it,'' Mishkin said. ``After this proposal,
it's clear that the offer that we made is more than fair to all the
players and, I think, meets the needs that we've heard about. I
cannot explain why it was rejected, but it was.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've made them our final offer, and they've rejected it.
We've done the best we could.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter will discuss the proposal with the union today. Mishkin
said that after Hunter turned down the offer, he doubted Hunter
would recommend it for a vote of the union rank and file.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Mishkin said. ``He (Hunter) has said publicly
that if he and the negotiating committee don't think it's a good
deal, whatever that means, he won't put it to a vote. There's no
reason to think he's changed his mind. But there will be no more
offers.''
</P>
<P>
   Several agents think the two sides are only a couple of issues
apart, the biggest being a so-called franchise-player designation
that would allow teams to offer any player, regardless of
experience, a salary worth 35 percent of the cap.
</P>
<P>
   As the owners' offer stands, only players with a minimum of 10
years of experience would be eligible for the maximum salary
allowable, a seven-year deal worth 35 percent of the salary cap.
Players with less experience _ zero to six years and seven to nine
years _ would be eligible for maximums of 25 percent and 30 percent
of the cap, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Agents are concerned that few 10-year veterans would receive the
highest-paid seven-year deals, so they would like to expand the
number of players eligible for the 35-percent salary slot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's going to give (San Antonio's) Tim Duncan what he's worth
10 years from now?'' said one agent. ``The only guy who would fit
in that (category) is Scottie Pippen, and I'm not sure somebody
would (pay him 35 percent of the cap).
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that (the franchise-player designation) would be huge.
I think that would show them (the players) that they protected the
little guy by changing the minimum, they protected the middle class
by adding another exception, and then they protected the superstars
by not limiting it (the 35-percent cap salary) to a 10-year
player.''
</P>
<P>
   Plans for Sunday's meeting weren't finalized until Saturday
night. The league was represented by Stern, deputy commissioner
Russ Granik and special assistant Bob Lanier. The union was
represented by Hunter, president Patrick Ewing and chief outside
lawyer Jeffrey Kessler.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
