<HEADLINE>
GIBSON IS ONE BIG BADGER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM BARRERO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ At school, on the street, at the mall or anywhere
he's out and about, people never stop marveling at Aaron Gibson.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter that, according to the experts, he will be a
first-round NFL draft pick this spring. It's his sheer size that
makes that all-important first impression on anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Six feet, seven inches. Three-hundred and seventy-one pounds.
</P>
<P>
   And Gibson, a soft-spoken, introspective sort who only now is
beginning to fulfill his potential as a player, doesn't mind the
attention one bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It never gets old,'' Gibson said. ``It never will.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the gawkers are those in the know in football who can't
say enough about Wisconsin's right tackle, who also happens to be
the largest player you will find on any NCAA football roster.
</P>
<P>
   Draft guru Mel Kiper Jr. says Gibson is one of the nation's top
three line prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson also was the nation's only player to be named a finalist
for the Lombardi Award and the Outland Trophy.
</P>
<P>
   He can bench press 475 pounds, squat 745, has a vertical leap of
31.5 inches, can dunk a basketball and can do the splits (he won a
locker-room bet with some teammates a while back).
</P>
<P>
   This past spring, Gibson earned a perfect score of 8.0 from the
National Football Scouting combine, after performing a series of
agility drills and physical tests.
</P>
<P>
   And to think that Gibson, a senior with a 47{-inch waist and
size-19 shoe, has played just three seasons for the Badgers after
being ruled academically ineligible as a freshman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years ago, he was playing primarily at tight end for us,''
Wisconsin coach Barry Alvarez said. ``But every year he gets
better. People recognized him and he was noted for his size. Now,
he's noted for being a good football player, and that's what's
satisfying to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibson also is pleased to be receiving the national attention
that has come his way in 1998, but he knows what a long road it was
to reach this destination.
</P>
<P>
   Recruited out of Decatur Central High in Indianapolis, Gibson
arrived at the Madison campus weighing a whopping 435 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until this year that Gibson began a season weighing
less than 400 pounds, a significant breakthrough in itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were huge ups and downs,'' Gibson said of his early days
at Wisconsin. ``There were a lot of times where I just gave up on
it and said, `Forget it, I'm not doing it anymore.' But people
talked to me here and got me back. It was just a lot of hard
times.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, fast food and poor eating habits in general were
Gibson's undoing. Those days are far behind him, and he says he
feels like he has reached an optimal weight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I could use 10 pounds more off, but not too much more
than that,'' Gibson said. ``Any more and I might start losing
strength.''
</P>
<P>
   Although these days Gibson looks like he was born to be an
offensive lineman, football didn't used to be a part of his life.
</P>
<P>
   Before a three-inch, 100-pound growth spurt between his freshman
and sophomore years in high school, Gibson's passion was swimming.
</P>
<P>
   Once his size set in, however, swimming was out and he had to
basically adjust to a new existence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a really painful experience,'' said Gibson, who has a
14-year-old brother, Adam, who is 6-5, 320 pounds. ``It hurt (to
grow so quickly) but it just happened.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be too simplistic to say Gibson's growth as a football
player just happened, but Alvarez notices a work ethic in Gibson
that should carry him even further.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you watch Gibby at practice, he hangs on every word you
say,'' Alvarez said. ``He's like a sponge. He just loves to be
coached, he wants to get better and he has.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never been around someone as physical or as good as he
is.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the praise, Gibson insists he isn't thinking about
the future, specifically the thought of an NFL career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's there, but I don't think about it,'' Gibson said. ``When
the time comes, I'd just like the opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   And who's going to tell him no?
</P>
</TEXT>
