<HEADLINE>
BLAND TOBIN MAKES HIS MARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was no Gatorade shower, no drench warfare, but only
because there were no idle moments.
</P>
<P>
   And chaos interrupted the obligatory shoulder ride off the
field, a time when traffic was moving in all directions.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the Cardinals needed the last play of the last game
in their first century of football to sew this one up.
</P>
<P>
   But ain't that Mr. Beige?
</P>
<P>
   Yet, sometime after doing his side shuffle for the media, after
defending the owner and shrugging off any personal implications,
Vince Tobin let loose. He walked through the locker room shaking
hands, and no defense in the world could stop the smile, one that
leaked out of his face and spread to his ears. And the final hug
was not for his clipboard, but for Jamir Miller, who puffed on a
victory cigar.
</P>
<P>
   He'll never admit it, but Tobin crossed a bridge Sunday, a man
invited to the postseason for the first time as head coach. And
while he'll never be compared to Lombardi, he has proved to be just
what he claims to be _ a good football coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vince takes a loss harder than any coach I've ever been
around,'' player personnel boss Bob Ferguson said. ``Sometimes he
looks like road kill on the sidelines. Sometimes it takes all of my
comedy background to pull him around on a Monday morning. Vince
really, really deserved this.''
</P>
<P>
   Really, this was all so symbolic, so typical Tobin. A
fourth-and-inches where his first inclination was to go for the
throat, which he should've, only to second-guess himself. A
decision that allowed San Diego to tie the score, adding kerosene
to the fire of speculation. And, finally, a football team whose
well runs deep, deeper than normally associated with the logo.
</P>
<P>
   That, too, is Vince Tobin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our spirituality is sustained by him,'' Simeon Rice said.
``Guys digging deep, guys having the confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   A football team showing one distinct side of Tobin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got to be the perseverance he's shown,'' Pat Tillman
said. ``He took a team that hasn't done (bleep) for so long and he
kept plugging away. Kept plugging away.''
</P>
<P>
   Football coaches can be a matter of taste, and I like mine to
breathe fire, the kind who can motivate cats to bark and pigs to
fly.
</P>
<P>
   That is not a Tobin specialty. And while you're going to get
plenty of armchair ammunition from this guy, a coach who is
prisoner of his sideline indecision, here's the bottom line:
</P>
<P>
   He never wavered from Jake Plummer, the right move in
retrospect, and his patience has been rewarded. He has brought an
element of stability and an element of discipline to the Cardinals,
a team that is among the least penalized in the league. And he's
delivered an element of professionalism, sorely needed post-Buddy
Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   But here's where I pause and raise a glass to Vince Tobin:
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, with a .500 team, with injuries decimating the
defense and a season slipping away, he designed a makeshift defense
that single-handedly stymied the Saints. A day when he outcoached
Mike Ditka, his former boss in Chicago. A day when Tobin may have
kept a tenuous season alive.
</P>
<P>
   And last Monday, in the wake of an emotional win over the
Saints, some players grumbled that Tobin was acting too glum. What
he was really doing, however, was bringing them back to ground
level, reminding all that 8-7 was fool's gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll probably be like that (today),'' Corey Chavous said.
``He'll probably be mad at the defense, and he should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's what Tobin should've done Sunday night: He should've
strutted into the media room and told Arizona it had a winner in
town. He should've worn a T-shirt that read, ``How Ya Like Me
Now?'' He should've brought the mascot with him, offering the bird
to all his critics.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not his style, nor will it ever be. Which is fine,
because on this night, in this season, with this team, there's
nothing wrong with a shade of bland. Not when it takes you to
Dallas. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
