<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRONCOS' ROMP SHOWS HOW FAR SEAHAWKS HAVE TO GO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Maybe the Seahawks are close to being contenders.
Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   The talent-laden roster is richer than a Christmas ham, so the
inclination might be to stay the course. Try again. Better luck
next time.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, there will be some who can spin the 8-8 season that
coach Dennis Erickson and his staff coaxed from these high-priced
Seahawks as an indication that things aren't so broke that they
need radical fixing.
</P>
<P>
   Those would be the people who did not see what took place Sunday
in Denver. Those would be the people who did not see a reigning
Super Bowl champion down on its luck rise to the occasion.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the Broncos met the cynics and naysayers head on. The
difference between a winning franchise and a confused franchise was
on display.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the fourth quarter, with the ball on the Seahawk 1-yard
line, John Elway took the snap. The Broncos quarterback had Terrell
Davis directly behind him. The reigning Super Bowl MVP was working
on a 2,000-yard rushing record, and the delirious Mile High Stadium
crowd was begging for Davis to carry the ball, again and again.
</P>
<P>
   But Elway did not hand off to the train of a running back so
aptly named ``T.D.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Elway started to roll to his right. The Seahawk pass
rush was nowhere to be found, so for one crystal clear moment, it
was conceivable that the 38-year-old Elway was going to keep
rolling and take the ball in for the score, all by himself, much to
the delight of the success-drunk crowd.
</P>
<P>
   But Elway did not run. Instead, streaking across the end zone
was No. 84 _ a big man, big hands, big target.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon Sharpe was slanting right, his feet pitter-pattering
across the white letter ``O'' in B-R-O-N-C-O-S. Nary a Seahawk
defender was near Sharpe, so naturally Elway the slinger did the
right thing. He side-armed the ball into Sharpe's arms. Touchdown
Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Elway pumped his fists. Sharpe did another touchdown dance. And
the formerly 13-0, bound-for-history Broncos were back on track,
crushing the poor souls who stood in their reigning Super Bowl
champion way.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, those poor onlookers were the Seahawks, losers 28-21,
although the final score says nothing of the gross disparity
between them and the Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   Those poor onlookers were a collection of talented, confused,
proud, embarrassed and hungry Seahawks who refuse to believe that
their .500 season is a true reflection of their talent.
</P>
<P>
   More important, they refused to accept that this same
disappointment will be repeated next season. In 1999, the Hawks
want to party like the Broncos are doing again this season.
</P>
<P>
   If it means a change at the top, then the Seahawk players are
willing to accept that. In fact, they say they would like the
change to come sooner rather than later. Sooner, as in this week.
Sooner, as in Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is going to be a change, let's get it done now,''
Michael Sinclair said, although he was not publicly campaigning for
the firing of his coach. He was merely campaigning for the
direction to be set _ now _ eliminating the months of uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks just want to win. In fact, from the sound of their
postseason comments, they are dying to win. They just need some
tools to work through those tough games against Pittsburgh or
Denver. They need some guarantees that there will be no more
implosions against Oakland or Dallas or Kansas City. All those
things happened in '98.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, if the Hawks stumble like they did in 1998, you can bet
that Chad Brown or Shawn Springs is going to go ballistic, without
any worry about whose feelings they hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am embarrassed,'' Springs, the Pro Bowl cornerback, spat out
in loud tones that made it clear he wanted everyone to know his
disgust.
</P>
<P>
   ``Changes need to be made. You saw it.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, the Pro Bowl linebacker, agreed. ``I think we are fooling
ourselves. We continue to fall short, so that's not close (to being
contenders).
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're close, that means occasionally you're supposed to
land on the other side. A tough game against a winning team, we
find a way to drop it. We always rally late, make it look good, but
we're not making them close.''
</P>
<P>
   If anyone had doubts about the difference between a winner and
an underachiever, Sunday's AFC West season finale between the
Broncos and Seahawks was all the proof required to make an informed
judgement.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos were a team full of purpose. They were a team full
of potent weapons, be it Elway or Davis, Sharpe or wide receiver
Rod Smith, who grabbed nine passes for 158 yards, including a
33-yard touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see that team out there, they've done the things they need
to do to get into the playoffs,'' Seahawk receiver Mike Pritchard
said. ``They re-established Terrell Davis. They have the weapons.
They used everybody. Here, I wish we could have done that, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Pritchard is a former Bronco who knows what it's like to stand
in the Denver locker room and hear coach Mike Shanahan implore his
team to be and play like the winners.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should hear a Mike Shanahan speech,'' Pritchard said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Broncos must have heard something. They met the
challenge put forth by their coach to build momentum heading into
the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos could easily be in Miami on Jan. 31, when the Super
Bowl gets under way. They have that kind of force, that kind of
mindset, those kinds of weapons that are deployed to the maximum
without hesitation or confusion.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks don't. At least they did not in 1998, when the
expectations to make the playoffs were hardly unreal.
</P>
<P>
   Word should come soon about whether Erickson and his staff will
be given another chance. Word has to come soon. The Pro Bowlers and
the pricey free agents and the long-time Seahawk veterans are
desperate for the opportunity to make it out of December. Change is
in the air.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I staff columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-28-98 0055EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
