<DOCNO> NYT19981228.0006 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 00:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7997 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CHARGERS_CARDINAL     12-28 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CHARGERS_CARDINALS-AZR </SLUG>
  
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fifty-two yards away awaited a goal that at times has seemed 52
years away.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Jacke, who had kicked game-winning field goals on the
final plays of the previous two games, hit the ball soundly with
three seconds left. Moments earlier, he had missed from 42 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Ten horrible years flashed while that ball was in the air. High
ticket prices. Poor public relations. Bad personnel decisions.
Shaky coaching. Poor play. A decade of scorn from a community that
refused to embrace them.
</P>
<P>
   Those days are gone. During the ball's 52-yard flight, a
long-suffering team and its distant community became one. The Sun
Devil Stadium crowd of 71,670 seemed to be saying what Cardinals
fullback Larry Centers said he was
</P>
<P>
   thinking while watching the ball sail toward the north goal
post:
</P>
<P>
   ``Get there! Get there!''
</P>
<P>
   They're there. Jacke's kick cleared with room to spare, the
clock showed 0:00, and the Cardinals ended the NFL's longest
playoff drought Sunday with their first winning season in Arizona
and a 16-13 win over the San Diego Chargers.
</P>
<P>
   Aeneas Williams, a five-time Pro Bowl cornerback who endured
seven non-winning years, wept as he left the field.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Williams, describing the co-existence of the franchise
and the community, said, ``It has been a marriage all along, but
it's like we were sleeping in different rooms. We're all sleeping
in the same room now.''
</P>
<P>
   Centers, who in his ninth season has been around longer than
anyone on the roster, said he was numb.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been through so many tough years here,'' Centers said.
``Right now, it's hard to let it out. Maybe later tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The relationship has changed between the Big Red and its fans,
who for this game surprised even unflappable Bill Bidwill, the
team's owner, with unprecedented support. The Cardinals have come
back and come back, often after having no business having to come
back. This, the biggest game in the Arizona portion of their
history, was an example of it.
</P>
<P>
   But they never quit, and the community took notice. The
Cardinals (9-7) now move on to face the Dallas Cowboys, to whom
they lost twice this season, to open the playoffs Saturday at Texas
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals got there the only way they know how, the hard
way. They took a 13-3 lead into the fourth quarter before the
Chargers (5-11) controlled the ball for 17 plays and used more than
eight minutes while driving for a field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Then the action got fast and furious. The Chargers got the ball
back, trailing, 13-6, and receiver Ryan Thelwell slipped behind the
Cardinals' secondary for what appeared to be a game-tying touchdown
reception. But the ball bounced off his hands to safety Kwamie
Lassiter for his fourth interception of the game with 4:21
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals put themselves in position to ice the victory,
driving to the Chargers' 25. Facing fourth and inches, with the
two-minute warning to give him time to mull the decision, Cardinals
Coach Vince Tobin went against his better judgment and sent Jacke
onto the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quarterback sneak is what I wanted to do in the first
place,'' Tobin said.
</P>
<P>
   Jacke missed right, and the Chargers had the ball at their 32
with 1:55 and one timeout left. The Cardinals' defense had taken
direct hits from the Chargers' rushing game all afternoon, but it
had kept them out of the end zone. And when the Chargers faced
fourth and 19 at the Cardinals' 30 with 22 seconds left after a
third-down sack by Mark Smith, their chances of withstanding this
challenge looked good.
</P>
<P>
   Then quarterback Craig Whelihan found Thelwell open in the end
zone between cornerback Corey Chavous and Lassiter to tie the score
with 16 seconds to go.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Metcalf, who played for the Chargers last season, correctly
anticipated a squib on the ensuing kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few yards shorter and one of the wedge guys would have had
to fall on it,'' Metcalf said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the ball hopped to Metcalf at the 10. There was a huge
seam, and he headed directly north for 46 yards to the Chargers' 44
with seven seconds and one timeout remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, I thought I was going to run into the tunnel (beyond
the north end zone),'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Jake Plummer, who had a tough day against the
league's top-ranked defense, quickly threw a 10-yard pass to Frank
Sanders, who had suffered a twisted knee on the opening play of the
second quarter and thought he was finished.
</P>
<P>
   ``They X-rayed it at halftime and it was fine,'' Sanders said.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals used their final timeout, putting their fate once
again on the foot of Jacke, who was signed this month after Joe
Nedney suffered a season-ending knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I missed that one before just for the TV ratings,'' Jacke said
after making the game-winning kick for the third consecutive week.
``Over the years, I've been better from that distance than shorter
ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Bidwill acknowledged that he didn't jump up and down before he
was handed the game ball and ushered through the bedlam.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this is a great thing to have had happen,'' he said.
``Emotion _ there was and there wasn't. It's just a great thing for
the fans and the franchise.''
</P>
<P>
   Which, at last, were inseparable. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
