<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 00:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7998 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDINALS-HISTORY     12-28 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINALS-HISTORY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME DECENT HISTORY FINALLY COMES ABOUT  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Offensive tackle Lomas Brown's buddies told him not to go the
graveyard in the desert, home to losing football teams, ones
without hope.
</P>
<P>
   Trainer John Omohundro has heard worse in his 32 years with the
Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   This was the franchise that had the NFL's highest ticket prices
before it played a game in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   This was the team that lost its franchise quarterback in a
non-contact drill at a night practice. Timm Rosenbach was never the
same after suffering the torn anterior cruciate knee ligament.
</P>
<P>
   While the Cardinals were beating the San Diego Chargers at Sun
Devil Stadium to end the NFL's longest playoff drought, Rosenbach
was in Cabo San Lucas, Mexico, running a charter tour boat service.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Tupa, another of the 16 starting quarterbacks the team has
had in Arizona, is punting _ yes, punting _ for New England. At
least, he's still in the league. The same can't be said for Stan
Gelbaugh, Jay Schroeder and Jim McMahon.
</P>
<P>
   ``My children waited a whole lifetime for this,'' Omohundro
said. ``They had to eat a whole bunch of dirt in school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't describe what it feels like to have had so many years
of frustration.''
</P>
<P>
   Omohundro's misery had been shared by many. Benny Greenberg, 72,
has been with the team for 33 years. Assistant trainer Jim
``Machine'' Shearer just completed his 25th season.
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback Aeneas Williams felt for them, and himself. This is
his first winning season in nine years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cried like a baby after the game,'' Williams said. ``I
wasn't afraid to let the tears fall.''
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Jamir Miller also was emotional.
</P>
<P>
   ``How sweet it is,'' Miller said. ``All eyes are on us. People
can't say the Cardinals are jokes anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Vince Tobin told the team there would be days like Sunday.
He was asked so many times his first few months on the job about
the franchise's wretched past, he came up with a line he repeated
often: ``I'm not interested in historians. I'm interested in
pioneers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up on a farm,'' said Tobin, a native of Burlington
Junction, Mo. ``So I knew what pioneers do.''
</P>
<P>
   Tobin told that to Brown, his first high-profile free-agent
acquisition, in the winter of 1996. It didn't matter that the
Cardinals had missed the playoffs since 1982 or been without a
winning season since 1984.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took a lot of flak for coming here,'' said Brown, who was a
seven-time Pro Bowl selection in Detroit. ``A lot of people said I
just went for the money, and I was not interested in winning, but
now we are in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   NFL executives told Bob Ferguson that he was crazy for taking a
Cardinals
</P>
<P>
   personnel job when Tobin was hired nearly three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   This team changed coaches every four seasons, it drafted a
kicker in the second round in 1986, it used its first-round pick
the next year on a quarterback (Colorado State's Kelly Stouffer) it
never signed and took running Tony Jeffery instead of Thurman
Thomas in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   How desperate were the Cardinals in 1992? They traded their
first-round pick for wide receiver Randal Hill and followed that up
by taking their next quarterback of the future, Tony Sacca, in the
second round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had heard that stuff that you could never win in Buffalo, in
Seattle with an expansion team,'' Ferguson said. ``I've been there.
You know things change. . . I figured we had everything to gain and
nothing to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Losing was all the Cardinals had done since moving from the St.
Louis in 1988 except for an 8-8 season in 1994, the year Buddy Ryan
proclaimed the Valley had a winner in town.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Jake Plummer is in town. He arrived at the Cardinals
facility two years ago and started leading the team to comeback
wins, nine in his first two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   This year, first-round pick Andre Wadsworth, nicknamed ``The
Gift,'' by teammate Simeon Rice, joined the team. Rice said
Wadsworth was the gift who would lead the team to the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't come easily. Eight times, the Cardinals' games were
decided by three points or less, including Sunday's
playoff-clinching win on a 52-yard field goal by Chris Jacke on the
final play.
</P>
<P>
   ``This season has been incredible,'' vice chairman Tom Guilfoil
said. ``It has been more exciting than the `Cardiac Cardinals' of
the 1970s. The whole season has been scripted in Hollywood.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-28-98 0058EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
