<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 01:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7999 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-BRONCOS-     12-28 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-BRONCOS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEAHAWK PLAYERS SAY SOME GAVE UP IN 8-8 SEASON FINALE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ As Shawn Springs left the field at Mile High Stadium
Sunday, the Seahawks' Pro Bowl cornerback issued a warning to
reporters waiting outside the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please do not interview me,'' Springs said. ``I will tell you
the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, he started by correcting the score.
</P>
<P>
   The scoreboard had it: Denver Broncos 28, Seahawks 21.
</P>
<P>
   According to Springs, ``That should have been 45-0, Broncos.''
</P>
<P>
   In a season finale where the Seahawks were hoping to make a
statement for next season as well as the future of their embattled
coach, Springs' biting words said a lot about what went wrong in
this game, and in this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stink,'' Springs said. ``Some people quit. Some people
played. It was obvious. You all saw it.''
</P>
<P>
   What most people noticed, especially the 74,057 fans in the
stands, was Terrell Davis running for 178 yards to become the
fourth player in NFL history to have a 2,000-yard rushing season.
Or 38-year-old John Elway looking like 28-year-old John Elway in
passing for 338 yards and four TDs. Or a Denver team that had lost
two straight after winning its first 13 games ironing out any and
all problems heading into the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   What Springs and some of his defensive teammates witnessed was a
lack of effort by some of their own teammates that allowed the
Broncos to dominate the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys didn't play hard enough,'' defensive end Phillip Daniels
said. ``I don't think everybody played like they should.
Everybody's got a gap up front and when somebody doesn't play
theirs, that's when big runs happen.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the Seahawks wanted to point any fingers. But, as
Springs said, it was there for everyone to see _ especially club
president Bob Whitsitt, who did not make the trip with the team but
is expected to make a decision this week on whether head coach
Dennis Erickson will return next season.
</P>
<P>
   A defense that has been the heart and conscience of this team
all season suddenly coming up heartless at times cannot help
Erickson's case or cause.
</P>
<P>
   At one point in the third quarter, strong safety Jay Bellamy was
yelling at rookie middle linebacker DeShone Myles between plays.
Later, Pro Bowl linebacker Chad Brown had to step in to stop
Springs from going after Myles.
</P>
<P>
   What happened Sunday cannot be blamed on one player. But it was
definitely an ugly way to end a season that started with three
straight wins and such lofty expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel bad for Coach E.'s situation, but it wasn't just him.
It was everything,'' Springs said.
</P>
<P>
   With the loss, the Seahawks finished 8-8 for the second straight
season and are out of the playoffs for the 10th year in a row _ the
longest postseason drought in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks were not blown out of any games, and for the most
part played hard every week _ if not always well. But to fall this
far short of expectations, well, someone must be held accountable.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the things that plagued us all year came back and
hurt us today,'' quarterback Jon Kitna said.
</P>
<P>
   This game got out of control in a hurry. By halftime, the
Broncos led only 14-7. But a closer look at the numbers shows it
was one of the most lop-sided seven-point halftime leads in league
history.
</P>
<P>
   In the first 30 minutes, Elway passed for 220 yards, Kitna for
96. Davis ran for 82 yards, Seattle's Ricky Watters ran for 10. Rod
Smith caught six passes for 121 yards, Joey Galloway three for 33.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ran into a buzzsaw today,'' Erickson said. ``They ran the
ball. They threw the ball. They just seemed to do anything they
wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't stop in the second half, despite the Seahawks scoring
two fourth-quarter TDs to close the gap on the scoreboard. The
Broncos rolled up 511 yards, just four shy of their season high.
They held almost a 16-minute bulge in time of possession.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apparently, they wanted it more than we wanted to stop them,''
Brown said. ``It's disappointing. I'm disappointed in myself. I'm
disappointed in my teammates. It's been a disappointing year. It's
been a disappointing two years. Eight-and-eight again and not in
the playoffs. That's not why I play the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Sinclair has been through a lot in his eight seasons
with the Seahawks. The Pro Bowl defensive end has survived a couple
of coaching changes _ from Chuck Knox to Tom Flores in 1991 and
from Flores to Erickson in 1995 _ and the ownership switch from Ken
Behring to Paul Allen. Sinclair was there for the 2-14 season in
1992 and the total collapse that was the season-ending 35-9 loss at
Cleveland in Flores' last game in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Sinclair said Sunday's season-ending loss was not in the same
class as the one that lost to the Browns in '94. He said the main
thing missing from this collection of talented players is a
mindset.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to win, the mindset is going to have to change,''
Sinclair said. ``It's amazing how other guys who used to play here
who are with other teams, they're busting it because they've got a
different mindset.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the difference between saying ``Here we go again,'' and
``No, we're not going there,'' when you fall behind early.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a mindset,'' Sinclair said. ``And we have to get away
from that.''
</P>
<P>
   This final chapter in the Seahawks' season of unfulfilled
expectations ends the same way it started. With a few truthful
words from Springs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm embarrassed for the City of Seattle,'' he said. ``Some of
us quit. Flat out.''
</P>
<P>
   Alluding to the $55 million of Allen's money that was spent to
bring in players the past two years, Springs added, ``I feel
embarrassed for Mr. Allen wasting his money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
