r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-FRAUENHEIM-NOTEBO     12-28 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-FRAUENHEIM-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TYSON TIES HIS FORTUNES TO OLD FOE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mike Tyson has allied himself with an old foe in an attempt to
pull his career out of the controversy that has scarred it so
badly.
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Tommy Brooks helped plot Evander Holyfield's triumph
over Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   As an assistant to Holyfield's trainer Don Turner, Brooks
searched for and found all the weaknesses that proved to be Tyson's
undoing. As an able enemy, Brooks knows as much about Tyson as
anyone.
</P>
<P>
   If our biggest critics are indeed our greatest allies, then
Tyson has found an important friend. The relationship, the battle,
is just beginning in workout sessions at Phoenix's Madison Square
Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks is trying to point out weaknesses to Tyson. For Tyson,
the key is a willingness to learn. To listen. For Tyson, that
always has been a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the guys around him have been yes men,'' Brooks said
last week as Tyson trained for his comeback bout against Frans
Botha on Jan. 16 at Las Vegas' MGM Grand. ``He was training them.
That's not the way it's supposed to operate.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, it hasn't.
</P>
<P>
   During Tyson's first session in the Brooks regime, the former
heavyweight champion was asked to punch as fast as he could within
30 seconds. Tyson was ordered to do it again. And again. Finally,
he threw up.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks said he screamed at him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Punch, punch,'' Brooks yelled. ``You can't stop punching in a
fight if you throw up.''
</P>
<P>
   Above all, Brooks said he is trying to re-instill the
fundamental rigors of a brutal trade once called ``the hurt
business'' by Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to take a refresher course, no matter how long you've
been fighting,'' Brooks said. ``Now that he's been beaten twice,
guys aren't intimidated like they used to be. Maybe he needed to
get beat to realize the bad habits he got into.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Brooks himself has heard questions with some implied
criticism of his decision to jump from Holyfield to Tyson. Why the
move from a perceived good guy to a self-proclaimed hell-raiser?
Holyfield's staunchest fans grumble about Brooks' lack of loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   But for Brooks, the move was about business. It represented a
chance to establish himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a kid with eight or 10 fights left,'' said Brooks.
``Holyfield and I will always be tight as far as I'm concerned. But
this is business. I got to look out for my family. I mean, how long
can you be an assistant?'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
A Tyson counter &QL; 
 &QL; 
There was talk show criticism of Sheriff Joe Arpaio's decision last
week to let Tyson counsel juvenile inmates in the tents and cells
at the Estrella jail complex.
</P>
<P>
   Go ahead and complain, said Tyson, who generates controversy at
the mere mention of his name.
</P>
<P>
   ``To all the people who complain about me being here, those
people should come and talk to them,'' he said. ``They're scared to
even look at these kids. They're afraid that they'll rob them.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Briefly . . . &QL; 
 &QL; 
Longtime Valley trainer Willy Borchert is suddenly caught in a
zoning battle to save his west-side gym. He faces a Jan. 7
deadline. Borchert has been training amateurs for 26 years at the
neighborhood gym, which was the first home for ex-World Boxing
Association featherweight champ Louie Espinoza, the first Arizona
fighter with a major title.
</P>
<P>
   Best fighter ever? Burgermeister George Foreman says it is
neither Sugar Ray Robinson nor Muhammad Ali. ``There's never been a
better boxer than Joe Louis,'' Foreman told the BBC. And, yo, actor
Sylvester Stallone, best known for the Rocky series, had this to
say at a recent fund-raiser sponsored by Oscar De la Hoya: ``The
only guy I could fight now is Senator John Glenn.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
