<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 01:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8001 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-ARIZONASTATE-AZR &LR;      12-28 0544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARIZONA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTENTION: ASU SET FOR TOURNAMENT 
</HEADLINE>
 STATE-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   No matter how fervently they preach the virtues of going to
class, studying hard and being diligent, responsible
student-athletes, college basketball coaches love this time of
year.
</P>
<P>
   Classes and exams are over. Next semester is still an object in
the distance. The players are theirs.
</P>
<P>
   And theirs alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't have anything to worry about now except
basketball,'' Arizona State Coach Rob Evans said.
</P>
<P>
   Evans' teams at Mississippi, particularly his later editions,
used this time to utmost advantage. The past three seasons, Ole
Miss was 15-2 in December after the semester break. The pattern
seems to be continuing with the Sun Devils, who play Navy in the
second game of the ASU/Fiesta Bowl Classic tonight at Wells Fargo
Arena following the opener between Alaska-Anchorage and Southern
Methodist at 5:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The winners meet Tuesday night after the 5:30 consolation game,
and even though Navy is 8-2 and reached the NCAA Tournament last
season, Evans will be very disappointed if ASU doesn't win its own
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   After a 2-4 start, ASU has won four in a row, including upsets
of Nevada-Las Vegas and Texas A&AMP;M. The obvious reasons include the
return of freshman Kenny Crandall and senior Mike Batiste. But
Evans sees real progress, not just in games but practice, where he
and the coaches have turned up the intensity dial a few notches.
</P>
<P>
   And the Sun Devils have responded.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing,'' Evans said. ``I see a sense of purpose, of
focus. I told my staff, `These guys really want to learn.' They're
trying to execute, trying to give effort. It just appears to me
it's like, `Boy, this is what the coach has been talking about.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I really feel these guys are getting better. Now is the time
we've got their total attention, and and if they're going to get
better, they're going to get better fundamentally.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans gave the players what amounted to 2{ days off, and had
them report back for practice Christmas night. On Saturday, they
worked out twice. Batiste called it the best three practices in a
row all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been totally concentrating on things we have to do, and
we're mentally focused,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been doing a lot of drills like we did at the beginning
of the year,'' freshman Chad Prewitt said.
</P>
<P>
   Evans said the return to fundamentals emphasizes defense and
passing. Marist shot nearly 52 percent in ASU's 85-77 victory
Tuesday, but Evans attributed that to his players ``already having
their bags packed,'' and said the defense has improved over the
past month.
</P>
<P>
   But it's still not where he would like it to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really feel like we can score,'' Evans said, noting that ASU
shot better than 50 percent (60.4 percent) for the first time
against Marist. ``Our thing is we've got to stop people.''
</P>
<P>
   By Christmas night, everyone was back after going home for the
holidays except point guard Alton Mason, who got hung up returning
from Nebraska and also missed Saturday's practices. Evans said
Mason probably wouldn't start against Navy, ``not as punishment,
but because it wouldn't be fair.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
