<HEADER>
A8002 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES_SCHOENFEL     12-28 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES_SCHOENFELD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COYOTES' PLAY CREATES AN ALL-STAR COACH  
 SCHOENFELD NO LONGER LIVES IN DOGHOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jim Schoenfeld grabbed his car keys and was heading out the door
to practice Sunday morning when one of his children, sitting at the
breakfast table, stopped the Coyotes coach to congratulate him.
</P>
<P>
   The conversation between Katie Schoenfeld and her father went
something like this:
</P>
<P>
   ``Great job, Dad. You get to coach in the All-Star Game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks, honey, but I think you're wrong. I don't think that's
correct.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it is. The head coaches from the two teams that have the
best winning percentages in each conference will coach in the 49th
annual NHL All-Star Game on Jan. 24 at the Ice Palace in Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   Schoenfeld and Ken Hitchcock of the Dallas Stars get the nod
from the Western Conference and will coach the North American squad
of U.S. and Canadian players. The question as to which man becomes
the head coach and which becomes the assistant for next month's
game will be determined tonight.
</P>
<P>
   It's simple math. If the Coyotes (20-6-4) beat the Los Angeles
Kings at America West Arena and the Stars (21-5-6) lose at home
against Nashville, Schoenfeld will be designated the head coach.
Under that scenario, Phoenix would have a .742 winning percentage,
Dallas .729.
</P>
<P>
   If both the Coyotes and Stars win tonight, or both teams lose,
Schoenfeld will serve as assistant because Dallas' winning
percentage will be better.
</P>
<P>
   The selections will be announced formally Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell you the truth, I haven't given it any thought because
I didn't think it was a done deal,'' said Schoenfeld, who twice
played in the All-Star Game as a member of the Buffalo Sabres
(1977, 1980) but will make his first appearance as a coach. ``But,
hey, if that's the way it goes down, I like it, because I think
it's more of a recognition for our team. I happen to be the coach,
but it's what the team has accomplished that's going to enable me
to go there.''
</P>
<P>
   And to think, a year ago at this time, rumors were surfacing
that Schoenfeld was on the verge of being canned. After 30 games
last season, the Coyotes were 13-14-3, and Schoenfeld was sporting
a career coaching record of 195-194-57.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to remember who was calling for his head _ the
media and ``some'' of the fans,'' Coyotes captain Keith Tkachuk
said. ``We had all the confidence in the world in him, but I think
Shoney was put in an unfair situation. The easiest thing to do is
put a coach on the hot seat.''
</P>
<P>
   Owner Richard Burke was so impatient, however, he publicly
vented his anger more than once in Schoenfeld's direction. As
injuries began to take their toll on the club, however, Burke and
General Manager Bobby Smith summoned reporters to a closed-door
meeting and assured them that Schoenfeld's job was safe _ for the
time being.
</P>
<P>
   The rumblings around the organization as the team headed into
training camp this season were that the Coyotes would have to show
a marked improvement through the first 20 games for Schoenfeld to
feel safe. They have, and he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're happy for everybody, for all of us,'' center Jeremy
Roenick said. ``Shoney went through a little bit of a tough time at
the beginning of the year with the question of whether he was going
to remain coach here all year. But he's worked hard. All the
coaches have. We've come full circle in a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Schoenfeld, who might end up coaching Tkachuk and Roenick in the
All-Star Game, came to Phoenix a year ago, saying this likely will
be his last coaching stop. If it didn't work out with the Coyotes,
he said, he probably wouldn't get another chance elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Now, who knows? He's got the franchise off to its best start in
its 20-year history. With a win or tie tonight, the team can set a
club record for going undefeated in 12 consecutive home games.
Schoenfeld and the Coyotes are being mentioned as Stanley Cup
contenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought this might be my last opportunity,'' he said. ``How
do I feel about it now? I don't know. I don't dwell on stuff like
that very much.''
</P>
<P>
   Just like coaching in the All-Star Game. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
