r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDINALS-COWBOYS     12-28 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINALS-COWBOYS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
READY TO TAKE OFF GLOVES  
 CARDS REMEMBER BITTER DALLAS LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The gloves are still hanging in No. 67's locker at the
Cardinals' training facility, awaiting their date with destiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm going to wear them in the game, too,'' Cardinals
offensive guard Chris Dishman said.
</P>
<P>
   The gloves in question are the ones Dishman was wearing on Nov.
15, when the Cardinals dropped a disappointing 35-28 game to the
Dallas Cowboys. The game ended with receiver Rob Moore being
interfered with in the end zone as the game officials chose to
ignore it.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Dishman wrote the score on each glove and vowed
to hang them in his locker, forecasting the Cardinals and Cowboys
would meet again in postseason.
</P>
<P>
   They will on Saturday in Texas Stadium, where Arizona hasn't won
since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough loss, and I still think about it. There isn't a
day that goes by in the locker room that I don't see those gloves.
They are there for a reason, to remind of a loss that was probably
the toughest I've ever had,'' he said after the Cardinals'
playoff-clinching win Sunday. ``I've been looking forward to this.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of great moments when I played at Nebraska, but
this ranks up there with any of them. I was hoping we could turn it
around sometime. We had the lead going, and they were doing the
wave. It reminds me of Nebraska.''
</P>
<P>
   The reaction in the Cardinals' locker room ran the gamut. Some
talked about a third meeting with the Cowboys after two losses,
while others wanted to savor the moment and talk about the date
with Dallas later.
</P>
<P>
   ``We learned in our last game with them that we can play with
them,'' center Aaron Graham said. ``The first game (38-10 to open
the season) we didn't play well and they gave it to us pretty much,
but the second game showed us we can play with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know one thing, I bet they probably don't want it to come
down to the wire again with us having the ball. If nothing else, we
certainly have a lot more experience than anybody in that situation
now than they do.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Andre Wadsworth didn't want to visit the past,
preferring to look ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever happened in the past with Dallas is in the past and
out the window,'' he said. ``It's now just a one-shot deal. We
don't have to worry about what any other team is doing. All I know
is Dallas is in our way to get to our goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know how it is in this sport, anyway. They could have beat
us 53-0 twice, but the game still has to be played and anything can
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore thinks the Cardinals have learned much since the November
date with Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've learned that our offense can set a tempo,'' he said.
``In the first two games with Dallas, we never set a tempo
offensively and challenged their defense, which we have to do this
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question we're more equipped to do it now. We've
made the plays when we've had to, which is the sign of a
developing, maturing team. But we do it the hard way.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing is certain, the Cardinals don't seem in awe of the
Cowboys, despite the two losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not at all,'' said safety Tommy Bennett. ``The first game they
got us in the air and ground pretty good. The second game was a
different story. We had a few key turnovers that put points on the
board, but we still had a chance to win in the end, and I think
we'll cross the bridge this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Dallas had a bad year last year and didn't make it to the
playoffs, so I'm sure they will want to prove something, too.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
