<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINALS-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METCALF REDEEMS SLOW SEASON WITH BIG RETURN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cardinals kick returner Eric Metcalf has had a disappointing
season this year, averaging only 6.9 yards on punt returns and 20.8
on kick returns entering Sunday's game.
</P>
<P>
   But he made one of the biggest plays of the year Sunday when he
returned a kickoff 46 yards, which helped set up Chris Jacke's
52-yard, game-winning field goal as time expired.
</P>
<P>
   ``They squibbed it pretty deep,'' Metcalf said. ``I don't know
if they were playing for us to do a middle return, that's what you
normally do on a squib. But I know a lot of people thought we were
just going overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy I was able to do that in crunch time. A lot of times
this season I haven't been very excited because I didn't feel I had
really helped the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Metcalf plans to have a nice conversation with his father,
Terry, a running back for the Cardinals in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to say, `It's a Metcalf getting them to the
playoffs again.' '' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Nowhere to go
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals running back Adrian Murrell had his worst outing of
the season, gaining only 25 yards on 18 carries. On 15 of his 18
carries, he gained a yard or less.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to give them credit,'' Murrell said of the Chargers.
``They're not ranked Number 1 defensively for nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Murrell also was involved in the game's most controversial play.
He was awarded a touchdown on a 4-yard run in the first quarter,
although replays showed he was stopped short of the goal line on
the second-down play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I scored on that one,'' Murrell said. ``But we
would have scored, I guarantee you.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
No Leaf
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, San Diego's interim Coach June Jones
announced that rookie quarterback Ryan Leaf would see some action
in a backup role to Craig Whelihan. But Leaf never left the
sideline.
</P>
<P>
   ``June, I respect him more than anybody,'' Leaf said. ``Whatever
he thinks is best for me and best for this football team is the
best decision-making he could have done. Whatever he was thinking,
it was the right thing I suppose. So leave it at that.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Masters of the close shave
</P>
<P>
   With Sunday's victory, the Cardinals set an NFL record for
winning the most games in a season by three points or less. The
Cardinals were 7-1 this year. The previous record was held by
Denver, which went 6-2 in 1984. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Catching on &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Frank Sanders' eight catches, good for 106 yards, gave him 89
for the season, most in the NFC and second in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   After straining his left knee on the opening play of the second
quarter, he thought he was finished for the day.
</P>
<P>
   But like the team, Sanders found a way to come back, making the
reception that put Chris Jacke into range for the final field goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was bad,'' Sanders said of his injury. ``It
throbbed all through the second quarter. I wasn't able to do
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   It felt better when he came back after halftime. And better yet
after making the catch to set up Jacke.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've just been very fortunate to win games like this all
year,'' he said. ``We let teams off after we have them down. We're
exciting to the finish. This year, the maturity of this team has
shown. These are games we didn't finish last year.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Staff writers Kent Somers, Lee Shappell and Tim Tyers contributed
to this article. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
