r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDINALS-LASSITE     12-28 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINALS-LASSITER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LASSITER TIES LEAGUE RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kwamie Lassiter said God was looking out for him on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he did. Then he didn't. Then he did. And then he didn't.
</P>
<P>
   So it goes for an NFL defensive back, even on days when his team
clinches its first playoff berth in 16 years and he intercepts four
passes to tie an all-time league record.
</P>
<P>
   With the Cardinals trying to protect a 13-6 lead late in the
fourth quarter, Lassiter and Corey Chavous appeared to be beaten by
Chargers receiver Ryan Thelwell for a possible tying touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``He should have made the play,'' Lassiter said. ``We're paid to
make plays. But he bobbled the ball as Corey was going to hit him,
and it popped into my hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it hit Thelwell in the hands, then his knee and then
popped into Lassiter's hands. It was manna from heaven.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the fourth quarter with the Cardinals still protecting
a seven-point lead, it was Lassiter who broke up a possible scoring
pass to Mikhael Ricks near the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw him go up and I thought about going up, but I knew Corey
was in front of him, so I just yanked him backwards as hard as I
could and the ball came free,'' Lassiter said, recalling another
moment of glory.
</P>
<P>
   It set up a fourth and 19 at the Cardinals' 20 with 22 seconds
remaining. And for all his previous glory, Lassiter could have been
fitted for goat horns, because the Cardinals were in a zone blitz
with three-deep coverage, and Chargers quarterback Craig Whelihan
found Thelwell behind Lassiter and Chavous for the game-tying
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just snuck one in on us,'' said Lassiter, whose four
interceptions suddenly lost some glitter. ``Whelihan is a good guy.
He throws well but had some bad luck. He threw that one right in
there between us.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in a `cover 3' and I had guys on both sides of me that
I had to watch. I broke on the ball, but he just squeezed it in
there.''
</P>
<P>
   With only 16 seconds left, did Lassiter think the Cardinals'
destiny would be settled in overtime?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not at all,'' he said. ``We still had 16 seconds, and don't
forget we have Jake (Plummer). I have a lot of faith in him and all
my teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I'd like to win and blow teams out, but we'll take
wins any way we can get them. I've been here for four years, and
I'm happy for the guys who've been here longer. We've never smelled
the playoffs before.''
</P>
<P>
   Lassiter's first interception was made at Arizona's 30 and led
to a 37-yard Chris Jacke field goal that gave the Cardinals a 10-0
lead. His second came on a last-second desperation pass at the end
of the first half.
</P>
<P>
   His third pick came at the Cardinals' 12 when Whelihan attempted
to go deep to Ricks. Finally, his fourth, with 4:21 remaining, gave
him eight for the season, the most by a Cardinal since Aeneas
Williams had nine in 1994. His season total led the NFC.
</P>
<P>
   Lassiter has come a long way, considering he lost his starting
job to rookie Pat Tillman before the season and didn't crack the
starting lineup until midseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just happened to be in the right place at the right time
today,'' he said. ``I never got down when I wasn't starting because
I was in on nickel-and-dime coverages and I was on special teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you allow me to play, I'm going to make plays for you. Me
and Pat are cool, man. We both want to help this team win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
