<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINALS-JACKE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINCHING KICKS ROUTINE FOR JACKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There, on the bottom of the Cardinals' victory pile, the kicker
was getting crushed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little guy,'' Chris Jacke said. ``It hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, he wasn't feeling much pain. As he peeked out from the
bodies on top of him, he saw the message on the scoreboard: ``Wild
Cards.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacke's 52-yard field goal with no time remaining gave the
Cardinals a 16-13 victory over San Diego and ended the NFL's
longest playoff drought at 15 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   It was his third winning kick in three weeks. ``He seems to hit
when it really, really matters, not just when it matters,''
quarterback Jake Plummer said. All three of Jacke's winners came on
the final play.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a (TV) ratings bonanza,'' Jacke said.
</P>
<P>
   His 52-yarder made up for what he called a ``horrible day.''
</P>
<P>
   He missed a 45-yard field goal in the third quarter and a
42-yarder with 1:55 left that would have given the Cardinals a
10-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, his kick went wide right, and the Chargers went 68
yards in 10 plays to tie the score at 13 with 16 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   ``A 42-yarder, you should be able to make it nine times out of
10,'' Jacke said. ``It's unforgiveable.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Jacke missed his 42-yard attempt, Cardinals Coach Vince
Tobin decided to bypass going for the first down on fourth and 1 at
the Chargers' 25.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly I have second thoughts,'' Tobin said. ``Since he
didn't kick it through, I wished we would have quarterback sneaked,
which is what I wanted to do in the first place. Then, I decided we
were right in the middle of the field. Either way, if we had gotten
the first and 10 or if we had kicked the field goal, the game would
have been over.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacke got another chance after Eric Metcalf's 46-yard kickoff
return gave the Cardinals possession at San Diego's 44. A 10-yard
pass completion with three seconds left gave him a chance to atone
for his misses.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what you have to have here, the confidence to bounce
back,'' said Jacke of his 15th career winning kick. ``I went out
there like it was a fresh start.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacke has made only one kick longer, a 54-yarder in 1993. Still,
his teammates were confident he would convert.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's from Green Bay,'' defensive end Simeon Rice said. ``He
knows all about pressure. He knows all about nail-biters.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacke was congratulated in the locker room by Joe Nedney, whose
knee injury is the reason Jacke joined the team a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   Jacke won a Super Bowl ring with the Green Bay Packers two years
ago, but was out of work for most of the past two seasons before he
won a tryout over Cole Ford, the former Oakland Raiders' kicker,
after Nedney was injured. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-28-98 0109EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981228.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 01:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8007 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDINALS-DRAFT-A     12-28 0233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINALS-DRAFT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIN HELPS CARDINALS IN DRAFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   That blockbuster trade the Cardinals made with San Diego last
March is looking better all the time.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the deal, the Cardinals will get the Chargers'
first-round pick in next year's draft, which will be eighth
overall.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals made sure they got a top-10 pick by beating the
Chargers, 16-13, on Sunday at Sun Devil Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Chargers (5-11) finished with the same record as the Detroit
Lions but will draft ahead of them because of a softer schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we made the trade, we wanted to build for the future,''
Cardinals Vice President Bob Ferguson said. ``We didn't know what
pick we'd get from them. I know they're a much better team than
their record.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals (9-7) also have their own pick in the first round.
If the draft were held today, that choice would be 19th overall,
the lowest pick among playoff teams.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the San Diego trade, the Cardinals traded down one spot
in the first round and picked third overall, a choice they used on
Florida State defensive end Andre Wadsworth.
</P>
<P>
   They also acquired wide receiver Eric Metcalf, linebacker
Patrick Sapp and a 1998 second-round pick, which they used on
Southwestern Louisiana offensive tackle Anthony Clement. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-28-98 0109EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
