<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 01:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8008 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-HOLIDAY_ARIZONA-A     12-28 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HOLIDAY_ARIZONA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UA TRIES TO JOIN FOOTBALL'S ELITE  
 WANTS WINNER IN 2 BIG SPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Arizona was the only NCAA Division I school last
week with two teams in different major sports ranked among the top
10, yet the Wildcats still have one reputation.
</P>
<P>
   As a matter of fact, it's a slam dunk.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona is No. 5 in the Associated Press football poll. In
basketball, Arizona is ranked No. 8 by AP and No. 1 with its fans.
</P>
<P>
   The national rankings are a sure mark of success for each
program, but the comparison seems to end there. Why?
</P>
<P>
   It's an an intriguing question, one that raises several others.
Above all, it highlights Arizona's football program this week as it
approaches a crossroads Wednesday night in the Holiday Bowl at
Qualcomm Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The opponent is Nebraska, a piece of the rock. An Arizona
victory would be a step toward the elite level that the school's
basketball program has long occupied. With a defeat, it's back to
football anonymity and March Madness.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true,'' said Arizona quarterback Ortege Jenkins, who has
also been a reserve guard on the basketball team. ``I think we have
had a great football season, but it's kind of been overshadowed
because of the (1997) national championship and then the Pacific-10
Conference titles in basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``People look at a winning football season and a Pac-10
basketball title differently, especially when you win Pac-10 titles
back to back to back.''
</P>
<P>
   The difference is reflected at the box office. Basketball games
at Arizona's McKale Center are a guaranteed sellout. Other than a
sellout for the Wildcats' lone football loss to UCLA this season,
the only guarantee at Arizona Stadium was empty seats.
</P>
<P>
   The box office question is a sticky one, especially when it is
asked of football Coach Dick Tomey. He bristles when the two
programs are compared for their attendance figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no comparison between 13,000 for basketball and
50,000 for football,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A calculator will prove Tomey right every time. Nonetheless, an
Arizona basketball ticket is a precious commodity. A football
ticket is not. The difference between the two is enthusiasm, which
is hard to measure but a factor, nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins forecasts a change, at least at the football end of the
scale. In time, he said, Arizona football will generate the kind of
enthusiasm enjoyed by the basketball empire ruled by Lute Olson.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this year, and from this point on, I really believe we
will be a well-balanced school between football and basketball,''
Jenkins said.
</P>
<P>
   But Arizona's versatile quarterback also knows his history. Few
schools ever strike that balance. Trivia question: Can you name
Nebraska's five greatest basketball moments? Correct answer: No.
There aren't five.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska is a football school, just as surely as North Carolina
is stamped with a basketball reputation. North Carolina has had
some very good football teams, but the school is known for only one
great athlete. And no, Michael Jordan was not a quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   However, there are at least two schools that have managed to
maintain a high level of success in both football and basketball at
the same time. In the Pac-10, there's UCLA. In the Big Ten, there's
Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the future, Arizona can be looked at like one of those
schools,'' Jenkins said. ``Coach Olson has young guys right now who
are off to a real good start. Basketball just keeps going along at
the same level.
</P>
<P>
   ``In football, we've got a whole lot of young guys who are just
getting started. Coach Tomey and this team is just on the rise now.
We're starting to set a standard.''
</P>
<P>
   In large part, Jenkins said, it is the football team's job to
alter the fans' way of thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Tucson, people are just used to winning in basketball,''
said the sophomore, who has been sharing the quarterback duties
with junior Keith Smith. ``It's something that's been a pattern for
so many years.
</P>
<P>
   ``But for as long as I'm here and Keith is here, we're going to
try to set the standard. But doing that, we can let our friends,
younger players and recruits know that something is going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way is to first win 11 games and then hopefully win a
12th against Nebraska. There's really no other way to go about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   It's called tradition, and it's no slam dunk. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-28-98 0113EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
