<HEADLINE>
MCALISTER SEES HOLIDAY BOWL AS SHOWCASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Arizona cornerback Chris McAlister sees the Holiday
Bowl game against Nebraska on Wednesday as an important stage on
which to further prove himself to NFL scouts.
</P>
<P>
   McAlister already figures to be the best prospect on the field.
Still, there are lingering doubts that he promises to eliminate.
</P>
<P>
   There have been some questions about McAlister's willingness and
ability to play against bigger receivers. In the wide-open Pac-10,
there was little opportunity or reason to play a physical game. The
league is about speed and finesse.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska possesses plenty of both, but the Cornhuskers are
defined by a teeth-rattling option attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a chance for people to see the other side of Chris
McAlister,'' said the consensus All-American, who could be among
the first 10 picks in the NFL draft. ``I love the physical side of
football. I love playing run support. In the Pac-10, corners don't
get a chance to do a lot of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``More or less, what people have seen most from me is playing
off natural talent. I've worked hard to improve my strength in the
weight room. Now, we'll see if it's paid off.'' &QL;  &QL; 
Briefly . . .
</P>
<P>
   Arizona running back Kelvin Eafon didn't practice Sunday because
of a slight ankle sprain, which is not expected to sideline him
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Different numbers: For Arizona (11-1), there is motivation in
trying to win its 12th game for the first time. For Nebraska (9-3),
there's the fear of losing a fourth game for the time since 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Coach Dick Tomey, when asked how he made the Keith
Smith-Ortege Jenkins quarterback rotation work: ``I didn't make it
work. They did.''
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska Coach Frank Solich, on whether the Wildcats resemble
any team in the Big 12: ``They probably remind me of Kansas State.
They are really a big-play team, which Kansas State was also. The
fact that they're so multidimensional is the big test for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska linebacker Jay Foreman, son of former Minnesota Vikings
great Chuck Foreman, isn't exactly impressed with San Diego's
weather. ``I thought it would be really hot, but it's actually been
pretty cold,'' Foreman said a few days after he left Lincoln, Neb.,
where it was minus-3 degrees. &QL;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
