<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FIESTA-TENN-WILSON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILSON FUELS VOLS  
 LEADER HAS LEARNED TO CHANNEL EMO TIONS  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Florida State Coach Bobby Bowden learned a lot about Tennessee's
defense after watching film of the Volunteers' Sept. 19 victory
over Florida.
</P>
<P>
   He saw big plays by Al Wilson, Al Wilson and, well, Al Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   The senior linebacker, who forced a school-record three fumbles
and had 12 tackles and a sack, was at the heart of Tennessee's
20-17 overtime win. Although the Seminoles also would beat Florida
down the road, Wilson's effort was memorable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very, very impressive,'' Bowden said.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden gets an up-close look at Wilson on Jan. 4, when Tennessee
and Florida State meet in the Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're here because of the team, not because of one
performance,'' Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   True, but the efforts of the 6-foot, 225-pound senior are a big
reason a defense that lost seven starters excelled this season.
</P>
<P>
   After Wilson's performance against Florida, Tennessee linebacker
Raynoch Thompson called it ``the greatest defensive game I've seen
since Warren Sapp in bowl games.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensive coordinator John Chavis said he doesn't know whether
he's ever coached anyone more competitive.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson earned first-team All-America honors despite missing
three games because of a shoulder injury. He was a Butkus Award
semifinalist and finished third on the team in tackles with 77. He
also had three double-digit tackle games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody on the team has respect for him because he plays the
game the way it should be played,'' linebacker Eric Westmoreland
said. ``Even with an injury, he doesn't want to come out. I
remember against Arkansas, he had a groin injury, but stayed in the
game and probably aggravated it even more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plus, he's always in the weight room.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson epitomizes what the Volunteers want from their defense: a
good decision-maker with an impressive combination of size and
speed. If he can get to the quarterback, he will.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson's biggest contribution, though, may be his leadership.
Some wondered where Tennessee would go in 1998 without former
quarterback Peyton Manning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was an important part of this team, but we knew early on
that other players would have to step up,'' Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee Coach Phillip Fulmer said Wilson ``has been a great
leader for this football team, especially for what we needed this
season.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as emotion . . . Al actually had to channel some of
that and mature because at times he was incredibly vocal and hard
on his teammates,'' Fulmer said. ``It was to the point he could,
instead of being a positive influence, he could be a negative
influence. He's been incredibly good this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Westmoreland said, ``He's such a high, emotional player. When he
comes on the field, everybody knows he's on the field. He's so
intense. And that brings out the intenseness on the whole defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the huddle, he's the same all year around, every day. He
likes to talk to us, get us going, and I think that's rubbed off on
me and other players. They're getting the attitude where they're
talking more also.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson would have been a high draft pick if he had made himself
eligible for the NFL after his junior season.
</P>
<P>
   As the Volunteers prepare for their national championship game,
they know just how fortunate they are. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-28-98 0117EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981228.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 01:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8012 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-FIESTA-VOLSFOES-A     12-28 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FIESTA-VOLS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEMINOLES NEED WAY TO STOP VOLS' MAGIC 
</HEADLINE>
 FOES-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   George DeLeone, the defensive coordinator and associate head
coach at Syracuse, admits he's not getting much sleep while
preparing for an Orange Bowl clash with Florida's nightmarish
offense.
</P>
<P>
   And since he's awake anyway, he often finds himself thinking
about a questionable pass-interference call made against his
defense late in the game that cost his Orangemen a chance to beat
Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fourth and 10,'' DeLeone said. ``And at home. How about that?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one that will haunt you for the rest of your career.''
</P>
<P>
   But having now seen the rest of the season unfold to find
top-ranked Tennessee in the Tostitos Fiesta Bowl against
second-rated Florida State, DeLeone figures Syracuse was just
another piece that fell into place along the Volunteers' way to
their date with destiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some intangibles on that team that go beyond the
talent level and the scheme,'' DeLeone said. ``The only way I can
describe it is that they're on a mission. They're feeling that they
can't be beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Syracuse isn't the only team that fell victim to Tennessee's
magic this season. The Vols needed four fumbles and overtime to
escape Florida. And only after Arkansas quarterback Clint
Stoerner's dumbfounding fumble with 1:43 to play did the Vols come
back to beat the Razorbacks, 28-24.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at our game, they were beat,'' DeLeone said. ``You
look at Florida, they were beat. You look at Arkansas, they were
beat. And they won all three of those games. I think that says it
all about this Tennessee team right there.''
</P>
<P>
   Beano Cook, a college football analyst for ESPN Radio, couldn't
agree more.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling is, Florida State is the better team,'' Cook said.
``But Tennessee will find a way to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've had all the breaks. They got a lucky call against
Syracuse on fourth down, or Syracuse would have gotten it.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm saying is, Florida State is ``supposed'' to win.
That's what the guys in Vegas say, and I believe those guys. They
live better than the rest of us. But I'm not saying that Florida
State is ``going'' to win.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, so forget for the moment that Tennessee is apparently
rolling loaded dice. How does a team go about beating the
Volunteers if all the planets are aligned favorably?
</P>
<P>
   DeLeone said it may be harder now than when Syracuse played the
Vols, because they've modified their offense to make it more suited
for Tee Martin than his predecessor, Peyton Manning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key now is to stop the run and keep Tee Martin from
beating you on naked bootlegs and passes out of the pocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``Martin is a better quarterback than people give him credit
for. He had to adjust his style, and they had to gear their offense
more to play action and the run game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other thing about them is they've got a bevy of wide
receivers. Peerless Price is going to go down with their great
ones, and when you start listing those guys, it's a pretty
impressive list.''
</P>
<P>
   DeLeone said linebacker Al Wilson is ``the spiritual leader'' of
the Volunteers, but he saved his strongest praise for the Tennessee
offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   ``That line has a lot to do with the chemistry and toughness
that define their football team,'' DeLeone said. ``They lost the
best quarterback in the country in Manning, and an NFL running back
in Jamal Lewis, and yet they've been just as productive.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, you've got to find a way to neutralize that offensive
line, and Florida State's defensive line is their strength. That's
going to be a great match-up to watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Second, you keep Martin in the pocket and make him beat you
from there. Then, gang up on the run and in some shape or another
change up your coverages to confuse their receivers, with added
attention to Peerless Price. &QL; 
``I mean, look at our game. Look at the Florida game. Florida
fumbled four times, three of them inside the 10. After that stuff
keeps happening, you've got to ask yourself: Is this divine
intervention? Or is it just a bunch of guys who refuse to lose?'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-28-98 0118EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981228.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 01:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8013 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-FIESTA-SEMINOLES &UR;      12-28 0529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FIESTA-SEMINOLES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLORIDA STATE'S SINGLE LOSS MEANINGLESS, ANALYSTS BE LIEVE 
</HEADLINE>
  FOES-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   All right, so there was a blip on the way to Tempe _ a 24-7 loss
to North Carolina State in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's like Pearl Harbor,'' ESPN college football analyst
Beano Cook said. ``You never forget it. But that's ancient
history.''
</P>
<P>
   This is Florida State at bowl time, winner of 10 in a row,
confident, poised and ready to take on No. 1 Tennessee (12-0) for
the national championship in the Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``The advantage goes to Florida State,'' ESPN analyst Lee Corso
said. ``They've been there, done that.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the third time in the 1990s that Florida State is in a
bowl game with national championship implications. It has won one,
beating Nebraska, 18-16, in the '94 Orange Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Corso admitted Tennessee has an edge at quarterback because of
the versatility of Tee Martin. His counterpart, Marcus Outzen, will
be making only his third career start for the Seminoles.
</P>
<P>
   But there is also the Bobby Bowden factor to consider, and
because of that, not many are willing to give a definite nod to
Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden is 15-3-1 in bowl games at Florida State. His 16 bowl
victories rank second behind Penn State's Joe Paterno, who has 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look over the 20th century, the greatest records are by
FDR, Paterno and Bowden,'' Cook said. ``They don't lose in November
or bowl games.''
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina State defensive coordinator Jeff Snipes said he
likes Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lucky day against those guys,'' Snipes said.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second game of the season. Florida State struggled to
beat Texas A&AMP;M, 23-14, the previous week. The Seminoles were on a
47-1 run against Atlantic Coast Conference competition, and North
Carolina State was never perceived as a threat.
</P>
<P>
   But quarterback Chris Weinke was picked off six times, and the
national championship game never looked so distant.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was (Weinke's) second start, and we did a good job that
day of confusing him,'' Snipes said. ``We were able to run a lot of
different coverages at them.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinke bounced back to have eight consecutive games without
throwing an interception before he suffered a season-ending neck
injury. But in Outzen's second start, the Seminoles beat Florida,
so the team's not lacking confidence in him.
</P>
<P>
   The Volunteers will try their best to confuse Outzen.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't matter,'' Snipes said. ``They have a lot of good
athletes down there. Even their third-team quarterback could start
for anyone in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not trying to take anything away from the job Weinke has
done. They have a great supporting cast.''
</P>
<P>
   Flanker Peter Warrick is one of the country's most dangerous
threats, and the Seminoles' defense forced 13 turnovers in their
last four games. But they'll be greatly challenged by Martin and
wide receiver Peerless Price.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone talks about their offense being powerful and putting
a lot of points on the board,'' Snipes said. ``But the defense also
is in the top 10 every year.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
