<HEADLINE>
INJURED VOLUNTEERS PLAN TO PLAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tennessee may see two of its injured starting defensive linemen
back for the Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteers Coach Phillip Fulmer said he is pleased with the
progress of tackle Jeff Coleman and end Corey Terry.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman suffered a knee sprain in Tennessee's 24-14 victory over
Mississippi State in the Southeastern Conference championship game.
Terry is nursing a pulled groin.
</P>
<P>
   Both are still being monitored. Fulmer was not ready to say how
much each would play and currently has Coleman listed on the depth
chart behind tackles Billy Ratliff and Ron Green.
</P>
<P>
   The Volunteers arrived in the Valley on Saturday night and began
workouts at Scottsdale Community College Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Both players participated in light workouts. &QL;  &QL; 
Underdog again
</P>
<P>
   Fulmer doesn't seem the least bit bothered by the decision of
most oddsmakers to make 11-1 Florida State a four-point favorite,
even though Tennessee is 12-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team has responded to those kinds of challenges, and I
would hope that they would respond again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteers quarterback Tee Martin believes his teammates aren't
caught up in the underdog issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why we're not favored,'' he said. ``People may
think that their defense is better than our defense, or their
offense has more big-play players than our offense has. We don't
focus on that. We look at this as the biggest game of our lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like everything about this rivalry. The sound of it. The
feel of it. Florida State comes in as a team that's well-respected
across the nation, and we come in as a team that gained respect as
the season went on. That's a good rivalry: a team that has the
respect and a team that has had to work for it.'' &QL;  &QL; 
Taking it slow &QL;  &QL; 
The Volunteers found the sunshine Sunday a welcome relief from
Knoxville, where temperatures have been in the 30s and 40s.
</P>
<P>
   Fulmer kept practice light and plans to begin heavy workouts
midweek to avoid peaking too early. &QL;  &QL; 
Quick hits &QL;  &QL; 
Tennessee and Florida State will be meeting for only the second
time in history. The Seminoles won the first, 10-0, in Knoxville in
1958.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State arrives today. &QL;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
