<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 01:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8018 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-JETS-BOS     12-28 1144
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-JETS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS SENT FLYING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Once again they were left answering the
same old question.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   Why were the Patriots flat? Why didn't they come to play Sunday?
Why do they have such peaks and valleys? Why couldn't they get up
for a game against Bill Parcells and the New York Jets, who swept
the season series with a 31-10 pummeling of the Patriots before a
sellout at the Meadowlands on a beautiful day?
</P>
<P>
   The horrific loss, which rivaled only the one Nov. 8 to the
Atlanta Falcons (41-10), cost the Patriots a home playoff game.
Instead of hosting Miami at Foxboro Stadium, they'll be heading to
Jacksonville to face the Jaguars, a team they've handled well over
the years.
</P>
<P>
   But with no momentum to speak of.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got our asses kicked all over the football field,'' said
receiver Shawn Jefferson. ``Those guys came to play. I have no idea
why we didn't. Teams that eventually go all the way are teams that
can avoid these dips. How we can play so well one week against the
49ers and come in here like this ... a game against a team in your
division ... I have no idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Pete Carroll, the players, the fans _ they all were at a
loss for an answer.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots, who finished the season with a 9-7 record and
placed fourth in the AFC East, entered the game with their usual
array of injuries, the defense minus outside linebacker Todd
Collins, lineman Chris Sullivan, and middle linebacker Ted Johnson,
and the offense without quarterback Drew Bledsoe and wide receiver
Terry Glenn.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Zolak started his second straight game and probably last
of the season, and from the outset it was apparent the Jets had his
number and this would not be another miracle game. The Jets put
Zolak in the position of having to play from behind, and his
options became few.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get down in a game early, there are only so many
things you practice other than taking your shots downfield,'' said
Zolak.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots never got pressure on Vinny Testaverde, who went 17
for 27 for 179 yards, with four touchdowns and one interception.
The defense allowed the Jets a whopping 13 of 19 (68 percent)
third-down conversions, which helped New York finish the year 12-4
and appear a lock to go far into the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a tough game for the Patriots today,'' said Parcells,
the former Patriots head man. ``But that's a good team, and we
might see them again.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. It depends on whether the Patriots who beat the Bills,
Dolphins, Steelers, and 49ers the last six games show up in
Jacksonville, or whether it's the team that played the Rams and
Jets.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game is gone,'' said Jefferson, who caught one of the two
passes completed to wide receivers by Zolak. The other was a
44-yard touchdown pass to rookie Tony Simmons during garbage time
in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to put this one out of our heads right now because any
lingering effects of this could be deadly,'' said Jefferson. ``For
whatever reason we didn't come to play. Hey, no sense analyzing it
to death. Just move on and know in our hearts that we are a good
team and that we can come back and play well and beat
playoff-caliber teams.''
</P>
<P>
   On a 36-degree day with minimal wind and the sun shining, the
Jets won the toss, received, and scored. They marched from their 10
to the Patriots' 18, with Curtis Martin, who gained 102 yards on 29
carries, making runs of 8 and 17 yards. The Patriots did limit New
York to a 36-yard John Hall field goal.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets got the ball at their 46 after the Patriots were forced
to punt following an intentional grounding penalty on Zolak. They
used the running game again, but on third and 5 from the 14,
Testaverde found Wayne Chrebet for an 8-yard gain. Two plays later,
the Patriots left tight end Kyle Brady wide open for a 4-yard
touchdown pass, his fifth score of the year, three of them against
the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   By early in the second quarter it was 17-0. That came as a
result of a rare fumble by running back Robert Edwards, who coughed
up the ball for the first time in 15 games after being hit by left
tackle Jason Ferguson. The ball was recovered by Ray Mickens at the
Patriots' 33.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just dropped the ball,'' said Edwards, who was tackled
around the ankles by Ferguson. ``Nobody hit me. That was a surprise
to me too. That's something I have to work on.''
</P>
<P>
   The only glimmer of hope before the half came following that
score when, with 8:56 left, the Patriots started at the 28 and went
on a methodically effective drive that featured an 18-yard run by
Edwards (on which he fumbled but recovered). Zolak even connected
with Derrick Cullors on a third-and-5 for a 15-yard gain to the
Jets' 25.
</P>
<P>
   Desperately needing 6 points, Zolak hit Ben Coates for an
18-yard gain to the 7. But the Patriots could do very little,
getting it down to the 2 on a 7-yard pass to Edwards on third and
goal from the 9. New England was forced to settle for a 19-yard
Adam Vinatieri field goal, making it 17-3 with 3:26 remaining in
the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots got the ball back with 2:19 remaining in the half,
but a strong opportunity to get back in the game went up in smoke,
starting with a sack for an 8-yard loss by the Jets' Anthony
Pleasant after New England had converted a third-and-6 play to
their 35.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to block, run, and tackle well to win a game like this
and we didn't do any of it,'' said Carroll. ``We couldn't stop
their running game and we couldn't put the pressure we needed on
their passer to get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots went three and out on their opening possession of
the second half and the Jets went 60 yards for a score to make the
outcome all but official.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots left receivers open, but was it the lack of pass
rush that caused this?
</P>
<P>
   ``From my point of view we didn't rush the passer like we should
have,'' said defensive line coach Ray Hamilton. ``Ron (Lynn,
defensive backs coach) might say his guys didn't cover as well as
they should have.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots did have defensive end Willie McGinest back, and he
made it through his limited time without reinjuring the groin that
has kept him out of seven games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just came out flat,'' said McGinest. ``They jumped on us
right away. If anything, I hope this game boosts us. This will show
us that we just can't show up. We have to play hard and take it to
them like they took it to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Veteran defensive tackle Henry Thomas, who reinjured his right
ankle during the game but is expected to play Sunday, said, ``I
don't have too much to say right now. I don't want to say anything
because I get the feeling we'll be seeing these guys again.''
</P>
<P>
   And after that game, will they be searching for answers again?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-28-98 0131EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
