</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SHAUGHNESSY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS HEADING WRONG WAY WITHOUT PARCELLS 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Hmmmm. How does one write about the
plight of your local football team without the appearance of piling
on?
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's 31-10 debacle (oh, if it were only as close as the
score sounds) against the hated Jets is only the latest piece of
evidence that the Patriots are going the wrong way. And since we
New Englanders are into blame, let's remind you again that the
blame for what is happening to your football team lies at the feet
of the owner you once loved.
</P>
<P>
   It's amazing how Bob Kraft has escaped the wrath of Patriot
Nation. John Harrington gets the bleep kicked out of him for losing
Roger Clemens and Mo Vaughn. Just as Haywood Sullivan was harpooned
for losing Carlton Fisk, and Harry Frazee earned infamy for selling
Babe Ruth.
</P>
<P>
   And yet Kraft is somehow not held accountable for screwing up
his football team _ a team he plans to move to Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft torpedoed the Patriots when he overruled Bill Parcells on
draft day 1996. The big double cross, of which too much already has
been written, set the wheels in motion for Parcells's exit from New
England. And then Kraft put out the spin that Bully Bill was
leaving anyway. He just didn't want to be here.
</P>
<P>
   No. Parcells would have stayed if Kraft would have stayed out of
the way. The Patriots had a rare window of opportunity: They had a
young Super Bowl team on the rise. Parcells would have stayed for
that. But he couldn't live with a double-dealing owner who wanted
to be the star of his team. And now Kraft is the star of a team
that has gone from 11 ... to 10 ... to nine wins since Parcells
left.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's game only compounds the embarrassment. The 1996 Super
Bowl Patriots are now a shell of what Parcells left behind. And the
1996 1-15 Jets have become AFC East champs with a 12-4 rec-ord.
Since Tuna left New England, the Patriots are 19-13, the Jets
21-11. And the disparity on display Sunday bordered on abject
humiliation.
</P>
<P>
   It's not about injuries anymore. And it's not about ``making
plays'' or ``finding ourselves.'' It's about an owner who had our
greatest local coach since Red Auerbach and ran him out of town
because he wanted to play Strat-o-matic football (The Patriots
press guide claims that ``while attending Columbia, (Kraft) also
played `scatback' for the Lions'' _ which must have happened while
Tim Johnson was up to his knees in rice paddies back in 'Nam).
</P>
<P>
   Kraft's defenders, of which there are many (he did, after all,
save the team from going to St. Louis and poured a lot of money
into player payroll) tell us to just ``get over it.'' Bill is gone
and that is that.
</P>
<P>
   Fine. But how are we supposed to ``get over it'' when Kraft and
his team can't ``get over it''? The owner is still obsessed with
the Tuna. Why else would he call for a tampering probe after an
innocuous phone call between Parcells and Drew Bledsoe?
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Pete Carroll can't get over it. Earlier this year, in a
telling moment of candor when he didn't expect to be quoted,
Carroll said that everything Parcells says is a ``crock.''
Carroll's got to be furious about the unfair comparisons (hey, it's
not Pete's fault that he's no Parcells, Phil Bengtson had to follow
Vince Lombardi in Green Bay).
</P>
<P>
   The Patriot players can't get over it. They keep getting humbled
by the Jets. It's now, 3-1, Jets, since the Tuna bolted for the
Swamps of New Jersey, but if not for a blocked field goal from 29
yards, it would be 4-0. The margins are widening. And most football
experts believe the Patriots have better overall talent.
</P>
<P>
   There is no way to overstate the magnitude of Sunday's
butt-whipping. Take a look at time of possession _ 38:51 for the
Jets to 21:09 for the Patriots. New England couldn't manage a first
down until it was 17-0 with seven minutes left in the first half.
It was so bad that Jet fans actually left early and New England's
only touchdown was a Dominique Wilkins-meaningless, garbage-time
score with a minute remaining.
</P>
<P>
   After the loss, Poor Daddy Pete looked like Charlie McCarthy
without Edgar Bergen. What could he say? Hey, we all know it's
tough going to battle without Ted Johnson, Bledsoe, and Terry
Glenn, but this was pathetic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we have to find out what we're all about again,'' he said.
``We didn't play well. And it looks like there's no energy, no
excitement about your game when you can't stop them. We have to put
a club together that can play playoff-caliber football.''
</P>
<P>
   It was certainly not the muscle-flexing Pete we saw last week
after the Patriots took advantage of a San Francisco team that
forgot to show up in Foxborough.
</P>
<P>
   Players know. The Jet room is littered with ex-Patriots who
moved to Jersey. Many are still friends with Patriot players. They
talk. They can see what has happened but have to be careful what
they say in public.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the ``scatback'' owner, once more ubiquitous and
quoteworthy than Marty Meehan, doesn't say much about his team or
his coach anymore. But this has got to be killing him. The Patriots
are going the wrong way because Bob Kraft couldn't live with the
greatest NFL coach of this generation. The Jets have become what
the Patriots could have been, and New England Patriots fans are the
losers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-28-98 0132EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981228.0026 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 01:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8022 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS     12-28 1116
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THINGS UP IN AIR WITH CARROLL AT CONTROLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ All week Pete Carroll closed his
practice sessions from the prying media's eyes. Sunday you had to
wonder what the hell he was doing behind those closed doors,
spiking their eggnog?
</P>
<P>
   Carroll led his New England Patriots into Giants Stadium Sunday
intent on making a statement about his team and himself. This
morning he has to hope they didn't make one because his
playoff-bound Patriots were destroyed by the New York Parcellses,
31-10, in a game that was far worse than that terrible score would
indicate.
</P>
<P>
   This holiday season the Ghost of Coaches Past continued to haunt
Carroll and the Patriots because once again Parcells and his staff
not only beat them but slapped them silly. Parcells's team
outplayed Carroll's and he outcoached his counterpart and this
time, not even Carroll's players would argue otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill had them ready to go,'' said linebacker Chris Slade.
``The funny thing is, they had nothing to play for, but they came
out ready and we didn't. We got outplayed and outcoached.''
</P>
<P>
   The most alarming proof of the latter was that at the two times
his team should have been most prepared to meet Parcells's
challenge _ at the start of the game and at the opening of the
second half _ it played its worst. In both instances his offense
did nothing and his defense was routed, so whatever plan he
concocted behind those closed doors was utterly bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
   In the first quarter, the Jets scored on consecutive drives
while controlling the ball for more than 17 minutes (the second
drive dragging on into the second quarter). New England answered
with three plays that netted it 3 yards of offense.
</P>
<P>
   When the third quarter dawned, the same thing happened. The Jets
scored on back-to-back drives while the Patriots' offense produced
7 yards of offense.
</P>
<P>
   Who should get the blame for this? The planner, or the ones who
execute the plan? Both, is probably the right answer, but a week
ago, after a victory over the 49ers, the chief planner made a point
of arguing that ``there's more than one way to do this.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps so, but the early returns are in and they indicate maybe
there is only one way to do this because Sunday Carroll's way led
New England to a dismal 31-10 defeat against a guy who does it the
other way.
</P>
<P>
   The other way, of course, is Parcells's way, and thus far it has
accomplished the following over the past two years. Parcells
inherited a team that was 1-15 before he got to New York and it has
gone 21-11 since his arrival. Carroll inherited Parcells's AFC
champions, changed the way things were done and many of the people
who were doing them, and after a 4-0 start against arguably four of
the worst teams in football last season, he has gone 15-13 with
that team.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the Patriots have had serious injuries that have
affected their season. What they have not had is serious injuries
every week for the past 28 weeks, yet they are barely a .500 club
over that nearly-two-year stretch. And when it comes to going
head-to-head against Parcells, it has been even worse.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll is 1-3 against Parcells but should be 0-4, having won
their first meeting in overtime when a chip-shot 29-yard field goal
for a Jet win was blocked at the end of regulation. Each meeting
has been slightly worse and in none of them has Parcells's team
scored fewer than 24 points. If there is a silver lining to this, I
missed it and so have most of Carroll's charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want this to be a rivalry,'' safety Lawyer Milloy said.
``But game in and game out we play like we do against them. That's
not a rivalry. I don't care what anyone says.''
</P>
<P>
   By game's end, the Jets had controlled the ball for nearly 39
minutes, had converted 68 percent of their third-down situations,
and amassed nearly 100 yards more of total offense. In addition,
were it not for a garbage time touchdown pass to Tony Simmons,
backup quarterback Scott Zolak would have completed only one pass
to a wide receiver all day in a game in which his team was trailing
by 28 points for too much of the time.
</P>
<P>
   How that is possible is difficult to understand but that's true
of about everything that went on Sunday, as even Carroll conceded.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came into this game, in our approach, that this was a
playoff atmosphere, a playoff mentality, and we were nowhere near
that,'' he said. ``Our level of play, our inability to stop them on
defense, and our inability to make a first down. We couldn't do
anything today.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got what they wanted to get done today and we didn't get
anything done. We really accomplished nothing. There was nothing
that was redeemable today.''
</P>
<P>
   The same was true two weeks ago in St. Louis. The same was true
earlier in the year against Atlanta. The same has been true in too
many of their meetings with Parcells. As Shawn Jefferson said
Sunday, ``Good teams don't have all these ups and downs.''
</P>
<P>
   No they don't. So what are the Patriots as they enter the
playoffs Sunday against Jacksonville? That is anybody's guess, but
safety Willie Clay understood yesterday that whatever they are is
not what they should be.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been the same crap for two years,'' Clay said. ``I'm
shocked and embarrassed that we came down here and played like
this. I don't care who's playing in the game. They dictated
everything to us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, there's a problem. The last two games on the road
have been pathetic and embarrassing. I don't see anything positive
coming out of this. You don't profit when you lose a game like
this.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been a resilient team but we make it real hard on
ourselves. We make it tough. This is supposed to be like a college
rivalry and to come in here and get dismantled is embarrassing.''
</P>
<P>
   If that is all it is, Pete Carroll's ways may yet triumph. But
there are whispers now inside his locker room and there are doubts.
More and more, as Parcells's mastery over his former team
continues, questions are asked and criticisms of the regime are
whispered in dark corners.
</P>
<P>
   There has been doubt about how things are being done for quite
some time now on Pete Carroll's team, whether he understands it or
not. The doubters are not just external. They are internal, as
well, and there are far more of them than he thinks.
</P>
<P>
   What happened Sunday only fuels that doubt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see a transformation from my rookie year here,'' Milloy
said. ``I see what we had over there (with the Jets) now. We're
struggling now just to stay alive. It shouldn't be like that.''
</P>
<P>
   No, it shouldn't.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-28-98 0138EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
