<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 01:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8032 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-DOLPHINS-     12-28 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-DOLPHINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOLPHINS' HEARTS WERE NOT IN IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Miami Dolphins need not worry about the Patriots
this week. They have a more difficult task at hand and it has
nothing to do with Buffalo and everything to do with themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins were slaughtered Sunday by the
better-than-you-think Atlanta Falcons, 38-16. It was over in the
first eight minutes, by which time the Falcons had a 21-0 lead.
Atlanta running back Jamal Anderson set a slew of records, the
defense forced six turnovers, and the Dolphins went back home with
plenty of work to do.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Jimmy Johnson, the Miami coach, was asked if he
thought there was still hope in the second quarter when Miami,
trailing, 21-0, had a couple of offensive spurts and managed to get
within 21-6.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' the coach said.
</P>
<P>
   He then said, ``Once it got out of hand, I don't think we played
real hard.''
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, valuable defensive end Jason Taylor broke
his collarbone in the first quarter and is out for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the shellacking, the Dolphins still managed to land a
home game next weekend in the playoffs. That happened because the
Patriots were similarly mauled and because Miami has the edge in
the fifth tie-breaker against Buffalo. According to NFL rules, the
team which has either the best differential against division
opponents or the coach who looks less like Newt Gingrich gets the
home field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't matter,'' sniffed Johnson, ``because if we don't play
a heckuva lot better, we'll be embarrassed again. I'm upset with
myself, with the team, with everything.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not the way you want to enter the postseason and Miami,
which six days before had looked terrific against Denver, was
alternately hapless and hopeless. The final stats were utterly
meaningless. The Dolphins managed more first downs, more total
yards, and had the edge in time of possession.
</P>
<P>
   And they were never in the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons got an unexpected boost before the game, when
convalescing coach Dan Reeves, who just had bypass surgery, stopped
by the locker room for a 2-3 minute chat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a pleasant surprise to see him,'' said quarterback
Chris Chandler, who was lifted early after a back injury. ``Maybe
that's why we started the way we did.''
</P>
<P>
   First play from scrimmage: Chandler fakes to Anderson, who draws
everyone from Fulton County. Chandler rolls right, hits O.J.
Santiago, and the big tight end rambles 62 yards for a touchdown.
Twenty-four seconds had elapsed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got fooled early,'' said Miami linebacker Zach Thomas. ``We
paid too much respect to Jamal. We wanted to shut him down early.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Falcons' next possession, it took them a director's-cut
four plays to score. Chandler and Tony Martin combined for a
53-yard completion and then the quarterback and Santiago
collaborated on a 3-yard TD. The game was not even four minutes
old.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler was hurt on the play, however. Kenny Mixon hauled him
down awkwardly resulting in a back strain for the quarterback.
Chandler did not return _ his 3-for-3 for 118 yards should upgrade
his rating _ but is expected to be fine.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons then basically won the game after a switch of
possessions. Dan Marino, hurried and harried all day, threw a ball
into the flat that had Joe Kapp written all over it. Ronnie
Bradford picked it off, returned it 11 yards for a TD, and the
score was 21-0 with eight minutes gone. Miami still had not managed
a first down.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really tough, because we did not challenge them at all,''
said Marino, who was 21 of 36 with one TD and two interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   It was 24-6 at the half and Atlanta then put the hammer down in
the third. Recreating their opening scene, the Falcons scored on
their first play, this time a 35-yard pass from Steve DeBerg to
Martin. That followed a Miami fumble. Less than two minutes later,
Anderson rambled 36 yards for a TD after another Miami fumble. Two
plays. Two TDs.
</P>
<P>
   The redoubtable Anderson finished with 103 yards on 18 carries.
He set an NFL record for most carries in a season (410), led the
NFL with most 100-yard games (12), and set club records for rushing
yards (1,846), touchdowns (16), rushing touchdowns (14), and most
consecutive 100-yard games (five).
</P>
<P>
   These guys are good. The Dolphins found that out for themselves
Sunday, and someone else may well get the same awakening two weeks
from now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
