<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 01:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8033 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-MCDONOUGHCOLUMN-B     12-28 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS' DEFENSE REALLY TAKES TO ITS TASK 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL McDONOUGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ This was pro football's version of total
disarmament. The Jets Sunday took away every weapon the Patriots
had.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to take away their run first,'' said veteran New
York linebacker Mo Lewis, ``and if we could do that, we didn't
think they could move the ball on us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets spent the day taking the ball away from the Patriots
with ease, handing it over to their offense, which moved with ease.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stopping the run and making them throw precision passes was
what we hoped to do, and our players did a good job of that,'' said
Jets linebackers coach Al Groh.
</P>
<P>
   Patriots quarterback Scott Zolak didn't have a chance Sunday
because the Jets defensive coaching staff knew what his strengths,
and weaknesses, were.
</P>
<P>
   They took away two things he likes to do, the deep ball to the
outside and the short crossing pattern to the tight end.
</P>
<P>
   Their feeling was if Zolak could beat them with sideline throws
and slant patterns, good luck to him. But the Jets coaches knew
those patterns are not what Zolak does best.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' offense had three plays in the first quarter, when
the Jets controlled the ball for 13 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   In the third quarter it was just as bad for New England. Twice
they had the ball, and twice they couldn't get a first down.
</P>
<P>
   Leading, 17-3, at the half, the Jets scored on a 17-yard pass to
Dedric Ward in the third quarter, then put together a drive of 8:49
at the end of the third and into the fourth that produced a 24-yard
touchdown to Keyshawn Johnson and put the game out of reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``The running game set up our offense,'' said Jets quarterback
Vinny Testaverde. ``A lot of the passes that went well for us came
off play-action. We had a good rhythm going on offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Said backup quarterback Glenn Foley from the next locker, ``Our
offense right now is as good as any in the league. We have so many
ways to go with the ball, and our offensive line's pass protection
has been great. I don't know when the last time we gave up a sack
was.'' The line has given up one sack in five games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their defense was different than the last time we played
them,'' said Testaverde, who clearly was cutting the Patriots some
slack. ``They've got the two linebackers (Ted Johnson and Todd
Collins) out, and some other guys are hurt. I think this helped our
running game.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Martin, who generally plays better as the game goes
along, had 51 yards rushing in the first quarter, giving some
balance to the New York attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like they slid their coverage toward me more this
game than they did in the first one,'' said Johnson, who is as good
as any wide receiver in the game right now. Johnson had another big
game, making drive-sustaining catches, and helping big-time on the
touchdown catches by teammates Kyle Brady and Martin.
</P>
<P>
   ``On both of those,'' said Johnson, ``they slid the coverage
toward me. I told some of them (defenders) to `keep it up. I enjoy
it. I'm happy that you're spending so much time with me and leaving
the other guys open.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets dominated, driving the ball comfortably for long
periods of time with their effective short-passing game. They were
an incredible 13 for 19 on third-down plays.
</P>
<P>
   They stuffed the Patriot offense by jumping on the pass patterns
that Zolak has had the most luck with.
</P>
<P>
   Twice Robert Edwards made decent runs, and both of them came
after he was stopped at the line of scrimmage and bounced outside.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets, spurred on by a huge crowd on a beautiful day, played
with a sense of purpose, closing the regular season by winning 12
of their last 14 games.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots played like a beaten team. They gained 249 yards on
52 plays, and they got 71 on a run by Sedrick Shaw and 44 on a
touchdown pass from Zolak to Tony Simmons in the final minute for
115 of those yards. That means they gained just 134 yards on the
other 50 plays.
</P>
<P>
   The most chilling quote came from a member of the Jets who was
formerly a Patriot:
</P>
<P>
   ``They said when we left there they wanted a team like San
Francisco. They got it. San Francisco quit last week. They quit
this week.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
