<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981228.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 01:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8040 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-RYANCOLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-28 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RYAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINGING PRAISES OF THE TUNA 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Tuna, I've Just Met A Coach Named The Tuna
</P>
<P>
   And Suddenly I've Found How Wonderful The Game Can Be
</P>
<P>
   The Tuna, I Play For A Coach Named The Tuna
</P>
<P>
   Whatever He Says Goes; The Super Bowl Belongs To Me
</P>
<P>
   The Tuna: Say It Loud, It's A Donkey Braying
</P>
<P>
   Say It Soft And It's Leon Hess Praying
</P>
<P>
   The Tuna, I'll Never Stop Praising The Tuna!
</P>
<P>
   (With apologies to Stephen Sondheim)
</P>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ What a wonderful thing it is to be a New
York Jet.
</P>
<P>
   It's a fine thing if you're Curtis Martin, who just became one
this year, and it's infinitely better if you're linebacker Mo
Lewis, who is one of 17 players knowing the pain of being a 1-15
Jet under the hapless Rich Kotite two years ago and who is the only
member of the team who ever has participated in a playoff game
while wearing the green and white of the Fabulous Exit 16W Jets.
</P>
<P>
   That was seven years ago, when Mo was a rookie on a team that
got into the playoffs the last day of the season and that didn't
know its metaphorical you-know-what from its metaphorical elbow.
``In '91, it was, like, `Let's just get to the playoffs,'''
recalled Lewis. ``We went to Houston not prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   And lost _ naturally.
</P>
<P>
   Thus began the slow descent into football Hades. The Jets went
from bad to worse to something infinitely more undignified _
laughable. ``Around here,'' said one veteran observer of the Exit
16W pigskin scene, ``J-E-T-S used to stand for Just End The
Season.''
</P>
<P>
   And right now it stands for a potential Denver nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team,'' said Lewis, ``has everything to gain.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets aren't a team, they're a revival meeting. The Rev. Bill
Parcells has set up his tent here in the Meadowlands. He has 53
guys with the thick necks and the sleek calves hanging on every
word. First he gave them credibility. Then he gave them
respectability. Now he's got them thinking they can win _ win it
all _ but only, of course, if they do exactly what he tells them.
</P>
<P>
   The Exit 16W Jets are not the most talented team in the AFC.
They may not even be the most talented team in the division. But
who can argue that at this point in time they aren't a Super Bowl
threat because they are a frightening team, spelled T-E-A-M?
</P>
<P>
   ``With Bill Parcells, I've learned you don't have to have the
best players at every position,'' pointed out Martin, who gained
102 yards during Sunday's pathetically easy 31-10 Jets victory.
``It's the way he gets you to play as a unit. That's where the
power is. He has a way of bringing out the best in every player.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing I understand now more than in past seasons,''
explained 12-year veteran Vinny Testaverde, ``is that in order to
win you've got to have an entire football team. It's not just
offense or defense. It's offense, defense, and special teams.
That's what we've got here.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's game told the world all it really needs to know about
the 1998 Exit 16W Jets. It is an NFL betting axiom that in games
played late in the season, and assuming the teams are supposed to
be somewhat comparable in talent, the edge should go to the team
that needs the game more. In this matchup the Patriots, with a
chance to grab a home playoff game, had a great deal at stake. The
Jets were playing to become the first team in franchise history to
win 12 games. That's nice, but, well, c'mon, it just doesn't
compare as a motivation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows how much he's changed things around,'' said Keyshawn
Johnson, the cocky and very talented wide receiver. ``He had us
believing the game mattered. In the past you might have thought we
had nothing to play for, but here we are, 4-0 in the month of
December.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is not easily impressed. But when the subject is Bill
Parcells, his admiration is boundless. He is, after all, one of
those 1-15 survivors.
</P>
<P>
   ``1-15 to 12-4,'' he said. ``In two years? It's ridiculous. It's
crazy. You step back and say, `Damn, what kind of coach is this?
Teams just don't do that. Something is significant about the guy
who is guiding us in that direction.''
</P>
<P>
   The guy in question was in a happy mood after watching his team
embarrass a Patriots squad that looked like a last-second
substitution provided by the Hockomock League in lieu of a
legitimate NFL team. ``The only thing I can tell you is that we've
buried all the ghosts,'' Parcells said. ``All the ghosts are buried
now. If you dig 'em up, it's because you want to dig 'em up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets' follies are complete ancient history. They stopped
being a farce the day Parcells walked in and let them know that
this was the First Day of the Rest of Their Lives. He let them know
what was tolerable and what wasn't. He gave them a sense of
direction. Now that direction heads toward Miami Jan. 31. The Jets
aren't entering what The Tuna once again referred to as ``the
tournament'' just for the benefit of a resume.
</P>
<P>
   The Tuna is in this to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got more things to do,'' he said. ``But I look forward
to it. This is the fun part of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our job is to keep our focus,'' said Martin, ``but that won't
be hard because Coach Parcells has been there before. He knows
exactly how to get us ready.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets might lose, but it won't be because of lack of proper
preparation. Faith in the leader is no issue here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said it before,'' explained Testaverde. ``The best
decision I've made all year was to come to the Jets and play for
Bill Parcells.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I'm concerned,'' said Martin, ``Coach Parcells is
the best coach ever to coach anything.''
</P>
<P>
   1-15 to 12-4 in two years? Martin might have a point.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-28-98 0142EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
