A8051 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-DEFENSE-     12-28 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-DEFENSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO STOPPING THE JETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ By the second quarter, this game had all
the energy of a baseball exhibition, the drama and the suspense
already long gone with one team, the Jets, so dominant and the
other, the Patriots, so abject.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of respect for the Jets,'' Patriots safety
Lawyer Milloy would say long afterward, when asked why and how such
a trouncing could occur, ``but I think we have too much respect for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   How?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're always too conservative against them,'' Milloy went on.
``They always have something for us, and whatever we do they seem
to always counter it. But we never seem to do things correctly. And
that's everybody, players, coaches, and everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots could do nothing Sunday _ block, tackle, pass, run,
defend, pressure or, yes, even guess. The Parcells Effect on the
Patriots now seems so pronounced that even when New England tried
to blitz Jets quarterback Vinny Testaverde ``every time we went out
there (on a blitz), they either ran the ball the other way or they
got completions on their downs,'' said Milloy.
</P>
<P>
   A knife doesn't move through butter any easier than the Jets'
offense moved through the New England defense. Patriot fans can
talk about Drew Bledsoe all they wish, and what might happen if he
plays Sunday in Jacksonville, but Bledsoe may make little
difference if the defense plays as horribly as it played two weeks
ago in St. Louis or as poorly as it did Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came into this game, in our approach, that this was a
playoff atmosphere, a playoff mentality,'' said a shocked Pete
Carroll, the Patriots' coach, ``and this was nowhere near it. We
couldn't do anything. We really accomplished nothing. There was
nothing that was redeemable.''
</P>
<P>
   Milloy cast a cold eye on the wreckage and said all the talk
about New England and the Jets being a ``rivalry'' is ridiculous.
``You want it to be a rivalry, but game in and game out we play the
way we play against them, it's not a rivalry,'' said Milloy. ``I
don't care what anybody says.''
</P>
<P>
   The pattern of the game developed immediately. The Patriot
defense could not stop the Jets' offense and then the Patriot
offense would put in a cameo appearance, doing nothing, and the
defense again was led out onto the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of the game,'' said New England wide receiver Shawn
Jefferson. ``You know the offense feeds off the defense and the
defense feeds off the offense, but none of us did nothing. No one
fed off anybody ... it was evident.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a sad commentary on the Patriot defense that one of its
best plays of the game _ stopping Testaverde on a third-and-10 on
the Jets' first drive of the game _ came when it had only 10
players on the field. When the Patriots tried the regulation
allotment of players, the Jets and Testaverde made 13 of 18
third-down opportunities, the Achilles' heel of the New England
defense all season.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots tried to blitz Testaverde, said defensive
coordinator Steve Sidwell, ``but basically what happened was when
we tried that in some situations they picked it up. They did a good
job on that.''
</P>
<P>
   What a defense wants to do, Sidwell went on, ``is that you want
to get to third downs, so you have a chance to make a play, but we
didn't get it done. Obviously, we need to be better there.''
</P>
<P>
   Sidwell said the defense was off-balance. ``Because of their
passing game, we tried to play some pass defense on early downs,''
he said, ``and obviously that didn't work out because they ran the
ball a lot and had some success on us. We changed our defense so we
did better against the run, but we still never solved it
completely.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets must be given credit for their offense, especially its
balance, ``but we were always off guard,'' said Sidwell. ``When we
tried to pressure them, it really ended up hurting us. They were
picking it up and we also had some opportunities to make some
plays, and we didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   In short, Sidwell said, ``This wasn't our finest hour.'' Not
good, especially when the football hours now are very short.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-28-98 0144EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
