<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BLEDSOE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLEDSOE WILL TRY TO PLAY SUNDAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ If physically possible, Drew Bledsoe
will play in Sunday's wild-card playoff game against the
Jacksonville Jaguars at Alltel Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe, the emergency quarterback in Sunday's 31-10 blowout at
the hands of the New York Jets, will have his broken right index
finger examined Wednesday by a team of doctors at Massachusetts
General Hospital. Every attempt will be made to have Bledsoe fitted
for a splint that will hold the pin in his finger in place well
enough for him to play, according to team sources.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe watched as Scott Zolak went 14 for 31 for 127 yards and
one touchdown, a 44-yard bomb to Tony Simmons near the end of the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe huddled with owner Bob Kraft and team officials before
the game to talk about his situation.
</P>
<P>
   He is expected to test the finger early this week, get fitted
for a splint, and then attempt a return against the Jaguars.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Pete Carroll, asked at his postgame news conference about
the possibility of Bledsoe's return, said, ``There's a chance he'll
play, but we have to find out what Drew's status is early this
week.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots had hoped that Bledsoe would be ready for Sunday's
game, but once the team beat the 49ers to gain entry into the
playoffs, it opted not to use him.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe has had several X-rays of the finger, and he indicated
late last week that it was showing signs of healing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-28-98 0145EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
