<DOCNO> NYT19981228.0044 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 01:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8054 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BILLS-SAINTS-BOS &LR;      12-28 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BILLS-SAINTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILLS TUNE UP IN NEW ORLEANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Any of the 39,707 fans showing up at the Superdome
Sunday expecting to see Doug Flutie play quarterback for the
Buffalo Bills against the New Orleans Saints were disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   With a playoff spot secure, Bills coach Wade Phillips took the
safe way out and rested Flutie, who was nursing a sore leg, and
went back to Rob Johnson, who began the season as the starter
before being sidelined with a rib injury that allowed Flutie to
finally become an NFL star.
</P>
<P>
   But more about that later.
</P>
<P>
   Any fans who showed up at the Superdome Sunday expecting to see
the Saints perform well also were disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   With nothing at stake in a truly meaningless last game of the
regular season, the Saints also took most of the day off,
figuratively and at times literally, as they fell behind, 28-0, in
the first half before showing some signs of life in the final
quarter in what turned into a 45-33 defeat.
</P>
<P>
   For the Bills, Sunday was merely a tuneup for this weekend's
wild-card game in the AFC playoffs. The only question the Bills
wanted answered entering the game was who they were going to play.
</P>
<P>
   The win over the Saints, combined with losses by the Patriots
and Dolphins, means the Bills have a Saturday showdown in Miami
against the Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   They will face the Dolphins knowing that Johnson, who had not
played since suffering an injury against Indianapolis Oct. 11, can
step back into his starting role if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``After not playing for 12 weeks, it felt good to finally go out
and get some reps,'' said Johnson, who became the starter Wednesday
when Phillips told Flutie he would be sitting out this final dance
of the regular season. ``I felt a little rusty at first, but things
started to come along.''
</P>
<P>
   So they did. Johnson, who was the designated quarterback of the
future for the Bills after signing a five-year, $25 million
contract in the spring, completed 12 of 18 passes for 216 yards and
three touchdowns in guiding the Bills to that 28-0 lead three
minutes into the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But Phillips, who received the game ball Sunday after guiding
the Bills from an 0-3 start to a 10-6 season, was more interested
in who didn't play than who did.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Bills knew their playoff fate before the game _ either
a trip to Jacksonville or Miami _ Phillips felt no need to use his
regulars.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told me on Wednesday to take a rest this week,'' said
Flutie, who suffered a leg bruise in last week's loss to the Jets.
``That was tough for me to take. I always want to play. But I
understand why he did it.''
</P>
<P>
   With Flutie out and Phillips going deep into his depth chart on
defense, the Saints came marching back into the game behind the
power of backup quarterback Billy Joe Tolliver.
</P>
<P>
   After starter Kerry Collins was pulled by Saints coach Mike
Ditka following a horrendous (3 of 12 for 23 yards, 1 fumble)
effort, Tolliver fired away for the remainder of what turned into a
3-hour-24-minute marathon.
</P>
<P>
   Tolliver completed 23 of 41 passes for 296 yards and three
touchdowns and added a touch of suspense to the proceedings when he
led the Saints to two touchdowns in the final two minutes, aided by
consecutive onside kick recoveries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to play everybody,'' said Phillips. ``I wanted Rob
to get a chance and he did and he had a good game.''
</P>
<P>
   So did most of the Bills _ at least offensively.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's time to move on. ``We're down to 12 teams now,'' said
Flutie, making it clear he can't wait to head to Miami. ``And
there's not one team out there that we can't go out and beat.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
