<SLUG> BC-BKC-PROVIDENCE-PURDUE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROVIDENCE STUNS PURDUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE _ Coming off 16 days off after two straight losses,
Providence Sunday entered its biggest game of the season, taking on
No. 9 Purdue, the team expected to win the Big 10 championship.
</P>
<P>
   So what did the Friars do? Pull off a major upset, taking an
87-82 win before 11,288 at the Civic Center.
</P>
<P>
   Providence caused 27 turnovers, 18 in the first half, and the
Friars attempted 18 more field goals (74-56). Purdue (12-2), which
had an eight-game winning streak halted, made 57.1 percent of its
shots and won the rebounding battle, 43-25. But it couldn't hold on
to the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Providence, which is 7-4 under first-year coach Tim Welsh, was
ahead at every point but two, at 55-54 on a Brian Cardinal jumper
off the wing with 15:50 left, and at 59-58, with Tony Mayfield
connecting on a jumper in the paint with 13:45 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   The Friars got 22 points from Jamel Thomas, with Erron Maxey
tossing in 15 and Kendrick Moore 14. Purdue also had three scorers
in double figures, led by Greg McQuay's 23.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their quickness was a big factor, they really got to us,''
said Purdue coach Gene Keady. ``That was the difference in the
game. We were tentative against the press, we didn't attack it, we
didn't take it baseline-to-baseline and score. That's what we want
to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``We preach it, we work on it every day, we watch tape. Don't
thread the needle, make the easy pass. Bad passes lead to bad
shots. We've got to do a better job of teaching that.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a major win for Providence. ``Any time a new staff comes
in, you're rebuilding, and today was one of those blocks that was
huge,'' Welsh said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This can establish our future and we can establish ourselves
as a quality basketball team. Any time you can beat a Gene Keady
team, that proves we have a chance to be a very good team.''
</P>
<P>
   Welsh liked that Providence took so many more shots. ``Eighteen
more shots, that's why we won the game,'' he said. ``Good things
happen if you take 18 more shots. You don't have as good a shooting
percentage to win, but you're getting more attempts. It's a key
statistic ... and the turnover ratio was unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   After a good start this season, the Friars sputtered, but now
they appear to be back on track. ``If we have high energy on
defense, we're going to play well,'' Welsh said. ``That's the key
to our team. Today we played a complete game. We don't overpower
anybody. We played with feistiness, we played with heart. I liked a
lot of things we did.''
</P>
<P>
   The teams were tied at 62 on a 3-pointer by Purdue's Alan
Eldridge off the wing with 11:55 left. Providence then built an
8-point lead, 76-68, after a Maxey layup with 6:40 remaining. Corey
Wright's 3-pointer with 3:25 to go put the Friars in front, 81-78.
</P>
<P>
   After getting it to 83-82 on a tip-in by McQuay with 1:03 left,
Purdue's Jaraan Cornell attempted three 3-pointers. He missed them
all, even though he was open, the last with eight seconds left. He
was 0 for 6 on 3-point tries in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Providence played what it calls a ``3-D'' defense to guard
against late 3-pointers. ``We don't want to get caught with any
screens,'' said Welsh. ``We'll give up the inside, but we make sure
to get out to the shooter and contest it and scratch and claw to
get the rebound.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than contesting the shot, we kicked around whether or
not to foul, but with 13 seconds left, there's too much time, with
foul shots and things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
