<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 02:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8059 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CHARGERS-CARDS-HN     12-28 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CHARGERS-CARDS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
TEMPE, Ariz. _ The ball seemed to float through the dry desert air
as if in slow motion as 71,670 fans held their collective breath.
<TEXT>
<P>
   And when the ball finally split the uprights with no time
showing on the scoreboard clock, it was Arizona kicker Chris Jacke
_ not quarterback Jake Plummer _ who was crowned king for a day.
</P>
<P>
   When Jacke's 52-yard field goal gave the Cardinals a 16-13
victory over San Diego on Sunday afternoon, pandemonium erupted at
Sun Devil Stadium. Fans descended from the stands, climbed the
fence that circles the field, overwhelmed security and swarmed the
Cardinals as they tried to leave.
</P>
<P>
   It was a dangerous situation but one that was inevitable because
the victory meant so much to Arizona. With the dramatic win, the
Cardinals won the last wild-card spot in the NFC. They will visit
NFC East rival Dallas on Saturday at Texas Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals (9-7), who blew a seven-point lead in the final
half-minute before Jacke's kick, finished with a winning record for
the first time since 1984 to clinch their first playoff appearance
since the strike-shortened 1982 season and their first ever in
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Until Sunday, the franchise hadn't reached the playoffs in a
legitimate season since 1975.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder the fans staged such a wild celebration while owner
Bill Bidwill clutched a game ball in the corner of the dressing
room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just drained emotionally,'' said Bidwill, who moved the
team from St. Louis in 1988 and is hoping to get a public
referendum for a new stadium in May. ``This win was so important
for the players, coaches, fans _ everyone. We earned this trip to
the playoffs. We didn't back in. We didn't have to depend on
someone else to help us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight, I'm going to have three scoops of ice cream to
celebrate.''
</P>
<P>
   When they play the Cowboys, who have won 16 of the last 17 times
the teams have met, the Cardinals will have a chance at their first
playoff win since 1947 _ when Bidwill's father owned the team and
it was based in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cried like a big baby,'' Cardinals cornerback Aeneas
Williams said. ``I wasn't afraid to let the tears flow.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've climbed to the mountaintop, and we can see the Dallas
Cowboys. History shows that it's hard to beat any team three
times.''
</P>
<P>
   History shows it's hard for the Cardinals to beat any team.
</P>
<P>
   Their last six wins were by three points or fewer. They came
from behind to win in the fourth quarter six times.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the Cardiac Cards,'' fullback Larry Centers said. ``We
like to make it exciting for our fans. They pay their hard-earned
dollars to watch us, and we have to make sure they get their
money's worth.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to rain on the Cardinals' parade, but they didn't beat a
team with a winning record. They didn't even beat a team with a
.500 record.
</P>
<P>
   The only team they played that finished over .500 was Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole world can continue to doubt us, but the bottom line
is that we're in the playoffs, and it's a great feeling,'' Centers
said. ``It's a brand-new season, and we need to realize the
importance of this game. We have to be meticulous in our
preparation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since we haven't been in the playoffs, we don't really know
how we'll react. We'll have to wait and see. But I'm confident that
we'll keep displaying the type of character we've shown this
season.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals struggled on offense Sunday but showed the type of
character that had been missing for years.
</P>
<P>
   Jacke, who left Green Bay over money issues and spent 1{ years
out of football before the Cardinals signed him this month, kicked
field goals of 37 and 36 yards. Running back Adrian Murrell was
credited with a four-yard touchdown, though replays showed he went
down at the one.
</P>
<P>
   ``The officials knew we were going to get it in on the next
play,'' Center said of the phantom touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   After John Carney kicked his second field goal to cut the
deficit to 13-6, the Chargers appeared to be doomed when Craig
Whelihan's long pass bounced off receiver Ryan Thelwell's hands at
the Arizona seven and was intercepted by safety Kwamie Lassiter.
</P>
<P>
   It was Lassiter's fourth interception of the game, tying an NFL
record.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals drove to the San Diego 25 with two minutes left,
but Jacke missed a 42-yard field-goal attempt.
</P>
<P>
   The Chargers got the ball with 1:55 remaining and drove 45
yards. On fourth-and-20 from the Arizona 30, Thelwell earned
redemption with a touchdown catch. Carney's kick tied the score at
13 with 22 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking about the coin toss (to begin overtime), but
then I had a feeling that Eric (Metcalf) would put us in great
shape on the return,'' Cardinals receiver Frank Sanders said. ``And
I was right.''
</P>
<P>
   Metcalf, who was traded from San Diego to Arizona in the
offseason as part of the deal that allowed the Chargers to draft
quarterback Ryan Leaf, had been a non-factor until his last kickoff
return of the season.
</P>
<P>
   He returned it 46 yards to the San Diego 44.
</P>
<P>
   With seven seconds left, Plummer threw a quick 10-yard pass to
Sanders, who went down immediately calling for a timeout, and Jacke
trotted on for the field goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty much straight down the middle,'' Jacke said. ``I
just turned to the sideline, and I was mobbed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
