<HEADER>
A8199 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAMMEUS-FORETELL-KAN &LR;      12-28 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-FORETELL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THINGS WILL HAPPEN IN 1999, THOUGH MAYBE NOT THIS STUFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1998 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I would like to meet the prognosticator who, a year ago,
predicted Bill Clinton would be impeached by now for lying about
sex with a White House intern. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The certain non-existence of such a prescient person is proof of
how astonishingly difficult the prediction business is. Well, wait.
The prediction task itself is easy. You just predict stuff. But
getting it right. Ah, that's where the trouble comes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And yet I am not cowed by the seeming impossibility of the job.
Rather, it quickens my pulse, just as another Bill's pulse was
quickened by the sight of a certain Monica's thong underwear. Or,
anyway, something like that. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So do not speak to me of how utterly unbelievable some of my
predictions are for 1999. If reality is going to behave in this
utterly contemptible, over-the-top, out-of-control, run-amok way,
those of us in the prognostication business will simply have to go
some to keep up. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With that as a wandering, distracted caveat, here is what to
look for in the coming year, one that has three 9s in it, which
means certainly something or other _ if not the opposite: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Al Gore will announce two things: 1) He's going to run for
vice president again _ if anyone will have him. 2) He's started to
wear thong underwear. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ The Dow Jones Industrial Average will end 1999 at 6.12. Six of
the 6.12 points will be represented by the funeral sector, kept
busy scraping up investors from Wall Street. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ The Chicago Cubs and the Kansas City Royals will battle in the
World Series, which the New York Yankees will win. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Hillary Rodham Clinton will be impeached for lying about an
affair with Al Gore that began when he playfully showed her his
thong underwear. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Monica Lewinsky will be elected to the Senate from California
to replace Sen. Barbara Boxer, who will be impeached for lying
about an affair with Al Gore that began. . .well, you know. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Pilgrims from around the world will flock to Vernon, Texas,
birthplace of Ken Starr, after word gets out that a simple
housewife there has started seeing a mysterious image of Starr on
the local water tower at night. On some nights, she claims, she has
seen the image cry real tears. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Rep. J. Dennis Hastert's term as Speaker of the House will
last four days, after which he will quit in anger over political
enemies purposefully mispronouncing his last name by starting it
with the letter ``B.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Madonna will announce she is leaving the study of Jewish
mysticism to study Al Gore. Her infatuation with him began. . . &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ At the end of the year Richard Nixon will still be dead. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Scientists will announce they finally have arrived at the
so-called Grand Unified Theory of Everything. Oddly enough, it will
have something to do with unpopular vegetables, Vince Foster and
the Texas School Book Depository. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Saddam Hussein will leave power in Iraq and take a job as
understudy to TV talk show host Jerry Springer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ The race for the Republican presidential nomination will be
thrown into chaos when all potential candidates drop out. Within a
week, the Draft Ken Starr movement will be judged unstoppable. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ The Internet will shut down when it's discovered that the Y2K
problem can't be solved without first solving the little-known
Y1.99K problem. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Can you say King Charles without laughing? Me either. Still. .
. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
