<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WEEK IN REVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
 
 (Repeating for all needing.) (bl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   History, the Polls Say, Is In the Eye of the Beholder
</P>
<P>
   Scholars called President Clinton's impeachment historic, but
judging by what people told pollsters, the public cared more about
the weather.
</P>
<P>
   The Pew Research Center sampled public opinion before, during
and after the House impeachment vote. About 34 percent of those
queried said they followed the impeachment drama ``very closely'' _
compared to 39 percent who cared that much about the weather.
</P>
<P>
   But skeptical journalists raised their eyebrows, noting that the
participants in the long-running Pew survey said they found the
1996 presidential election more compelling than the death of Diana,
Princess of Wales.
</P>
<P>
   _ By FELICITY BARRINGER &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Babies, Texas Style  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Improved fertility treatments and a growing demand from
infertile couples has created a global surge in multiple births _
triplets or more _ from 1,034 in 1971 to 4,973 in 1995 in the
United States alone. The latest case was the birth last week of
octuplets to a Houston woman. It started doctors worrying anew
about the ethical issues raised.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a victory,'' said Dr. Benjamin Younger of the
American Society for Reproductive Medicine. ``A lot of these kids
survive but, unfortunately, they survive with major handicaps.''
</P>
<P>
   The infants, born to Nkem Chukwu, a Nigerian-born American
citizen, maintained a fragile hold on life at week's end.
</P>
<P>
   _ By RICK LYMAN
</P>
<P>
   Feed Up in Israel  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lifting his hand in the air, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu voted to bring down his own government two years early,
sheepishly joining an overwhelming majority vote by a fed-up
Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu, the Likud prime minister, had depended on a
right-wing coalition that fell apart after he signed the
land-for-security peace plan at the White House in October.
Although he won back some on the right by freezing compliance with
the plan due to what he called multiple Palestinian violations, his
government had become irreparably dysfunctional.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DEBORAH SONTAG
</P>
<P>
   Catching a Smuggler
</P>
<P>
   A subsidiary of RJR Nabisco Holdings Corp. pleaded guilty to
federal criminal charges and admitted that it had helped a
smuggling ring funnel millions of cigarettes into Canada in the
mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The guilty plea, by RJR's Northern Brands International unit,
marked the first time that a tobacco company had been convicted of
complicity in the shadowy world of international cigarette
smuggling.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said the smuggling helped the company get around
high Canadian taxes meant to discourage cigarette smoking, and
critics said the conviction could undercut the industry's efforts
to block an increase in cigarette taxes in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   _ By CHRISTOPHER DREW
</P>
<P>
   Balloonists' Saga
</P>
<P>
   Christmas found three of the world's greatest balloonists down
in the Pacific Ocean, half way to their goal of circling the Earth
non-stop. In at least 22 previous attempts at global
circumnavigation, no balloonist had ever come this close to
success.
</P>
<P>
   The 160-foot-high ICO Global Challenge ended its voyage when it
hit a low-pressure system over the ocean. Still, its crew _ Richard
Branson, Per Lindstrand and Steve Fossett _ will be accorded a
special place in ballooning archives. They managed not only to
avoid all the countries where hostile governments would have forced
them down but fought their way through storms, uncooperative winds
and exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sorry to have let people down,'' Branson said, speaking
to his London headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   _ By MALCOLM W. BROWNE
</P>
<P>
   Relief for Angina
</P>
<P>
   One injection of an experimental drug directly into the heart
through a small incision in the chest has greatly relieved, even
eliminated, the chest pain of angina that standard drugs and bypass
surgery had failed to control, according to preliminary findings
from two continuing studies in the United States and Germany.
</P>
<P>
   One drug is gene therapy to produce a protein called vegF, for
vascular endothelial growth factor. The other drug is a protein
called FGF-1, for fibroblast growth factor.
</P>
<P>
   Independent experts urged caution for a number of reasons. One
is the small numbers _ about 25 patients have been tested so far.
Another is uncertainty about the duration of benefit because the
first patient was treated only 10 months ago. A third is that for
ethical reasons no patient could receive a placebo as a scientific
control to allow more rigorous comparison.
</P>
<P>
   _ By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN
</P>
<P>
   A League of Their Own
</P>
<P>
   As the National Basketball Association moves toward a January
deadline meant to jumpstart the season or cancel it, the American
Basketball League simply ran out of money.
</P>
<P>
   Although the ABL, a rival of the NBA-backed Women's National
Basketball Association, had built up teams with gold medalists from
the 1996 Olympics and handed out six-figure salaries to their
stars, it could not attract the corporate funds and television
deals necessary for survival. A third of the way through its third
season, it said it will file for bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   ``TV exposure is critical to sponsors, licensees and
investors,'' said ABL co-founder Gary Cavalli in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It became clear that, although we had the best product, we
could not find enough people willing to confront the NBA and give
us the major sponsorships and TV contracts we needed.''
</P>
<P>
   A Vaccine for Lyme Disease
</P>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration cautiously approved the
marketing of a Lyme disease vaccine for the first time last week.
It is intended for those who live or work in grassy or wooded areas
where ticks infected with the Lyme bacteria abound.
</P>
<P>
   Optimal protection requires three injections spaced over a year,
but effectiveness is 78 percent and those vaccinated still must
guard against ticks. Approval was only for people 15 to 70 years
old.
</P>
<P>
   _ By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN &QR;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
