<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Tanks for Nothing
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of gas stations and thousands more school districts,
fire departments and trash collectors that store fuel in
potentially leaky underground tanks face fines of up to $11,000 a
day unless they shut them down.
</P>
<P>
   The deadline, set 10 years ago by the Environmental Protection
Agency, was to give owners of the tanks time to replace them or fix
them so they would not leak fuel into the underground water supply.
</P>
<P>
   Scratching Labels
</P>
<P>
   Seagram's $10.4 billion acquisition of the entertainment giant
Polygram from Philips is the biggest merger in the history of
popular music, resulting in the world's largest record company. But
with the new year, nearly 200 rock bands will be dropped along with
some 3,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   The merger will either restructure or dissolve major record
labels like Geffen, A&AMP;M, Island and Mercury, affecting Sting,
Hanson, Sheryl Crow, U2, Elton John and Aerosmith, among others.
The transition will be hardest for the more than 100 middle-level
acts like Aimee Mann, Girls Against Boys and Cowboy Junkies, who
are waiting until next month or February to discover whether they
will still have a record contract.
</P>
<P>
   Others who have already suffered have been up-and-coming bands
like MxPx, Cold and Swirl, where promotions have stopped while
record-label employees await word on their own fate.
</P>
<P>
   _ By NEIL STRAUSS
</P>
<P>
   A Standoff Over Bananas &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A tip to holiday party-givers: If you are planning on serving
pecorino Romano cheese, stock up now. Same thing goes for those who
just can't make it through the next few months without another
gold-nibbed Mont Blanc pen.
</P>
<P>
   Those goodies are on the Clinton administration hit list in the
latest move in the banana wars. When it comes to the rules for
importing and exporting bananas, Europeans can't seem to go along
to get along. It's gotten so nasty of late that President Clinton
told Europe that unless it complies with a World Trade Organization
ruling to open its banana market, he will slap 100 percent tariffs
on $500 million in European goods, perhaps as soon as February.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as one of his economic aides put it the other day, ``You can
kiss that pecorino goodbye.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea, of course, is to force the Europeans to comply with
the ruling, which makes the banana issue a test of the world's new
dispute settlement system for trade.
</P>
<P>
   But like most post-Cold War conflicts, this one is a lot more
complicated than it appears. Latin American and Carribbean nations
that produce bananas have enormous swaths of their economies at
stake. And it means a lot to Dole Food Co. and Chiquita Brands,
which insist that Washington must stand up for its overseas
interests. Only cynics would suggest that it helps that Carl
Lindner, who controls Chiquita, is known as a generous donor to
both parties. _ By DAVID E. SANGER
</P>
<P>
   Good Times Foil a Genre
</P>
<P>
   Oh, where have all the trench coats gone?
</P>
<P>
   In the good old days, there were communists under every bed, and
America and the Soviet Union were always within one scrap of
microfilm _ hidden in, say, a priceless sculpture or the heel of
shoe _ of blowing each other to Technicolor smithereens.
</P>
<P>
   And writers of spy thrillers were whispering all the way to the
bank.
</P>
<P>
   But the Cold War is deader than a double agent gunned down in a
frigid Moscow back alley, and while the world can still be a
decidedly treacherous place _ think of Iraq or Kosovo, or Capitol
Hill _ the espionage novel is whimpering out in the cold. Today's
conflicts, one publisher said, just aren't as sexy as ``the good
old Americans against the communists.''
</P>
<P>
   Tales by the likes of John le Carre, Frederick Forsyth and Ken
Follett, which once staked out the best-seller lists for months at
a time, now make, at best, fleeting appearances.
</P>
<P>
   What's a self-respecting spy author to do? Go into politics?
Start a talk show? No, they're just yanking off the trench coats
and slipping into something a little more, well, millennial. Or so
they hope.
</P>
<P>
   Forsyth, noted for ``The Odessa File,'' has changed both
publishing house and agent (``literary,'' not ``secret,'' that is)
and written a sequel to the 1910 novel ``The Phantom of the Opera''
called ``The Phantom of Manhattan.'' It has something to do with
cleaning fish in Coney Island.
</P>
<P>
   Follett's latest is ``The Hammer of Eden,'' populated by aging
hippie eco-terrorists. And le Carre's next book, ``Single &AMP;
Single,'' promises heavy breathing and sinister doings in the world
of international finance. (It begins with the execution of the
ultimate 1990s villain: a lawyer.)
</P>
<P>
   So is the Cold War literary history? Maybe someday it will come
back as nostalgia. ``You have to wait,'' said Charles McCarry, a
novelist and former officer of the CIA, ``for the Cold War to be
quaint as a little Napoleonic war.''
</P>
<P>
   A Merchant-Ivory production, perhaps, with impeccable period
trench coats.
</P>
<P>
   _ By HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
