<HEADLINE>
BEST SELLERS: HARDCOVER BOOKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For release on Sunday, Jan. 03.) 
(Eds: This file is the abbreviated best-seller list for hardcover
books. Please see BESTSELLERS-HARD-L-NYT for the full version that
includes how many weeks each book has been on the list and where
the book stood the previous week.) 
(rl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rankings reflect sales for the week ending Dec. 19 at almost
4,000 bookstores plus wholesalers serving 50,000 other retailers
(gift shops, department stores, newsstands, supermarkets),
statistically weighted to represent all such outlets nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   An (x) indicates that a book's sales are barely distinguishable
from those of the book above. A (b) indicates that some bookstores
report receiving bulk orders for a book.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FICTION  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. A MAN IN FULL, by Tom Wolfe. (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux,
</P>
<P>
   $28.95.) Life in Atlanta on the cusp of the millennium, as
</P>
<P>
   Old South values collide with a new world.
</P>
<P>
   2. BAG OF BONES, by Stephen King. (Scribner, $28.)
</P>
<P>
   A series of terrifying events besets a best-selling novelist
</P>
<P>
   four years after his wife's sudden death.
</P>
<P>
   3. RAINBOW SIX, by Tom Clancy. (Putnam, $27.95.)
</P>
<P>
   John Clark, heading an international task force,
</P>
<P>
   investigates terrorist incidents in Switzerland,
</P>
<P>
   Germany and Spain.
</P>
<P>
   4. MIRROR IMAGE, by Danielle Steel. (Delacorte, $26.95.)
</P>
<P>
   Identical twin sisters experience quite dissimilar lives
</P>
<P>
   in New York and France early in this century.
</P>
<P>
   5. THE SIMPLE TRUTH, by David Baldacci. (Warner, $25.)
</P>
<P>
   The appeal by a man serving a life sentence for murder
</P>
<P>
   creates chaos in Washington's legal community.
</P>
<P>
   6. THE POISONWOOD BIBLE, by Barbara Kingsolver.
</P>
<P>
   (Harper Flamingo, $26.) Five female characters,
</P>
<P>
   a missionary's family, narrate this novel set in
</P>
<P>
   the Belgian Congo during that country's fight for
</P>
<P>
   independence.
</P>
<P>
   7. WHEN THE WIND BLOWS, by James Patterson. (Little,
</P>
<P>
   Brown, $25.) A young girl helps a widow and an FBI
</P>
<P>
   agent uncover a deadly plot.
</P>
<P>
   8. HARRY POTTER AND THE SORCERER'S STONE, by J.K.
</P>
<P>
   Rowling. (Levine/Scholastic, $16.95.) A Scottish
</P>
<P>
   boy, neglected by his relatives, finds his fortune
</P>
<P>
   attending a school of witchcraft.
</P>
<P>
   9. THE VAMPIRE ARMAND, by Anne Rice. (Knopf, $26.95.)
</P>
<P>
   The progress of an eternally young man from ancient
</P>
<P>
   Constantinople to contemporary New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   10. A NIGHT WITHOUT ARMOR, by Jewel Kilcher.
</P>
<P>
   (HarperCollins, $15.) The singer-songwriter's
</P>
<P>
   poems contemplate love, family, Alaska and life
</P>
<P>
   on the road. (b)
</P>
<P>
   11. ALL THROUGH THE NIGHT, by Mary Higgins Clark.
</P>
<P>
   (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $17.) The mystery of a missing
</P>
<P>
   child and a missing chalice is solved in time for
</P>
<P>
   Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   12. CHARMING BILLY, by Alice McDermott. (Farrar, Straus &AMP;
</P>
<P>
   Giroux, $22.) At a party to celebrate a man's memory,
</P>
<P>
   many secrets of the past come to life.
</P>
<P>
   13. MEMOIRS OF A GEISHA, by Arthur Golden. (Knopf, $25.)
</P>
<P>
   The life of a young woman growing up in Kyoto who has
</P>
<P>
   to reinvent herself after World War II begins.
</P>
<P>
   14. TODAY I FEEL SILLY &AMP; OTHER MOODS THAT MAKE MY DAY,
</P>
<P>
   by Jamie Lee Curtis. Illustrated by Laura Cornell.
</P>
<P>
   (Cotter/HarperCollins, $15.95.) The ever-changing
</P>
<P>
   moods of a young girl.
</P>
<P>
   15. THE LOCKET, by Richard Paul Evans. (Simon &AMP; Schuster,
</P>
<P>
   $15.95.) A young man learns much about life, love and compassion
</P>
<P>
   while working in a nursing home.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONFICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. THE GREATEST GENERATION, by Tom Brokaw. (Random
</P>
<P>
   House, $24.95.) The lives of men and women who came
</P>
<P>
   of age during the Depression and World War II.
</P>
<P>
   2. THE CENTURY, by Peter Jennings and Todd Brewster.
</P>
<P>
   (Doubleday, $60.) An account of the 20th century,
</P>
<P>
   complete with photographs and first-person narratives.
</P>
<P>
   3. TUESDAYS WITH MORRIE, by Mitch Albom.
</P>
<P>
   (Doubleday, $19.95.) A sportswriter tells of
</P>
<P>
   his weekly visits to his old college mentor,
</P>
<P>
   who was near death's door.
</P>
<P>
   4. BLIND MAN'S BLUFF, by Sherry Sontag and Christopher
</P>
<P>
   Drew with Annette Lawrence Drew. (Public Affairs, $25.)
</P>
<P>
   American submarine espionage from the early Cold War
</P>
<P>
   years to the present.
</P>
<P>
   5. THE PROFESSOR AND THE MADMAN, by Simon Winchester.
</P>
<P>
   (HarperCollins, $22.) How a murderer helped compile the
</P>
<P>
   Oxford English Dictionary.
</P>
<P>
   6. THE AMERICAN CENTURY, by Harold Evans with Gail
</P>
<P>
   Buckland and Kevin Baker. (Knopf, $50.) A copiously
</P>
<P>
   illustrated political history of the 20th century that
</P>
<P>
   emphasizes America's role.
</P>
<P>
   7. WE INTERRUPT THIS BROADCAST, by Joe Garner. (Sourcebooks,
</P>
<P>
   $45.) How radio and television reported historic events
</P>
<P>
   over the past 60 years.
</P>
<P>
   8. FOR THE LOVE OF THE GAME, by Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Edited by Mark Vancil. (Crown, $50.) The NBA superstar's
</P>
<P>
   profusely illustrated memoir.
</P>
<P>
   9. THE ENDURANCE, by Caroline Alexander. (Knopf, $29.95.)
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Shackleton's 1914 Antarctic expedition.
</P>
<P>
   10. A WALK IN THE WOODS, by Bill Bryson. (Broadway,
</P>
<P>
   $25.) A journalist finds beauty and humor while hiking
</P>
<P>
   the Appalachian Trail.
</P>
<P>
   11. LINDBERGH, by A. Scott Berg. (Putnam, $30.) The
</P>
<P>
   checkered life of Charles A. Lindbergh.
</P>
<P>
   12. EVERYTHING AND A KITE, by Ray Romano. (Bantam, $22.95.)
</P>
<P>
   The comedian and star of the television show ``Everybody
</P>
<P>
   Loves Raymond'' describes his life.
</P>
<P>
   13. A PIRATE LOOKS AT FIFTY, by Jimmy Buffett. (Random
</P>
<P>
   House, $24.95.) Traveling from Florida to the Amazon,
</P>
<P>
   the singer-songwriter reflects on his life.
</P>
<P>
   14.(x) CONVERSATIONS WITH GOD: Book 3, by Neale Donald
</P>
<P>
   Walsch. (Hampton Roads, $22.95.) More discussions of
</P>
<P>
   moral questions.
</P>
<P>
   15. THE TEN COMMANDMENTS, by Laura Schlessinger and Stewart
</P>
<P>
   Vogel. (Cliff Street/HarperCollins, $24.) The significance
</P>
<P>
   of the Ten Commandments today.
</P>
<P>
   16.(x) BEST FRIENDS, by Sharon J. Wohlmuth and Carol Saline.
</P>
<P>
   (Doubleday, $24.95.) Thirty-four accounts of relationships
</P>
<P>
   that became more significant than family ties, illustrated
</P>
<P>
   with photographs.
</P>
