<HEADER>
A8229 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAMES-VAN-DER-BEEK-IN     12-28 1428
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAMES-VAN-DER-BEEK-IN-VARSITY-BLUES-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAMES VAN DER BEEK: A TEEN IDOL PLAYS FOR RESPECT 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
NIRDI RELIS in New York at 212-499-3333, or by fax at
212-499-3382.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of James Van Der Beek with Amy Smart in a
scene from ``Varsity Blues.'' 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    It's not easy to be 21 and stuck in high school.
 &HT;    James Van Der Beek knows, because he has to shed five years
daily for his role as 16-year-old Dawson Leery on the hit WB
series, ``Dawson's Creek.''
 &HT;    ``The first step in finding Dawson is shaving to get that
sensitive, peach-faced look,'' the actor says. ``If we film for too
long, I have to shave again and again.''
 &HT;    The sensitive, peach-faced look seems to work, though, because
teen-age female viewers have been drawn to Van Der Beek as if he
were the small-screen version of Leonardo DiCaprio.
 &HT;    Which is particularly amusing, he says, because during his
real-life high-school years girls generally ignored him.
 &HT;    ``I never really fit in,'' Van Der Beek says over breakfast at
New York's Regency Hotel. ``I mean, who really feels like they fit
in in high school?
 &HT;    ``I laugh that Dawson has all these female fans,'' he adds,
``because I was just as big of a dork in high school, and nobody
had a crush on me.''
 &HT;    It's safe to say that those days are history. Recently Van Der
Beek was asked to leave a store ``because I created a scene.'' Even
on the road he isn't safe.
 &HT;    ``I'll be driving and I'll hear a shriek, like a muffled shriek
of pain,'' he says. ``Then I'll turn around, and it will be this
minivan filled with teen-age girls. I don't know who's driving _ I
just hope it's not their mom going, `We're going to get him! He's
turning into the gas station!'''
 &HT;    While filming his new movie, ``Varsity Blues,'' a football drama
which was shot last year in Austin, Texas, he couldn't even go out
to eat without being mobbed.
 &HT;    ``At one point, I was in a restaurant and it just got out of
hand,'' Van Der Beek says, sighing. ``I was freaked out by it, so I
snuck out the back and went back to the hotel.
 &HT;    ``My life is so different now,'' he adds, ``but I guess it's
just an adjustment. My daily routine has changed _ but I'm not
complaining, because fame has been 90 percent great and only 10
percent bad.''
 &HT;    The good part includes his first starring movie role. ``Varsity
Blues,'' opening Jan. 15, casts Van Der Beek as a high-school jock
who tangles with a surly, win-at-any-cost coach (Jon Voight).
 &HT;    Helmets and shoulder pads weren't new to Van Der Beek.
 &HT;    ``In junior high school I played football,'' he says, ``but I
got a concussion.''
 &HT;    In fact, it was while recovering from that injury that he got
into acting.
 &HT;    ``I was so bored that I tried out for a local community play,''
he recalls, ``and landed the role of Danny Zuko in `Grease.'''
 &HT;    Don't come to ``Varsity Blues'' expecting a sensitive,
Dawsonesque athlete, the actor warns.
 &HT;    ``We hired real high-school football players who played my
teammates on this movie,'' Van Der Beek says. ``These guys were
pretty unimpressed by my sensitive portrayal of Dawson Leery. They
had no qualms about kicking my a-- on a field or in a bar.''
 &HT;    And Van Der Beek had no qualms about kicking right back.
 &HT;    ``I liked that this character had an edge,'' he says. ``I keep
getting movie scripts where I would play the sensitive guy. It's
like Hollywood is saying, `Get that kid who plays Dawson. He does
that well.'
 &HT;    ``Well, I want to do something a little different.''
 &HT;    To accentuate the difference, he dyed his hair dark brown and
hit the gym to put on 15 pounds of muscle.
 &HT;    ``I knew I would have to do something drastically different to
make sure girls weren't like, `Oh, it's Dawson on the football
field,''' he says.
 &HT;    It remains to be seen whether they'll care. Van Der Beek
experienced their ardor firsthand at a recent promotional meeting
with fans at a Seattle convention center. About 1,000 people were
expected, but more than 5,000 showed up and stormed the stage.
 &HT;    ``They had to literally whisk me away, with security guards
yanking me out of the building,'' Van Der Beek marvels. ``We had to
send an empty limo off as a decoy. Then I had to run to the bottom
of the building, where I was taken away by a police car.''
 &HT;    Still, he thinks it's worth it.
 &HT;    ``Absolutely,'' he says without hesitation. ``I can't go to the
mall, but I get to work with Jon Voight. I never want to sound like
some whiny guy going, `Oh, I'm so famous now I can't stand it.'''
 &HT;    Actually, he adds, Voight helped him learn how to deal with his
fame.
 &HT;    ``The person who put things in perspective for me was Jon
Voight, who said, `You have the power to make people very happy by
doing something very simple. You're in a position where you can
give people little gifts that will make them smile,''' Van Der Beek
recalls. ``He's right.''
 &HT;    The actor still remembers where he came from, because it was
only a few years ago that he was back in Cheshire, Conn., growing
up as the eldest of three children of a telecommunications account
manager and a gymnastics-studio owner.
 &HT;    School wasn't always easy. Van Der Beek struggled with dyslexia,
but still managed to win an academic scholarship and become a
National Honor Society member, a student proctor and a choir
member.
 &HT;    And a teen actor. After ``Grease,'' the aspiring thespian found
an agent, who helped him get cast in an Off-Broadway play, and soon
such television movies as ``Angus'' and ``I Love You, I Love You,''
which co-starred a then-unknown Claire Danes.
 &HT;    As an English major at Drew University in Madison, N.J., Van Der
Beek took off afternoons to audition in New York. His college
career ended, however, when one of those auditions led him to
Dawson Leery.
 &HT;    ``When I signed on to be Dawson, I thought I was going to be on
a critically acclaimed show that nobody watched,'' he says.
 &HT;    It didn't work out that way. But Van Der Beek insists that he
still doesn't feel like a star. His biggest extravagance to date
has been a new truck, and he avoids the Hollywood party scene _
which isn't hard, since he spends most of his time on the
``Dawson's Creek'' set in Wilmington, N.C.
 &HT;    And playing Dawson hasn't helped him do better with girls, he
reports, though he admits to having a steady girlfriend. Still, he
says, if anything his success has made romance even more difficult.
 &HT;    ``Now I have a tendency to question motivations,'' the actor
says. ``Why is a girl talking to me? Does she want me or Dawson?''
 &HT;    Nowadays, the teen-age girls who aren't speculating about his
off-camera romantic life are probably speculating about Dawson's
on-camera affairs of the heart. As any self-respecting teen-ager
can tell you, the character is torn between the mysterious Jen,
played by Michelle Williams, and his sweet childhood friend Joey,
played by fellow teen phenom Katie Holmes.
 &HT;    Fans want Dawson and Joey to get together once and for all,
which Van Der Beek wouldn't mind.
 &HT;    ``If they can make it as interesting as when they're not
together, then sure,'' he says. ``I think the audience wants it.
But the audience also doesn't want it _ everyone loves the
anticipation of letting them get together.''
 &HT;    Speaking of anticipation, ``Dawson's Creek'' fans have one
particular question they're buzzing about: Will Dawson ever lose
his virginity?
 &HT;    Van Der Beek hems and haws.
 &HT;    ``Um,'' he says, laughing, ``I guarantee you it will probably
happen during sweeps. That's all I know.''
 c.1998 Cindy Pearlman  
