w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRENDA-BLETHYN-IN-LIT     12-28 1330
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRENDA-BLETHYN-IN-LITTLE-VOICE-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRENDA BLETHYN, THE BIG VOICE OF `LITTLE VOICE' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
NIRDI RELIS in New York at 212-499-3333, or by fax at
212-499-3382.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Brenda Blethyn in a scene from ``Little
Voice.'' 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    ``Brenda who?''
 &HT;    That's what a lot of people thought when Brenda Blethyn's name
was announced as a nominee for the 1996 Academy Award as Best
Actress.
 &HT;    Despite critical acclaim for her performance in Mike Leigh's
family drama ``Secrets &AMP; Lies,'' the little-known stage actress
couldn't believe it, either.
 &HT;    ``Oh, it was a dream,'' Blethyn says. ``Frankly, I was
overwhelmed at having won the Golden Globe. That suited me just
fine, and I didn't need anything else.
 &HT;    ``To get the Oscar nomination as well, that was wonderful.''
 &HT;    Then there was Oscar night, as Cuba Gooding Jr. prepared to name
the winner.
 &HT;    ``I didn't expect at any time to win, except for that 30 seconds
when he was standing there with that envelope,'' the actress
recalls. ``I embarrassed myself for three days for even having had
that thought.''
 &HT;    Blethyn lets loose a husky, loud howl of laughter, a sound heard
often during a conversation with her at a Manhattan hotel. Truth be
told, she probably hasn't stopped laughing since ``Secrets &AMP;
Lies,'' which made her suddenly an in-demand actress, both in her
native England and in Hollywood.
 &HT;    ``It's been a wonderful time,'' she says. ``I'm happy. The Oscar
nomination changed my life.
 &HT;    ``I love theater and TV and radio, too'' she adds, ``but I've
been concentrating on films now. I'd only made three films when I
did `Secrets &AMP; Lies,' so I'm still a novice in the film world.''
 &HT;    Blethyn's latest film, ``Little Voice,'' based on Jim
Cartwright's play, ``The Rise and Fall of Little Voice,'' stars
Jane Horrocks _ for whom the play was written _ as Little Voice, or
L.V. for short. She's a painfully shy young woman with an uncanny
knack for perfectly mimicking such singing legends as Judy Garland
and Shirley Bassey.
 &HT;    Blethyn plays Mari, L.V.'s horribly self-absorbed and ill-garbed
mother, with Michael Caine as Ray Say, a low-rent talent agent
who's also Mari's slimy boyfriend. Say and Mari envision pots of
gold and a ticket out of their working-class English town, if only
they can prod the excruciatingly withdrawn L.V. into singing in
public.
 &HT;    As played by Blethyn, Mari is a soused, would-be sexpot, all
gaudy makeup, cruel wit and tacky clothes. There's no better Mari
moment than the one in which she dances and sings along to ``Disco
Inferno.''
 &HT;    In short, Mari is even less elegant than Blethyn's workaday
``Secrets &AMP; Lies'' role, neither of whom resembles the real-life
actress, chic in a stylish, dark-gray pantsuit.
 &HT;    ``I normally play sympathetic characters, so Mari was a nice
change of pace,'' Blethyn says. ``Our craft is to make you believe
we are these people. I mean, Mari is so far removed from me that it
was joyful.
 &HT;    ``She's not particularly likable,'' the actress adds, ``and we
enjoy not liking her. There was a bit of a temptation, because of
that, to round her edges, to make her more likable.''
 &HT;    Blethyn shakes her head and purses her lips.
 &HT;    ``I thought that it would have been so patronizing to Mari and
to the audience to do that,'' she says. ``So I went for broke.
 &HT;    ``When I watched the movie,'' she adds, ``I found Mari funny,
then not so funny. Then I didn't like her very much. But ultimately
I felt some kind of compassion for her.''
 &HT;    Blethyn counted Horrocks among her friends even before making
``Little Voice.'' She considers Horrocks ``fantastic'' in the film,
and is even more enthusiastic about Caine, with whom she shares
most of her biggest scenes.
 &HT;    ``He's a peach, just wonderful,'' Blethyn says, her face
lighting up. ``My first day, I was nervous about working with him,
but he put that to rest in an instant.
 &HT;    ``My first scene with him was leaping on him and kissing him! He
kept saying I was doing it wrong.''
 &HT;    Since her ``Secrets''-fueled rise to prominence, Blethyn has
made several movies, including the little-seen ``Music from Another
Room'' (1998), a recent cable drama entitled ``Girls Night''
(1998), the upcoming romance/thriller ``Night Train,'' with John
Hurt, and ``Daddy and Them,'' a comedy about a dysfunctional
family.
 &HT;    Blethyn sounds particularly enthusiastic about ``Daddy,''
written and directed by Billy Bob Thornton, who also co-stars in
the ensemble film.
 &HT;    ``I play an Englishwoman who marries into this family,'' Blethyn
says. ``I actually marry Jim Varney. He is one of the funniest men
I've ever had a conversation with.
 &HT;    ``Andy Griffith plays Daddy, and he's wonderful,'' she says
enthusiastically. ``I went in on my days off just to see him work.
We shot it in Arkansas, and everything on every menu there is
deep-fried, and everyone says `deep-fried' as `deep frah-eyed.'''
 &HT;    Blethyn, who lives in London with her longtime boyfriend,
Michael Mayhew, an artistic director at the National Theatre,
doesn't even try to deny that she's savoring her time in the
spotlight.
 &HT;    ``I worked for 10 years before I went to drama school,'' she
says, smiling. ``I worked in an office as a secretary. I had a good
job and made a good wage.
 &HT;    ``As it happened, I'd tried acting with an amateur acting
company and found that I absolutely loved it. People kept saying,
`Hey, you're not bad at this.'
 &HT;    ``I never thought I could do it professionally, and I kept
putting it off and putting it off,'' the actress recalls. ``Then I
thought, `Here I am, 27. If I don't try, I'll spend the rest of my
life regretting it.'
 &HT;    ``I didn't tell anybody, so nobody would laugh at me.''
 &HT;    Nobody laughed. Blethyn went on to join the prestigious National
Theatre, where she performed in numerous plays, then turned up in
British TV productions and in the films ``The Witches'' (1990) _ in
which Horrocks also appeared _ and ``A River Runs Through It''
(1992). Then came ``Secrets &AMP; Lies,'' and the rest is ... well,
some sort of history, anyway.
 &HT;    ``I've never been out of work, ever,'' Blethyn says. ``And,
after I decided to have a go at acting, I never doubted I could
make a living at that.
 &HT;    ``My ambitions have never been much further than what I've
accomplished, if you know what I mean,'' she says. ``If you get the
chance to do what you hope to do, then you're fortunate.
 &HT;    ``But I never, ever thought I'd be on a stage in Hollywood,
never, ever thought I'd be at the Oscars. Those were not my
ambitions.
 &HT;    ``So I'm happy,'' she says, beaming. ``I was happy when I worked
in an office, I was happy at the National Theatre and I'm happy
now.''
 &HT;    The question is, what would it take to make Blethyn even
happier?
 &HT;    ``I'd love to get one of those really glamorous roles, with
fantastic costumes, a bit haute couture,'' Blethynsays, laughing
that laugh again. ``They always ask me to be so dowdy. I try not to
take that too personally.''
 c.1998 Ian Spelling  
