w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EMILY-WATSON-IN-HILAR     12-28 1262
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMILY-WATSON-IN-HILARY-AND-JACKIE-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMILY WATSON FINDS STRANGE MUSIC IN `HILARY AND JACKIE' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
NIRDI RELIS in New York at 212-499-3333, or by fax at
212-499-3382.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Emily Watson in a scene from ``Hilary and
Jackie.'' 
 By JEANNE WOLF  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    You can't judge by appearances.
 &HT;    Emily Watson, for example, is a very grown-up actress, well into
her 30s. But she has the flawless skin, luminous blue eyes and
cherubic features to pass for a teenager _ not a bad thing in a
business that places a premium on youth.
 &HT;    ``I guess there are advantages to looking the way I do,'' she
says, grinning. ``I suppose it promotes career longevity. Also it
keeps you from getting too self-important, because people don't
always take you seriously.''
 &HT;    Watson's air of adolescent innocence added edge to her 1996 film
debut, ``Breaking the Waves.'' She got an Academy Award nomination
for her portrayal of a tortured wife who embarks on a series of
degrading sexual liaisons to please her dying husband.
 &HT;    Not exactly date-movie stuff, and her latest film, ``Hilary and
Jackie,'' is arguably even more harrowing. Watson plays cellist
Jacqueline du Pre, the real-life star who was cut down in her late
20s by multiple sclerosis, the crippling nerve disease which
finally claimed her life in 1987 at age 42.
 &HT;    ``I first heard the story of Jacqueline du Pre from the
director, Anand Tucker, at a lunch in London,'' Watson recalls. ``I
knew he was going to do a low-budget film, but I went straight to a
telephone afterwards, called my agent and said, `I have to be in
this.'
 &HT;    ``It wasn't a career decision,'' she says. ``It was just an
emotional reaction that I couldn't ignore.''
 &HT;    Part of Watson's fascination with du Pre was the debilitating
effect that fame had on her even before she was stricken with MS.
 &HT;    ``Jackie became sort of an overnight celebrity while she was
still in her teens,'' Watson says. ``It was a life of planes, hotel
rooms and performing. It sort of ate her up.''
 &HT;    Watson faced two daunting challenges _ learning to play the
cello and portraying the ravages of MS. The cello came first, and
she practiced until her fingers bled.
 &HT;    ``I had studied cello for a few months as a teenager,'' the
actress says, ``but my playing was rubbish, really. So I spent
three months holed up in a rehearsal room, doing hours of practice.
 &HT;    ``I was working in a building where a lot of real musicians,
some of them very famous, came to rehearse,'' Watson adds with a
laugh. ``I'd come out of my room and they'd be like, `Who was that
woman murdering the Elgar Concerto?'
 &HT;    ``I remember that once my teacher was on the phone to somebody
while I was practicing. This person said to her, `What is that
horrible noise?' It was like, `If that's a new student, get rid of
them.'''
 &HT;    You won't hear her playing in the film, but Watson did manage to
duplicate du Pre's distinctive style.
 &HT;    ``I was able to mime the playback with a real freedom,'' she
says. ``I wanted to get that sense of abandon that Jackie had when
she played _ she was like this passionate, wild cat. Actually the
cello is a very sexy instrument, and she put her whole body, every
fiber of her being, into playing it. It was magnetic.''
 &HT;    Even more important, arguably, was that Watson accurately
portray the crippling effects of multiple sclerosis.
 &HT;    ``I spent a lot of time with doctors and MS patients,'' Watson
says. ``I felt a great responsibility to really try to get as close
as I could to what MS is really like. I kept a couple of walking
sticks and a wheelchair in the room where I was rehearsing the
cello. When I wasn't playing, I was working on what it's like to
lose control of your body.''
 &HT;    ``Hilary and Jackie,'' based on ``A Genius in the Family,'' the
biography by Jackie's older sister Hilary and her brother Piers du
Pre, focuses on the close relationship between the two sisters,
both of whom were musicians.
 &HT;    While Hilary (Australian actress Rachel Griffiths) originally
showed great promise as a flutist, it was Jackie who became an
international success. Meanwhile her sister married British
conductor Kiffer Finzi, had two children and lived a quiet life in
a rural English town.
 &HT;    The three _ Hilary, Jackie and Kiffer _ form an odd sort of
triangle in the film, as in a sense do Hilary, Jackie and Jackie's
career, and even Hilary, Jackie and Hilary's might-have-been
career.
 &HT;    Watson can identify with the basic situation, she says. Her own
older sister, like Hilary, lives a quiet existence in an American
college town.
 &HT;    ``She's married to a professor at Cornell and has a baby,''
Watson says, ``so she's raising a family while I'm off around the
world, acting in movies.''
 &HT;    Watson herself is married to British actor Jack Waters, and
admits that her own artistic life puts certain strains on the
marriage.
 &HT;    ``There are moments when I can understand how Jackie felt about
hotel rooms and time zones,'' Watson says. ``I think, in that
respect, her life is a cautionary tale for anyone who's flirting
with fame.
 &HT;    ``I always try to tell myself that I'm coping marvelously,'' she
adds. ``But it's not always easy to maintain a relationship by
telephone. Believe me, we have massive phone bills, because we
speak about three times a day when we're away from each other.
 &HT;    ``Sometimes I think it may be better for him if I'm away while
I'm in a film,'' Watson continues. ``I'm a royal pain to live with
when I'm working. I'm very focused on my character, and I'm always
exhausted. In fact, the other day a photographer posed me on the
bed for a publicity shot and I feel asleep.''
 &HT;    Watson has good reason to be tired. Seizing her moment in the
wake of ``Breaking the Waves,'' she has hurled herself into a
series of movies, including appearing opposite Daniel Day-Lewis in
``The Boxer'' (1998), with Christian Bale in the upcoming
``Metroland'' and for director Tim Robbins in ``The Cradle Will
Rock.'' Currently she's in Ireland, on the set of ``Angela's
Ashes.''
 &HT;    There's renewed Oscar buzz surrounding Watson's performance in
``Hilary and Jackie,'' but the actress says that the crowning honor
has already come her way.
 &HT;    ``After we finished filming, I tried to put out of my mind
whether I had done justice to it all,'' she says. ``Then I got back
home to London and there was a message on my answering machine from
Hilary, who had just seen the film. She simply said, `Emily, you
were Jackie.'
 &HT;    ``And I just burst into a flood of tears. It was such a relief
to know that she felt that.''
 c.1998 Pentacom Productions  
