<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAITH-FORD-IN-MAGGIE-WINTERS-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MAGGIE WINTERS': A MATTER OF FAITH 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
NIRDI RELIS in New York at 212-499-3333, or by fax at
212-499-3382.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Faith Ford in a scene from ``Maggie
Winters.'' 
 By DAVID KRONKE  
 c.1998 TV Guide Canada  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Times change, and so do people.
</P>
<P>
   When Faith Ford made the jump from the lightning-paced newsroom
on ``Murphy Brown'' to the sleepy small town of ``Maggie Winters,''
her fictional world became ostensibly more simple but her character
became much smarter.
</P>
<P>
   Maggie, Ford's character, had been voted ``most likely to
succeed'' in high school, but divorce sends her reeling out of
Chicago and back to her tiny hometown of Shelbyville, Ind., where
she tends to be a step or two ahead of those around her.
</P>
<P>
   Ford can identify with Maggie's disorientation. Last year, she
was a supporting player on the long-running ``Murphy Brown.'' Now
she's starring in her own sitcom. And, like Maggie, she's recently
divorced _ from actor Robert Nottingham in 1997 _ though she's also
recently married, to writer/personal trainer Campion Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   Relaxing in her dressing room in jeans and a powder-blue
turtleneck sweater, Ford looks back cheerfully.
</P>
<P>
   ``To everyone else, this might seem like an intense year,'' she
admits, ``but it's intense in a positive way. So I'm up for
positive intensity, because I've had enough of the other kind of
intensity.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly no one would have begrudged Ford a while off with her
new husband _ they wed only a few weeks before she began
``Maggie's'' full season. But the combination of the quality of the
script and her sense of connectedness to the character sold her on
the show.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, she says, she decided to ``just jump right into this
and not brood and overanalyze, which is something I'm classically
known for doing. I thought, `This is one time I'm not going to
overthink this.'''
</P>
<P>
   She does have second thoughts, she admits. She rarely gets time
to rest in her dressing room, she says _ indeed, it's three months
since the clocks were turned back, and her VCR is still an hour
off.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you can always look back,'' Ford says with a shrug.
``Maybe it's not good to have that much time off, for me, because I
have a tendency to be an Earth girl, to really, really like that
other side that is not about acting.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I wasn't raised that way,'' she adds. ``My mother worked
my whole life. So it's so much a part of who I am that I think the
healthiest thing for me is not to have more than a couple of months
without employment.''
</P>
<P>
   The series is barely half a season old, but the performers
already have firm grasps on their characters, as evidenced by an
afternoon's rehearsal on the set.
</P>
<P>
   Tom (Brian Haley), the former high-school football star now
relegated to tending bar and reliving his past glories, has _
thanks to Maggie's meddling _ been evicted from his apartment. Lisa
(Alex Kapp Horner), Maggie's long-suffering friend whose search for
love takes her to all the wrong places, is experiencing belated _
and, to both parties involved, bewildering _ hormonal interest
toward Tom, as Robin (Jenny Robertson), their happily married and
extremely procreative pal, looks on with concern.
</P>
<P>
   The debate this afternoon is just how Lisa should approach Tom
after he has made an impassioned speech about losing his apartment,
given that Lisa herself is supposed to be somewhat ambivalent about
her attraction to Tom.
</P>
<P>
   The first runthrough, a generically sympathetic hug, conveys
little, while the second, a fierce, full-body jump into his arms,
is considered over the top.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson suggests something in-between, demonstrating an
embrace that melts into caressing Haley's face.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're a good actress,'' Haley says with a grin, and for a few
moments all three actresses take turns hugging and fondling him.
Horner rips off Haley's baseball cap and runs her fingers through
his hair, and the actor blushes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This happens every time I have to do a romantic scene _ I'm
uncomfortable,'' Horner admits.
</P>
<P>
   Haley suggests that he be oblivious to Horner's advances, more
consumed with the loss of his apartment. Horner suggests that she
realize midembrace what she's doing and then yank herself away.
</P>
<P>
   ``She loves me,'' Haley muses, ``but I'm in my netherworld, so
it doesn't register with me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Which,'' Horner adds, ``is the only reason I'm attracted to
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Robertson then suggests that Horner play the scene closer to
Haley from the outset, so that Lisa ``folds into him'' more
realistically before letting herself go. Haley offers to sit on the
sofa arm next to Horner, giving her easier access to him, and
Horner comes up with the idea of a friendly back massage that gets
out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a hug, but it's very sensual,'' she observes.
</P>
<P>
   Ford, who as Maggie rouses Lisa out of her reverie, has another
idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could lift your hands off him,'' she says, demonstrating a
mingling of distaste and embarrassment in the gesture. ``We had
hugs like that on `Murphy Brown' a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   They try it, and it looks to be a keeper.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels funnier,'' Haley says.
</P>
<P>
   Such collaborative rehearsals on ``Maggie'' are the norm, Ford
says, inspired by her experience on ``Murphy Brown.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think after doing that for so long, I could go into a
situation where someone says, `OK, now you would do this and do
that,''' she says. ``They're open to your input in forming these
characters.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford says that, while Maggie will continue to grow and be
successful in her work, the divorce will remain a key element of
the character.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's going to always have damage under there,'' the actress
says. ``What real people do is they just put it away for a while.
That's what Maggie does. She's complex without being too
neurotic.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, she adds, the series depends on Maggie not resolving
her conflicts entirely.
</P>
<P>
   ``If for one minute she's got it all together, then you don't
care anymore,'' Ford says. ``She's a person who doesn't settle.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford remains in contact with her former colleague, ``Murphy
Brown'' star Candice Bergen, from whom she's received some advice
about headlining a series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to her, `I just do the best job I can and then I let it
go,''' Ford recalls, ``and she said, `No, you can't let it go,
because you have a hit.' She keeps me very uplifted.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Ford is headed for the real town of
Shelbyville. She's been invited to be the grand marshal for its
annual parade, a prospect which excites the actress, a small-town
girl herself who believes that television has something to learn
from the Shelbyvilles of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a whole chunk of this land that's been completely
unexplored and is so interesting to me,'' she says. ``They have
real lives and real problems, but they don't dwell on them the way
they do in the city. They don't go to therapy over them _ they just
do what they have to do and move forward, and life goes on.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is considerably different from the Hollywood world that
Ford herself inhabits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly I feel fortunate with my success,'' she says. ``But
again, sometimes you look back and think, `God, what would it have
been like if I'd taken a more simple road in my life?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea what that would have been like,'' the actress
adds. ``Maybe I would've been bored, I don't know. But I guess it
takes a simple person to lead a simple life, and I guess I was just
never that simple.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (David Kronke is the Los Angeles-based senior writer for TV
Guide Canada.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
NIRDI RELIS in New York at 212-499-3333, or by fax at
212-499-3382.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) &QL; 
