<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Holiday doings at the Tiger firehouse
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIGER, Ga. _ My favorite holiday party wasn't the cocktail
reception with the reindeer ice sculpture we attended in Atlanta.
It wasn't the candle-bedecked dinner that ended in flamed pudding
drama.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Christmas potluck supper at the Tiger firehouse.
</P>
<P>
   My husband and I were lucky to be included. Not just everybody
gets invited. But our farm is just down the road from the
firehouse, and many of the 18 volunteer firemen are our neighbors.
What was so amazing about this year's party is no sooner had fire
Chief Mike Hopkins said the blessing, then the alarm sounded.
</P>
<P>
   The action was quite something to behold.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody hollered, ``It's an in-house, three alarm.''
</P>
<P>
   The firemen jumped up from the tables without taking even a
bite. Without putting even a hot roll in their pockets or taking
along a single cookie. They hurled themselves into the truck in
less than three minutes. Plates filled to the brim with homemade
casseroles were left untouched on the poinsettia print tablecloths.
</P>
<P>
   Our dinner tables, set right beside Tiger's newest sleek red
fire engine, trembled a little as the huge engines started to roar.
The red candles flickered as sirens on trucks only a few feet away
started to blare. I stopped up my ears.
</P>
<P>
   Lo and behold, the large steel doors rolled up in a grand
rippling sound, ending with staccato clanks, like an off-key
Hallelujah chorus. Lights flashed. I wanted to stand up and cheer.
But I could tell it wasn't the right thing to do. Doing your duty
is an everyday thing in Tiger. It's what's expected. Not even on
holidays is duty a big deal. I know that because my husband, John,
was born in the small mountain town. He has that salt-of-the earth
approach that tends to the basics even when frills beckon.
</P>
<P>
   The old timers around me kept right on eating their sweet
potatoes. I was too stunned to pick up my fork.
</P>
<P>
   The doors closed and the conversation buzzed on _ though each
table had several empty places. The sirens were a distant scream by
the time I took a sip of my hot cider. One of my neighbors tapped
me on the shoulder to point out the hand-crocheted ornaments on the
Christmas tree beside the huge wheel that holds the fire hoses. The
desserts beckoned _ German chocolate cake and banana pudding.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, I asked my friend, John Ruth, who's been a
volunteer fireman for seven or eight years, what time he got back
the night of the party. ``A little after 10,'' he said. ``It was a
trailer, burned pretty bad _ but nobody was hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   How many alarms for Tiger this year, I asked Ruth. ``That was
number 180,'' he replied, a count that includes auto accidents.
</P>
<P>
   The firemen, ranging in age from 18 to 70, get no pay, of
course. They are required to put in a minimum of 60 hours training
a year, but nobody keeps track of how many total hours they spend.
That's not the point. The point is why they do it. Most give a
single reason. They just like to give something back to the
community. Admirable, yes, but I had the feeling there's more. At
least for Ruth. He's approaching 70 now, but a stranger would never
guess it. He has a childlike sparkle in his eyes and the energy
level of a teen-ager. When he talks about fire fighting, he exudes
the excitement of a kid playing with a shiny new fire truck under a
Christmas tree.
</P>
<P>
   What is it, really, I said, that makes you love this?
``Action,'' he replied. ``If you don't like action, you don't want
to be a fireman.''
</P>
<P>
   Martha Ezzard is a columnist for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution. E-mail: mezzard(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
