<HEADER>
A8240 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TX-MINORITY-ENROLL29-     12-28 1265
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TX-MINORITY-ENROLL29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    College admission law has mixed results
 &HT;    By Mary Ann Roser
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A Texas law touted as a colorblind way to lure
more black and Hispanic students to in-state colleges produced
uneven results at the state's major universities and did not pack
the punch some lawmakers had expected.
</P>
<P>
   University officials said, however, that it's too soon to judge
whether Texas' effort to trump affirmative action in college
admissions is working. Many students, parents and counselors were
unaware of the 1997 law, which required state universities this
fall to admit residents graduating in the top 10 percent of their
high school class.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a story that's unfolding, and it would be difficult to
predict the end when we're just beginning,'' said University of
Texas Admissions Director Bruce Walker. But for UT, at least, ``the
top 10 percent law is heading the train in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Policymakers expected the state's most selective schools, namely
UT and Texas A&AMP;M University, to get the biggest bang out of the
law. They were among the few schools that previously rejected some
top 10 percent students. But a look at applications and enrollments
of students in the top 10 percent at those schools _ and two others
_ show mixed results and no apparent patterns:
</P>
<P>
   _UT gained applications from students in all racial groups in
the top 10 percent this fall and enrolled more from each group this
year than last year.
</P>
<P>
   _Texas A&AMP;M got fewer applications from top 10 percent students
across the board. Even so, it managed to enroll more Hispanic
students in the top 10 percent than it had the last two years. A&AMP;M
also enrolled more whites in the top 10 percent than in 1997 and
1996.
</P>
<P>
   _Texas Tech University in Lubbock got fewer applications this
fall from Asian, black and white students in the top 10 percent.
But more Hispanics applied and got in.
</P>
<P>
   _The University of Houston, which already automatically admitted
students in the top 10 percent, got more applications from
top-ranked students and enrolled slightly more from each racial
group.
</P>
<P>
   Walker and other officials suggested it would take time for
Texans to become familiar with the law, which is being watched by
other states, including California, where affirmative action also
is forbidden.
</P>
<P>
   Texas lawmakers saw the law as a way to combat enrollment drops
of African Americans and Hispanics, two groups historically
underrepresented in Texas colleges. The declines in 1997 came after
the federal Hopwood ruling ended racial considerations in
admissions.
</P>
<P>
   Because of segregation in Texas high schools, lawmakers argued
that the law would give students in schools dominated by blacks and
Hispanics a shot at enrolling at the most selective schools. Test
scores would not be considered, another advantage for blacks and
Hispanics because they generally score lower on standardized tests
than whites and Asians.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have so far is very inconclusive,'' said David
Montejano, who directs UT's Center for Mexican American Studies and
helped craft the law. ``The 10 percent plan is a framework from
which to work. What it does is shift the emphasis away from
admissions to recruitment. The key is the application rate.''
</P>
<P>
   In comparing the University of Texas and Texas A&AMP;M, UT attracts
more Asian and Hispanic applicants in the top 10 percent, while
Texas A&AMP;M draws more blacks and whites.
</P>
<P>
   At UT, 58 percent of Asians in the top 10 percent statewide
applied this fall, compared with 30 percent of Hispanics, 23
percent of whites and 14 percent of African Americans. While all of
those application percentages were higher than 1997 levels, they
were slightly lower than in 1996, the last year affirmative action
could be used.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Hispanic students who benefitted from the law was Eric
Saenz, who wanted to attend UT but had a low college entrance exam
score. His father, Benito Saenz, said the 10 percent law was a
``godsend'' for Eric, who ranked in the top 10 percent of his class
at La Joya High School in Hildago County. He was admitted to UT and
is majoring in kinesiology.
</P>
<P>
   At Texas A&AMP;M, 15 percent of all Texas black students in the top
10 percent applied, along with 29 percent of whites, 23 percent of
Hispanics and 16 percent of Asians. All of those percentages were
below the 1996 and 1997 levels.
</P>
<P>
   In the face of such varied results, the Legislature should not
tinker with the law, said its author, state Rep. Irma Rangel,
D-Kingsville, chairwoman of the House Higher Education Committee.
</P>
<P>
   She has been discouraged to learn that many students and
counselors in Texas didn't know about the law. ``How can we
implement a law when the independent school districts don't know
about it?'' Rangel asked.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent talk to about 300 high school students she
discovered only a handful had even heard of the law. ``I was very
depressed,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Rangel said Texas A&AMP;M did not attract more minority applicants
because it did not do enough outreach. But William Perry, A&AMP;M's
executive associate provost, said the school worked hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm not so sure is how much of an overall effort was made
on the part of state government and the (Texas Higher Education)
Coordinating Board to do some sort of heavy-duty marketing and
public relations campaign,'' Perry said.
</P>
<P>
   Rangel said if she proposes any change, ``it probably will be
some directive to our universities and the Coordinating Board to
not keep this matter a secret.''
</P>
<P>
   But some lawmakers are said to be mulling changes to stiffen
academic requirements because of concerns that some students in the
top 10 percent will take easy classes and not end up succeeding in
college.
</P>
<P>
   Average scores on the Scholastic Assessment Test, or SAT, of top
10 students were down a few points at UT and Texas A&AMP;M but up at
Tech. Montejano said the differences were not statistically
significant.
</P>
<P>
   Augustine Garza, deputy director of admissions at UT, said he
believes the credentials of top 10 percent students is high. He had
concerns about the capabilities of only 10 such students out of
4,607 who applied to UT this fall. Five of the 10 chose not to
enroll.
</P>
<P>
   Dartinya Harris, a Pflugerville High School graduate who won an
alumni-sponsored minority scholarship to attend UT, said adding
academic requirements sounded like a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go to a school with a curriculum that's not that
challenging, you can be in the top 10 percent and it doesn't really
say much,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Lansdowne, an Austin parent, agreed. Her daughter,
Katherine, had a 3.6 grade point average on a scale of 4.0 and 20
honors courses at the LBJ Science Academy, but did not rank in the
top 10. Katherine was denied regular admission to UT, was put on a
waiting list and ended up getting in a few days before classes
began. She dropped out in frustration after a billing snafu shut
her out of her classes.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Lansdowne said she supports diversity but thinks the law
penalizes some highly capable students, including minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Academy director Daniel Gohl said he is discussing the problem
with UT.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have students who get into some of the most highly
selective schools in the country, but they can't get into UT,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Rangel said she would fight any attempts to add more academic
requirements to the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guarantees an admission,'' she said. ``The students have
to make or break themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
