<HEADER>
A8243 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CYBERSCENE29-COX     12-28 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERSCENE29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Get tips on healthy eating for holidays
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The holidays give new meaning to the thought of being
fat and happy.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe you'd be happier still if you knew a way to eliminate
the fat and keep the happiness. You've already made it through the
first part of the holidays, but New Year's celebrations loom. You
may already have developed some bad eating habits that make those
pants you got for Christmas a little on the tight side.
</P>
<P>
   Let's turn to the Web today to get some help fighting the battle
of the holiday bulge.
</P>
<P>
   We'll start at a site called Holiday Survival Guide, where
you'll get a daily diet tip at
http://healthyideas.com/holiday/tip/. Don't look for miracle cures
here. Instead, you'll find sensible advice.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, you'll learn most of us get the lion's share of
our calories from the evening meal.
</P>
<P>
   So smart dieters try to increase what they eat at breakfast and
lunch and cut back on the food consumed in the evening. Besides
helping with your diet, you'll probably sleep better, too.
</P>
<P>
   This page has an added feature you'll appreciate. You'll find
some holiday recipes that have just the right festive touch but
that also are healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, some of the traditional New Year's food in the South is
both good for you and just flat-out good. So stock up on those
turnip greens and buy some extra black-eyed peas this year.
</P>
<P>
   Our next Web site is from a hospital, and you'll find that
hospitals are doing their best these days to keep you from becoming
an overnight guest.
</P>
<P>
   This hospital is located in Akron, Ohio, but _ operating on the
theory that folks in Akron eat just about as you do _ I'm going to
recommend you drop in on a page called Health Tips from Your
Hospital _ Holidays at
</P>
<P>
   http://www.agmc.org/health4.htm.
</P>
<P>
   Dealing with stress
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of the reasons this is a good thing to do. For
one, there's more here than just diet tips.
</P>
<P>
   While you'll find advice about eating and overeating, you'll
also find out about some other holiday health hazards, including
one you've likely mentioned to a friend in the last day or so:
stress.
</P>
<P>
   This is the most joyous time of the year, but it's also one of
the busiest. And stress and overeating go hand-in-hand for some
people.
</P>
<P>
   So take a holistic approach to controlling your eating and your
health. You'll find, for instance, ways to simplify your holiday
tasks and to take the classical medical approach of triage _
handling the most critical and worthwhile tasks and postponing or
eliminating others _ with your life in general.
</P>
<P>
   The point is that everything, when it comes to your health, is
connected. Add in the fact that each person has unique dietary
needs and quirks, and you'll see why you need an entire Web full of
information to make rational decisions about eating, at this time
or any other time.
</P>
<P>
   That's the beauty of the next site called: Sympatico:
HealthyWay: Diet &AMP; Nutrition Directory at
</P>
<P>
   http://www1.sympatico.ca
/Contents/Health/DIRECTORY/B3-C06-01.html.
</P>
<P>
   This is simply a collection of links that can take you to sites
dealing with everything from caffeine to cholesterol to health and
fitness for children. That way, using this page, you can customize
the health information you get based on your own lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
