<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEEWAX-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The last word on a scary economy
 &HT;    By Marilyn Geewax
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Only once every 1,000 years does a scribe get a chance
to remark upon life at the turn of a millennium. The rollover of
all digits in a date is an event rarer than the election of a sane
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   So starting next week, I no longer will be writing strictly
about economic issues. Instead, I'll be spending a year pondering
the dawn of a new age. But allow me to squeeze in three last words
on our economy:
</P>
<P>
   It worries me.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, I have been hearing economists say that all would
be right with the nation if only we could defeat inflation, balance
the federal budget, boost stock prices and push the unemployment
rate below 5 percent. So here we are.
</P>
<P>
   We have achieved a level of prosperity that previous generations
could not have imagined. In the early part of the century, many of
our grandparents had to stuff cardboard into their shoes when the
soles wore out. Our parents lived in 1,200-square-foot houses and
went to movie theaters in July to enjoy a bit of air conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   Today the typical new home has nearly 2,200 square feet and is
packed with appliances and comforts. We now have the highest rate
of homeownership in history, and more vehicles than people in this
country. We live longer, eat better and buy more than any
generation ever. Even poor Americans look rich relative to the
average person in Haiti, Honduras or other countries just a short
distance from our borders.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the richer we get, the more we want and the less satisfied
we seem. Our mountains of track shoes, computer games, golf clubs
and coffee makers can't quell our urge to spend more. Millions of
Americans have convinced themselves that unless both parents work
50-hour weeks, their families won't ``survive.''
</P>
<P>
   This shopping compulsion, which some economists are calling
``affluenza,'' is driving us to spend more than we earn. The U.S.
household savings rate, which was nearly 6 percent of income as
recently as 1993, has officially vanished. The Commerce Department
reported that in November, purchases of goods and services exceeded
disposable income. Rising incomes allowed the savings rate to nudge
up to a pitiful 0.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Frantic spending normally happens only after a war or
depression, when consumers rush to satisfy pent-up demands for
basic goods. But we have been enjoying 94 consecutive months of
strong growth and vigorous consumer spending. We should now be
moving into a period of heavy saving for rainy days. But we aren't
saving nearly as much as we were during the last recession.
</P>
<P>
   Warning signs
</P>
<P>
   This consumer frenzy is making us more and more vulnerable to
future economic downturns. When this growth bubble finally bursts,
we'll have scant savings to see us through for the short term. Not
only are we failing to prepare for a recession, we are not saving
for our retirement years. Long after our VCRs have been thrown into
the landfill, we will still be alive, needing medicine and food.
Will we then expect our children to support us?
</P>
<P>
   As a nation, we have achieved most of our economic objectives,
from running a federal budget surplus to vastly improving our
manufacturing productivity. But as individuals, we are failing to
reach sensible goals, such as paying off bills, investing for
retirement, saving for the next generation's education and spending
more time with loved ones.
</P>
<P>
   Unless we can find a cure for our affluenza, we may end up with
very full landfills and very empty lives in our older years.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
