<SLUG> BC-KABAT-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Commentary: So long, Norman Rockwell
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By VICKI MARSH KABAT
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Who's up for Monopoly?'' my husband called out one afternoon
during the recent holidays. Two sons rallied to the challenge; the
third was out with friends.
</P>
<P>
   They only made about two laps around the board, though, before
one son left with a friend to go to a movie, and the other son
received a phone call and also left to meet up with friends.
</P>
<P>
   My husband sat there sadly, his ``Get Out of Jail Free'' card in
his hand. I walked over and handed him a ``You Inherit $100'' card.
</P>
<P>
   ``Feel better?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   I must confess that during the holidays I hold a personal grudge
against Norman Rockwell. When he captured forever the idyllic scene
of happy, loving family gathered around a table of bounty, beatific
smiles on each cleanly scrubbed and angelic face, he put thousands
of mothers into therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Right up there with him in my book are Hallmark commercials, the
Waltons and all women's magazines. Don't even mention Martha
Stewart. What I wouldn't give to have a fully loaded glue gun and
an hour alone with her.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, we see the magazine covers, the television ads and
the greeting cards, and that blankety-blank Rockwell image starts
circling around in our heads. First thing you know, we're up to our
elbows in glitter, ribbon, cookie dough and turkey gizzards trying
to re-create ``The Perfect Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   The pressure magnifies when the first child goes off to college
and returns for the holidays. Never mind that when he was growing
up, you only cooked one or two meals a week and lunch was a
grab-as-you-can affair. Suddenly you feel compelled to whip up
steaming hot, nutritious meals at every turn.
</P>
<P>
   One turn is all I have in me. It's a sad thing when, after only
a couple of days at home, your child begins to reminisce fondly
about the dorm food at college.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a strange holiday season for us. The children are
gathered around, and yet they aren't. A friend of mine experienced
this over Thanksgiving. For days ahead she busied herself gathering
the ingredients for a wonderful meal, setting out cornucopias and
festive autumn wreaths. She bought candles for the table and dug
out the real cloth napkins. Her expectations for the Rockwell
Thanksgiving were sky-high.
</P>
<P>
   When the kids all came home the day before Thanksgiving, she was
ready. She sat attentively at the breakfast table waiting to hear
all their news, but they slept in late, grumbled grouchily when
they did get up, slurped down some coffee and then left to meet
friends. At lunch they arrived in shifts, grabbing a sandwich,
scooping up a handful of chips and waving a ``Later'' as they
headed back out the door.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the Thanksgiving meal came, she was totally
disheartened. Her idyllic family holiday had gone south, along with
all the men in her family, who were on a hunting expedition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was OK that they had other plans,'' she told me later. ``I
didn't begrudge them that. It's just that I set myself up for
something that just isn't realistic for how we live our life. Why
do we do that?''
</P>
<P>
   Why, indeed.
</P>
<P>
   As my husband and I gathered up the abandoned Monopoly game that
afternoon, we realized our lives, too, had reached a turning point.
</P>
<P>
   We no longer are the center of our children's universe. They
have friends, activities, plans. And almost none of it involves us.
Unless, of course, they need money. Then we give them a handful of
slightly crumpled, orange $500 bills and hope we never have to use
that ``Get Out of Jail Free'' card.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Marsh Kabat writes for the Waco (Texas) Tribune-Herald.
She can be reached online at VMKabat(at)aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The AMERICAN-STATESMAN, AUSTIN, TX
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-12-24-98 1006E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
