<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWATCH29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's almost 1999, and then comes the big one
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ So you wanna party like it's 1999? Well, there are
lots of folks willing to help you do just that. As millennium fever
sweeps the planet and the Internet, you can check the Web to find
out just how big the party is going to be and how you can join in.
</P>
<P>
   The Worldwide Observatory of the Year 2000
</P>
<P>
   (http://www.tour-eiffel.fr/teiffel/an2000uk/) is updated almost
daily and provides users with every millennium-related event from
the scientific to the just plain fun going on around the world. The
interactive forums allow you to send an electronic New Year's card,
talk about the Y2K problem or vote for the most remarkable people
of the last two millenniums. So far, it's a pretty interesting list
that includes Ghandi, Einstein, John Lennon and Kurt Cobain, among
others.
</P>
<P>
   Everything you always wanted to know about the millennium and
then some can be found at Countdown 2000
(http://www.countdown2000.com). Organized by topics such as
``Celebrations'' and ``Doomsday News'' (killer asteroids and so
forth), and including an online souvenir shop, Countdown2000 pretty
much contains everything you need to know to celebrate and fear the
coming century.
</P>
<P>
   At Everything2000 (http://www.everything2000.com), you'll find
trivia that's big on celebrating, surveys and the more festive
aspects of the millennium. Here you'll find countdown calendars,
screen savers, surveys and feature stories on how the world is
getting ready for the big day, plus a little sorely needed
millennium humor. The category is a little thin right now and
invites users to send in their own Year 2000 jokes and stories. The
site also boasts the best list of places to go and things to see on
Dec. 31, 1999, in the United States and around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The millennium has also provided an excellent excuse for
everyone to make lists of nearly everything that's happened in the
last 100 or 1,000 years. Fiftythings (http://www.fiftythings.com)
offers lists of cultural, environmental, musical and ordinary
things worth saving in the next millennium. The lists change every
month and include everything from bicycles to cats to the Lilith
Fair. A particular favorite is the list of jokes with the
explanation ``you gotta keep a sense of humor in the next
millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   National Geographic Online takes a very realistic look at what
the world will be like in the 21st century at
</P>
<P>
   http://www.nationalgeographic.com/features/2000/index.html. The
site's ongoing millennium coverage looks back on the century's
great explorers and inventors and takes a look ahead to the
problems of population and hunger facing the planet in the next 100
years. The National Geographic site is an educational and welcome
relief from the gloom and doom millennium sites populating the Web.
</P>
<P>
   What's New
</P>
<P>
   Healthfinder: Sponsored by the U.S. Department of Health and
Human Services, this site does a nice job of organizing the
often-confusing mass of health and nutrition information from
federal and state agencies. An exhaustive list of subjects is
covered in several sections.
</P>
<P>
   http://www.healthfinder.gov/
</P>
<P>
   IRA Corner: Stop by this helpful site to learn the basics about
IRAs, especially the new Roth IRA. Keep clicking into a long list
of related sections on all aspects of creating, altering,
inheriting or otherwise tinkering with your account(s). The FAQ
segment is particularly useful.
</P>
<P>
   http://www.smartmoney.com/ac/ira/
</P>
<P>
   Internet Stars: You want stars? You get stars. This huge index
of celebrity sites boasts links to more than 3,000 sites, with new
ones added continuously. Search alphabetically for your favorite
actor, actress, model, pop star or talk show host.
</P>
<P>
   http://www.internet-stars.com/
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
