A8249 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN29-COX     12-28 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Trying to keep cool in a flurry of runny noses
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ This column is not for the squeamish. It's
ugly and it's personal. It's about runny noses. Everybody in the
eighth grade seems to have one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ms. Schuett, (Shniff! Shluup!), I need to blow my nose
(Shluunk!).'' Understatement of the year, I'm thinking. This kid
doesn't need Kleenex, he needs a bucket. I tell him to go to the
restroom and not to come back until he's emptied his sinuses.
</P>
<P>
   What is it with kids and runny noses? When I was in the first
grade, I sat next to a boy named Arthur. He was infatuated with me
and used to send love notes and mushy valentines. I was afraid to
touch them because Arthur's nose remained in a state of chronic
drip. It dripped on his desk work, hopelessly smearing his ovals
and slants, it ran down the front of his clothes when he forgot to
wipe it on his sleeve, and in the winter when he showed up with a
muffler wound around his face - Uck!
</P>
<P>
   In second grade Arthur and I were in a play together - I was
Anna, and he was Olaf of the Fjords. We ate fish and sat with our
parents in front of the stove to keep warm. At a tender moment in
one particularly moving scene, Olaf was supposed to take my hand
and reassure me that we would survive the blizzard. Of
</P>
<P>
   course, it wasn't the blowing snow and howling wind I was
worried about. I was
</P>
<P>
   going nuts about touching Arthur.
</P>
<P>
   During rehearsals when the magic moment arrived, I was unable to
bring myself
</P>
<P>
   to do it - to take Arthur's hand. The teacher threatened to give
my part to Phyllis if I didn't shape up. I hated Phyllis. Talk
about a rock and a hard place. I loved the idea of being Anna, but
not to Arthur's Olaf. I went home and whined to my mother who in
turn had a talk with my teacher, Miss Jude. The next day at
rehearsal Miss Jude explained to the cast that since the play took
place in a cold country, my character would be wearing gloves. Man!
How do you spell R-E-L-I-E-F?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, I'm a fine one to talk. I was born with sinuses like
sewers and allergies to everything including my first boyfriend's
hair tonic.
</P>
<P>
   Each morning as I stood at the side door ready to leave for
elementary school, my mother would run through her 3-H checklist:
hair clips, homework, handkerchief (a big one of my father's that
she pinned to the front of my dress). Without my ``mop'' as the
family jokingly referred to it, I was unfit for socialization.
Once, I lost it on the way to school and the teacher caught me
wiping my nose on my petticoat. I was mortified.
</P>
<P>
   One of the serious drawbacks of a nose like mine is that air
cannot be taken in through it. All of my life I've been a
mouth-breather except once in a hotel
</P>
<P>
   room in Los Angeles. It was such a tremendous breakthrough that
I woke up my
</P>
<P>
   husband to share the moment. ``Kiss me!'' I insisted, wanting to
demonstrate that
</P>
<P>
   I could kiss and breathe at the same time rather than having to
break off mid-buss to gasp for air. His glassy-eyed stare suggested
he wasn't nearly as thrilled as I had hoped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Huh?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can breathe through my nose. Kiss me!''
</P>
<P>
   ``You woke me up at 4 o'clock in the morning to tell me you can
breathe through your nose?'' Insensitive lout. I guessed the
honeymoon was over.
</P>
<P>
   This morning I came to school prepared with a roll of paper
towels to stem the flow. Fifteen eighth graders sit facing me.
Fourteen of them are in varying stages of upper respiratory
infections. In between the snuffles, snorts, and raucous fits of
coughing, I'm trying to explain the workings of a 3-point,
5-paragraph essay. I tell them I feel like I'm trying to teach
writing in a pneumonia ward. They hack on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forget it,'' I say, finally. ``Everybody except Dan grab a
paper towel and go out into the hall and blow.'' Quite a tableau.
Fourteen kids lined up blowing their noses and snorting like bull
elephants. But it was an exercise in futility. Five minutes later
we had to do it all over again.
</P>
<P>
   Winter has just begun, I'm thinking to myself, and already we're
only getting five minutes to the blow. At this rate we'll be
finishing our essays in summer school.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Send mail to: 320
West Madison,
</P>
<P>
   Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or email: eschuett(at)nwonline.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
