<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Visions of fast-food, paintball, and learning between goal posts
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Having made the unforgivable mistake of trying to
take New Road from Valley Mills Drive to Franklin Avenue on an
early pre-Christmas evening, I had time to ponder the future.
</P>
<P>
   I had time because the traffic was backed up almost from Waco
Drive to Valley Mills, partly because the traffic signals are timed
to give maximum mobility to people on Franklin and Waco Drive. This
gives those on New Road almost none. It took five traffic-light
changes to traverse two blocks.
</P>
<P>
   The super store/restaurant explosion at New Road and Franklin
has initiated a traffic crush only seen in Waco for Big 12
Saturdays and Harley dismounts. And it's just begun. The location
already has a Super Wal-Mart, Super Kmart, Lowe's, McDonalds,
T.G.I.Fridays, Chick-Fil-A, Outback Steakhouse and a strip center
featuring Petsmart-Service Merchandise. Soon it will have a Luby's,
Der Weinerschnitzel, Jack in the Box and a Chevron convenience
store. Add to these the recent arrival of two16-screen theaters in
the Franklin corridor and you've got a grilled gridlock sandwich,
with only minimal access to comb the new and growing Wal-Mart hive.
</P>
<P>
   With Franklin Avenue designed, as a Trib story explained, ``for
truckers, not shoppers,'' you've got developments in full gallop
without the means to manage the consequences.
</P>
<P>
   But Franklin-New Road isn't the only example. In Waco schools,
we have a commitment to spend $13 million over 20 years for a new
stadium although the district isn't sure how it will pay for other
crucial classroom needs.
</P>
<P>
   And with the City of Waco we've got a crumbling recreation
infrastucture _ a dead Lions Park Pool most prominent _ leaving
children out in the street.
</P>
<P>
   I'm trying to imagine the consequences of all of these. To be
honest, I can't bear to look . . .
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 23, 2003 _ ``Rescue teams sifted through shards of asphalt
and cinder block to find survivors from the castastrophe Tuesday
when the weight of new development at New Road and Franklin caused
the earth's crust to collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``One geologist called the grand opening of the new Der Super
Weinerschitzel hot dog super store, going up where a meager hot dog
stand stood in 1998, 'the last straw, structurally.'
</P>
<P>
   ``'I figured this might happen back when the new Super Tony
Roma's plopped down there right beside the new Luther's Barbecue,
next to the new Coulters. Waco should have zoned against
high-density rib eating.'''
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 1, 2001 _ ``Parents complained today to the Waco
Independent School District administration when a first-grade
class, a kindergarten class and a multi-age class convened for the
new school year between the 10-and 30-yard lines, the 40-and
40-yard lines and the 30-and 10-yard lines, respectively, of the
district's new football palace, Paul L. TAASon Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``The district said it had to scramble because of an unforeseen
classroom space crunch. Officials said they expect students and
teachers to have temporary roofs over their heads by November.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the meantime, it's good that we installed artificial
turf,'' said a WISD source. ``This allows learning to continue in
any weather condition.''
</P>
<P>
   July 8, 2003 _ ``Waco police reported 43 more incidents Friday
night in this summer's rash of paintball drive-by shootings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Officials say the incidents stem from animosities and gang
allegiances spawned at the city's only viable youth recreation
outlet: the 45-acre Guerrilla Planet paintball complex off Highway
84.
</P>
<P>
   ``Police counter-insurgency squads armed with pepper spray have
targeted marauding packs of masked, camouflage-clad juveniles
loaded with latex.
</P>
<P>
   ``While promising to study ways to give young people more
constructive means of occupying their time, city leaders issued
this advisory to soothe a paintball-terrorized town: ``Don't leave
home without your smock on.''
</P>
<P>
   John Young's column appears Tuesday, Thursday and Sunday in the
Waco Tribune-Herald. E-mail: jyoung(at)mail.wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
