<SLUG> BC-TECH-TOOLS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    World Book Discoveries DVD brings French accent to history
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ IBM has entered the field of DVD-ROMs with World Book
Discoveries, a massive encyclopedia devoted to the student of
history and, more or less incidentally, to the student of Gallic
software design.
</P>
<P>
   Once again we encounter those wildly creative Frenchmen in whose
designs form rises like a helium balloon above the American
concepts of function.
</P>
<P>
   Discoveries is, of course, huge; it covers the contents of five
normal CD-ROMs, in which form it is also available. Being
French-designed, it is of course also beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   As I have remarked in the past, the French software designers
march to the beat of a different drum, and Discoveries presents the
beats of a great many drums, some of them so loud you can scarcely
hear the narration, but that, you will find, isn't really important
because the narration is superficial and usually is repeated in the
text.
</P>
<P>
   Discoveries is very, very big on sound, most of it signifying
nothing. In the sections on the creation of the universe, for
instance, there is a lot of eerie space music. Discussions of great
battles are accompanied by screaming, yelling and clashing of
spears, and screens on the rise of mammals on earth give rise to
disembodied grunts and snarls.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is undeniably atmospheric, but if you spend very
long at a given screen it can become annoying.
</P>
<P>
   The unifying feature of French design, of course, is
disunification, at least by the standards of U.S. software design.
If you have spent much time with encyclopedic software, you become
used to certain general traits.
</P>
<P>
   Hot spots on a screen are identified by text in a different
color, or by the cursor changing shape as it passes over the spot.
The French scoff at such consistency in the same way a Cordon Bleu
chef would sneer at an underdone sauce.
</P>
<P>
   If you consider the organization of Discoveries in layers, the
top layer is a corridor, or gallery, in which you move down an
ill-lit, portentous hall with back-lit illustrations along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Each is a portal into an era. This, certainly, is a very nice
conceit. It works pretty well, too, but below that upper layer
things seem to get somewhat unsteady.
</P>
<P>
   I could try to explain the more detailed methods of navigation
through this giant CD-ROM, but it would only confuse you because it
certainly confuses me.
</P>
<P>
   Discovering Discoveries
</P>
<P>
   Suffice it to say Discoveries is truly an adventure; you never
know what you will discover next. The basic keys _ other than
trying to memorize the little manual _ are the sometimes
hard-to-see menus at the top of the screen. These have menus within
menus within menus that will generally get you where you want to go
within a given era.
</P>
<P>
   Discoveries is aimed for the most part, it would appear, at the
grade- and middle-school level. There are, for instance, five
references to Albert Einstein, who is usually represented by a
photo showing him sticking his tongue out at the viewer. All of
these assure the reader that Einstein was one of the greatest
scientists who ever lived, the man who postulated the theory of
relativity and turned upside down our notions of the universe.
</P>
<P>
   If you need any notion of what his theories amounted to, you'll
have to go elsewhere. I could find no mention anywhere, for
instance, of the speed of light.
</P>
<P>
   You may come upon a full-screen picture, very nicely rendered,
of the Trojan Horse, and see little Trojans lowering themselves out
of its belly.
</P>
<P>
   Barely discernible over the lowering orchestral music, a woman
intones: ``Troy, in the time of the legendary heroes: The Trojan
horse.'' If you never heard this story, you may well wonder what is
going on here.
</P>
<P>
   You may well wonder for a long time, because there is no text.
Annoyed, you click on Search and search for Trojan. You find
several references, including one to the picture of the Trojan
Horse. There is, as far as I could tell, no text discussing the
Trojan Horse.
</P>
<P>
   Feeling these Frenchmen may be akin to the least desirable end
of the horse, you return to the picture, and idly passing the
cursor over a part of it and letting it rest, you see it turns into
a microphone.
</P>
<P>
   If you turn it into a microphone at the gate of Troy, you get
the beginning of the legend. If you accidentally hit the mike at
the horse's underbelly, you get the middle of it first.
</P>
<P>
   Does all this mean World Book Discoveries is a wash? Absolutely
not. The information it contains should be more than enough for any
lower-grade project, and is presented in often unique and useful
ways.
</P>
<P>
   It is ravishingly beautiful. It is entertaining. The student can
lift not only all the text and all the art and copy it into a word
processor, but the sound can be copied, too.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, it is an opportunity to see the concepts of
organization the way Inspector Clouseau understood them. And, to be
sure, I suspect French software designers get a few giggles out of
Microsoft Encarta, too.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
