<SLUG> BC-SHARP-DRIVING29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gift of driving skill is a loving present
 &HT;    By Linda Sharp
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ On Christmas Day, I was reminded that often our best
gifts are those we give away.
</P>
<P>
   At last year's Detroit auto show, I won a Skip Barber
Performance Driving School session. Having been an instructor for
the organization, I saw no reason to take advantage of the prize,
so I passed it along to my friend Norma Jean.
</P>
<P>
   Norma Jean is not a bad driver. Fact is, I always considered her
a good one, but like many women _ through constant ``friendly
driving tips'' from her husband _ she lacked confidence in her
ability.
</P>
<P>
   An impromptu lesson about how anti-lock brakes function _ in the
middle of busy Peachtree Industrial Boulevard during a driving
rainstorm _ was the final straw for Norma Jean and her husband's
driving relationship.
</P>
<P>
   She cried, ``Fine, if you think I need driving lessons, I'll get
them _ but not from you.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus the need was created for my gift. Norma Jean picked
Barber's Lime Rock, Conn., school. Aside from her husband's
``helpfulness,'' she had other reasons for attending.
</P>
<P>
   ``Secretly, I always wanted to be a race-car driver, but more
importantly I wanted to be a good, safe, street driver. As the
daughter of a trucker, I felt that I had been raised on the rules
of the road and the basics of how to survive in case of a mistake,
but I knew I lacked real confidence in my ability. I also had
something to prove to the `king of the road.'''
</P>
<P>
   Norma Jean learned a lot at Skip Barber.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came away realizing that in my California driver's ed class,
I learned how to pass a test, not how to drive a car. I now know
that what we typically know about driving, we learn through our own
personal mistakes or failures. The best part of this school was
that I was allowed to learn without the price of failure. I came
away knowing the three basic elements of driving deal with load
transfer of the contact patch (tire's grip), a vehicle's stored
energy (for every action there is a reaction) and most importantly
that there are three ways to control a car _ the brake, the
throttle and the steering wheel.''
</P>
<P>
   Her instructor took her for a ride in a Dodge Viper, where he
only used the throttle and the steering wheel. ``It made me aware
that not only are some cars more than average drivers can handle,
and that my desire to be a race-car driver was unrealistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Next they put the class through skid control in a Dodge Dakota
pickup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had never experienced a skid before. I still don't like the
sensation, but I now know that I can deal with one should it
happen. Overall, they taught me my limits behind a steering wheel.
While I know now that I will never be a racer, I came away knowing
that I really am a good driver ... but I learned there is always
room for improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   Driving is like any other skill; you have to work your way up to
a level of excellence.
</P>
<P>
   Norma Jean concluded, ``Being prepared behind a steering wheel
is more than just a gift of love, it can be a gift of life.''
</P>
<P>
   She planned on giving a course to her teen-age son and persuaded
her sister to give her 50-year-old brother-in-law and 30-year-old
son a performance driving school session as their Christmas gift
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Happy holidays and drive safely.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Sharp is a training consultant to auto manufacturers.
Write her in care of Wheels, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O.
Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. Or send comments online to
sharpdriver(at)worldnet.att.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
