<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNOBUDDY29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Careful tweaking can enhance dial-up Net connection
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There you sit, still finding wrapping paper scraps
under the couch, happy but mentally breathless after all the
holiday rush. And there's still New Year's ahead, so you can't
quite sit still.
</P>
<P>
   You have a brand-new computer, fully equipped with enough RAM
memory to run a respectable space program and with the fastest
analog modem money can buy. But dang _ using the Web is still like
running in mud, you had time to fix a turkey sandwich while the
last Web page loaded. Your cable company does not yet offer cable
modems in your area, despite the fliers that come in the mail
promising high-speed salvation soon. ISDN connections and ADSL seem
sort of excessive for a person such as yourself.
</P>
<P>
   You suspect that if your phone lines were just a little better,
you could move along faster. Maybe the 56k bps modem isn't fast
enough, but there's probably a little bit of speed left in it, if
you just knew how to tweak all the settings to get the most speed.
</P>
<P>
   So today we'll look at ways to get more from what you already
have and speed up your Internet connection. Truth is, none of this
stuff is foolproof, but maybe it will help. We'll cover a lot of
ground in a small amount of space, but maybe some of these
suggestions will start you off in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
   Let's start with the software on your computer. Most experts
agree that the default settings for connection to the Internet _
Windows 98 and 95 use a system called Dial Up Networking, called
DUN _ can be changed on many computers to create a better and
faster connection. But messing with these settings, unless you have
a propeller on top of your beanie hat, is really confusing and can
make things worse.
</P>
<P>
   That's why, if you are serious about changing these DUN
settings, you need to spend $15 on a little program called
TweakDUN. If you've read this column for a while, you can probably
count the commercial programs that I've recommended on one hand. I
don't do this very often, but I've used this program for a while
and I'm convinced it's a good one. You can order it from its makers
by going to this address on the Web _
http://www.pattersondesigns.com/tweakdun/.
</P>
<P>
   I won't go into a lot of detail because I want to save a bit of
space to talk about your telephone line and what you can do if it
has problems. But let me offer one last bit of advice. If your
modem is already connecting in the 40k bps range and up, I would
follow some of the best tech advice available: Leave things alone;
you're already doing better than 80 percent of all dial-up modem
users.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble down the line
</P>
<P>
   Now let's look at that telephone line. You have to understand
that it just wasn't made for sending and receiving data. Analog
modems are basically gadgets for tricking the telephone system by
converting the digital computer information into various squawks
and squeaks.
</P>
<P>
   There are dozens of reasons why a telephone line might not be
adequate. You can start _ if you have problems _ by calling the
telephone company. If there is audible line noise and if the
problem originates outside your home, not in the wiring inside your
home, you might get some free help. As modems have become more
common, and since many phone companies are now in the Internet
business, you may find knowledgeable help.
</P>
<P>
   If the problems are inside your home, then that wiring is your
responsibility. So a lot depends on how much it is worth to you to
fix the problem. If you have line noise you can hear, try finding
the phone junction box where the phone service enters your home.
Most of these boxes have a connection built in for connecting a
phone directly to this box. Do that and listen.
</P>
<P>
   If the line noise is absent at the box, but can be heard at your
phone, you know the problem is somewhere in your wiring.
</P>
<P>
   You'll pay $125 and up to get a professional to fix things if
the problem is in your wiring.
</P>
<P>
   (I'm not going to recommend you rewire your home yourself. I'll
figure that if you are actively considering this, you know enough
already. And if the idea sounds insane to you, then it probably
is.)
</P>
<P>
   OK, that's a start toward speeding things up and perhaps that
will hold you until you can get a cable modem or some other method
of high-speed access.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
