<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEPMOMS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New wives and husbands' ex-spouses find ways to blend families
peacefully
 &HT;    By Ricardo Gandara
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Watch Regina Arnold and Julie Thompson and you'd
think they were old high school classmates, maybe even cousins.
They were partners in scuba diving classes and homeroom moms
together. They use the same pediatrician. The affection and respect
they have for each other is something reserved for best friends.
</P>
<P>
   That's an extraordinary relationship when you consider Regina
was married to Jim Thompson, who is now Julie's husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say, 'You must be sisters.' I'll say, 'No, we just
married the same guy,'' says Thompson. They both laugh.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship is much smoother than the one at the start of
the new movie ``Stepmom,'' in which Susan Sarandon plays Jackie,
whose ex-husband marries Isabel, a vain, ambitious fashion
photographer played by Julia Roberts. It's a bumpy ride for Jackie,
who can't cope with the idea of Isabel becoming her kids' stepmom.
It gets more complicated when Jackie is stricken with cancer and
Isabel struggles in her new role as stepmom.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold and Thompson are proof that moms and stepmoms can
co-exist when they share a child. The mothers say they get along
great because their priority is 14-year-old Jhett, a son Arnold had
with Jim.
</P>
<P>
   The same can be said for Beth McQueen and Debbie Foulkes. They
co-parent 10-year-old Gillian, Debbie's daughter by Dennis McQueen,
who is now married to Beth.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kinds of relationships are powerful to children,'' says
Anna Gonzalez-Sorensen, an Austin family and marital counselor who
also is part of a blended family. She has three grown children by a
previous marriage and her husband Don has two. ``They become a
model for getting along.''
</P>
<P>
   It's crucial to the relationship between a mother and the
stepmom to have the biological parents get along. ``If Jim and
Regina did not have a good communicative relationship, my
relationship with Regina would not be possible,'' says Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold says it has helped that she and Thompson respect each
other's role in raising Jhett. ``I thought ahead about a lot of
things before dissolving my marriage to Jim, like the fact that
there would be another woman called a stepmom. Over time, we've
learned how each other feels. We have walked in each other's
shoes,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson has two other children, 3-year-old Tanner and
18-month-old Jarett, with husband Jim. Arnold has two other
children, 4-year-old Olivia and 2-year-old Madeline with her
husband, Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   In this extended family, as both women describe it, there is no
bad-mouthing by any of the parents. ``We've also put our egos and
jealousies aside,'' says Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   They've known each other a decade now and describe their
relationships with words such as ``special'' and ``comfortable''
and ``open.'' Thompson even calls Arnold one of her best friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh there are always differences, like in most families, but we
talk it out,'' says Thompson. ``There is nothing I can't talk to
Regina about.''
</P>
<P>
   The relationship has been cordial since the beginning, when
Thompson began dating Arnold's ex-husband. ``Jim would talk to me
about the women he was dating. He said Julie was the one and that
she was a keeper. So, I already knew Julie was a nice person. Jim
would also counsel me about the men I was dating,'' says Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Thompson and Arnold's relationship grew closer.
Today, they spend a lot of time together, as do their children. The
families do Easter brunch at the Thompsons every year. Every Dec.
23, the two families get together to exchange gifts and have
dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez-Sorensen says the more that divorced families blend,
the less traumatic it is for the children. ``The children are
better off,'' she says. ``From what they see, they learn
forgiveness and good will. They build a community. No one is
deprived of their mothers and fathers.''
</P>
<P>
   And they don't hate the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   Foulkes and McQueen also started on the right foot. Foulkes'
ex-husband, Dennis, came to her and told her he was in love with
Beth. ``I was pleased for him,'' says Foulkes. ``He said a lot of
good things about Beth. He said she was a Christian. I got to know
Beth for six months before they got married. In that time I was
convinced that Beth had a genuine interest in my daughter's
well-being. I respect that. She's also a very caring person and
helps her church and volunteers in the community.''
</P>
<P>
   Beth McQueen doesn't distinguish between 10-year-old Gillian and
her children, 3-year-old Madeline and 11-month-old Meredith, with
Dennis. They are expecting a third child in April. ``They are all
my children,'' says McQueen. ``Gillian even calls me mommy. She
calls Debbie mom,'' says McQueen.
</P>
<P>
   McQueen says she and Foulkes began to bond more when she started
having children. ``I think she was glad that Gillian was becoming a
big sister. Our relationship grew, and I attribute a lot of that to
Debbie being easygoing and flexible,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   The two couples don't pay much attention to the divorce decree
that says the McQueens are allowed to keep Gillian one weekday and
every other weekend. The girl now stays overnight with the McQueens
twice during the week and every other weekend. When there is a
scheduling conflict, they work it out.
</P>
<P>
   Foulkes and her ex-husband also have a civil relationship, which
helps everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez-Sorensen says the peace must be a big benefit to
Dennis. ``He has a relief that these two women are getting along
and he's not in the middle. He's a happier person for his kids and
his marriage,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Foulkes has not remarried so there is not another man in the mix
making decisions about Gillian. She and the McQueens have come to
major decisions about the girl's life. Gillian was baptized in the
Catholic faith with Foulkes' blessing. Beth is the godmother.
Gillian also attends a Catholic school, and the two families split
the tuition.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez-Sorensen realizes that making a blended family a happy
one is a challenge. She advises adults to resolve their feelings
between each other first. ``Then, get rid of the blaming and free
each other to go on with your lives,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   A mother and stepmother sometimes have to talk out their
feelings, even if it means going to a counselor. ``The biggest
things they have to do is get their egos out of the way and
remember that a child's mental health and welfare should be their
priority,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
