<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GATECH-PAGE29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Craig Page has all the right moves
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ For all the places he's lived and all the
``places'' he's been, Georgia Tech center Craig Page has shown what
he can do when he stays put.
</P>
<P>
   For one of the few times in his life, Page hasn't gone anywhere
for a while. He is a fixture at Georgia Tech, an anchor on the
offensive line. He has played 34 consecutive games since switching
from the defensive line. In that time, he has gone from an
uncertainty to All-American.
</P>
<P>
   After an outstanding season, Page started reeling in the awards:
First, it was the Jacobs Award, as the ACC's top blocker, then
first team All-American honors by the Football Writers Association,
followed by being a finalist for the Outland Trophy, being named
second-team All-American by ``Football News,'' and earning first
team All-ACC.
</P>
<P>
   That last award was the only one he had set out to achieve at
the beginning of the season, wanting to live up to being named
preseason All-ACC. This time three years ago, he was hoping someday
to be honored only as Georgia Tech's top lineman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can remember my first football banquet, watching (former
center Michael) Cheever winning offensive lineman of the year,''
Page said. ``I thought, `Wouldn't it be great to win that some
day?'''
</P>
<P>
   About that time, in Jan., 1996, Page was just getting used to
the ideas of being a Yellow Jacket and an offensive lineman.
</P>
<P>
   Tech had recruited him out of Jupiter (Fla.) High as a defensive
lineman. Coach George O'Leary, then the defensive coordinator, had
offered Page a scholarship, but had to withdraw it, he said Sunday,
when then-coach Bill Lewis ``wanted to go in another direction.''
Page decided to attend Louisville instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Lewis was wanting to wait on a recruit he had coming in
the next weekend,'' Page said. ``I told him I wasn't going to sit
around here and wait. I didn't like that very much. When I talked
to Coach Lewis he seemed aloof. He didn't seem concerned about me a
whole lot.''
</P>
<P>
   But after Page's redshirt year, coach Howard Schnellenberger
left for Oklahoma, so a big reason for Page's being there was gone.
</P>
<P>
   By then, O'Leary had taken over as Tech coach. Page was curious
to see if he was still interested. O'Leary was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still had some hard feelings for Tech,'' Page said.
</P>
<P>
   But he respected O'Leary and wanted to get to a better football
program.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was only fitting that Page move from one college. He'd
done the same in high school _ at Niceville (Fla.) High for his
first two years, Jupiter for his last two.
</P>
<P>
   As the youngest of four children, Page spent his childhood
moving from one Air Force base to another.
</P>
<P>
   He was born in the Langley (Va.) Air Force base hospital, and
has also lived in Kansas, Germany, Alabama, Texas, Alaska and
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were in Texas and had been there a couple of years, he
came up to me and said, `Dad are we getting ready to leave
again?''' his dad, Warren Page, said. ``I thought he'd had a
(problem) with a kid down the street. But that wasn't it.''
</P>
<P>
   The same kid who learned to salmon fish and snow ski in Alaska
had become acquainted with Southern football.
</P>
<P>
   His high school coaches had told him colleges would want him as
an offensive lineman, but Page was determined to stay on defense.
</P>
<P>
   He transferred to Tech as a defensive lineman and that's where
he played on the scout team. But by November '95, Page had changed
his mind. Cheever was graduating and Page hadn't seen any action in
two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to play,'' Page said. ``It was difficult at
first. I was playing with older guys and I didn't want to let them
down, be the weak spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Strength was one area where Page had always excelled, and he
remains one of Tech's strongest players. It was technique where he
had to do most of his learning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can remember in high school watching the offensive line mess
up and thinking, `How hard can it be?''' he said. ``When I moved
over I realized it's not easy. It took patience. It took time.'' As
the latest in a line of 10 All-American centers at Tech, Page's
picture will hang in the hall leading to the locker room. A
permanent gesture for the guy who's always been on the move.
</P>
<P>
   Now, his next move maybe to the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
