<SLUG> BC-MAC-REPORT-ADVISORY-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   The weekly MAC-REPORT column will not move this week.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-28-98 0959EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981228.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 10:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8275 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A29-COX     12-28 1394
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane S. Greig
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   Q: I want to know how to send a pizza to Texas from New Jersey.
Someone on my list wants a pizza from Lenny's on Chestnut Street in
Ridgewood. Any ideas?
</P>
<P>
   _M. Rogers
</P>
<P>
   A: Here is the preferred packing method from Kay Welch, owner of
Mailboxes Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Wrap the cooked pizza in plastic and bubble wrap. Enclose it in
a Styrofoam cooler with a small amount of dry ice. Pad with packing
peanuts and overnight the box. The overnight charge on a 10-pound
box will be expensive. Trick will be to find someone on the New
Jersey end to do this. Is there an area college? Can you sweet-talk
Lenny into helping you? Keep me posted.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Were you the one with a recipe for making ornaments out of
dung? _Pat G.
</P>
<P>
   A: Not exactly. Just the recipe for making centerpieces out of
cow patties. Guess you could just poke a hole for a ribbon hanger
near the top and call it an ornament. Here is the method from Pat
Beach of CalPat Ranch: Flatten patties by rubbing them on concrete.
Soak in a mixture of Elmer's Glue and water (half and half). Let
dry thoroughly (two days or so should do it). Lacquer or paint the
patties.Q: I am looking for a Nat ``King'' Cole album of Christmas
songs in Spanish. I have tried everywhere I know of. _Dot G.
</P>
<P>
   A: Closest I came was ``Cole Espanol, Vol. 2'' which can be
ordered by area record stores. Sorry, no yuletide tunes.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My 86-year-old grandfather gave me a very old velvet painting
that has been hanging in his living room ever since I can remember.
This painting means a lot to me. The only problem is there is a cut
in the painting about six inches long and I am afraid it will get
worse. I was hoping you could help me find somebody who repairs
these or has any suggestions on what I should do. This is something
that will stay with my family forever. _Joey Gutierrez
</P>
<P>
   A: You are not the only one to have a painting in need of a
little dry dock work. Supporting the velvet with additional fabric
backing may be what the piece needs. For your files, call the
American Institute for Conservation of Historic and Artistic Works
at (202) 452-9545 and ask for a free copy of ``Guidelines for
Selecting a Conservator.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Considering the political situation of the country right now,
you would be doing a great public service if you were to publish
the e-mail addresses of all national congressmen and senators. I
have tried to find Sen. Gramm's e-mail address to no avail. As
elected representatives of our government, you would think they
would want to make it as easy as possible to communicate with their
constituents. I understand the polls show the majority of the
American people are against impeachment, but the general consensus
is that our representatives are ignoring our voice. _Hector Cadena
</P>
<P>
   A: Sen. Gramm only has a fax number, a snail-mail address and a
telephone number. No e-mail. No kidding. Call Project Vote Smart at
(800) 622-SMART or visit www.vote-smart.org for the names and
addresses of representatives in any state.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am a member of a local high school's National Honor
Society. As impossible as it may sound, I would like to get Troy
Aikman to be our guest speaker at next year's induction ceremony.
Is there any way you could help me contact him or his
representative? _J.B.
</P>
<P>
   A: Requests must be made in writing on official letterhead _
maybe school letterhead. Send it to P.O. Box 630227, Irving,
75063-0227 or fax it to (972) 506-9005. No. 8 is prohibited from
autograph sessions and does not make public speeches. Hope he says
yes to your invitation.Q: Do the Heisman winner and his school both
get a trophy, or is there just one trophy? _R.M.
</P>
<P>
   A: Two trophies _ one for the winner and one for the school. The
trophy is a statue originally made by sculptor Frank Eliscu. His
model? New York University tailback Ed Smith, a former high school
buddy.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My son is the best man at his best friend's wedding. He wants
to do it right. What is expected? _C.F.
</P>
<P>
   A: A best man helps complete a groom's responsibilities. In days
of yore he guarded the couple from marauders _ of particular
importance if the groom had absconded with a bride. Here's a duty
list _ many are enumerated in Emily Post's ``Etiquette.''
Pre-wedding: Organize a groomsmen party, make a rehearsal dinner
toast, get the groom to the ceremony _ sober, in one piece.
Ceremony: Hold the bride's ring, stand with the groom, give the
groom's donation to the celebrant, sign the marriage certificate as
a witness. Reception: Mingle with guests, trouble-shoot on behalf
of the groom's family, make a toast, dance with the bride, help the
groom change clothes, return groom's wedding clothes. Honeymoon:
Arrange for transportation from reception, make sure groom has
tickets and itinerary. And, oh yes _ give the couple a wedding
present and have a great time!Q: Have you been told to have your
dryer cleaned? Not just the lint screen. I was given a dryer (used)
and a fire started due to lint buildup below the laundry screen. It
is my mission to advise people to clean dryers once a year. _A.B.
</P>
<P>
   A: General Electric customer service agrees dryer screen ducts
should be cleaned regularly. News to me. Thanks! Disconnect dryer
power. Remove the screen and use the vacuum cleaner hose to remove
lint.Q: A lady said her 70-year-old mother came to the United
States five years ago. She mentioned her mother's Social Security
and Medicare check. I thought Social Security checks were for those
who had worked and gained so many units.
</P>
<P>
   _L. Anderson
</P>
<P>
   A: ``Generally you must work and pay taxes into Social Security
in order to receive benefits,'' says spokeswoman Sandra Talbot,
``or receive benefits as a dependent or survivor of another.'' A
maximum of four credits may be earned each year. Most people need
40 credits (10 work years) to qualify. The United States has
agreements with other countries to honor work credits. Are you
certain she is not receiving Supplemental Security Income, which is
needs-based? Medicare benefits may be paid to those who
automatically qualify by receiving Social Security benefits and to
those with medical insurance, partially financed by monthly
premiums paid by those who choose to enroll.
</P>
<P>
   For details on Social Security or Medicare call (800)
772-1213.Upshot/Update/Uproar:
</P>
<P>
   _ In a panic over that ``Lost in Space'' devotee or ``Hercules''
junkie? Try something from the sci-fi collectible hot line ``800
Trekker,'' suggests reader Bill Hamlin. Popular items include the
alien key chain ($5.95), ``Area 51_ Secret Research Facility: No
Trespassing'' sign ($9.95) and Area 51 special agent's security
pass ($5.95). They are all out of the Darth Vader answering machine
tapes _ maybe for Valentine's Day? Overnight delivery available.
</P>
<P>
   _ Thinking about putting those wilting poinsettias out of their
misery? If your plants are looking a little forlorn, it may be time
to compost them or plant them. ``The Old Farmer's Almanac
Traditional Holiday Recipes'' advises poinsettias be moved to a
less prominent location _ as long as the temperature stays above 55
degrees. Keep the soil barely moist. When the danger of frost
passes, sink the pot up to its rim in outdoor soil where it will
receive morning light. Cut the top off the plant to promote
branching.
</P>
<P>
   _ Time to don tuxedos, gentlemen, and muse on the origin of the
suit that makes every man handsome. Called the equivalent of a
full-dress uniform or a penguin suit, the tux was fathered by
Griswold Lorillard, copying the Prince of Wales. The prince cut the
tails off his formal attire while visiting the warm climes of
India. Lorillard frequented the Tuxedo Club in New York. Many
followed suit (as it were) since the Lorillards were THE too-too
and much-much family of the area. Coronations to proms to New
Year's Eve, the tuxedo _ with cummerbund, braces (suspenders) and
studs _ is a winner.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane S. Greig at P.O. Box 670, Austin, Texas 78767;
(512) 445-3697; e-mail jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512)
445-3968.
</P>
<P>
   For copies of Jane's book, ``Thanks for Asking!'' _ a
compilation of more than 600 favorite questions and answers _ call
(800) 424-6291.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
