<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8281 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPCL-YEAR-BOS &LR;      12-28 0305
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPCL-YEAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTN EDITORS:  

</HEADLINE>
  
 For Immediate Release
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; 1998 was a banner year in the arts and finance, with
mega-scandals and mega-deals dominating the news. The Boston Globe
offers this look back: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   YEAR-OVERVIEW (Undated) -- Pop culture was, of course,
overshadowed by the chief executive soap opera, ``As the White
House Turns,'' in 1998. By Matthew Gilbert. 1650 words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   YEAR-SOUNDTRACK (Undated) _ It was the year of the soundtrack.
By Joan Anderman. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   YEAR-TV (Undated) -- All-news cable networks found that
Monicagate sent ratings soaring. By Don Aucoin. 500 words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   YEAR-MOVIES (Undated) -- Taking the war movie farther than ever
before, Steven Spielberg has never seemed a more authoritative
image-maker. By Steven Spielberg. 1050 words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   YEAR-TV-MCBEAL (Undated) -- ``Ally McBeal'' is TV's best drama _
if not its most watched, which, of course, is ``ER.'' By Matthew
Gilbert. 1100 words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   YEAR-POP (Undated) -- An alarming year. There's no other way to
describe which way the wind blew in the pop-music business in '98.
Steve Morse. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   YEAR-ROCK (Undated) -- There are blues-based jam bands and
tightly coiled punk bands. The octopus that is pop reaches in every
direction. By Jim Sullivan. 1190 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   YEAR-BUSINESS (Undated) -- By any measure, corporate mergers and
acquisitions dominated business news in 1998. An eye-popping $4.98
trillion worth of deals were logged by Securities Data Co. by last
week, triple the $1.6 trillion record set in 1997. (2 takes)
</P>
<P>
   For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  All stories will bear the BOS
designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
