<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD DAYS FOR DEALING; GM IN A DAZE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN R. WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When, I am often asked, is the best time to buy a car? The best
day in my book is today _ Boxing Day, the day after Christmas, when
hardly a creature is stirring or buying in any auto showroom
anywhere. Next Monday isn't bad, either.
</P>
<P>
   The week between Christmas and New Year is the last week of the
last month of the calendar year. Monthly sales quotas and the
yearly quotas are hanging in the balance, quotas that may determine
bonuses or other emoluments _ such as a trip to Hawaii or some
other grand place. To meet quotas, dealers may be willing to cut
the gross profit margins extra slim.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the dealer may have manufacturer cash incentives to
share with you, maybe on top of a customer rebate. Frequently, the
choice is the dealer's whether to go with the incentive as a
customer rebate or as the dealer's edge to pocket if he can.
</P>
<P>
   Keep in mind that excessive incentives may be the bait to make
you jump for a lousy vehicle that wouldn't otherwise sell. But
everybody seems to be offering something, even on those really good
cars.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota, for example, until Jan. 4 offers $800 on the 1999
Tacoma, up to $500 on a '99 Camry with an added tickler of $10 or
$20 for the sales manager. A '98 Camry carries a $750 incentive
plus a potentially bigger bonus for the sales manager. It's up to
the regional sales managers to set the policy on what is offered to
customers, what is apportioned dealers. But no matter who is
offered the bait, the money is still on the table _ if you know
about it. You will always know about customer incentives, but the
dealer spiffs are not widely publicized. Dealers would prefer to
offer you a piece of the dealer incentive and let you think you got
a terrific deal at his expense rather than to tell you up front how
much he has to play with. Well, wouldn't you?
</P>
<P>
   Cadillac, not exactly a luxury leader anymore, is offering
dealer/customer incentives of up to $3,000 on '99 Devilles, $2,000
on Eldorado or Seville, dealer's call on how to apportion. The '98
models command even bigger incentives, $5,000 to $6,000, a clear
case of weak demand generating big rebates. The Cadillac incentives
expire Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln, too, is offering luxury model incentives in its
Northeast region, up to $3,250 on '99 Town Cars and Continentals,
$5,000 on '98 models _ through Jan. 14.
</P>
<P>
   Hyundai took a different tack, offering $500 on '99 Accents and
$750 on '99 Tiburon and Elantra models until Jan. 4. On '98 models,
the rebates range from $1,500 to $2,000. On top of that, the
dealers are offered bonuses determined by sales volume. In the
East, it could mean an extra $750 to the dealer for each car sold
in excess of a minimum quota; on the West Coast, the dealer
incentives are even more generous.
</P>
<P>
   Subaru, too, is offering $500 to $750 customer or dealer cash on
'99 Legacy, $500 on Impreza. Rebates on '98 models range from $500
to $1,250.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan is offering dealer or customer cash (regional sales
manager's choice) of $2,000 on all 1998 models.
</P>
<P>
   Among the customer rebates listed are some interesting
variations on the theme. Ford, for example, offers hefty rebates to
customers who buy alternative fuel or bi-fuel vehicles, cars or
trucks that will stoke up on natural gas or liquid propane. A
Taurus that burns ethanol comes with a $1,000 incentive, and
college graduates who got the sheepskin between Oct. 1, 1996, and
Jan. 5, 1999, are entitled to an extra $400 discount.
</P>
<P>
   A regular source of dealer/customer incentives in effect is
Automotive News, a weekly automotive trade paper that lists them
all in the back pages.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a very good year for automobile and light truck
sales, but there are still a lot of them unsold, and this week and
next are not exactly prime times to move cars _ which is why the
bait gets so much better. Of course, your absolute best deal these
days is probably a two-year old used car that somebody else leased,
those so-called program cars.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   General Motors, if you haven't been paying attention, opened a
Buick factory in China this week, in typical GM fashion. The
factory is open but not yet ready to function, and, in the process
of the christening (if such a word is applicable in the People's
Republic), Chairman John F. Smith showed clearly what's wrong with
GM: The guy at the helm is unfamiliar with cars.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times reported Smith was to drive the first Buick
off the Shanghai assembly line but couldn't budge it _ he couldn't
find the brake. After popping the hood looking for the parking
brake, Smith was reminded that in Buicks the brake is operated by a
foot pedal.
</P>
<P>
   The factory isn't producing yet, but the opening date had been
set, and so one car had to be finished in order to save face _
whose face, we're not sure. At this point, though, GM would be
better off looking after the other end of the corporate anatomy;
the company is in serious trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The Buick plant is to build large cars with $40,000 price tags
as a way of entering the Chinese market _ I am not making this up.
In a country where the car of choice for the affluent is a
bare-bones VW and the transport aspired to by the masses is a
bicycle, how does Chairman Jack figure to justify a $750 million
investment to churn out 100,000 Buick sedans annually? Just how
many Chinese can afford a $40,000 car?
</P>
<P>
   Selling Buicks in this country is getting to be a hard sell. The
state-of-the-art Buick City plant, celebrated not long ago as the
salvation of Michigan, is gonzo. Buick production in '98 is lagging
'97 by more than 60,000 cars as of Dec. 24. How long before the
Chinese-built Buicks start showing up in American showrooms, and
some more domestic plants get phased out as ``inefficient''?
</P>
<P>
   When GM moved A-body production to Mexico, then-Chairman Bob
Stemple stood in front of reporters and swore that Mexicans were
buying them all, but Mexican-built Buicks were sitting in Virginia
showrooms across the river from where he was standing (or should
that be lying?). Mexicans were buying hardly any.
</P>
<P>
   GM has committed to investing $2 billion in China while at home
it has been so cash short that this summer it announced it was
pressing suppliers for additional discounts _ up front, in cash. If
you or I did that, it's called ``kickback'' or ``extortion.''
</P>
<P>
   GM is piling up unfunded pension liability, squeezing suppliers,
squeezing dealers, and scraping to keep a positive cash flow, but
reports have it that the company coffers are far from full. When
the economy goes limp _ as it always does in time _ the noise you
hear may be GM falling apart.
</P>
<P>
   Other automakers do not comment on the GM condition, but one
Ford executive, when pressed, ended the conversation with the
statement that Ford was looking forward to making worthwhile
acquisitions of mismanaged companies.
</P>
<P>
   What's worse managed than General Motors, once controlling more
than half the American car market, now selling itself the delusion
that it will ``lean down'' to 24 or 25 percent and the good times
will roll again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-28-98 1027EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
