<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 10:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8310 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANIMALS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-28 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANIMALS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROTECT PET FROM UNWISE EATING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VICKI CROKE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This may be the perfect moment _ as you wash down your fifth rum
ball with a belt of eggnog _ to talk about ``dietary
indiscretion.'' No, not yours _ your pet's.
</P>
<P>
   Dietary indiscretion is a clinical term, believe it or not, that
describes the propensity of some of our pets to eat things that can
be dangerous and even deadly.
</P>
<P>
   The holidays bring certain cautions. Keep the cats away from
tinsel. (They can swallow it and have intestinal obstructions.)
Keep the dogs away from chocolate. (It's toxic, baker's chocolate
and dark chocolate especially so.) But there are plenty of hidden
dangers, too, that you might not think of.
</P>
<P>
   Mushrooms in the yard, moldy food in the trash, rotting leaves,
socks, even sticks can make your pet incredibly sick.
</P>
<P>
   That's what a &UR;  &LR; Massachusetts couple discovered this month when
their two previously healthy huskies died within hours of each
other. Both had been seen rooting around in the back yard. But what
exactly killed them may never be known. Whatever they ate made them
so sick that bacteria from their digestive tracts crossed over into
the bloodstream. Once that happened, both dogs went into what is
known as ``septic shock,'' in which the body is overwhelmed by
bacteria carried in the blood to all parts of the body.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Douglas Brum, a veterinarian at Angell Memorial Animal
Hospital in Boston, says lots of seemingly innocuous things around
us can be deadly when dogs ingest them. The sepsis that the huskies
died from is not all that common, but it does happen. There are two
ways for animals to become septic. One is for a stick or some other
sharp instrument to be swallowed and perforate the stomach or
intestinal lining. The other is for something to make the dog so
violently ill with vomiting and diarrhea and to become so
dehydrated that the digestive tract breaks down.
</P>
<P>
   Dogs find all kinds of things in the garbage and get into all
kinds of trouble, Brum says. Teriyaki sticks used to skewer meat
are a common source of danger. But mold can be deadly too, Brum
says. Moldy food in the garbage and even moldy leaves can cause the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   All veterinarians who see emergency cases make two points: You
need to be on guard about what your dog or cat gets into; and,
should one suddenly have severe diarrhea or vomiting, get the pet
to the vet right away.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John Berg, chairman of the department of clinical sciences
at Tufts University School of Veterinary Medicine, is the man who
scrubs up and operates on pets to remove the strange things they've
eaten.
</P>
<P>
   Berg removes foreign bodies such as beef vertebrae (the bulk and
shape make them very dangerous), sticks, cellophane wrappers that
raw meat comes in, and bulky cloth items such as socks, hand
towels, and even pantyhose. Berg has found rocks, little plastic
toys, nipples from baby bottles, golf balls, and rocks in dogs'
intestines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some dogs are just more prone to chewing and swallowing all
kinds of stuff,'' Berg says. And though dietary indiscretion is not
specific to any breed, young puppies tend to have more of it. ``A
savvy old dog is much less likely to do something like that,'' Berg
says.
</P>
<P>
   Cats often get into what are known as ``linear foreign bodies''
_ tinsel, string, dental floss, cassette tape. Berg warns cat
owners to resist the temptation to pull a string that they see
caught in a pet's mouth. Yanking a thread that runs from a cat's
mouth down into the digestive tract can cut the bowel.
</P>
<P>
   There are so many things to keep out of animals' mouths. But it
is the holiday season, so what can we give them?
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jim McKiernan, a veterinarian at the Northside Hospital in
Hooksett, N.H., recommends carrots, plain rice cakes, and popcorn
without the butter as healthy snacks. ``But if you really want to
indulge them,'' McKiernan says, ``do it with love: Toss a ball,
take them for a walk, spend time with them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
