<DOCNO> NYT19981228.0139 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 10:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8320 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN30-CO     12-28 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: ``Bombs away!'' diplomacy backfires
 &HT;    For release, Dec. 30, 1998.
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Saddam Hussein is a bad guy. We certainly think so. We like to
think the Iraqi people also think so. But do they?
</P>
<P>
   It can be rationalized that Hussein remains in power the way
Fidel Castro does _ by eliminating his enemies before they have an
opportunity to coalesce.
</P>
<P>
   But there are those remaining who, by our actions, are so
alienated by us that they rally around the very person we see as
their oppressor.
</P>
<P>
   When we bomb Baghdad, we like to say that we are aiming strictly
at military targets, that we have nothing against the Iraqi people.
But we kill them nevertheless because they are in the way of our
incoming.
</P>
<P>
   If they hated Hussein before, they hate us even more now.
</P>
<P>
   The four-decade embargo of Cuba has similar tones. We're not
bombing Havana, but we maintain an economic policy that makes life
rough for the Cuban people. Castro still eats well.
</P>
<P>
   The 1989 invasion of Panama by the Bush administration may have
caught us a pock-faced, drug-dealing dictator in Manuel Noriega,
but at least 500 Panamanian civilians were killed in the process;
one Panama organization claims the number to be as high as 4,000.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, there are many Panamanians who hate our guts.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. foreign policy has a short leash; do what we say, or the
bombs are coming _ and they may fall anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the most recent bombing of Iraq, it was done
unilaterally. It was not by a vote of the Security Council of the
United Nations, although we said we were attacking because Iraq
wasn't honoring its obligation to the UN.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is at a crossroads. With the Soviet Union
broken up, we remain the world superpower. But any nation with
nuclear capability can be just as much a superpower as the U.S.;
just one strike is all they need.
</P>
<P>
   Our continual explanation that we have nothing against these
people and those people, that we're only trying to get rid of the
bad guy on top, rings hollow, particularly when we don't go after
the bad guy on top.
</P>
<P>
   It is painfully apparent that our most modern weapons of
destruction are not as precise as the Department of Defense would
like us to believe. The statistics on direct hits of military
targets are woeful. It is one thing to miss the target, it is
something else to hit innocent people.
</P>
<P>
   How many millions of people have we turned against us by some of
our strong-armed foreign policy, little of it successful? Saddam
Hussein and Fidel Castro still rule. What difference did we really
make in Haiti, in Somaliland, in Libya, in Lebanon?
</P>
<P>
   Also take note that the latest operation against Iraq (not
Hussein, but Iraq; Hussein wasn't targeted) cost the U.S. in excess
of $1 billion. And what was the end result? The most optimistic
report I hear is that it set back Iraq's war machine for a year.
</P>
<P>
   So do we do it again in 1999? Do we have a specific DOD budget
line item for bombing Iraq? Did we really need to do the bombing,
or did we need to nurture the bottom lines of defense contractors?
</P>
<P>
   Could a close look at one of those missiles have had ``Use
Before Dec. 31, 1998'' printed on it?
</P>
<P>
   Is the price of continuing as the self-appointed policemen of
the world getting to be too costly to the U.S., both in dollars and
stature? Perhaps the next Congress, when it gets done with the
Clinton/Lewinsky humiliation, can look into that increasingly
important issue.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
