A8321 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN30-COX     12-28 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Carville in Tel Aviv? Oy vay
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's see how many ways we can find that this is a really bad
idea: Israel's Labor Party has hired James Carville as a political
consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Carville is the Ragin' Cajun of Democratic _ and more
specifically, Clinton _ politics. He operates in two modes _
``attack'' and ``attack harder.'' Carville is not what you would
call nuanced. He is what you would call lunatic.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli politics does not lack for, shall we say, a certain
vigor _ and especially not now, with an election called in hopes it
can tidy up after Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's sour
government has flopped.
</P>
<P>
   Even an ordinary Knesset debate can crank up global warming. Add
in the fact that Israel has enough political parties for any two or
three democracies and you have a political system that cannot be
said to want for dispute or provocation.
</P>
<P>
   Bringing Carville to Israeli politics is a service along the
lines of carrying gasoline to a fire, as a hedge against it burning
itself out.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a more serious concern as well. The prospect of
political consultants who serve a U.S. administration also serving
a political party abroad is unsettling. The potential is large for
conflicts of interest and for connivance.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, the White House has often been too deeply involved in
Israeli politics. The Clinton administration all but campaigned for
Labor in 1996. You can see why. Netanyahu's Likud-led coalition is
one of the balkiest friends peace has ever had, but playing
favorites made Washington suspect with the winners.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's Labor Party is moving toward the center in the trendy
``Third Way'' manner of the Democratic Party under Bill Clinton, of
Britain's Labour Party under Tony Blair and of Germany's Social
Democrats under Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder. (Schroeder's and Tony
Blair's campaign managers have signed on with Labor, too. Is an
international party a-borning?)
</P>
<P>
   Not only has Carville been brought in, but he has in turn
involved former Clinton pollster Stanley Greenberg and media
consultant Robert Shrum.
</P>
<P>
   With Washington political consultant Steve Rabinowitz already
advising Labor chief Ehud Barak, Israel is beginning to look like
Washington East. (Likud has used Republican consultants: same
potential problem.)
</P>
<P>
   There's no great outrage here, at least not yet. Maybe the
internationalization of business and of economies inevitably
produces internationalized politics, too. Still, the muddle of
relationships and loyalties requires skeptical scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   Remember 1963's Profumo scandal? Party girl Christine Keeler (we
said ``party girl'' back then) was found to be alternately dating
(we said ``dating'' back then) British War Minister John Profumo
and Soviet military attache/KGB agent Yevgeny Ivanov. The affair
led to Ivanov's recall, Profumo's downfall and the collapse of
Harold McMillan's Conservative government.
</P>
<P>
   The problem wasn't that Keeler was having it on with Profumo or
with Invanov but with both. Mr. Carville, meet Miss Keeler.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
