<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Monday, Dec. 28, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Tuesday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SUN-POWER (San Francisco) _ If you thought San Francisco's
mega-blackout was bad, just wait until our old friend the sun turns
against us. Its next celestial fit is likely in mid-2000 _ possibly
even next summer _ and could bring continent-sized power outages
and global cell-phone screw-ups that could make the Dec. 8 blackout
look like a burned-out refrigerator light bulb. By KEAY DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   TRUE-DEATH (San Antonio) _ From Mexico City to San Antonio, the
questions gnaw at friends, family and colleagues mourning the early
December murder of the San Antonio Express-News' Mexico City bureau
chief, Philip True. Here is a complete picture of the situation. By
ROBERT RIVARD.
</P>
<P>
   FOG (San Francisco) _ Fog continues to cause a giant mess at
local airports here, causing delays of up three hours. By JIM
HERRON ZAMORA.
</P>
<P>
   GAYS _ (San Francisco) _ Survey shows why homosexuals love this
city. For all the hassles, gays here have it good, and they know
it.By CAROL NESS.
</P>
<P>
   MARY-DONOHUE (Albany, N.Y.) _ With her marriage in disarray and
her daughter in diapers, 33-year-old Mary Kenney rejected her
matriarchic mother's advice and enrolled in law school here. It was
a critical juncture in the career of the woman now answering to the
name Mary Donohue, who is lieutenant-governor-elect of New York. By
JOHN CAHERA.
</P>
<P>
   COSMETIC-SURGERY (San Francisco) _ In the wake of scores of
deaths around the country linked to cosmetic surgery, several
legislative reforms targeted to the boom in ``rejuvenation''
surgery are being considered in California. State legislators and
medical officials are calling for stricter standards. By ELIZABETH
FERNANDEZ.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DOCTORS-NICARAGUA (Posoltega, Nicaragua) _ In the cool of early
morning at a refugee camp on the outskirts of this farming town,
nurse Ann Souter of California and Dr. David Harris of Minnesota
hurry down a row of roughly built tents. They are providing health
care to dozens of families who lost their homes in the late October
flooding of Hurricane Mitch. By TYCHE HENDRICKS.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   D'ESTE-POETRY (San Francisco) _ The poetry of Jessica d'Este is
not well known outside Britain, the Continent and selected places
on the East Coast, where she recently concluded a speaking tour. It
should be. Her latest book of poetry, ``Wine, Woman and Song,''
offers a feel for the romance of the English language. By Edvins
Beitiks.
</P>
<P>
   VIETNAM-POETRY (San Francisco ) _ Up to now, books of poetry on
the Vietnam War were wrapped around separate themes: poems by the
veterans themselves, by Vietnamese, by demonstrators against the
war, by noted poets adding their own voices to the chaos. The
latest anthology, ``From Both Sides Now'' is a combination of all
those. By Edwins Beitiks.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN'S-SOCCER (San Francisco) _ Next July 4, as part of what's
being called ``The Year of the Sportswoman'' in the San Francisco
Bay area, Brandi Chastain could well be playing at Stanford
Stadium. When she's not working as an assistant coach with the
Santa Clara women's soccer team, Chastain is a key member of the
U.S. national squad. And if things break right, she and her
teammates may make the semifinals of the Women's World Cup. By
DWIGHT CHAPIN.
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ A reader writes, ``There seems
to be a contradiction in the outlook of fishermen and especially
hunters that I don't understand. (They) say they want to protect
wildlife, then they go out and (kill) something they want to
protect. Makes no sense.'' By TOM STIENSTRA.
</P>
<P>
   PRO-FOOTBALL (San Francisco) _ Awards must be given out for the
only two things that make sports watchable: Excellence and
ineptitude. By JOHN CRUMPACKER.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ARTIST-AWARD (San Francisco) _ San Francisco artist Ruth Asawa,
whose work graces museums and homes around the country, finally
receives the degree she earned 52 years ago but failed to get
because of post-World War II racism. By JULIE CHAO. &QL;
</P>
