<DOCNO> NYT19981228.0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 12:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8423 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      12-28 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1998: A YEAR OF E-MAZING EVENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ What if they throw a millennium party, and no
one comes? What if the Four Horsemen of the Apocalypse turn out to
be just parking-control officers on Cushmans? If the power fails at
the turn of the year 2000, how will we know whether it's because of
Y2K or the electric company?
</P>
<P>
   Correct. The power will come back faster if it's knocked out by
Y2K, as the millennium computer bug is known.
</P>
<P>
   The year 1998, the year of living astonishingly, has given
Americans a case of amazement burnout. We cannot be surprised
anymore. And as human beings who naturally seek stability, we fight
surprise at every turn.
</P>
<P>
   Man, there have been a lot of turns this year.
</P>
<P>
   These are just a few of the horrifying things we all have come
to accept: Housewives drive armored vehicles. Yes, the
four-wheel-drive is the new station wagon.
</P>
<P>
   Even well-dressed people talk to themselves on the street. They
shout into ever-smaller black boxes, but the technology isn't quite
as good as picking up signals directly in your fillings.
</P>
<P>
   The British are trying to reconquer America by hypnotizing our
children with multicolored creatures with televisions in their
abdomens. Older children already are fixated on overweight British
women with platform shoes and Cockney accents.
</P>
<P>
   Almost forgot. The president of the United States had pathetic
sex with a 21-year-old intern, and tried to wriggle out of it by
redefining sex and the word ``is.''
</P>
<P>
   The American people, always fuzzy on sex and grammar, gave him
record approval ratings.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton were the great president he wants to be, he wouldn't
be satisfied with merely redefining words. He'd create new ones.
</P>
<P>
   Before 1998, how many people ever heard of the word
``perjurious''? In recent months, it's been popping out the mouths
of pundits and politicians as if they were uncuddly Furbys.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton needs new words for lying, instead of ``misled,'' which
sounds too much like ``mislaid.''
</P>
<P>
   If Republicans call Clinton's grand jury testimony
``perjurious,'' he should counter by saying he was merely being
``fibacious,'' ``lietudinal'' or ``whopperatic.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone else should make a New Year's resolution never to say
anything like, ``It's not about sex. It's about lying.''
</P>
<P>
   Leave it to Americans to put the Ten Commandments in the form of
multiple-choice questions.
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't a good year for women, and I don't just mean the
feminists that Bill Clinton put through the cognitive dissonance
grinder.
</P>
<P>
   This was the year a male basketball league shut down but stayed
in business, while a women's basketball league kept playing and
went bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
   I guess you'd call this a case of women hitting the glass
backboard, if backboards weren't glass already.
</P>
<P>
   In other sports and entertainment news, 1998 was the year of the
little blue pill, endorsed by formerly cranky former Sen. Bob Dole.
We haven't heard any endorsements from Elizabeth yet.
</P>
<P>
   Well, there is an ad for Viagra in Ladies Home Journal, with the
slogan ``Let the dance begin.'' Call it the Pfizer hustle.
</P>
<P>
   HMOs don't like prescribing Viagra, though, probably because it
can lead to more expensive procedures like prenatal care or, in the
wrong dosages, divorce.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of years ago, if anyone told me Bob Dole would be doing
ads for male-potency drugs, while Bill Clinton was unzipping and
getting better ratings than Ronald Reagan, I would have said that
Larry Flynt had taken over the government.
</P>
<P>
   He did. And it's about time someone replaced Kenneth Starr with
a professional pornographer.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing is amazing anymore.
</P>
<P>
   This is the year of e-stuff. On top of e-mail, which became
e-evidence in the Microsoft case, we now have e-commerce, e-trading
and e-tailing (as in ``retailing,'' not what private eyes do).
</P>
<P>
   Christmas 1998 was the first big year for e-tailers on the
Internet, as people ordered e-toys, e-books and other e-presents
for their e-children and e-laws.
</P>
<P>
   The question is, how will the e-tailers handle e-returns? Will
people have to stand in on-line lines with their e-ceipts?
</P>
<P>
   I don't think this Internet thing has been worked out yet.
</P>
<P>
   As commerce got more virtual, and government got more unreal,
Americans have gotten back to the basics like beer, starchy food
generously infused with fat, and the passive enjoyment of large men
bashing into each other without cries of ``perjurious.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Jets-Bills football game on Dec. 19 got vastly
higher ratings than the historic impeachment vote in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   You can accuse Americans of apathy, but I say the people showed
good sense. The Jets-Bills game, unlike the Starr-Bill game, hadn't
already been going on for five years, and the outcome wasn't
determined in advance.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, 1998 is the year we had amazement beaten out of us, and
1999 could be a Groundhog Year, except with senators this time.
</P>
<P>
   Millennium, schmillennium. If Y2K shuts down the government, how
will we know?
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
