<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTIST-AWARD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTED ARTIST RECEIVES COLLEGE DEGREE MORE THAN 50 YEARS LATER 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN: Wisconsin)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIE CHAO  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In an art career spanning more than 50 years,
Ruth Asawa has received honorary doctorates and prestigious art
awards. Her work graces museums and homes around the country. Her
sculptures are found throughout downtown San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   And earlier this month, she returned to Wisconsin to collect the
bachelor of fine arts diploma she should have earned a half-century
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Asawa's academic career was interrupted by the suspicions about
Japanese-Americans that grew from World War II. Asawa was among the
110,000 Japanese-Americans sent to internment camps during the war.
Starting in 1942, she and her family were detained for six months
in Southern California and then for a year in Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   Asawa, however, was determined to get an education.
</P>
<P>
   By 1943, some internees were allowed to apply to college or get
jobs, as long as they weren't on either coast. Asawa, the fourth of
seven children, said she chose Milwaukee State Teachers College
because, at about $50 a year, ``the tuition was the cheapest.''
</P>
<P>
   She loved her classes _ painting, pottery, weaving,
jewelry-making _ and hoped to become a teacher. At the end of her
third year, in 1946, she went to see an adviser about getting
placed for a practice teaching position, a requirement for becoming
a teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said they wouldn't place an Asian,'' she said without a
trace of bitterness.
</P>
<P>
   Asawa shows no hostility toward the school (now the University
of Wisconsin at Milwaukee) that thwarted her teaching career, nor
to the system that put her and her family behind barbed wire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned to accept everything. If it doesn't happen, you go
in another direction,'' she said. ``I didn't feel the (racial)
tension that we feel now.''
</P>
<P>
   That attitude is reflected in her work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't really get involved in ethnic studies too much because
my training was European,'' she said. ``I'm working in a human way
rather than a color way. It's really an effort to find what every
human has in common.''
</P>
<P>
   Just 28 credits shy of her degree, Asawa had no choice but to
leave Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   Persuaded by some friends, she headed to Black Mountain College
in North Carolina, a now-defunct experimental arts college attended
by people who would later become some of the most famous and gifted
modern American artists.
</P>
<P>
   Asawa's classmates included artist Robert Rauschenberg, director
Arthur Penn, composer John Cage and choreographer Merce Cunningham.
As part of her laundry duty at the school, she recalls that she
made artist Willem de Kooning's bed.
</P>
<P>
   She spent three formative years at Black Mountain, which is also
where she met her husband, architect Albert Lanier.
</P>
<P>
   She moved to San Francisco in 1949, and over the next several
decades became a backbone of that city's arts and arts education
community, serving on the San Francisco Arts Commission and the
California Arts Council, and was instrumental in the creation of
the School of the Arts, a public high school in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't walk down a street in San Francisco without someone
coming up and saying (to her), `You once taught me,''' said Susan
Stauter, the school district's artistic director for secondary
schools. ``Everyone from the cop on the street to the lady ringing
the Salvation Army bell.''
</P>
<P>
   The irony is that without a college degree, Asawa couldn't get a
teaching certificate. And without that important piece of paper, no
district could officially hire her.
</P>
<P>
   She could teach only by volunteering or with outside funding,
such as through a grant. She once had to have a certified teacher
in the room with her for a summer art course, she recalled in an
even tone that is the closest to indignation she can muster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody around me says, `Why do you need the degree?''' she
said. ``But without a degree, you can't really teach in this
city.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, James DePaul became the theater director at the School
of Fine Arts at the University of Wisconsin at Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   When DePaul visited San Francisco earlier this year to conduct a
workshop at the School of the Arts, he became aware of Asawa's
connection with Milwaukee and decided something needed to be done.
</P>
<P>
   He contacted Richard Zauft, associate dean of the School of Fine
Arts, who dug up Asawa's transcripts from Milwaukee State Teachers
College, then got her transcripts from Black Mountain College,
which are archived at the University of North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Patching all her credits together, Zauft decided she had enough
for a degree, with one exception. It's another irony Asawa recounts
with a laugh: ``The only class I didn't have that was required was
sculpture.''
</P>
<P>
   But Zauft said the diploma she finally got Dec. 19 is bona fide.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't an honorary degree; it was a real degree.''
</P>
<P>
   Asawa hopes the significance of the degree will extend beyond
her own teaching career and open doors for other artists, who have
traditionally had difficulty connecting with academia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they'll recognize art as equal to the academic
subjects,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
