<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8469 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOMINICAN-HURRICANE-B     12-28 1373
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOMINICAN-HURRICANE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOMINICAN HURRICANE VICTIMS FEEL HOPE SLIP AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CINDY RODRIGUEZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JUAN DE LA MAGUANA, Dominican Republic _ In the dark,
10-year-old Nicholas Cedano can't see the hundreds of people piled
on cots and foam mattresses around him. But he can feel them.
</P>
<P>
   Each night for the past three months, he has drifted to sleep to
cries _ sometimes his own.
</P>
<P>
   On this night, screams pierce the air from an infant whose body
is dotted with a bloody rash. A man who has lost his three children
whimpers.
</P>
<P>
   Stench from the concrete latrines a few feet from the back door
fills the thick air. Mosquitoes whine around Nicholas's face.
</P>
<P>
   The child lies wedged between three brothers and his parents on
a wooden cot. Although it's hot, he wraps his tiny body in a sheet,
hoping the bugs won't bite through.
</P>
<P>
   This has been Nicholas's life since Sept. 22, when Hurricane
Georges swept through the Dominican Republic, killing more people
here than in any Caribbean nation. Then, five weeks later,
Hurricane Mitch wreaked still greater havoc on Honduras and El
Salvador. And aid to this town began to dry up.
</P>
<P>
   Three months after Georges, people here say they are forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have us here like animals,'' said Nicholas's mother,
Bertha Sidio Cedono. ``We've been left here to die.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 820 people live cramped in La Escuela de Bellas Artes,
a two-story music school that has been transformed into one of a
half-dozen shelters in this city alone.
</P>
<P>
   No running water flows at this shelter. There is no milk for the
children. No medicine. Rice and cooking oil are issued in weekly
rations.
</P>
<P>
   Some children run around naked and barefoot, mostly because
donated clothes and shoes don't fit.
</P>
<P>
   When the hurricane struck, 120-mile-per-hour winds whipped the
Rio San Juan, a river that splits upstream of Mesopotamia, a
village in San Juan de la Maguana.
</P>
<P>
   That day, the two streams converged into one gigantic raging
body, which swept away bridges in its path. Mudslides that came
from mountains miles away joined with the waters, burying people,
pets, and cattle.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-two people have died here and 243 nationwide, according to
Rafael Lopez, a spokesman for the Civil Defense office.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Cross puts the tally in San Juan de la Maguana at 76,
while many Dominicans believe more than 1,000 people have died
here, their bodies entombed by rocks and mud.
</P>
<P>
   In Mesopotamia, wooden crosses rise from mounds of earth where
corpses were hastily buried.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eight people are buried there,'' said a teenage boy, pointing
to a protrusion in the ground. ``They weren't identified. They just
stuck them in there, buried them like animals.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Warning came late
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many Dominicans accuse the government of purposely undercounting
the dead to stave off criticism that it did not warn people in
time.
</P>
<P>
   Hours before the storm, the newly appointed Civil Defense
director, Elpidio Baez, went on national TV and told his country
the eye of the storm would not pass through the Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Baez disregarded warnings from the US National Hurricane Center,
saying the center's computers had been wrong before. But as the
storm approached, he appeared again on TV, trembling. His voice
quaking, he told people to head to the nearest shelter.
</P>
<P>
   But for many, the warning came too late. In Mesopotamia, many
people refused to leave their homes as soldiers from the nearby
army station pleaded with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people didn't want to leave,'' said soldier Juan Carlos
Ferrer Polanco. ``They thought if they leave, someone would steal
what little they had.''
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin Moreta, 68, can't remember much of what happened that
day. He said he was carrying his 3 1/2-year-old grandson and
walking out of his home with two other grandchildren when the river
tore them away from him.
</P>
<P>
   He was treated at a local hospital, where doctors pumped muddy
water from his stomach. When they told him his grandchildren were
swallowed by the water, he didn't want to live.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're buried somewhere,'' he said. ``I don't know where they
could be. I wish God had taken me instead.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Repairing the damage &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The fertile fields that produce rice, beans, and plantains are
the lifeblood of Mesopotamia and many rural Dominican villages.
</P>
<P>
   The fields provide many of the few jobs available for locals. On
a good day, a crop picker might earn $6 _ enough for food. Those
who scrimp are able to buy a pair of shoes for their children every
few years.
</P>
<P>
   Georges destroyed miles of these fields. It wrecked $500 million
worth of crops, said Omar Liriano, spokesman for President Leonel
Fernandez. Total damages, including the loss of 200,000 homes, are
estimated at $3 billion, said Lopez of the Civil Defense office.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid accusations that it is pocketing the money, the
government has turned over most of the international aid _ which
included about $35 million from the United States _ to the Catholic
Church to dispense, Liriano said. Some of that aid has come from
the Dominican community in Massachusetts, a state that saw more
immigrants from the Dominican Republic last year than from any
other country.
</P>
<P>
   Liriano said the government has two main responses to Georges'
damage: build houses for those left homeless and replant crops so
that people will have jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Prefabricated ranch-style wood homes will be constructed
nationwide, he said. In San Juan de la Maguana, fields were cleared
to build 2,000 homes.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the government has built about three-dozen
temporary homes of pressed wood to house people who are now in
shelters. The structures stand on a barren field, and each is
branded ``Temporary Housing 00001,'' ``Temporary Housing 00002,''
and so on.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're working as fast as we can. We haven't forgotten them,''
said Teofilo Tejeda Puello, an engineer supervising the project.
``They're not living a desperate life.''
</P>
<P>
   Tejeda blamed the people living in the shelter for the dirty
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``They leave garbage in there,'' he said. ``They could control
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Felix Abreu, a contractor, agreed: ``They're supposed to relieve
themselves in the latrine but they go outside, right on the
ground.''
</P>
<P>
   An army officer standing nearby laughed. Later, the soldier said
what they were saying was ``not true. They're defending the
government because they work for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Less than a mile away, outside the back entrance of the shelter,
the ground is muddy. Putrid smells drift from concrete latrines,
and pools of water seem to move.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look closely,'' a woman said. ``There are worms in there.''
</P>
<P>
   A few feet away, a little girl stands barefoot in an oversized
T-shirt, eating white rice with her fingers. `I don't know what
we'll do'
</P>
<P>
   Each week, every family at this shelter gets a small bar of
soap, a box of bleach for disinfecting the floor, 5 pounds of rice,
and 2 ounces of cooking oil.
</P>
<P>
   The first few weeks, they got milk, spaghetti, and beans. Now,
they rely on friends and relatives to bring them food. Otherwise,
many say, they would die from malnutrition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're giving out the last of what we have,'' said Esperanza
Encarnacion, 38, the music school director who, for the past three
months, has been in charge of giving out food. ``If we don't get
more food, I don't know what we'll do.''
</P>
<P>
   For deeply religious Dominicans, the answer is often prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Every day, at 3 p.m., the 820 people in the shelter gather
around Madre Sol, a nun from a nearby church. Standing on the tile
floor amid dusty foam mattresses, they clutch plastic rosaries.
</P>
<P>
   In unison, they say the ending of the Hail Mary, ``. . . now and
at the hour of our death. Amen.'' A woman holding an infant places
the baby's fingers on the rosary.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Cedano stands nearby after another troubled night's
sleep, a white plastic rosary dangling around his yellow T-shirt.
Because his school was destroyed in the storm, he stays in the
shelter all day, leaving the family cot only to pray with Madre
Sol.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thinking I want God to make me an obedient boy,'' Nicholas
said. ``I want Him to save us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
