<SLUG> BC-VIETNAM-POETRY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`POETRY OF VIETNAM' IS AS MUCH HISTORY AS VERSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDVINS BEITIKS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Up to now, books of poetry on the Vietnam War
were wrapped around separate themes: poems by the veterans
themselves, by Vietnamese, by demonstrators against the war, by
noted poets adding their own voices to the chaos.
</P>
<P>
   The latest anthology, ``From Both Sides Now: The Poetry of the
Vietnam War and Its Aftermath'' (Scribner, 320 pages, $30) is a
combination of all those _ an even-handed, numbing offering of
poems you're not likely to find anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   The book was edited by Philip Mahony, a lieutenant with the New
York police, and a poet who has published two volumes of his own _
``Supreme'' and ``Catching Bodies.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``From Both Sides Now,'' Mahony has compiled an anthology
that includes veterans of the Vietnam War, the voices of Vietnamese
soldiers and refugees, orphans, war widows, and the poetry of Jeff
Miller, one of four students killed by the Ohio National Guard at
Kent State University in May 1970.
</P>
<P>
   Mahony's interest in the Vietnam War was kindled by David
Vancil's 1995 book, ``Homesick Patrol.'' With an eye toward 1998,
the 25th anniversary of the Paris peace talks, Mahony began
arranging poems of Vietnam in chronological order _ ``from the
Buddhist self-immolations of the 1960s to people getting drafted,
people in boot camp, the first experiences of the Vietnam War, the
war dragging on, the bombings, the GI's coming home ... up to the
present day with the Vietnam War memorial. The last chapter _ `Lost
in a Foreign Silence' _ is by Vietnamese poets in this country,
trying to figure out their place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most anthologies are a showcase for poets,'' Mahony said.
``But this is a document about the Vietnam War. The poets are less
important than their message. It reads like a history, start to
finish.''
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 300 poems in Mahony's anthology, ``and you
can understand every one of them,'' he said. ``Hopefully, this will
have an influence on the overall poetry scene. I had a double-edged
intention in putting this together _ to reawaken interest in the
Vietnam War, and to address the problem of elitism in poetry.''
</P>
<P>
   Reading thousands of poems, Mahony found himself ``having to
reject so many good ones ... I had to pick five out of maybe 100
poems on the Vietnam Memorial. On the other hand, I only found
three on Agent Orange. And it wasn't until a month before I
finished that I found a poem on the Gulf of Tonkin incident.''
</P>
<P>
   It was hard to pick the poem that affected him most.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strongest poems strike at something that's going on in
your life right then, and Daniel Hoffman writes about this dream of
a little boy in a rice field, burned by napalm. It's his own son in
the dream. I have a 7-year-old son, and when I read that I said,
`Oh, my God.' That poem is so haunting, so sad. I can barely read
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mahony, who has been with the New York Police Department for 18
years, said the men and women in his unit ``really don't know how
to react to the book yet. But I think they respect the effort.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For those who have touched Vietnam, in any way, ``From Both
Sides Now,'' already in its second printing, brings it back
quickly, quietly, with each turn of the page. Here's a sampling:
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FIRST ENCOUNTER
</P>
<P>
   You have stopped for a break, stand up
</P>
<P>
   to put your gear on and hear shots,
</P>
<P>
   see the flash of the muzzles.
</P>
<P>
   You have been followed.
</P>
<P>
   The whiteness of the branches
</P>
<P>
   that have been cut along the way
</P>
<P>
   tells you you're on a new trail,
</P>
<P>
   but the sergeant is a stateside G.I.:
</P>
<P>
   barracks inspections, rules and regs.
</P>
<P>
   You are probably surrounded.
</P>
<P>
   There are five others beside you.
</P>
<P>
   You are twenty-three.
</P>
<P>
   You look quickly around you:
</P>
<P>
   the sky, the trees.
</P>
<P>
   You're far from home.
</P>
<P>
   You know now that your life
</P>
<P>
   is no longer yours.
</P>
<P>
   _ Leroy V. Quintana
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PASTORAL SCENE
</P>
<P>
   When I came the rice was pale green.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's cut in the barns.
</P>
<P>
   Peasants laugh,
</P>
<P>
   I hear them, here, across the rice fields.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ho Chi Minh
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MIDNIGHT AT THE VIETNAM VETERANS MEMORIAL
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-eight thousand American dead,
</P>
<P>
   average age: nineteen years, six months.
</P>
<P>
   Get a driver's license, graduate from high school, die.
</P>
<P>
   All that's left of them we've turned to stone.
</P>
<P>
   What they never got to be grows dimmer by the year.
</P>
<P>
   But in the moon's dim light when no one's here,
</P>
<P>
   the names rise up, step down and start the long procession home
to what they left undone,
</P>
<P>
   to what they loved, to anywhere that's not this silent wall of
kids,
</P>
<P>
   this smell of rotting dreams.
</P>
<P>
   _ W.D. Ehrhart
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE MISSING IN ACTION
</P>
<P>
   Hazed with heat and harvest dust
</P>
<P>
   the air swarm with flying husks
</P>
<P>
   as men whacked rice sheaves into bins
</P>
<P>
   and all across the sunstruck fields
</P>
<P>
   red flags hung from bamboo poles.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the last treeline on the horizon
</P>
<P>
   beyond the coconut palms and eucalyptus
</P>
<P>
   out in the moon zone puckered by bombs
</P>
<P>
   the dead earth where no one ventures,
</P>
<P>
   the boys found it, the foolish boys
</P>
<P>
   riding buffaloes in craterlands
</P>
<P>
   where at night bombs thump and ghosts howl.
</P>
<P>
   A green patch on the raw earth.
</P>
<P>
   And now they've led the farmers here,
</P>
<P>
   the kerchiefed women in baggy pants,
</P>
<P>
   the men with sickles and flails, children
</P>
<P>
   herding ducks with switches _ all
</P>
<P>
   staring from the crater berm; silent:
</P>
<P>
   In that dead place the weeds had formed a man
</P>
<P>
   where someone died and fertilized the earth,
</P>
<P>
   with flesh and blood, with tears, with longing for loved ones.
</P>
<P>
   No scrap remained; not even a buckle survived the monsoons,
</P>
<P>
   just a green creature.
</P>
<P>
   A viney man, supine, with posies for eyes,
</P>
<P>
   butterflies for buttons, a lily for a tongue.
</P>
<P>
   Now when huddled asleep together
</P>
<P>
   the farmers hear a rusty football
</P>
<P>
   as the leaf-man rises and stumbles to them.
</P>
<P>
   _ John Balaban
</P>
</TEXT>
