<HEADER>
A8484 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QUAYLE-BUSH-BOS &LR;      12-28 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUAYLE-BUSH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUAYLE TWIST: PERHAPS A RUN AGAINST BUSH? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Dan Quayle, who was plucked from obscurity by
George Bush in 1988 to become his running mate, is presumed by many
Republicans to have faded from the scene. But the No. 2 man in the
Bush-Quayle administration has another idea: He is plotting a
Republican primary campaign in 2000 that could wind up as Bush vs.
Quayle.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect that the former vice president will be a serious
opponent against the former president's son, Texas Governor George
W. Bush, is tearing apart the tight-knit world of people who call
themselves ``Bushies.'' Many former aides to President Bush, as
well as some former Quayle aides, are signaling that they will back
``W,'' as Bush's son is known.
</P>
<P>
   Even Quayle's longtime chief defender, former press secretary
David Beckwith, said it would be difficult to back Quayle over
Bush. ``I think it is unlikely I would support Quayle'' if Bush
runs, Beckwith said. Similarly, the former Bush White House
political director, Ron Kaufman, said, ``The vast amount of the
Bush team are urging the Texas governor to run.''
</P>
<P>
   But Quayle insists that he is undeterred, even if it means
battling with the Bush family that put him on the national stage in
the first place. ``There will be a number of people in very
uncomfortable positions,'' Quayle said in an interview. ``That's
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle said he talked ``obliquely'' with Governor Bush last
month about the potential contest, and said he has stayed in touch
with his ``dear friend,'' former President Bush. Neither
conversation has deterred him from running, Quayle said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Quayle recognizes that a Bush-Quayle showdown would raise
questions about his loyalty. ``It will be the media's delight,''
Quayle said. ``You will have a lot of copy. I just have to do what
I know is right for myself and what I believe is right for the
party and the country.''
</P>
<P>
   The conventional wisdom among Republican insiders in Washington
is that Quayle doesn't have much of a chance. After years of facing
ridicule for everything from his spelling foibles to his attack on
the television character Murphy Brown, Quayle's reputation might be
beyond repair.
</P>
<P>
   But Quayle is counting on being underestimated. Some former
aides said the 2000 race will finally give him a chance to define
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quayle's ability to reach into the Bush donor base and Bush
operative world obviously will be hampered by George W.'s
candidacy,'' said a former Quayle chief of staff, William Kristol,
now editor of the Weekly Standard. ``But I have always thought that
Quayle has to run as the Reaganite that he is, and not as a Bushie.
Quayle can't compete for the Bush loyalists, but he can compete for
the Reaganites.''
</P>
<P>
   That is a potentially powerful argument for Quayle. After all,
for all the focus on George W. Bush, the GOP's philosophy is
influenced far more by former President Reagan than by former
President Bush.
</P>
<P>
   That helps explain why Michael D. McCurry, a former press
secretary for President Clinton, said recently that he thinks
Quayle might outlast Bush. ``If I were betting right now, and I was
a Republican, I would sort of say Dan Quayle has got a better
chance of getting farther down that road than George W. Bush,''
McCurry said at a University of Virginia forum this month. McCurry
also served as press secretary for the 1988 Democratic vice
presidential nominee, Lloyd Bentsen, who bested Quayle in a famous
debate, but lost the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle, who is described by aides as almost certain to announce
a White House bid in January or February, insists he will be a new
man as a presidential candidate. As a vice presidential candidate
in 1988, the fresh-faced, little-known Indiana senator ran into
trouble when questions were raised about whether he sought to avoid
the draft.
</P>
<P>
   His vice presidential campaign was put on a tight leash, with
many of his statements drafted by Bush aides and many of his
movements limited to small media markets. He often seemed out of
the loop and uneasy, leading some to compare his manner to that of
a deer staring into the headlights of an oncoming car.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, Quayle said he would be in charge and his image
would be different. ``It is totally different running for
president,'' he said. ``When you are No. 2, you only have to be
concerned about No. 1. When you are running for the presidency, it
is your campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle's game plan is to turn his insider status inside-out. The
former US representative, senator, and vice president plans to run
as an outsider, perhaps even noting that some of his former Bush
allies are no longer with him. Although he might be dismissed by
the inside-the-Beltway crowd, Quayle remains popular outside
Washington for his social conservatism, particularly among members
of the Christian Coalition and those who oppose abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also opposes abortion, but the Texan has implied he will do
little about it, saying that the courts have spoken. That has led
some Republican social conservatives to call for an attack on Bush
and to look for someone else to support. Bush, meanwhile, has said
he is not certain he wants to put his family through the inevitable
scrutiny of a presidential campaign, a concern that was highlighted
when House speaker-designate Robert Livingston resigned after he
acknowledged extramarital affairs.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Quayle, a number of potential GOP presidential
candidates are courting the social conservative vote, including
Senator John Ashcroft of Missouri, former Reagan adviser Gary
Bauer, and publisher Steve Forbes, who might finance his own
campaign. Another likely GOP candidate, former Tennessee Goveror
Lamar Alexander, is putting less emphasis on his antiabortion view
and might run to the middle.
</P>
<P>
   It is in every candidate's interests to declare that he will be
one part of a two-man race, and Quayle is no exception. He presumes
he will be battling Bush in the early states of Iowa and New
Hampshire. Quayle, who has spent the last year raising $6 million
for his Campaign America political action committee, has a good
base in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   In New Hampshire, meanwhile, Quayle is counting on help from
former Governor John H. Sununu, the former Bush chief of staff and
the most prominent former Bush aide likely to support Quayle. Some
Republicans have spread the word that Sununu has a grudge against
George W. Bush, who reportedly delivered the message in 1991 from
his father that Sununu had to resign as chief of staff. Quayle,
however, said reports about the younger Bush's role in Sununu's
ouster were exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   Sununu ``has been very encouraging of me running for president
in New Hampshire,'' Quayle said. Sununu himself could not be
reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   But for most Bushies, the best choice for president is George W.
Bush. Andrew Card, who was deputy chief of staff for President
Bush, wonders whether Quayle missed an opportunity by not running
for Indiana governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan Quayle clearly has a base, and he has every right to see
if his base will expand,'' Card said. ``I just think George W. has
a more expandable base.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
