<SLUG> BC-SCI-WARM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1998; RECORD HEAT, EXTREME WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So _ how hot was it?
</P>
<P>
   The hottest in at least 1,200 years, judging from analyses of
deep-sea ice cores, glacier ice, tree rings and historical
documents.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists say 1998 will almost certainly wind up as the warmest
in the 100-odd years that consistent weather records have been
kept, in the Northeast as well as worldwide. And suggestive but
less definitive evidence indicates the record would stand up much
further back than that.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just an anomaly: 1997 was the previous record-holder
for average warmth, and the decade of the 90s has been the warmest
on record, perhaps a strong portent of our future if predictions of
global warming hold up.
</P>
<P>
   And like Mark McGuire's adding nine home runs to a record that
had stood for decades, this year's temperatures bested the previous
marks by a wide margin. Worldwide, this year's average temperature
is a full degree Fahrenheit above the average for the past 118
years.
</P>
<P>
   It is the local manifestations of those higher averages that
people really notice, he said, such as the warmest winters on
record in some Northeast cities, or the astonishing run of hot
weather in Texas last summer, when the temperature topped 100 for
60 days _ 29 of them in a row. And early December, in New England
and in other parts of the country, continued the trend with a run
of unprecedented seasonal temperatures; several cities broke
all-time records for December. Recent cooling, especially last
week's bitter cold snap, may temper the month's average somewhat
for the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Globally, however, December is on track to set a record.
``December probably won't come in at quite the same level'' as the
year as a whole, said Kevin Trenberth of the National Center for
Atmospheric Research in Boulder, Colo., but ``we're still over a
quarter of a degree above the previous record.''
</P>
<P>
   That may not sound like much, he said, but ``in previous years,
we broke the record by a few hundredths of a degree, or maybe a
tenth.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Northeast _ the six New England states plus New York, New
Jersey, Pennsylvania, West Virginia, Maryland, and Delaware _ 1998
will ``most likely end up as the warmest calendar year on record,''
said Keith Eggleston, head of the Northeast Regional Climate
Center, located at Cornell University in Ithaca, N.Y. He says there
is a 96 percent chance that the regional annual record will fall,
based on records dating to 1895 and compiled from more than 100
locations.
</P>
<P>
   It was ``the warmest February on record'' for the area as well,
he said, and this month ``looks like it will be the warmest
December on record.'' January and May also ranked in the top 10
among average monthly temperatures, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Many other weather extremes have been experienced around the
world this year. The flooding of China's Yangtze river in August
left 2,000 dead and 14 million homeless. Hurricane Mitch was the
deadliest _ and the fourth-strongest _ hurricane of the century.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that amazed me about hurricane Mitch,'' said
Trenberth, ``was the amount of rainfall.'' The storm dumped 50 to
70 inches of rain in some places, he said, although firm numbers
are difficult to come by because the storm washed away some rain
gauges. That rain was the equivalent of ``the whole of Boston's
annual rainfall occurring in a few days,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Those extremes offer a hard lesson about the prospects for
global warming caused by human activities, Trenberth said. ``It's
not just the heat you want to worry about. Heat gives rise to
evaporation, which gives rise to flooding.'' And the changes in
weather patterns that bring flooding to one region often bring
drought to another, he said _ or even one extreme following the
other in the same place. For example, soon after Texas was parched
by a summer heat wave, it was swamped by severe flooding.
</P>
<P>
   Does this rising tide of record-smashing weather add up to a
stronger case for the reality of global warming?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, indeed,'' says Trenberth.
</P>
<P>
   Since the International Panel on Climate Control, a body of
1,500 climate specialists around the world, declared in 1995 that
humans' influence on climate was already discernible, he said,
``the evidence has grown stronger in several respects.''
</P>
<P>
   First, he said, ``the temperatures keep breaking records.'' And
better methods of determining past temperatures are now ``pushing
the temperature records back in time much more reliably,'' showing
how extraordinary the current warming really is.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month at a meeting of the American Geophysical
Union, a team of scientists presented evidence that 1998 will
almost certainly be the warmest year in at least 1,200 years _
contrary to some earlier claims that there was an equally warm
spell in Medieval times, from about the 9th to the 14th centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Overpeck, head of the National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration's paleoclimatology program, said his team used
``natural proxy sources, such as ocean and lake sediments, glacier
ice cores, tree rings, and historical documents'' to reconstruct
past global temperature averages. Their findings ``confirm that the
so-called Medieval Warm Period did not exist in the form of a
globally synchronous period as warm, or warmer, than today,'' he
said, adding that warm weather seen in that period was apparently
only a regional phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   The implications are important. This analysis, along with
several other recent efforts, adds to the evidence that the recent
temperature increases cannot be explained by natural climate
variations, and instead are a clear sign of human influence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our study of the Medieval Warm Period supports the likelihood
that no known natural phenomenon can explain the record 20th
century warmth,'' Overpeck said.
</P>
<P>
   Another recent study, published last month in the journal
Nature, reached similar conclusions. It compared the outcomes from
computer simulations of global climate done with and without the
inclusion of greenhouse gases added to the atmosphere by human
activities _ chiefly deforestation and the burning of fuel. The
researchers concluded that only these human activities can account
for the kinds of changes in climate that are being seen.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Wigley of the National Center for Atmospheric Research, head
of the team that did the study, said last week that contrary to the
claims of some scientists who are skeptical that global warming's
influence can be discerned, the study indicates that no other
factor, such as variations in the sun's output, can account for the
climate changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our analysis says that's not possible,'' Wigley said, while
``human activity can explain all of the variation.''
</P>
<P>
   It's possible that variations in the sun contribute to climate
changes _ perhaps including a slight warming early this century,
when human activities were less a factor _ but ``that's not enough
to explain'' the kinds of changes seen in recent decades, he said.
``Only in the last 30 years, human influence has become the
dominant factor'' in some global climate patterns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at a rather dangerous turning point,'' Wigley said,
where it is now clear that ``already our influences on climate are
actually the most important factor _ but we're turning up the knob
even further.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Prinn, director of the Center for Global Change Science
at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, is more cautious,
saying that while it is clear that human production of greenhouse
gases will cause some warming, it is too soon to know how much.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, Prinn says, even the best climate models ``do not
simulate natural variations very well.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Prinn adds, ``as far as policy is concerned, we cannot
afford to wait until we see'' clear evidence of humanity's impact,
because the impact of today's fuel burning can persist for decades,
possibly even centuries.
</P>
<P>
   If the world is indeed heading toward the kind of warming
predicted by the most dire of the present computer projections,
then the kind of weather we've been seeing will continue.
</P>
<P>
   Not that we should expect every year to break records from now
on. Trenberth points out that we can still expect considerable
variation because of natural cycles, such as El Nino events, which
contributed to the warmth this year and last. With El Nino gone for
now, he said, ``1999 is unlikely to be as warm as 1998.''
</P>
<P>
   And if next year is indeed cooler, he said, ``it's just a little
wiggle in the overall curve. We'll probably be breaking records
again a few years beyond that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
