<SLUG> BC-1999-WORLD-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YEAR BRINGS CHALLENGES, CONFLICTS AROUND THE GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Globe bureaus worldwide were asked about the most pressing
international issues for 1999. Here are their reports:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
THE UNITED STATES &QL; 
Distracted again? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While Washington's new year will be dominated by heated talk of
impeachment, officials from the State Department, Pentagon, White
House, and CIA will concentrate on something else: the crises
brewing overseas in the century's final days.
</P>
<P>
   They have plenty to consider.
</P>
<P>
   The Asian financial meltdown; instability in Russia; the
volatile mix of nuclear development and famine in North Korea;
violence between Israelis and Palestinians; killings in Kosovo;
drug-related corruption in Mexico; fighting in Angola and Congo.
Even reliable Western Europe is engaged in a trade fight with the
United States over _ of all things _ bananas.
</P>
<P>
   That there is conflict abroad is nothing new. But these days,
there is only one referee in the game _ the United States _ and
almost everyone agrees that referee is preoccupied with the fallout
of a White House sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   In six years, Bill Clinton has fashioned himself into a
peacemaker in Haiti, Bosnia, Northern Ireland, and the Mideast. But
Mideast peace is in jeopardy, nuclear weapons are proliferating,
and no one knows whether Clinton can give his undivided attention
to lead.
</P>
<P>
   In an ominous sign, Congress this year threw out the old rules
about conducting foreign policy. Even in the divisive atmosphere of
the Vietnam War, lawmakers limited themselves to criticizing
policies, not the president's motivations or personality. A week
ago, though, Trent Lott, the Senate majority leader, openly
questioned the timing of the attack on Iraq, which coincided with
the House vote on impeachment. &QL; 
_ DAVID L. MARCUS &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE MIDEAST &QL; 
Statehood for Palestine? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tremors of conflict in the Mideast will reverberate next year
around two epicenters: Jerusalem and Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   In Jerusalem, the most immediate concern is the coming April
elections. Israel's Parliament this month called for early
elections, effectively toppling Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's
government. The two leading opponents will be the Labor Party's
Ehud Barak and a recently emerged centrist, Amnon Lipkin-Shahak,
who seems to have the most momentum now. But Netanyahu, who has
cobbled together a coalition of far-right ideologues and
disenfranchised Russian and North African Jewish immigrants to
Israel, should not be ruled out.
</P>
<P>
   After the vote, May 4 looms dangerously on the horizon. It marks
the end of the five-year period agreed upon by Israelis and
Palestinians to resolve the issues surrounding a historic 1993
peace accord. It also marks the day Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat has vowed to declare an independent state.
</P>
<P>
   If Arafat declares statehood, Netanyahu has said he would
consider all previous peace agreements null and void. This
threatens peace throughout the Mideast.
</P>
<P>
   In Iraq, Saddam Hussein's fate remains as perplexing as ever. US
and British bombers launched sustained attacks earlier this month
on Iraq to retaliate for Hussein's blocking of UN weapons
inspectors. And Washington has indicated it is beginning a
longer-term strategy to try to topple Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   How to achieve this is the most vexing question in the region.
With Hussein's brutal regime tightening its grip on power amid the
desperate conditions caused by UN sanctions, the possibility of a
military coup seems remote. The United States has a long way to go
if it is trying to foster rebellion either among the Shiite
population in the south of Iraq or among the Kurdish population in
the north. And many analysts warn that even if a rebellion occurs,
its aftermath could leave Iraq torn apart along ethnic lines and
create a geopolitical vacuum that could destabilize the region. &QL; 
_ CHARLES M. SENNOTT &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
RUSSIA &QL; 
Yeltsin staggers to term's end &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The loud rock music still thumps, the woozy clients still sway,
and the dozens of inebriated teenagers at the bar still gyrate to
the music in an impromptu striptease.
</P>
<P>
   This is the Hungry Duck, Moscow's most notorious bar, where
tonight and every night, to borrow a phrase, they're going to party
like it's 1999 _ crisis or not.
</P>
<P>
   As a business, the high-flying Duck is an anomaly in Russia
after the Aug. 17 economic collapse. But in a way, the revelers are
symbolic of a country that still has not come to grips with how
serious its problems are. Ask anyone at the Duck, or anywhere in
Russia, and they will tell you that the situation is bad as always,
but manageable.
</P>
<P>
   It is not. Russia faces a budgetary crisis that could make this
year's meltdown look mild. The budget counts on billions in foreign
aid. But no one knows where that money will come from.
</P>
<P>
   By failing to service its domestic debts and allowing the
collapse of its financial system in August, Russia lost whatever
credibility it had with private investors. Russia stands to default
on the $17 billion it owes the International Monetary Fund. That
would doom Russia's already-low credit rating. With no lending and
little investment, it could be years before Russia gets better.
</P>
<P>
   Few parliamentarians, facing election in December, dare to be
perceived as cost-cutters in a nation tired of hardship. If the
government prints more money to pay its bills, hyperinflation may
cause even more social tension than Russia faces today.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow may still be partying. But 1999 could bring on the big
hangover. &QL; 
_ DAVID FILIPOV &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
ASIA &QL; 
Seeking an end to the fallout &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A year and a half since the collapse of key Asian economies,
financial instability remains the dominant issue in the region that
is home to 60 percent of the world's people. Some investors are
returning to Asia, believing that markets have bottomed out, but
many economists say the worst is not over.
</P>
<P>
   Next year could bring new attempts to prop up markets, like Hong
Kong did with its $15 billion stock-buying effort last August. If
Japan's economy continues to deflate, it could spark a new crisis
for neighboring economies, with China forced to devaluate its
currency. If Hong Kong then drops its currency peg to the US
dollar, pandemonium would strike Asian stock and property markets
and wealth would evaporate.
</P>
<P>
   With unemployment doubling last year in the worst-performing
nations, economist Eddy Lee worries the suffering will rise.
``You'll see it in terms of social unrest and instability knocking
onto political unrest,'' he said. Hong Kong and Singapore, with
higher per capita incomes than much of Europe, should adopt
unemployment insurance to cushion the blow, he said.
</P>
<P>
   China has experienced a wave of unrest and has cracked down on
dissent with arrests and trials. Indonesia is struggling with
democratic reforms, which could be scuttled by a return to military
rule or fundamentalism. Malaysia's economy has contracted, and the
government has quashed political dissent.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
