<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8496 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-1999-WORLD-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-     12-28 1525
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-1999-WORLD-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... political dissent.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The political fallout of the Asian economic crisis could be
``that autocratic governments that have failed to bring a
democratic mandate will collapse,'' said Robert McKee, chief
economist at Independent Strategy, a London-based global investment
company. &QL; 
_ INDIRA A. R. LAKSHMANAN &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
CANADA &QL; 
Unity through diversity &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Canada, 1999 will probably be a year of political
reconstruction as the beleaguered federal government in Ottawa
seeks ways to placate regional demands for more autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   Quebec's secessionists will be seeking to breathe fresh life
into a movement that took a hard hit at the polls in November's
provincial elections. Although the separatist Parti Quebecois was
returned to power, the margin of victory fell short of the mandate
Premier Lucien Bouchard had sought to pave the way for another vote
on independence.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of gaining a breathing spell, the uneasy
confederation called Canada is feeling other strains. In an odd
alliance, Quebec has joined forces with fiesty western provinces in
demanding that the federal government relinquish control over a
broad array of social programs.
</P>
<P>
   The new rallying cry of Quebec separatists and conservatives in
English Canada is ``social union,'' a vague but passionately felt
notion that Ottawa should continue shoveling tax money to the
provinces, but must stop dictating how that money is spent.
</P>
<P>
   Bouchard has suggested that ``social union'' may represent the
last, best chance of keeping the French-speaking province within a
unified Canada. But the result might be a Canada so decentralized
as to hardly count as a country.
</P>
<P>
   _ COLIN NICKERSON &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
EUROPE &QL; 
Coming together at last? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   European bankers are bound to be bullish over the century's end,
provided that the implementation of Europe's single currency goes
smoothly and a dictator doesn't continue to cast too broad a shadow
over the continent.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven of the European Union's 15 members are taking part in the
first phase of European monetary union, the most ambitious
initiative yet to create a united states of Europe. While the euro
will become the dollar of Europe, it will be virtual money in 1999,
not traded on the street but merely reflected in electronic
transactions as it is gradually phased in.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Tony Blair has his work cut out for him, trying
to convince a wary Britain that the single European currency is a
good idea. Blair will also have to spend time and political capital
in Northern Ireland, to make sure the peace process he has done so
much to foster does not fall apart.
</P>
<P>
   The coming year also will provide a revealing glimpse of
Franco-German relations. The French, who have led the EU with
Germany for the last two decades, worry that the alliance may
weaken because new German chancellor, Gerhard Schroeder, is so
preoccupied with domestic problems. Especially telling will be the
ability of the French and British to implement a Dec. 4 declaration
that called for a common European defense policy.
</P>
<P>
   As has been the case for much of this century, the looming
prospect of renewed violence in the Balkans overshadows every
European capital, which must absorb refugees and deal with the one
person held most responsible for perpetual instability in that
region: Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Like Iraq, Kosovo will be on the lips of every European foreign
minister in 1999, and it will leave a bitter taste.
</P>
<P>
   _ KEVIN CULLEN &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
AFRICA &QL; 
Stopping continental war &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Congo's history this century is about carving things up, about
unlimited riches and their pursuit by foreign interests. Europeans
and Americans did it. Now Africans are doing it.
</P>
<P>
   A rebellion that started five months ago against the fledgling
government of Laurent Kabila in the Democratic Republic of Congo
has turned into Africa's first continental war. Seven countries and
at least three foreign rebel groups are fighting in Congo. Another
seven states are poised on the periphery.
</P>
<P>
   Seven summits have failed to bring a cease-fire. Washington now
regards the war as unsolvable.
</P>
<P>
   Solving Congo's conflict means untangling antagonistic foreign
concerns. Rwanda's minority Tutsi-led government, which is fighting
alongside the rebels, regards its involvement as a matter of ethnic
survival. Hutu slaughtered nearly 1 million Tutsi in Rwanda in
1994; many of the Congo rebels are Banyamulenge, Tutsi from eastern
Congo who were denied citizenship by both Kabila and his
predecessor, Mobutu Sese Seko. Uganda, the rebels' other main
sponsor, needs an ally in Rwanda to balance the threat it faces
from Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   On the government side, Angolan troops are defending Kabila to
prevent Congo's rebels from linking with its own rebels. Zimbabwean
President Robert Mugabe backed Kabila, too, and secured lucrative
mining contracts for his close friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is how long Zimbabwe and Angola can prop up
Kabila,'' said Richard Cornwell, an expert in African conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Angola may be getting close to that point. It faces new fighting
back home, where rebels are rekindling a 35-year civil war. Despite
rising domestic instability, Mugabe refuses to support direct talks
between Kabila and the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Cornwell says, a cease-fire is the easy part. If
exhaustion and the new year silence the guns, Africa's stability
will depend on the much larger work of reconstructing Congo after
almost 40 years of post-independence plundering.
</P>
<P>
   _ KURT SHILLINGER &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LATIN AMERICA &QL; 
New dictatorial democrats &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Will Hugo Chavez's bark be worse than his bite?
</P>
<P>
   Venezuelans will start getting their answer next year, when the
former colonel begins his first year as president of Latin
America's oldest democracy. Chavez tried unsuccessfully to muscle
his way to power in a coup in 1992, but voters this month put him
in charge the old-fashioned way.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez has promised to dissolve the democratically elected
congress to create a new constituent assembly.
</P>
<P>
   His victory is not an isolated case. Last year, Bolivians
elected General Hugo Banzer as president. Banzer, who ruled the
country during a period of political turmoil from 1971 to 1974,
suspended most political activities and replaced civilian
administrators with military officers.
</P>
<P>
   One explanation offered by specialists for the resurgence of
military figures in Latin America is the growing dissatisfaction
among voters with corrupt civilian governments that have failed to
reduce poverty despite years of economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   Even in countries with seemingly safe civilian democracies, the
economic uncertainty that rippled through the region in 1998 may
continue to haunt governing parties next year.
</P>
<P>
   In Brazil, Fernando Henrique Cardoso was reelected president in
October but has been unable to get many reforms through congress.
Record-low oil prices have forced Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo
to propose the most severe budget in the country's history, just 18
months before presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   But much of Washington's attention next year will be focused on
Panama, where US troops are scheduled to complete their withdrawal
and hand over the Panama Canal by year's end. &QL; 
 &QL; 
_ RICHARD CHACON &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
UNITED NATIONS &QL; 
Fighting nuclear nightmares &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A generation of US policies designed to limit the spread of the
world's deadliest weapons collapsed with breathtaking swiftness
this year, confounding American nonproliferation experts and
raising the unhappy specter that military force may resurface as a
key deterrent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Cold War's end, the United States has combined
high-tech surveillance techniques with traditional diplomacy and
economic pressure to stop nations from acquiring nuclear,
biological, and chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
   But economic sanctions have done little to restrain nuclear
ambitions. In Iraq, 7 1/2 years of foreign occupation by remote
control cameras and UN weapons inspectors came to an end as US
bombers blew up scores of UN cameras and sensors along with the
weapons facilities they were monitoring. President Clinton said he
would rely on force to contain Iraq's weapons development, and the
Pentagon envisions a new role for tactical nuclear bombs to take
out rogue states in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Another popular post-Cold War fix _ critics call it nuclear
bribery _ collapsed in North Korea this year. In exchange for
Pyongyang's commitment to renounce nuclear weapons, the US pledged
to raise $4 billion to build two ``safe'' nuclear power plants in
North Korea. Frustrated by the slow pace of financing and
Washington's refusal to ease economic sanctions, North Korea has
begun to rebuild its nuclear weapons program.
</P>
<P>
   A cornerstone of US policy since World War II, the Nuclear
Non-Proliferation Treaty, also suffered a deadly blow. Angry that
the United States, Russia, Britain, France, and China have failed
to get rid of their own nuclear weapons, India announced its entry
into the nuclear club with an underground test. Rival Pakistan
followed suit. &QL; 
 &QL; 
_ COLUM LYNCH
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-28-98 1335EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981228.0158 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8499 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RETAIL-HOLIDAY-BOS &LR;      12-28 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RETAIL-HOLIDAY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINAL PUSH MAY MAKE HOLIDAYS A SUCCESS FOR RETAILERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; A year ago, post-Christmas sales saved the holiday season for
many retailers. The same could hold true for some merchants in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Bargain hunters have always been out in force on the day after
Christmas, and this year should be no exception. With mild weather
slowing pre-Christmas sales of apparel, many merchants have been
slashing prices since early December. Starting this week they'll be
slashing them even more.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor seems to be adding to the post-Christmas rush.
</P>
<P>
   With consumers so squeezed for time, holiday shopping peaks seem
to come later every year. Now it's gotten to the point where a lot
of shopping _ both in the malls and over the Internet _ spills into
the week after Christmas and even into mid-January.
</P>
<P>
   Cyberian Outpost, an Internet retailer of computer hardware,
software, and accessories, is one of several merchants praying for
a cold January.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's very cold outside, and you just got a new computer for
Christmas, the chances are you're thinking about buying software
and games,'' said Louise Cooper, vice president of worldwide
marketing. ``January can be a good month for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Why did on-line shopping explode this holiday season?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we've all run out of time,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A scarcity of time finally outweighed consumers' fear about
using their credit cards to make on-line purchases, she said.
</P>
<P>
   This shortage of time is having an impact on brick-and-mortar
retailers as well.
</P>
<P>
   For the past few years, Filene's has seen a steady increase in
the sale of gift certificates, something last-minute shoppers can
buy quickly.
</P>
<P>
   And these gift certificates are often redeemed in the week after
Christmas, said Filene's spokeswoman Regina Norfolk.
</P>
<P>
   If consumers are shopping later, many also seem to be focused on
value. For much of the year, many opted to stay out of department
stores and shop instead at places such as Wal-Mart or BJ's
Wholesale Club.
</P>
<P>
   In this vein, the most value-conscious of consumers now try to
outwait retailers, hoping they'll cut prices. And if that means
waiting until after Dec. 25, so be it.
</P>
<P>
   Given all this post-Christmas activity, plus the shifts in the
way consumers shop, it's too early to predict how the holiday
season will turn out.
</P>
<P>
   Based on income and stock-market gains and the low unemployment
rate, Massachusetts consumers could be expected to spend 5 to 6
percent more than last year, said Sara Johnson, chief regional
economist for Standard &AMP; Poors DRI, a Lexington forecasting firm.
</P>
<P>
   But Ken Gear, vice president of the Retailers Association of
Massachusetts, thinks local consumers will be more frugal. Local
sales should rise 3 percent, but that comes after a 7.5 percent
increase last year. ``If we did only the same as last year'' it
would still be a solid season, Gear said.
</P>
<P>
   With consumers finding different ways to spend their holiday
dollars _ on vacations, for instance, as well as on gifts, it's
becoming harder to make generalities about the season.
</P>
<P>
   Sales gains at department stores ``used to be a good barometer
for the season, but it's not necessarily as predictive now,'' said
Daniel A. Archabal, a retail analyst for the Boston office of the
Arthur Andersen consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Unseasonably warm weather has hurt some apparel merchants, but
part of the problem among these retailers may be from consumers
shopping somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of buying matching ski parkas for the family, they might
buy a digital camera, some home furnishings, or a computer that
costs less than $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   When his son was younger, Ed Siskin used to buy holiday gifts in
toy stores; now the chief operating officer of BankBoston Retail
Finance Inc. is going to places such as Circuit City looking for
computer games.
</P>
<P>
   That may explain why some traditional toy merchants seem to be
struggling this year while many consumer-electronics chains appear
to be headed for a strong holiday.
</P>
<P>
   According to industry figures, sales of video games and related
products should surge 24 percent this year to $6.3 billion, while
toy sales should rise 2 percent to $20.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Even the good fortune of some consumer-electronics giants
selling video games has to be taken in context.
</P>
<P>
   Several smaller chains closed their doors in the last year, and
their business is migrating to big chains such as Circuit City and
Best Buy Co., Siskin suggested.
</P>
<P>
   Given such changes, the best way to appraise the holidays is to
sort things out between winners and losers.
</P>
<P>
   In general, said Siskin, the ``top tier'' of retailers in most
categories is doing well, but the second tier may be falling
behind.
</P>
<P>
   The one true measure of a retailer's holiday performance is
fourth-quarter earnings, which in most cases won't be released
until February or March.
</P>
<P>
   Because they are heavily dependent on apparel, department stores
should have been hit hard by the warm weather that caused them to
slash prices on winter clothing.
</P>
<P>
   All those discounts should squeeze profits.
</P>
<P>
   But a look at Wall Street analysts' earnings estimates for
department stores doesn't reveal any clear pattern, other than that
discounters seem to be outperforming them.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts who follow J.C. Penney Co. have been slashing their
fourth-quarter estimates left and right, but those who track
Federated Department Stores Inc., operator of the Macy's chain,
have been mostly holding steady, said Charles L. Hill, research
director for First Call Corp.
</P>
<P>
   And even though about half of the 21 analysts who follow the May
Department Stores Co., which operates Filene's, have cut their
estimates in December, May is still expected to see a profit jump
of nearly 9 percent from last year.
</P>
<P>
   And according to First Call estimates, Wal-Mart and Dayton
Hudson Corp., known for its Target discount chain, are both on
track to post double-digit profit gains for the fourth quarter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
