A8503 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-WORK-BOS &LR;      12-28 1569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WORK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKAHOLICS OUT OF BALANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALISON BASS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Katherine Sanchez lived for her job. By the time she was 32,
Sanchez, who had not gone to college, had worked her way up from
receptionist to office manager of the Oakland branch of a national
elevator service company. She wrote reports, planned meetings,
supervised the secretaries, and was happy to work late when her
bosses needed her.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez was, in short, the ideal employee, according to those
who know her: a competent worker who gave her all to the job. But
when her boss suddenly took her title away _ and with it some of
her responsibilities, Sanchez went into an emotional tailspin. She
felt betrayed by people she had once called friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't stop crying on the way to work; I felt they had
stripped me of my dignity,'' recalls Sanchez, who finally left her
job a year later and was out of work for three years. ``For nine
months, I didn't go out of the house.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez's breakdown may be an extreme example. But in this era
of downsizing, as more men and women feel compelled to work longer
and longer hours, psychologists and workplace consultants say her
experience is part of a growing phenomenon: a culture of highly
competent worker bees who derive almost all their emotional
sustenance from the relationships they build at the workplace and
are devastated when that community doesn't live up to their
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Many male executives, of course, have always invested heavily in
their work, often to the point of ignoring their families, until
they become ill, or their wives unexpectedly ask for a divorce.
What's new about this phenomenon, say psychologists and
consultants, is its emergence among women workers and on so many
job levels _ secretaries, bank tellers, computer programmers,
business managers, and professionals.
</P>
<P>
   ``For many people, work has become their only source of
connection, of human community,'' says Ilene Philipson, a Berkeley
psychologist who studied this phenomenon among a group of 110
working women, including Sanchez, and reported her findings at a
recent work/family conference in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   None of the women Philipson studied had prior psychiatric
histories; none had even been to a psychotherapist. Most had worked
all their adult lives, in some cases taking time off only for brief
maternity leaves.
</P>
<P>
   These women, Philipson says, were pursuing a work ethic that
companies today encourage. As workplace consultants will tell you,
it is the people who invest most heavily in their jobs _ they are
the first to arrive at work, the last to leave, and they log on to
their computers at home _ who are most often viewed by employers as
MVWs _ most valuable workers.
</P>
<P>
   And it is precisely those workers who feel the most cheated or
betrayed when something goes wrong on the job, psychologists and
human resource managers find. They are also the ones whose
disillusionment can cause their output to plummet or plunge them
into depression and long-term sick leaves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Workaholics are not resilient workers,'' says Rosalind
Barnett, a psychologist at Brandeis and Radcliffe and coauthor of
``He/She Works.'' In several large studies, Barnett has found that
people who occupy multiple roles in the home, community, or
workplace are hardier psychologically than those who invest all
their time and energies in just one role.
</P>
<P>
   ``These men and women can better withstand the vicissitudes of
any one role because they have others to sustain them. So to the
extent that companies encourage a long work-hour culture, they are
defeating themselves,'' Barnett adds.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Ellis has seen this at play in her job as manager of
work/life programs for Sikorsky Aircraft Co., a helicopter
manufacturer in Stratford, Conn. ``The people who feel most cheated
when things don't go right are the ones who put in a lot of time,''
Ellis says. ``They say, `I've given up so much of my life, you at
least owe me a promotion or work that I want to do.' There is often
a huge disconnect in expectations between these workers and the
company.''
</P>
<P>
   In the most extreme cases, a sense of betrayal among troubled
workaholic men can end in violence, with disgruntled workers
shooting former employers and coworkers.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who react that way are so invested in their work
identity that when they don't have work to bolster their identity,
they hurt themselves or they hurt someone else,'' says Jonas
Goldenberg, who works with troubled employees as part of his job as
a social worker for an employee assistance program that contracts
with Boston area companies. ``But that is the extreme end of a
continuum that includes a great number of people who are invested
in their work to the detriment of involvement with their families
or outside interests.''
</P>
<P>
   A scattering of companies are making a concerted effort to
provide employees with tools to help them better balance their
lives. At Sikorsky Aircraft a few months ago, Ellis ran a ``life
designs'' workshop that prodded employees to examine their lives
and reorganize their priorities.
</P>
<P>
   But many employers are slow to recognize this emerging reality,
she and others say. The hidden cost can be found in the rise in
worker's compensation claims filed because of work-related stress
or depression and in the booming business that outplacement firms
are doing despite a robust economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the reasons that outplacement businesses are booming is
because many of them spend time building people's egos back up and
letting them know they are not bad people just because they've lost
their jobs,'' says Deborah Swiss, a Boston area management
consultant and author of the book, ``Women Breaking Through.''
``People today have a huge amount of ego invested in their jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Work is where you spend most of your time so for many of us;
the relationships at work tend to take on more emotional meaning
than the ones at home. It's where your heart is,'' says William
Pollack, a psychologist and principal in Spectrum Organizational
Executive Development, a psychological consulting firm in
Brookline. ``So if something bad happens at work, it's like your
spouse has divorced you or your mother and father have abandoned
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Work, of course, can be highly rewarding, even therapeutic, and
many people, particularly professionals who are in control of what
they do, can juggle extremely long hours without putting too many
emotional eggs in the office basket.
</P>
<P>
   But, psychologists say, there is a growing group of workaholics
who are at particular risk: men and women who don't have solid ties
to family, friends, or activities outside of work. For many of
these people, the company has replaced traditional institutions
such as family, church, the Rotary or PTO in fulfilling their needs
for recognition and community.
</P>
<P>
   This shift has been especially dramatic for women, as more and
more enter the paid work force. For many women, work has become the
center of their lives, ``a place of intrigue, gossip, friendships,
and jealousies,'' Philipson says.
</P>
<P>
   It provides an emotional landscape more real than any place
else.
</P>
<P>
   Work filled that need for Katherine Sanchez. A third-generation
Mexican-American whose parents both worked, Sanchez went to work as
soon as she graduated from high school. She took only brief
maternity leaves when she had her two children. After working in a
series of doctors' offices as a receptionist, Sanchez says, she
landed the job with the elevator company in her late 20s and began
working her way up.
</P>
<P>
   This job, Sanchez says, was going to be her ticket to corporate
America. So she gave it her all, routinely working more than 40
hours a week, staying late to finish last-minute assignments, and
filling in for other secretaries who were out sick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the more I gave, the better I would look,'' Sanchez,
now 42, recalls. ``I poured myself into my job.''
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't enough. After nine years with the company, the
branch manager whom she thought was a friend unexpectedly took away
Sanchez' title two months after she had been given a raise, she
says. Her boss told her she needed to be ``humbled,'' Sanchez says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was devastated,'' says Sanchez, adding that even her divorce
a few years earlier had not hit her as hard. ``I felt dead at work.
I had trusted these people and they betrayed me. To this day, I
have trouble trusting other people.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez says she was eventually referred to Philipson, who began
seeing her in group therapy and encouraged her to file a workers
compensation claim for work-related stress. She won the claim and
began a disability leave. She never went back to that job.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez now works for herself; she owns a secretarial
transcription service. The pressures to work long hours and please
clients are still there, she says, but she has learned how to
decline a job when it conflicts with her family time (her children
are now 14 and 12). And she has also become active in her
neighborhood, helping the police implement community policing and
improve relations with Hispanic residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had been so wrapped up in work I didn't know how to be a
mom,'' Sanchez says. ``But as far as my kids are concerned, we're
all stronger for it. They see how important it is not to make your
job your identity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-28-98 1339EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981228.0161 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8506 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ADULTERY-IMAGE-BOS &LR;      12-28 1485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADULTERY-IMAGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNFAITHFUL SERVANTS, UNFAITHFUL SELVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When pornographer Larry Flynt appears to take the moral high
ground by outing politicians for extramarital affairs, we are in a
very strange place indeed.
</P>
<P>
   The House of Representatives' speaker-elect, Republican Bob
Livingston of Louisiana, was only the first victim of Flynt's
campaign to out philandering legislative leaders by offering
informants a $1 million reward. The publisher of Hustler magazine
promises more exposes _ perhaps as many as a dozen _ very soon.
</P>
<P>
   When Livingston abandoned both the imminent speakership and his
seat because he was forced to confess marital infidelities, he put
the sex issue on the table in a way that President Clinton's
dalliance with Monica S. Lewinsky never did. The resignation raised
the possibility that politicians will, by their own estimation,
have to pass the ``adultery test'' to serve.
</P>
<P>
   So changed is the atmosphere that some politicians _ Dan Quayle
among them _ felt compelled last week to boldly proclaim they can
``pass'' the test. So changed, that now reasonable people debate
whether marital fidelity is a requisite for being a good
politician.
</P>
<P>
   There's been a lot of talk about adultery, but somewhat less
light shed on what we really know about the act that can destroy a
career as well as a marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Many people believe that a majority of Americans are unfaithful
during their marriages. But that impression comes from studies
drawn on a less-than-representative sampling.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, not as many people commit adultery as one might think.
In a 1994 University of Chicago study _ considered to be the most
accurate of its kind _ reseachers surveyed a representative sample
of the population by asking more than 3,000 people between the ages
of 18 and 59 about sex. The survey found that 25 percent of all
married men and about 15 percent of married women acknowledged
having an affair at some point in their marriage.
</P>
<P>
   The findings differed among the various age groups surveyed.
Some 37 percent of the men born in the decade between 1933 and 1942
had at least one affair, says Edward Laumann, a University of
Chicago sociologist who led the study.
</P>
<P>
   Laumann also found that more than 90 percent of the respondents
said an extramarital affair was morally wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Another ``truth'' about adultery: Politicians are more inclined
to infidelity than the rest of us. Laumann's survey found that
``physical vitality, sexual interest, social competence, and social
opportunity are the things that drive sexual expression.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Politicians,'' he says, ``are obviously selected for their
social competence, and if their sexual interest is high, the social
opportunity is there.''
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Washington and Hollywood are the two US cities with
the most macho culture and desirable, powerful men who are
surrounded by women, says John Gagnon, professor emeritus of
sociology at the State University of New York at Stony Brook, who
also worked on the study.
</P>
<P>
   ``Henry Kissinger said power is the greatest aphrodisiac and he
should know,'' Gagnon says.
</P>
<P>
   Taken together, those factors may partially explain the
extramarital affairs of President Clinton, Livingston, and a host
of others, known and unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Here's another ``truth'' about adultery that goes against what
many believe: It doesn't make you happy. Adultery is immensely
painful and destructive to those involved; Laumann's study found
that people in multiple-partner relationships had substantially
lower rates of physical and emotional satisfaction, but the
researchers could not determine if the discontent was the cause or
result of the infidelity.
</P>
<P>
   Measuring public views on adultery is not a simple matter.
Although the topic is in the news (now more than ever), it is not
something most of us care to discuss.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we disapprove of it, it is not something that most of us
inquire about,'' Gagnon says. ``There is nothing proactive about
it. If it involves your neighbors, your pharmacist, or your doctor,
that is their business and we tend not to bring our moral judgments
about this into the world in which we live.''
</P>
<P>
   For a long time, the mainstream press went along with that.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the time I was in government, there were stories around,
but they were always in the supermarket tabloids,'' says Thomas H.
Kean, the former Republican governor of New Jersey who left office
in 1990. ``Now, we have the type of atmosphere where Tom Brokaw,
The Washington Post, The New York Times and The Boston Globe feel
they have to print them. And I am not sure the American public
wants to hear it.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, however, there is no indication that the
mainstream press is about to back off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, things are out of hand,'' says Sanford Ungar, dean
of the School of Communications at American University in
Washington. ``I think a whole lot of us would never have gone into
journalism if we thought it was about being on the adultery beat.
But it is like we are bicyclists on a velodrome and we can't stop,
we can only slow down very gradually and, right now, we are racing
at top speed.''
</P>
<P>
   The event that pointed the way to the velodrome was Democratic
presidential hopeful Gary Hart's 1987 challenge to reporters to
follow him around to see if he was having an affair. Some reporters
from the Miami Herald took up the gauntlet, found Donna Rice, and
the former Colorado senator's campaign quickly went south.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, politicians hold their families up as an
example of their fitness for office. It is, says Gagnon, a strategy
employed only here.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in other Western nations have affairs without so much
as blinking an eye. To them, remaining faithful to your spouse is
almost a sign of a stunted life. Consider the example of French
President Francois Mitterand, father to two sons from his marriage
_ and a daughter by his mistress some 20 years earlier. French
voters thought nothing of it.
</P>
<P>
   Remember the flap Jimmy Carter caused in his Playboy magazine
interview in 1976 when he stated that he had committed adultery in
his heart many times? He didn't say he had affairs, just that lust
was no stranger to him _ but it was enough to land him in hot
water.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the public has been growing more forgiving it seems, and
has been inclined to forgive Clinton his foibles, indeed,
practically ignore his impeachment, in exchange for the peace and
prosperity that has coincided with his residence in the Oval
Office. Then along came Flynt and Livingston, whose actions seem to
tip the balance back toward the ``adultery test'' standard.
</P>
<P>
   An unabashed Clinton supporter who blames the president's
Republican attackers for initiating this scandal war, Flynt
announced his $1 million bounty in October in a full-page ad in The
Washington Post. He said he wants to expose the hypocrisy of
Washington's movers and shakers, not of ``a freshman congressman or
an unknown from Colorado.''
</P>
<P>
   Former CIA and FBI agents at an unspecified Washington private
detective firm, working on Flynt's behalf, are tracking down tips
on congressmen who have strayed. The women involved are being asked
to provide affidavits. Flynt said his initial round of suspects is
almost all Republican, including what he described as one ``really,
really big fish.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are several more who are going to bite the dust before
this is over,'' Flynt said.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the White House _ in comments that perhaps
inadvertently gave Flynt's efforts an extra measure of importance _
publicly urged him to stop his pursuit. ``The president despises
the politics of personal destruction that Larry Flynt and others
practice,'' press secretary Joe Lockhart said. ``He believes it
should stop.''
</P>
<P>
   But will it? Gagnon believes that it will take someone running
for office and saying, `` `I am qualified for this position because
of these reasons and my family life has nothing to do with it.'''
</P>
<P>
   If not, then, given the current climate, who will want to take
the adultery test?
</P>
<P>
   That type of inquisition ``could lead to the potential of having
very bland people _ or 10-year-old people _ running for office,''
Ungar says.
</P>
<P>
   Kean, who is now president of Drew University in Madison, N.J.,
is concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a young honor student in my office last week,'' Kean
said. ``He is going on to an Ivy League graduate school and he said
to me `I always thought of myself as someone who had a future in
government and I don't think that is true anymore.' '' He doesn't
want to choose a career, Kean sensed, in which his every personal
move would be subject to scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not helping the process,'' Kean said, ``and I have a
very strong feeling the future of democracy depends on the people
we get to serve it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
