A8520 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATCH-DOCTORS-BOS &LR;      12-28 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATCH-DOCTORS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS DEBATE `PATCH ADAMS' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Helping patients laugh can be a great way to help them
heal.
</P>
<P>
   It also can be a great way for doctors to get in trouble in
these days of micro-managed medicine, political correctness, and a
love-to-litigate society. Just how much trouble became clear last
summer when a patient at New England Medical Center who lost 300
pounds sued a physician she says placed a rubber pig nose on her to
advertise the weight-loss program.
</P>
<P>
   All of which is why doctors are likely to applaud the spirit, if
not the specifics, of Robin Williams's movie ``Patch Adams,''
according to a collection of Boston health care providers who saw
the movie. It tells the true story of a misfit medical student who
a generation ago risked his career by promoting the then-unheard-of
notion that humor is a key to healing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Humor is a form of engagement, of empathy, it's endearing,''
said Dr. Gene Beresin, who runs the child and adolescent
psychiatric residency program at Massachusetts General and McLean
hospitals. ``I use humor to make fun of the system, like Robin
Williams did when he put on a Pinocchio nose, then said that the
hospital would take care of all of that patient's health bills.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Deeb Salem, chief of medicine at New England Medical Center,
also is a big believer in making his patients laugh, but the pig
nose lawsuit has made him wary about when, how and by whom it is
used: ``I truly believe humor has a place in medicine, but great
care has to be given today because of being afraid not to offend
somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The more basic principle, whether it's humor or anything else,
is to ask after every contact with a patient, `Have I done what I
can to make them feel better after I've talked to them than they
did before?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Tom Delbanco has devoted much of his career to getting his
fellow practitioners to ask that question. But he's convinced the
new movie is likelier to set back than advance the discussion. ``I
think it will promote negative stereotypes of doctors and make
patients who already are frightened enough even more frightened of
the medical establishment,'' says Delbanco, the chief of general
and primary care medicine at Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mark of a real sense of humor is the ability to laugh at
oneself, but Robin Williams in this film laughed at everybody but
himself. He laughed at mentally ill patients, he laughed at fat
black nurses and snotty Southern doctors and many of his peers.
That's the way to sell movies but not to move the world forward.''
</P>
<P>
   The world of medicine was a much different place in the late
1960s and early 70s, when the real-life Adams was attending the
Medical College of Virginia. He'd been inspired to become a doctor
when he was institutionalized for depression as a teenager, but
medical school convinced him that doctors were spending too much
time treating their patients's diseases and too little getting to
know them as people.
</P>
<P>
   His remedy: dress up in a gorilla suit, don a red nose, fill a
patient's room full of balloons or their bathtub full of noodles,
and do whatever else it took to get a guffaw and, more important,
to connect emotionally with whomever he was treating. All of which
was a hit with many patients, but not with his conservative school
in that more conservative era.
</P>
<P>
   Flash forward to today, when doctors face decidedly different
challenges. On the one hand, our tightly-managed approach to
medicine often works against such sensitivity by giving doctors
less time to spend with patients even as today's political
correctness makes them worried about offending anyone and even
getting sued. At the same time, tuning in to patients' emotional,
psychological and spiritual needs is talked about more, taught more
and practiced more, both because health care providers understand
its importance and because they know it's an effective way to
compete for patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patch's red nose is a metaphor for making a human connection,
and that does happen today. Is it something you can teach? It is
something you can encourage but I don't think you can teach it,''
says Terry Schraeder, a former medical reporter for WCVB-Channel 5
who is now a fourth-year student at Tufts Medical School, where the
real Adams delivered an inspirational lecture two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a sort of essence of human connection that certain
doctors have . . . Most doctors don't have a red bulb on the end of
their nose and buttons on their jacket, but when they go in and
touch a patient's child, or talk to the patient, the interaction is
so human. It's honorable.''
</P>
<P>
   Chunhan Zhu, who practices acupuncture and Chinese herbal
medicine in Newton, says that sort of human interaction has always
been a cornerstone of complementary medicine. ``Some doctors may
not like this movie,'' he adds, ``but from my point of view this
movie makes sense for someone practicing holistic or alternative
medicine . . . A healer uses unlimited methods to make patients
healthier.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Herb Levine, emeritus chairman of cardiology at New England
Medical Center and a physician noted for his human touch, says
conventional medicine places much more premium on patient
communication than it did when he trained in the late 1950s. But it
still has a long way to go in applying the lessons Patch Adams is
teaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patch's message is such an important one that it's OK that it
is conveyed with hyperbole,'' Levine adds. ``There's not enough
humor today on the wards and at the bedside. It's a very effective
tool.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
