<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUR PROPOSALS FOR DEALING WITH MICROSOFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   US Department of Justice lawyers have presented an unusually
strong case that Microsoft's abuse of its monopoly power requires
some kind of remedial action. Assume for a moment that the
government wins its antitrust case against Microsoft. What happens
next?
</P>
<P>
   The literal answer, of course, is that Microsoft will appeal.
The company's chances of winning are not bad. As TheStreet.com
columnist Jim Seymour wrote recently, The same US Court of Appeals
panel that has already ruled in favor of Microsoft twice in
pretrial maneuvering is probably going to hear the appeal. And that
body has already made it clear it doesn't think Microsoft has
broken the law.
</P>
<P>
   But it is also possible that presiding Judge Thomas Penfield
Jackson, after finding in favor of the government, will certify the
case directly to the US Supreme Court. Should that happen, all bets
would be off. Microsoft's strategy of losing now but winning on
appeal would be out the window. And the question of what to do
about Microsoft would loom larger than ever.
</P>
<P>
   It is extraordinarily important _ to the software and computer
industries, the future development of the Internet and, therefore,
the global economy _ that whatever remedial actions are proposed
lead to greater competition and innovation in information
technologies. It would be a disaster if they did not.
</P>
<P>
   So what are the options? There are basically four:
</P>
<P>
   --Microsoft could be levied with a gigantic fine for its
transgressions and be admonished in no uncertain terms. Since
Microsoft has $17 billion in cash, no debt, and a negative attitude
toward government edicts, this solution is a nonstarter. Consumers
would not benefit. Competition and innovation in information
technologies would not be enhanced.
</P>
<P>
   --Some kind of regulatory structure could be established to
oversee Microsoft and the software industry in general. This is a
frightening prospect. The idea that thousands of government
busybodies would be making critical decisions about the future of
information technologies gives anybody a case of the willies. As
Fortune magazine columnist Stewart Alsop wrote recently, the likely
effect would be to turn Windows into an even worse product.
</P>
<P>
   --Break up Microsoft into some number of companies comprised of
its component parts. Microsoft One might be the Operating Systems
company (Windows, NT, CE). Microsoft Two might be the Applications
Software company (Word, Excel, Money and Outlook). Microsoft Three
might be the Media Company (Internet Explorer, etc.) Microsoft
Network, etceteras) You get the picture.
</P>
<P>
   The rationale for this idea, writes Alsop, is that this would
prevent the company from using market power in one arena to win
market power in another. But this solution would not encourage
innovation or competition in either operating systems or
productivity applications. Microsofts One and Two would still enjoy
monopolies. To make matters worse, the law of unintended
consequences would deliver a huge kicker. The newly capitalized
mini-Microsofts would be even richer (relatively speaking) than
they were when they were bundled together as Microsoft. Wall Street
would throw money at Microsoft One and Microsoft Two. Rational
investors wouldn't even think about funding companies that offered
competitive operating system and applications software. Theyd be
throwing money out the window.
</P>
<P>
   --The fourth option is Alsop's idea and merits serious
consideration. He proposes that the government take away the
intellectual-property protection Microsoft enjoys on its monopoly
products. Companies (and individuals), he explains, are allowed to
own certain intellectual property copyrights and patents
exclusively for a period of time. The idea is that this will
provide these companies or individuals with the freedom to develop
new ideas and be creative.
</P>
<P>
   Alsop proposes that government take away this exclusivity in
cases when it no longer provides an incentive for innovation, when
instead it becomes a way to prevent competition. It's clear that
we'd all be better off with other companies providing versions of
Windows that work with all the software out there. The competition
would keep Microsoft honest, and we'd get a better product as a
result.
</P>
<P>
   The downside of is that this proposal would almost certainly
require some kind of government regulatory commission. The upside
is that it would lead to genuine competition in the software
industry and enable a great deal of creative thinking. Venture
capital would flood into the operating-systems market and the
applications market in the same way it now floods the Internet
market. Consumers would be the real beneficiaries. One hopes that
Alsop's proposal gets the attention it deserves.
</P>
<P>
   (John Ellis is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
