<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-DELTEA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DELTA' IS WARM IF A LITTLE SLOW-MOVING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
DOWN IN THE DELTA 
Directed by: Maya Angelou 
Screenplay by: Myron Goble 
Starring: Alfre Woodard, Al Freeman, Jr., Esther Rolle, Mary Alice,
Loretta Devine, Anne-Marie Johnson, Mpho Koaho, Justin Lord, Wesley
Snipes 
Running time: 111 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 (drug-related material) 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Down in the Delta,'' Maya Angelou's film directing debut,
strongly establishes her ability to command emotional authenticity
and fashion rich, beautifully wrought images that tap into the
stabilizing dignity of family life. Essentially, it's a story of
reverse migration as a means of keeping a family together. The
Chicago branch, headed by Mary Alice's matriarch, originally came
north from Mississippi to better themselves economically. But now
things have soured.
</P>
<P>
   The grandchildren are hanging on, but their single mother,
played by Alfre Woodard, is sliding into a slow death from drugs,
alcohol, and an inability to land a decent job. Although her mother
and preteen son bawl her out, there's no labeling of Woodard's
Loretta, just a humane acknowledging that there's more facing her
than she can cope with. Her mother, feeling the inroads of age and
realizing she can't rescue the family on her own, sends daughter
and grandkids back to Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   The family's Southern branch has prospered. They live on a
comfortable farm relatives bought from the family that once owned
them as slaves. It's supported by a chicken restaurant run by Al
Freeman Jr.'s patriarch, brother to the weary Mary Alice character.
The latter had to swallow a bit of pride to relocate her offspring.
The sibling rivalry between the two strong-willed seniors has never
dissipated. One thing keeping it alive is a feud over a family
antique, the interesting history of which, you may be sure, is
eventually revealed.
</P>
<P>
   The surprise for Northern audiences may be the film's way of
quietly shattering stereotypes about the inability of
African-American families to live rewardingly in the South.
Certainly the family here does. Woodard is immense as the initially
tottering but eventually stabilizing Loretta, eating up the screen
with her expressive eyes, but if there's a deficiency in ``Down in
the Delta,'' it's that there isn't much dramatic conflict once she
arrives in her safe haven.
</P>
<P>
   Myron Goble's script pretty much charts her recovery and
progress in a straight line. Goble gives us more a family portrait
gallery than a family drama, one of the portraits being the late
Esther Rolle's as a declining matriarch, an appearance you can't
watch without feeling a lump in your throat. The most arresting
sight is that of Wesley Snipes, as Loretta's married cousin, an
educated and prosperous Atlanta businessman. You've never seen this
Snipes on screen. The antithesis of, say, Blade, he's probably the
movie character who comes closest to the real-life Snipes, who is
one of the film's producers and can take pride in its reinforcement
of positive African-American role models.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-28-98 1349EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981228.0169 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8551 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-LITTLE-VOICE-BO     12-28 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-LITTLE-VOICE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HORROCKS IS PITCH PERFECT IN `VOICE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
LITTLE VOICE 
Directed and written by: Mark Herman, based on Jim Cartwright's
play 
Starring: Jane Horrocks, Michael Caine, Brenda Blethyn, Jim
Broadbent, Ewan McGregor, Annette Badland, Philip Jackson 
Running time: 96 minutes 
Rated: R (language and brief nudity) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Little Voice'' plucks something gossamer from a world of
unremitting dreariness and spins it forth magically. It's the
Christmas season's fairytale movie and it rides the astonishing
performance of Jane Horrocks as a reclusive young woman in a
crumbling seaside town in the north of England whose voice is
several things, but not little. As the film opens, her voice is all
but nonexistent because she has been steamrolled by her widowed
mother, whose selfishness has turned her monstrous. Brenda
Blethyn's Mari is a rampaging cow avoiding with drink the fact that
her prospects are going downhill fast, and bolstering her
self-esteem by emotionally abusing her daughter.
</P>
<P>
   As the film opens, the job is nearly complete. Horrocks's Laura,
belittlingly nicknamed Little Voice by her braying mother, sits in
her room, virtually catatonic, grieving for her dead father, a
quiet man whose sole pleasure lay in listening to his records of
Judy Garland, Marilyn Monroe, Shirley Bassey, and other great vocal
blasts from the past. As Little Voice sees it, if she doesn't mourn
her father, nobody else will. Her communing with him takes the form
of listening endlessly to his old records and reproducing with
uncanny fidelity the voices in the grooves. Although she never
speaks up to her mother in her own voice, she matches her mom,
brassy decibel for brassy decibel, whenever she sings in the voice
of this or that diva.
</P>
<P>
   Their dead-end lives in their dead-end house on their dead-end
street goes round and round, turntable-style, until Michael Caine's
flashy Ray shows up and knocks the comedy of desperation into
orbit. Like Mari, Ray is going nowhere, but puts up a better front.
He's what Caine's Alfie might have wound up as, a terminal loser
still chasing the brass ring, which in his case takes the form of
finding an act he can exploit. After a night of seismic sex with
Mari, he's struck by the sound of Little Voice singing, tiptoes
upstairs to her bedroom retreat and starts pouring on the oily
charm. Ray _ Caine's best role and richest performance in years _
is charming, but he's also relentless and, if need be, brutally
nasty.
</P>
<P>
   They all can strike it rich, he claims, if Little Voice will
only journey from her room to the stage of the tacky beachfront
nightclub owned by Jim Broadbent. Ray pushes the right buttons,
saying her dead father would have wanted it, and so ensues her
night of 1,000 sequins. Little Voice's stagefright is cured by her
vision of her father approvingly sitting in the audience. And
Horrocks, who played the role for several years on the London
stage, is a knockout. The question is whether her spectacular
success will be more than a one-shot, and whether she'll ever find
her own voice.
</P>
<P>
   There's a hint that she might when she meets Ewan McGregor's
telephone lineman, who is as shy as she is. They communicate with
glances, but words do not come easily to either. Frankly, their
sweet little love story is quite eclipsed by the terminal seediness
of Caine and the equally versatile Broadbent as the sleazy
small-timers with big dreams. You couldn't ask for a juicier pair
of bottom-feeders trying not to drown in their own flop sweat.
Caine pounces onto Ray's sincere-seeming chicanery as a cat to
cream. ``Little Voice'' is a natural successor to ``The Full
Monty'' and Herman's previous film, ``Brassed Off.'' Powered by the
superb performances of Horrocks, Caine, and Broadbent (Blethyn is
too stridently one-note), it earns an instant niche in provincial
futility's hall of fame.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-28-98 1350EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981228.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8553 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-CDS-ONLINE-BOS &LR;      12-28 1222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-CDS-ONLINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIRED FOR SOUND SHOPPING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN ANDERMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's 1 a.m., and I'm looking for Love. Not the garden variety
that everybody and their little sister can get their hands on, but
the good stuff. The real thing. The way Love used to be, before
money and power and image mattered. I want raw Love. Passionate
Love. I want . . .``Rat Bastard.'' ``Rat Bastard'' is the EP that
Courtney Love _ the Love I'm looking for _ and her band Hole
released a year before their official debut, 1991's ``Pretty on the
Inside,'' came out. It has the original recording of the
incomparable ``Retard Girl'' on it, and I must have it. Now.
</P>
<P>
   In the dark ages, before computer screens lit the night with the
flat, obsessive glow of nonstop virtual shopping, the late hour
might have been an obstacle to the sort of instant gratification
I'm craving. But in today's wired world, retail is a 24-hour
phenomenon. In a click I'm at a record store the size of a stadium,
hundreds of thousands of CDs at my fingertips, satisfaction as
close as the piece of plastic balanced on my keypad.
</P>
<P>
   While shopping on line for current mainstream music is simple
and straightforward, tracking down obscure or out-of-print albums
does not qualify by any stretch of the imagination as instantly
gratifying. My search for Love begins at Amazon.com, the leading
Internet music retailer. In response to the keyword ``Hole,'' three
Hole album titles are listed on the screen, plus 57 other
``matches'' _ including jazz pianist Bill Evans's ``At Shelly's
Manne-Hole,'' and ``Dig Your Own Hole'' by the Chemical Brothers. I
have to click on the name of a Hole album, then select ``more
albums by this artist`` to learn that Amazon actually stocks eleven
Hole titles, among them imports and singles. A tricky bit of
navigation. Still, nowhere do I find my ``Rat Bastard.''
</P>
<P>
   And I don't find the title at CDnow.com or Musicblvd.com, the
Internet's other major retailers, nor Soundstone.com and Rock.com,
a pair of fast-growing upstarts. The trouble is not, however, that
those on-line stores don't stock the EP I'm looking for. It turns
out that the scrappy four-song ``Rat Bastard'' has been eloquently
rechristened (in accordance, no doubt, with poststardom marketing
strategy) ``First Session,'' a fact I discover only after checking
track listings on the unfamiliar titles.
</P>
<P>
   For the left-field fan or collector of old or obscure releases,
the road to on-line music shopping is fraught with such perilous
blind spots. But various sites supply a share of unexpected
pleasures and happy endings. Comparing the on-line music stores
depends entirely on your criteria for a satisfying shopping
experience; sheer volume of titles, certainly, but also ease of
navigation, design clarity, and extras like reviews, artist bios,
and links to other music are useful features.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of inventory, the big players _ Amazon.com,
Musicblvd.com, and CDnow.com _ are generally comparable. All three,
for example, came up with copies of Julie Driscoll's 1960 import
album, ``Streetnoise.'' Amazon also offers a ``Customers Who Bought
This CD Also Bought . . . '' section and fan reviews, which are so
minimally useful _ with no assurance of the writer's good taste,
knowledge, or credibility _ one presumes they function more as an
enticement for closet critics to shop there than as guidelines for
consumers. CDnow has a staff album advisor who reliably recommends
additional music based on one's selected artist, as well as links
to brief quotes from Rolling Stone reviews. But of the big three,
Musicblvd wins hands down for informative extras. There are links
to artist biographies, reviews, and features from a wide variety of
national music publications, and a novel list of _ and links to _
artists who have influenced the artist you're researching.
</P>
<P>
   While comparable, the big ones aren't, as it turns out, always
reliable. Case in point: In my search for Velvet Underground
drummer Maureen Tucker's first solo album, 1989's ``Life in Exile
After Abdication,'' neither CDnow nor Musicblvd carried it, and
Amazon listed it as out of stock. Tower Records' Web site, however,
had it _ for $13.99. The much lower-profile Soundstone.com also
sold the CD, and better yet, it was on sale for $9.79.
</P>
<P>
   Soundstone.com is a year-old company based in Somerville;
Soundstone president Kevin Sheehan bought Rock.com, which wasn't a
retail site, and launched it last October as the under-25 arm of
Soundstone's 25-plus/boomer business, and the pair is carving a
niche in a crowded big-name market by saturating the sites with
strong personality and the sort of service one expects to find at a
small boutique rather than a large warehouse, on line or off.
Shoppers can actually chat in real time with a customer service rep
about music, technical questions, ordering, or anything else that
pops to mind. You can check out live local music scenes in a number
of major cities, including select club listings and recommended
local CDs. They've got question-and-answer columns staffed by
actual experts _ Milo Miles on Soundstone and Brett Milano on
Rock.com. _ and archived essays about music and trends.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the collectors, those looking for rarities,
vinyl, 45s, and the like. Odds are slim you'll find what you're
looking for at the sites catering to collectors, but you'll likely
wind up wanting something you didn't even know you needed. At
Joe's-Record-Paradise.com, they keep things simple; categories are
jazz, rock, country, and ``the rest of the stuff.'' It's part
record store, part auction house; some prices are set; others are
open to bidding. You can find anything from an original mono
10-inch of Les Paul's ``Galloping Guitars'' for $20, to a set of 26
British-import Beatles 45s, for which bidding starts at $125. Joe's
also offers a thorough rating system to evaluate wear and
condition.
</P>
<P>
   Everythings-music.com is a tiny collectibles store/auction
house; no bells, no whistles, just a neat little list of stuff like
Juliana Hatfield's ``Only Everything'' in special fake-Buffalo-hide
packaging (out of print, of course) for $18, and a Misfits Coffin
Boxset (yes, the box is a coffin) for $70. Secondspin.com is the
giant flea market of on-line record stores; no awesome imports or
fancy features, just a constantly changing random sampling of CDs _
cheap, too. Ebay.com, the all-the-rage auction house, sports a
predictably eclectic array of music items _ from an autographed
(twice!) Tori Amos album to backstage laminates to current CDs and
obscure albums.
</P>
<P>
   Again, it's all a matter of style. If you know exactly what you
want and plan a surgical strike _ get in and get out with your
targeted CD _ the behemoths supply nearly identical 300,000-strong
inventories. For those of you inclined to smell the roses, perhaps
pick up a new idea or artist along the way, or just wander around
until something catches your eye, the smaller sites will serve you
well. And you just might find what you're looking for.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SOME SITES TO CHECK &QL; 
 &QL; 
Amazon.com &QL; 
Musicblvd.com &QL; 
CDnow.com &QL; 
Soundstone.com &QL; 
Rock.com &QL; 
Joe's-record-paradise.com &QL; 
Secondspin.com &QL; 
Everythings-music.com &QL; 
Ebay.com &QL; 
Towerrecords.com &QL; 
