   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-FOREIGN-JOURNAL _ BAGHDAD _ In good times, Iraqis live
under a restrictive regime and crippling economic sanctions. In bad
times, they have all that and missile attacks, too. Still, they are
hospitable to a visiting American correspondent whose government
has just attacked them with 400 cruise missiles. (Kaplow, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   PBP _ PARTY SWITCH (DEVELOPING) _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _
Republicans have been switching parties nationally since the last
national election. The trend happening here in Palm Beach County.
Is it because Republicans are fed up over the Clinton impeachment.
(Moffett, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   PBP _ NO BEGGING (DEVELOPING) _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ No
panhandling signs are going up at popular intersections in Palm
Beach County. The sign has the county logo and number to call for
the homeless coalition. (Pressly, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   US-LCRA-FLOOD-GAUGE _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Flash floods can rip
60-foot trees out of the ground, turn boulders into battering rams
and scrape homes off their foundation _ scattering the devastation
of a tornado over dozens of square miles. And no place in the
United States is more prone to flash floods than the Hill Country
west of Austin. With only hours to warn the growing number of
people living along the rivers and lakes of Central Texas,
including Lake Travis, the LCRA is taking steps to improve its
weather eyes and ears. Beginning in January, the river authority
will begin a $7.2 million program to almost triple the number of
rainfall monitors and flood gauges on rivers and creeks. (Lindell,
Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   w/AUS-GAUGE-SIDE _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Before there were river
gauges and technology, the LCRA relied on people to measure
rainfall and telephone in their results. If the weather was
particularly bad, the weather watchers were told to telegraph the
Austin Dam (Tom Miller Dam today). All this for $3.50 a year. Some
families have been doing this since the program began in 1939,
including Bonnie L. Rahe, 72, of Harper, who took over from her
father-in-law in 1974. (Lindell, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   TX-MINORITY-ENROLL _ AUSTIN, Texas _ A Texas law touted as a
colorblind way to lure more black and Hispanic students to in-state
colleges produced uneven results at the state's major universities
and did not pack the punch some lawmakers had expected. University
officials said, however, that it's too soon to judge whether Texas'
effort to trump affirmative action in college admissions is
working. A look at what's happening. (Roser, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   GA-PRIVATEPRISON-LAPSES _ ATLANTA _ Little more than a month
after the first private prison opened in Georgia, state inspectors
found security lapses, sloppy record-keeping and dirt during two
inspections of the D. Ray James State Prison, which Cornell
Corrections Inc. operates in Charlton County. According to reports
from state Department of Corrections monitors after inspections at
the Cornell prison on Nov. 18-19 and again on Dec. 9, the private
prison guards were not keeping track of inmates as they moved
around the prison. (Cook, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA: 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   FREAKNIK _ ATLANTA _ City police officers made $1 million in
overtime for last April's Black College Spring Break, according to
figures just wrangled out of the city. A committee is to be
appointed by the city in January to prepare for next year's
Freaknik, April 16-18. Will check to see if Daytona Beach's
decade-old competing Freaknik will lure away some of the black
college students who used to come to Atlanta. Daytona's event was
marred by the shooting death of a student this year.
(Ffrench-Parker, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
