<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-DANCING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SISTERS' LOVE MAKES JUMP FROM THE STAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
DANCING AT LUGHNASA 
Directed by: Pat O'Connor 
Screenplay by: Frank McGuinness, based on Brian Friel's play 
Starring: Meryl Streep, Michael Gambon, Catherine McCormack, Kathy
Burke, Sophie Thompson, Brid Brennan, Rhys Ifans 
Running time: 92 minutes 
Rated: PG (mild language and thematic elements) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Dancing at Lughnasa'' is a beautiful film of a beautiful play.
Not in the way you might think, not in terms of picturesque
scenery, although the play's pared-down Donegal world in August
1936, is lush and golden. Nor is it a thing of verbal flights,
although the speech is lively and pointed and in many ways loving
as it ripples among five unmarried sisters sharing a country
cottage that's also the home of the 7-year-old boy whose grown
voice we hear narrating the events of the chronicle. Director Pat
O'Connor gets the behavioral nuances right, knows what lies between
the lines of Brian Friel's play, turns it into a thing of glances,
of stifled hearts, of emotional radar readings among the five
tightly knit sisters.
</P>
<P>
   The play charts great relentless tectonic plate shifts beneath
the comforting routines of the Mundy sisters _ Meryl Streep's prim
schoolteacher, Kate, supporting the family; Kathy Burke's childless
earth mother, Maggie, presiding at the hearth; Brid Brennan's
steady Alice; Sophie Thompson's simple Rose; Catherine McCormack's
Christina, romantic, yet practical enough to know she'd derive
little comfort from marrying the flamboyant but commitment-shy
father of her child. Their quiet, contained courage, a genuflection
to which is the play's ultimate subject, is tested more than they
realize by a fateful event _ the return from Uganda of their
missionary brother, Jack.
</P>
<P>
   After hero-worshipping him from afar for years, their startled
glances eloquently register their feelings about seeng the brother
who returns looking frail and erratic and eccentric. His mental
circuitry has cross-wired the African and Celtic Catholic
religions. He regards them as interchangeable in their essentials,
no small point since Michael Gambon's ability to make us believe
that the old priest has his eye trained on something grander and
larger than pedestrian realities transports us into the heart of
the play's central metaphor. Extraordinarily for an Irish play _
and now film _ the Church doesn't figure much, except as an
impediment to spiritual sustenance.
</P>
<P>
   The title refers to the pagan harvest rites, complete with
bonfires, that predate the Church and still compel the
participation of the peasants in the hills behind the sisters'
rocky farm. Pointedly, but never heavy-handedly, Friel makes us
aware of the parallel between the Irish accommodation of paganism
and Christianity and the similar phenomenon with which Jack has
made his peace in Africa _ a factor in his being sent home into
forced retirement. Through Jack's disorientation, and the fact that
he has become an embarrassment to the Church and been put out to
pasture, Gambon confirms his standing as one of the best actors in
the English-speaking world by convincing us that Jack has been
touched by grace and a kind of pantheistic wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor and his cast also convince us that the sisters were
born with grace. Although they shun the pagan rites, they arrive at
their own eruption of joy, dancing to the music from a radio bought
by the boy's wandering father en route to join anti-Franco fighters
in Spain. The sisters' dance is the merest respite from the hard
lives to which they respond with touchingly inexhaustible spirits.
This is their great legacy to the love child they all nurture. Many
a memory play has been ruined on its way from stage to screen. Not
this one, though. ``Dancing at Lughnasa'' is a tender glory.
</P>
<P>
   (This is an expanded version of the review published here when
this film premiered at the Boston Film Festival.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
