<HEADER>
A8558 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-JOE-BOS &LR;      12-28 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-JOE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`JOE YOUNG' GETS A SMART, ENDEARING UPDATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
MIGHTY JOE YOUNG 
Directed by: Ron Underwood 
Screenplay by: Mark Rosenthal and Lawrence Konner, based on Ruth
Rose's screenplay and Merian C. Cooper's story 
Starring: Charlize Theron, Bill Paxton, Rade Serbedzija, Peter
Firth, David Paymer, Regina King, John Alexander 
Running time: 114 minutes 
Rated: PG (some menacing action violence and mild language) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When it first surfaced in 1949, ``Mighty Joe Young'' was an
endearing alternative to ``King Kong.'' Part of this was due to the
fact that the gorilla of the title role was smaller than Kong, only
about 15 feet high. Sort of like Kong's vulnerable kid brother.
Directed by ``King Kong'' director Ernest Schoedsack, it was
endearing the first time around and it's endearing now. The new
``Mighty Joe Young'' remake with Ron Underwood behind the camera
smartly updates the story to a time of increased ecological
awareness, increased technological capacity, and even more
frightening threats to the gorilla's survival.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as now, Joe has a couple of caring human friends. Charlize
Theron's primatologist and Bill Paxton's zoologist, working for a
nature conservancy. She reluctantly assents to his argument that
Joe would face less danger in his California animal preserve than
he would from poachers in his native Africa. And so he's shipped to
Los Angeles, where the poachers follow him. Joe knows something is
wrong, but the keepers misinterpret his thumpings and trumpetings
and rush to the beast label for this beauty-and-the-beast tale.
</P>
<P>
   As if self-preservation in the midst of idiots who don't even
know the threat exists weren't enough, Joe is of course smitten
with Therize, his pal since childhood, when their respective moms
were killed by the same poacher (Rade Serbedzija) who's on his
trail now. Like Joe, to say nothing of Kenneth Branagh in
``Celebrity,'' Keanu Reeves in ``The Devil's Advocate,'' and Tom
Everett Scott in ``That Thing You Do,'' Paxton's globetrotting
animal advocate falls for the pretty primatologist, too. So he's in
good company, if also in an unconventional triangle.
</P>
<P>
   Deep down, we know that Therize and Paxton are acting in front
of blue screens and playing to assistant directors holding ape
masks on sticks. We realize that the creature builders,
animatronics experts, and computer wizards added Joe later. They
all know their stuff, do a good job, and have more than a little
fun with such landmarks as Grauman's Chinese Theater and the
Hollywood sign, although the best scene comes when Joe hides from
pursuing cops under a freeway overpass before shambling off to an
amusement park for a tear-jerker ending that works despite itself.
</P>
<P>
   Movie buffs may be interested to note that Terry Moore, who
played the love object in the original, appears in this reprise in
a cameo with Ray Harryhausen, who built the original Joe. Also, for
karmic reasons, Paxton insisted that his late friend and
predecessor in the good-guy role, Ben Johnson, be genuflected to in
the form of a quickly-glimpsed movie poster for ``Wagonmaster,'' in
which Johnson starred. Karmic influences or not, the new ``Mighty
Joe Young'' works. This is one remake that isn't trying to make us
forget the original, but seems rather to embrace it and bring it
into the present in solidly crafted, family-friendly fashion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-28-98 1354EST &QL; 
