r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOCTORS-NICARAGUA-HNS     12-28 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOCTORS-NICARAGUA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HURRICANE VICTIMS FIND SOLACE IN THERAPY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYCHE HENDRICKS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   POSOLTEGA, Nicaragua _ At a crowded refugee camp set up on the
grounds of an elementary school, an American psychologist was
asking a group of peasant women about the hurricane that swept away
their homes, and in some cases, their loved ones.
</P>
<P>
   One woman, Susana Ramirez, had come to the shelter from the
village of Rolando Rodriguez on the side of the Casita Volcano.
After days of torrential rain in late October, the wall of a crater
lake in the volcano collapsed, and unleashed a flood followed and a
mudslide that wiped out Rolando Rodriguez and four other villages
and partially destroyed a dozen others.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez's husband and many of her neighbors were killed in the
storm.
</P>
<P>
   Clarisa Hernandez came from Torreon, which was mostly spared
when the wall of mud divided into two currents, leaving the village
on an island. But her nieces, nephews and cousins in Rolando
Rodriguez were killed.
</P>
<P>
   As the women spoke, they sat with arms held tightly across their
chests and eyes cast down, the day of the disaster replaying in
their minds, their sadness overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of raw pain and emotion isn't an uncommon phenomenon
for the psychologist, Adrianne Aron, who was in Nicaragua with a
team of U.S. doctors and nurses to treat the victims of the
hurricane named Mitch.
</P>
<P>
   At home in Berkeley, Calif., she ordinarily divides her time
between counseling troubled young people in the Alameda County
Juvenile Hall and treating Central Americans who fled war and
torture. She has also worked as part of Red Cross disaster teams
after both the Loma Prieta earthquake in 1989 and the Oakland Hills
firestorm in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Of the trauma and distress the hurricane victims were going
through, Aron said, ``We had a taste of this in a minor way with
our own earthquake. We became very distrustful of the bridges and
viaducts and freeways. We all found ourselves very nervous. If you
multiply that by a large number, that's what's going on in
Nicaragua.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, several of the Nicaraguan refugees said that when it
started to rain one December day, they began to panic that the rain
would launch another landslide.
</P>
<P>
   Two months after the storm, tens of thousands of Nicaraguans are
still living in shelters, 4,400 of them in the township of
Posoltega, where the volcano is located.
</P>
<P>
   The storm, which stalled over Central America for days in late
October, killed more than 9,000 people and left as many as 2
million others homeless in Honduras, Nicaragua, El Salvador and
Guatemala.
</P>
<P>
   Along with treatment the medical team provided to heal physical
ailments, Aron hoped to give survivors the tools to cope and help
each other begin to rebuild their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doris and I want to teach you something to help get rid of
tension,'' Aron said to the women in the camp, gesturing to Doris
Massey, who also lives in Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doris is a nurse and she has taught other nurses to do this,
but she can teach you, too,'' Aron said. ``It's good for a headache
and it can help if you've had trouble sleeping at night since the
hurricane. It's called massage.''
</P>
<P>
   Massey demonstrated a shoulder and neck rub on Aron, then asked
the women to break into pairs and try it. Ramirez put her hands
shyly on Hernandez's shoulders and tentatively began to work the
68-year-old woman's stiff muscles.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can make small circles with your thumb, the size of a
coin,'' Massey said. ``Keep it very slow.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans presented the technique to the Posoltega women as
a cure for physical ailments, but for Aron, the caring touch the
refugees were learning was also a way for them to begin to heal
their wounded spirits.
</P>
<P>
   They have received some help with basic necessities such as
food, clothing, water and medical care from their government and
private relief agencies. But the apocalyptic horror of the flood
and the enormous pain of losing their relatives and friends as well
as their homes and possessions has barely been addressed.
</P>
<P>
   With only a week on the medical brigade to tend to so many
affected people, Aron knew she must work strategically. She spent
much of her time sitting with groups of refugees and listening to
their stories. Then she offered them ways to express their
feelings, to support each other, and to begin to imagine a future.
</P>
<P>
   On her first day, Aron spoke with a despondent woman who had
lost four of her young children to the raging storm. As they spoke,
another woman joined in, explaining that five of her children had
died. With a van full of U.S. doctors waiting for her, Aron had
only time to say a few words and give each woman a warm hug.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to hook them up with one another,'' she said in
the van afterwards. ``They have to face Christmas now without their
children, so I'm hoping they can join forces.''
</P>
<P>
   The massage workshop, as well as drawing and singing groups Aron
organized among refugee children, were designed to encourage the
hurricane survivors to help one another.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never had a massage before,'' said Hernandez, smiling as
she thanked Ramirez for the treatment. ``But I like it. I'll do it
for my family now and I'll teach my husband how to do it, too.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you think about the disaster, your head hurts and your
body hurts,'' added Mayra Martin, another refugee, who attended
Aron's workshop with her mother and daughter, 10. ``But I feel
calmer now. I think I'll do this every day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
