<HEADER>
A8562 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-SHAKESPEARE-BOS     12-28 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-SHAKESPEARE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOPPARD'S `SHAKESPEARE' DAZZLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
SHAKESPEARE IN LOVE 
Directed by: John Madden 
Screenplay by: Marc Norman and Tom Stoppard 
Starring: Gwyneth Paltrow, Joseph Fiennes, Geoffrey Rush, Colin
Firth, Ben Affleck, Judi Dench, Simon Callow, Tom Wilkinson 
Running time: 122 minutes 
Rated: R (sexuality) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Shakespeare in Love'' is not only the year's most exhilarating
surprise. It's the best backstage comedy ever made. It gives the
kind of rush that ``Pulp Fiction'' or ``L.A. Confidential'' gave
us, the giddy sense that you're watching something daring itself to
fly, then bringing off the gamble. It's all liftoff, launched on an
inspired conceit. What, it asks itself, went into the making of the
play that made Shakespeare _ ``Romeo and Juliet''? Joseph Fiennes's
young Will, down from Stratford, trying to hustle a career in
bustling Elizabethan London in 1593, begins by being stymied with
writer's block. His new play, ``Romeo and Ethel, the Pirate's
Daughter,'' is not going well. In fact, it's not going at all.
</P>
<P>
   But then Tom Stoppard and Marc Norman's brilliant script starts
imagining him out of trouble and into love. Never, in fact, has
imagination filled the gaps in the life of a cultural icon so
gloriously, so knowingly, so satisfyingly. Things start happening
when, Fiennes's Will, so soulful that he can't avoid tripping over
his own heart, is struck by something about a boy trying out at the
Rose Theatre. What he doesn't know, but doesn't take long to find
out, is that the newcomer is a high-born stagestruck gentlewoman in
disguise in a society where women aren't permitted to do anything
so depraved as acting for a living.
</P>
<P>
   In no time, Gwyneth Paltrow's Viola De Lesseps becomes the
unhappily married Shakespeare's real-life Juliet, complete with
balcony scene at her stately home, where he risks death, since
she's engaged to Colin Firth's dangerous and nasty aristocrat. As
his love life improves, so does his new play. His quill starts
flying across the surfaces of his hitherto paralyzingly blank
paper. Christopher Marlowe, Elizabethan drama's top dog (drolly
played by Rupert Everett), hands Shakespeare the plot he needs. Ben
Affleck, another heaven-sent presence as Ned Alleyn, the matinee
idol of his day, supplies the name change. When Shakespeare wants
to rope the A-list actor into the production by offering him the
role of Mercutio, and Alleyn asks the name of the play,
Shakespeare, skipping not a beat, replies: ``Mercutio,'' reeling
the actor in by his own ego.
</P>
<P>
   Affleck, unfurling a flair for throwaway comedy, makes Alleyn a
generous figure. The film is a generous film, in keeping with the
reconciliatory impulse in Shakespeare's own comedies. ``Shakespeare
in Love'' delights in its characters, and we do, too. It isn't out
to debunk the ardent young writer who hasn't yet become the Bard,
although it can't help smiling at the humor he can't see in his own
besotted earnestness. This is also Paltrow's best role in ages. She
burns with fevered emotions _ paler, perhaps, than Shakespeare's,
but no less incandescent. At the end, when a series of perhaps
inevitable mishaps thrusts her into the premiere performance of
``Romeo and Juliet,'' she metamorphoses into theatrical aspiration
itself.
</P>
<P>
   This soaring, earthy, serendipitous enterprise is enriched
hugely by the rightness and relish brought to it by its
just-as-delicious secondary figures. Geoffrey Rush has fun playing
the desperation of the theater owner trying to avert disaster with
the new play. Tom Wilkinson is a steadily ingratiating presence as
the thug he owes money to, especially when it becomes apparent that
he's been bitten by the theater bug. Simon Callow is hilarious as a
killjoy master of revels who lives to shut down theaters. It's fun
to see the young John Webster, who later became famous as the
author of bloody revenge dramas, played as a bloodthirsty little
death's head by Joe Roberts. And the priceless Judi Dench weighs in
magnificently, with a full head of mischievous imperiousness as the
aged Elizabeth I. When she orders Shakespeare to next write a
comedy for Twelfth Night, we know where the name of his heroine,
Viola, came from.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to be a Shakespearean scholar to enjoy the film.
But the more you do know, the more you'll be tickled by the
script's way of accounting for the sources of various lines and
phrases we identify today as Shakespearean. The romance works, the
comedy works, most of all ``Shakespeare in Love'' works because of
its champagne script. Norman got the idea from his son who was
taking a drama course at Boston University in 1989. Stoppard
finished what Norman started. Although I have no idea who wrote
what, I can't resist noting that Stoppard has become the
English-speaking stage's natural successor to George Bernard Shaw,
on the strength of his playful, inventive wit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shakespeare in Love'' is also sexier than anything Shaw could
ever permit himself to write. It's something of a throwback to
Stoppard's ``Rosencrantz and Guildenstern Are Dead,'' and even more
of one to Stoppard's dazzling ``Arcadia.'' When it comes to
imagining what went on among our illustrious predecessors, Stoppard
simply has no competition. Hurtling through a believably yeasty
London with confidence and panache, ``Shakespeare in Love'' lives
by the word, and ought to at least get a best screenplay Oscar.
It's a bawdy, exuberant, nimble-witted, impassioned lark.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-28-98 1355EST &QL; 
