A8565 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-STEPMOM-BOS &LR;      12-28 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-STEPMOM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STEPMOM' PULLS THE HEARTSTRINGS A LITTLE TOO HARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
STEPMOM 
Directed by: Chris Columbus 
Screenplay by: Gigi Levangie, Jessie Nelson, Steven Rogers, Karen
Leigh Hopkins, Ron Bass 
Starring: Julia Roberts, Susan Sarandon, Ed Harris, Jena Malone,
Liam Aiken, Lynn Whitfield, Darrell Larson, Mary Louise Wilson 
Running time: 124 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 (language and thematic elements) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You'll laugh, you'll cry, you'll start looking at your watch.
That's the story on ``Stepmom.'' It begins as a nice starry workout
for Julia Roberts and Susan Sarandon as, respectively, new
stepmom-to-be and angry discarded mom. The stepmom, of course, can
do nothing right. The biological mom, who knows every tic and
twitch of the two kids she bore, can do no wrong. The natural mom
is angry, the kids are angry, the dad is keeping a low profile, and
Roberts's stepmom finds herself playing a losing game. The kids
don't want her around. And she's not too crazy about being their
punching bag, although she gamely hangs in there, playing the
unsinkable good sport, even though her new wife-and-mom role is
undercutting her fashion photography job.
</P>
<P>
   Sarandon's ex-wife who will never be an ex-mom enjoys twisting
the knife and does it stylishly. And yet both women remain
essentially sympathetic. It allows the film to ride the barbed
comedy of malevolence as Roberts's spunky interloper scrambles to
find ways to make the kids feel they don't have to hate her in
order to express loyalty to their mom. The resentfulness of the
kids (Jena Malone and Liam Aiken) is bracing and refreshing. It
does a lot to help stave off the sentimental, drawn-out
manipulativeness that brings the film down and yanks it out of its
boomer heaven, untroubled by money pressures, unfolding in
attractively chic locations _ Manhattan loft, charming old Nyack
Colonial _ neatly personifying parental angst over the clashing
demands of child care versus career.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Harris's presumably deep-pockets lawyer, who dumped Sarandon
and is trying to make a go of it with Roberts, is little more than
a peripheral figure, partly because his character could plausibly
view his position between ex-wife and new wife as a no man's land.
Although there's a shower scene between him and Roberts, there's an
almost total absence of anything like real heat between them. The
passion is exchanged by the two women. After a while, they're more
intricately involved with each other than either is with the man to
whom one was married and the other is about to be. The real subject
here is the dynamic between the film's two big female stars. But
because they're who they are, you know they're going to come out
about even in sympathy quotients.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stepmom'' constantly is engaged in a pitched battle with
predictability, right down to the obvious set piece, when Roberts's
stepmom loses the kids in the park. Sarandon's disapproving
biological mom, beneath her stern exterior, loves it because she
can have the moral high ground all to herself on this one. The
film's tear-jerker second half, drawn out unconscionably, is
ushered in by news that one of the players is ill, and bickering
must be replaced by bonding. The idea that room should be made for
tolerance and non-traditional family alignments isn't enough to
carry the film past the obviousness of its button-pushing. There
simply isn't enough weight given to the supposed gravity of the
situation to make the weep-o-rama palatable. There's a lot to be
said for watching Sarandon and Roberts pretend to spar, but
``Stepmom,'' despite _ or perhaps because of _ its five
screenwriters, makes it all seem more ersatz that it ought to have
been.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-28-98 1357EST &QL; 
