<HEADER>
A8568 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-HURLY-BURLY-BOS     12-28 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-HURLY-BURLY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HINTS OF HUMOR IN NIHILISTIC `HURLYBURLY' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
HURLYBURLY 
Directed by: Anthony Drazan 
Screenplay by: David Rabe, based on his play 
Starring: Sean Penn, Kevin Spacey, Robin Wright Penn, Chazz
Palminteri, Garry Shandling, Anna Paquin, Meg Ryan 
Running time: 122 minutes 
Rated: R (constant drug use, pervasive strong language, and sexual
material) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   David Rabe was dissatisfied with the original off-Broadway
staging of his play, ``Hurlyburly.'' That makes two of us. Three,
actually, if you count Sean Penn, who performed it in Los Angeles
and now, a decade later, stars in a transformed screen version of
``Hurlyburly.'' It isn't every script that gets a second and then a
third chance. So was ``Hurlyburly'' worth sticking with? The
answer, to my surprise, is yes. What seemed like a few hours of
nihilistic self-destructiveness from a roomful of misogynistic
Hollywood losers on stage emerges on screen with new clarity and
purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hurlyburly'' benefits immensely from a few shifts in emphasis
and direction. And from a sizzling and _ against the odds _
sympathetic performance from Penn. His character, a Hollywood agent
named Eddie who aptly describes himself as his own biggest
distraction, has become a guy who may not even know on a conscious
level that he's looking for something better than a frantic search
for sensation. But without ever moralizing, or even verbalizing it,
Penn's Eddie makes us feel he is groping his way toward something
better. While the ending is far from resoundingly affirmative, it
at least leaves the door open to hope.
</P>
<P>
   The play is fueled by Rabe's torrents of male bondingspeak. It's
guys being guys, playing to each other, not necessarily kind to one
another, but certainly treating each other better than they treat
the women who have the bad luck to fall into their orbit. As
director (and producer) Anthony Drazan has conceived it, Eddie and
his cronies Mickey (Kevin Spacey) and Phil (Chazz Palminteri) are
the three facets of a broken organism. Spacey's Mickey, Eddie's
glib partner in the agency, is taking what he calls a timeout from
his wife and kids to go the fast-lane route, but always in an
armored, detached way. Phil (Chazz Palminteri) is driven by
whatever convulsive spasm of emotion he's feeling at the time.
</P>
<P>
   If Mickey represents superego to a fault, Phil represents an id
in need of a lid. Eddie is somewhere in the middle. He's all
flailing ego, reachable provided you can get to him, which takes
some doing, given his penchant for distraction. There's an
unofficial fourth musketeer, a low-level Hollywood player played by
Garry Shandling, whose pseudocool is constantly eclipsed by his
desperation. He, God help him, thinks the other three are cool and
he wants to run with them. As an initiation fee, he drops in on the
Hollywod Hills condo shared by Eddie and Mickey with a gift, a
street waif, Donna (Anna Paquin), whom he describes as a care
package.
</P>
<P>
   What the benighted guys fail to see is that all three women who
come in contact with them are far stronger than they are, including
Paquin's waif, who's more resilient than she seems; Robin Wright
Penn's female loose cannon, who two-times both Eddie and Mickey;
and Meg Ryan's revelatory performance as a stripper who begins by
seeming a doormat, but ends up seeming the film's moral center.
Drazin's cinematographer, Changwei Gu, photographs many scenes and
moments through reflective surfaces _ mirrors, glass doors, a glass
coffee table, water in a pool. The question is whether Eddie can
ever bring himself to break through the reflections of reality to
begin dealing with the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   Corrosively as the characters are drawn, there remains room for
outcroppings of surprising humor in ``Hurlyburly.'' And while it
may seem the height of male self-involvement to worry about the
possible redemption of one or more of the guys and not the superbly
characterized women they victimize, you'll find yourself caring
whether Eddie can pull himself out of the nothingness he's trying
so hard to avoid facing. Penn's performance is amazing. His Eddie
has steam coming out of his ears, yet he's also something of a
patsy. The thing that makes him redeemable is that he's also
harboring a lot of pain. ``Gotta wake up,'' Eddie tells himself.
He's of a piece with Penn's other tightrope-walking performances
that make him one of the few actors whose work keeps you believing
in movies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-28-98 1358EST &QL; 
