<HEADER>
A8573 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-PATCH-ADAMS-BOS     12-28 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-PATCH-ADAMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS WINS A TOO-EASY ARGUMENT FOR HUMANE MEDICINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
PATCH ADAMS 
Directed by: Tom Shadyac 
Screenplay by: Steve Oedekerk 
Starring: Robin Williams, Monica Potter, Daniel London, Philip
Seymour Hoffman, Bob Gunton, Peter Coyote, Josef Sommer, Harve
Presnell 
Running time: 110 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 (some strong language and crude humor) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Patch Adams'' would seem to be a natural for Robin Williams.
Based on a true story, it's about a maverick doctor who shakes up
the establishment by clowning around with cancer patients in the
name of relating to them as people. He makes kids in a pediatric
cancer ward laugh when he cuts a slit in a red rubber ball, pops it
on his nose, and makes faces. He even breaks through the anger of a
dying pancreatic cancer patient by showing up in the guy's room
wearing gauze wings and singing ``Blue Skies'' to him.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, it sounds like ``Good Morning, Vietnam'' and
``Dead Poets Society'' in a hospital. And it could have been, it
could have been. There's nobody whose riffs you'd rather see in the
role of a shaker-upper than Williams. There's always enough pain
and sensitivity in his eyes to tell us that he's not just being
insensitive, that the humor may be his way of hiding his own thin
skin. Here, he gets more than the usual sympatico sendoff when we
see that his route to medical school was through his own
institutionalization for depression.
</P>
<P>
   It's while he's undergoing treatment that he discovers he's much
better at relating to the other patients than the doctors are. And
so, thus convinced that he can supply something the establishment
often lacks, he enters medical school. His grades are great, but
his antics in the name of reinventing the bedside manner and
personalizing medicine get him into trouble. The problem,
dramatically, is that it gets him into trouble we reject as too
simplistic. Granted, a film needs conflict, but the way ``Patch
Adams'' goes about getting it is too blatantly manipulative.
</P>
<P>
   Patch's chief antagonist is the med school dean, played by Bob
Gunton. In case you've forgotten, Gunton played the evil warden in
``The Shawshank Redemption.'' If you missed that prison film, you
can see the performance repeated here. Gunton is too much a
humorless martinet. And for that matter, Patch is too much a
wayward angel. Most good doctors, you suspect, steer a humane and
flexible course between the dean's rigidity and Patch's
loose-cannon antics. Didn't it ever occur to someone to have a
calmed-down Patch quietly walk into a room and simply take
someone's temperature?
</P>
<P>
   The film is too stridently polarized between the forces of
humane progress and unyielding rule-following. It does have one
figure, a senior physician played by Josef Sommer, who embodies
compassionate flexibility yet is comfortable within the structure.
His reasonable presence shows the rest of the film up as a
one-sided argument for emotional involvement with patients. It
would have been helped by an equally sympathetic figure on the
other side of the argument. Monica Potter and Daniel London as
colleagues who come to share Patch's ideas add to the likability
quotient. But instead of drama, ``Patch Adams'' gives us mere
iconography, and wastes Williams's iconoclastic dedicated doc.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
