<HEADLINE>
GLOBE CRITICS RATE FILMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
 ! poor, !! fair, !!! good, !!!! excellent  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; !!! &LR;  ``Central Station'' Classic humanist art cinema from
Brazil. Fernanda Montenegro is magnificent as a crusty old woman
whose heart is thawed when she accompanies a motherless boy
(Vincius de Oliveira) on a literal and symbolic journey to find his
father in Walter Salles's road film about contemporary Brazil
finding its identity, too. (R) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !!! &LR;  1/2 ``Dancing at Lughnasa'' A beautiful film of a beautiful
play (by Brian Friel) about five unmarried sisters in Donegal and
the refusal of their hearts and spirits to be crushed by the
grinding hardship they face and the return, in disgrace, of their
brother, a missionary priest who no longer sees any need to
distinguish between pegan religions and Catholicism. Meryl Streep
is the presiding sister. Michael Gambon is haunting as the
spiritual pilgrim. (PG) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !!! &LR;  ``Down in the Delta'' Richly-textured film directing debut of
poet Maya Angelou. In it, a single mother whose life is falling
apart in Chicago rights herself and her family after she returns to
her relatives and her roots in Mississippi. Alfre Woodard delilvers
a strongly-arched performance as the woman who becomes whole again.
You've never seen Wesley Snipes as he appears here in the role of a
soft-spoken, educated, prosperous Atlanta businessman. (PG-13) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !!! &LR;  ``Hurlyburly'' David Rabe's houseful of Hollywood loose
cannons make more dramatic sense here than they did on the New York
stage. Sean Penn is intense, yet sympathetic, as Eddie, trying to
lose himself in the fast-lane life, yet also wondering if he
shouldn't be keeping his ear cocked for a wakeup call. Strong
support from Kevin Spacey, as his too-cool pal, and from Chazz
Palminteri, Garry Shandling, Robin Wright Penn, Anna Paquin, and
Meg Ryan _ the latter three as women too strong to be destroyed by
the misogynistically destructive men. (R) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !!! &LR;  1/2 ``The Last Emperor'' Bernardo Bertolucci's Oscar-winning
film on the life of China's Pu Yi is as visually luscious as ever _
and even longer than when it was first released in 1987. This
director's cut of the film, restored to its hefty original 219
minutes, still soars despite some draggy moments, and remains
Bertolucci's masterpiece. (PG-13) (Renee Graham) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !!! &LR;  ``Little Voice'' Captivating fairytale about a reclusive young
woman in a crumbling seaside town in the north of England,
squelched into silence by her overbearing mother, except when she
uncannily reproduces the voices of Judy Garland, Marilyn Monroe,
Shirley Bassey, and the other divas she spends her days listening
to from her dead father's record collection. Jane Horrocks is
amazing as the girl whose voice is anything but little, Michael
Caine is wonderful as the sleazy agent who wants to exploit her
talent (he's Alfie, 25 years later) and Jim Broadbent is a big
help, too, as a seedy nightclub owner. (R) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !!! &LR;  ``Mighty Joe Young'' Solidly-crafted, family-friendly remake
of the 1949 film about a sensitive gorilla who suggests King Kong's
kid brother and is highly unhappy in so-called civilization.
Charlize Theron is the primatologist who turns it into a
beauty-and-the-beast story, and Bill Paxton is another plus in the
role of the guy who wants to save them both. (PG) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !! &LR;  ``Patch Adams'' This film about a nonconformist doctor who
clowns around with patients in the name of treating them more
humanely and effectively would seem to be made to order for Robin
Williams. But the manipulativeness of the clunky script keeps
getting in the way by stacking the deck. The docs are either rigid
martinets or compassionate shaker-uppers, almost never anything in
between. (PG-13) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !!!! &LR;  ``Shakespeare in Love'' The best backstage comedy ever made.
It's delightful for other reasons, too. Never has a script had so
much fun filling in the gaps in the life of a cultural icon as this
one does imagining what went into the writing of ``Romeo and
Juliet.'' Joseph Fiennes is an amusingly soulful Shakespeare,
Gwyneth Paltrow is luminous as the high-born woman he was thinking
of when he wrote Juliet and the supporting players are unfailingly
zestful, too, from Judi Dench's high-spirited Elizabeth to Ben
Affleck's droll matinee idol to Geoffrey Rush's desperate theater
owner. (R) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !! &LR;  ``Stepmom'' This starry workout for Susan Sarandon and Julia
Roberts, as discarded mom and stepmom to be, respectively, is fun
when it sticks with the comedy of antagonism. To start, anger
rules, especially with the resentful kids, caught in the middle of
their father's decision to leave their mom and live with a younger
babe. The string-pulling doesn't become a liability until it
introduces a dark plot strand that asks us to let the women come
full circle and start bonding. It becomes too pat and predictable
and prefab to not get in the way. (PG-13)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
