<HEADER>
A8581 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-LAST-EMPEROR-BO     12-28 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-LAST-EMPEROR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE `EMPEROR' GETS NEW CLOTHES, NOT PADDING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
THE LAST EMPEROR 
Directed by: Bernardo Bertolucci 
Written by: Mark Peploe and Bernardo Bertolucci 
Starring: John Lone, Joan Chen, Peter O'Toole, Ying Ruocheng,
Victor Wong, Dennis Dun 
Running time: 219 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 (adult situations) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eleven years after its initial release, ``The Last Emperor'' is
still one of the most visually luscious films of the past
quarter-century. Bernardo Bertolucci's Oscar-winning movie, a
full-bodied biography of the last man to rule as emperor upon
China's Dragon Throne, is breathtaking filmmaking _ even more so
since Bertolucci and his crew were the first Westerners allowed to
shoot a film within China's labyrinthine Forbidden City.
</P>
<P>
   Given that the film spans Pu Yi's life from age 3 until his
death at 62, one would have thought Bertolucci left few stones
unturned in detailing the times of a man who went from exalted
emperor to playboy exile to alleged war criminal. But as is so
common these days, Bertolucci has unveiled a director's cut of
``The Last Emperor,'' with several scenes adding nearly an hour to
the film's original running time of 160 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   These days, the words ``director's cut'' should be met with a
healthy sense of skepticism. Often, it's just an excuse for an
egomaniacal director trying to squeeze a bit more green out of
moviegoers by fattening his movie and resurrecting scenes that
should have been left buried. (Just the thought of James Cameron
someday releasing a director's cut of the
already-too-long-for-its-own-good ``Titanic'' makes me faint.)
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the most remarkable thing about this new edit of ``The Last
Emperor'' is that the additions do not make the film seem bloated
or unnecessarily padded _ and that's saying a lot for a film that
now runs three hours, 39 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The basic story, of course, remains the same. The film flashes
between two eras. As the film begins, it is 1950, and Pu Yi (played
as an adult by John Lone) is shuttled among Chinese men imprisoned
for war crimes and treason. In a railway restroom, he attempts
suicide _ and the story shoots back to 1908, and the events that
led him to this day of disgrace. At the tender age of 3, Pu Yi
ascends to the Imperial throne, emperor of China and ``Lord of
10,000 Years.'' Unaware of his power and prominence, he is a child
who misses his mother and wants nothing more than to go home. One
of the film's most stunning scenes is the little boy (energetically
played by Richard Vuu impatiently leaping from this throne toward a
billowing golden curtain. When the curtain is pulled away, the boy
stares in wonder at thousands of eunuchs, kowtowing to him.
</P>
<P>
   Pu Yi would sit on the throne for all of four years, becoming
just a figurehead once China was declared a republic. As a
teenager, his thirst for knowledge of the Western world was whetted
by Reginald Johnson, (Peter O'Toole), a Scottish tutor, and he
would dream of going to school in Cambridge. These moments are
blended with scenes of Pu Yi's imprisonment in a ``reeducation''
camp, along with his brother and longtime servant. Many of the
film's additions are in these sequences.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, ``The Last Emperor'' can be draggy _ even the
two-hours-plus version had its slow-as-molasses moments _ but they
have more to do with the dense historical matters than with the
film itself. For the most part, ``The Last Emperor'' is a
compelling story about a lost era, with splendid virtuoso
filmmaking that remains Bertolucci's masterpiece.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-28-98 1402EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
