A8584 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-28 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELEBRITIES: OPEN MOUTH, INSERT FOOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joe Eszterhas, who cranked out the screenplay of ``Showgirls,''
one of the most breathtakingly worthless movies ever made,
explained the film's raison d'etre thus: ``It's a spiritual
message. And forgive me, but I think it's almost a deeply religious
message on a very personal level.''
</P>
<P>
   I, for one, don't forgive him. But I've seen the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Eszterhas's quote is one of many in ``Stupid Celebrities,'' a
diverting little collection of dumb things said by famous people.
On the one hand, it may make you feel better about all the stupid
things you've said (or written) yourself. On the other hand, it may
depress you.
</P>
<P>
   It's the latest in a series of books by Ross and Kathryn Petras,
among them ``The 776 Stupidest Things Ever Said,'' ``The 776 Even
Stupider Things Ever Said,'' and ``Stupid Sex.'' The word
``stupid'' serves as a kind of catchall. Some of the quotes are
idiotic. But others might better be described as self-deluded or
egomaniacal or sexist. Some are merely shameless self-promotion.
These are celebrities after all.
</P>
<P>
   There are some famously ominous lines, among them Mick Jagger on
the prospect of aging: ``I'd rather be dead than singing
`Satisfaction' when I'm 45.''
</P>
<P>
   And there's Kathie Lee Gifford, who in her autobiography wrote
of her marriage to Frank: ``Cheating is out of the question.''
</P>
<P>
   Jagger pops up frequently, mostly saying outrageous things about
women, such as: ``I should think that being my old lady would be
all the satisfaction or career any woman needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone seeking examples of the male mind at its lowest ebb need
look no further than ``Stupid Celebrities.'' It's difficult to pick
a favorite, but I kind of like something Axl Rose said: ``It's
really hard to maintain a one-on-one relationship if the other
person is not going to allow me to be with other people.''
</P>
<P>
   Women, too, or some women anyway, say the darndest things.
``There aren't enough men to go around,'' Helen Gurley Brown is
quoted as complaining. ``Every time there's a plane accident, it's
one hundred men dead . . . and I literally think, `Why couldn't
some women have been on that flight?' ''
</P>
<P>
   As we know, movie stars say whatever it takes to call attention
to their latest project. Demi Moore, interviewed about the film
``Striptease,'' told one reporter she'd learned this about
stripping: ``It's not really about taking your clothes off.''
</P>
<P>
   So what is it about, Demi? ``Today's strip clubs are
capital-intensive female empowerment zones.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm glad to have that issue clarified.
</P>
<P>
   The rich really are different, nowhere more so than in their
attitude toward money. Deborah Koons Garcia is quoted as saying:
``Jerry died broke. We only have a few hundred thousand dollars in
the bank.''
</P>
<P>
   Rampant egomania rears its head on nearly every page of ``Stupid
Celebrities.'' Here's Barbra Streisand on herself: ``One thing's
for sure: Now when I look at `Funny Girl,' I think I was gorgeous.
I was too beautiful to play Fanny Brice.''
</P>
<P>
   Some lines are almost too stupid to believe, among them the
following, attributed to Sylvester Stallone: ``I'm astounded by
people who take 18 years to write something. That's how long it
took that guy to write `Madame Bovary,' and was that ever on the
bestseller list?''
</P>
<P>
   He must have been kidding. No?
</P>
<P>
   With ``Stupid Celebrities,'' the Petras have struck a rich vein
of gold. There are bound to be sequels because, as we see and hear
almost daily, celebrity is a bottomless well of stupidity. I hope
they add an index to their next collection so readers can turn
straight to the dumb things said by their favorite (or least
favorite) celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   (Diane White is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
