<HEADLINE>
SOMETIMES, THE RIGHT ATTITUDE CAN PAY DIVIDENDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL AND PATRICIA WEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sandy Rodgers of Amherst, N.H., sent us a letter the other day
about Circuit City.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the sort of letter we usually receive here. She didn't
complain about anything. She didn't say she had been ripped off. In
fact, it was just the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   Rodgers was one of a dozen readers who responded to our request
a month ago for tales of exceptionally good consumer experiences.
We thought there would be a lot more positive letters, given that
we get 20 to 30 complaint letters and calls each week. Despite the
low response rate, we still think it's worthwhile talking about the
good as well as the bad out there.
</P>
<P>
   In the sampling of stories that follow, a couple of themes
emerge. The companies in most cases went out of their way to make
sure their customer was satisfied. In some instances, it was
company policy, but in several of the cases another factor was at
work. Store officials said they helped a consumer not because of
any company rule but simply because the customer was so nice.
</P>
<P>
   Rodgers fits the nice category. She went to the Circuit City in
Manchester, N.H., on Nov. 24 to buy a TV for her husband for his
70th birthday. She ended up buying a floor model for $650 that
store officials loaded, unboxed, in the back of her Ford Explorer.
She remembers expressing some concern about the safety of the TV
back there, but says the loader told her it would be fine.
</P>
<P>
   About two blocks away from the store she heard a thud in the
back. She pulled into a Friendly's parking lot, opened the tail
gate and was barely able to get out of the way before the set
tumbled out and crashed to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   A woman at Friendly's helped her load the ruined TV back in her
car. With tears in her eyes, she drove back to Circuit City and
explained what happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without any hassle at all,'' Rodgers said, store manager Sean
McCarthy gave her another TV off the shelf and had it loaded in her
back seat. This time the TV was strapped in with a seat belt and
pinned in with the front seat. ``Friends who know this story are
amazed that a firm as large as this has any compassion. I am very
grateful,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy, who has been with Circuit City six years, stressed
that it is impossible to satisfy every single customer, ``But she
was so nice and I didn't want to disappoint her husband on his
birthday.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
A little less paranoid &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Kamens, 29, describes himself as a ``paranoid''
shopper. He seems to collect stories about bad consumer
experiences, such as the time a tire-maintenance program was not
honored or the day his contractor installed the wrong windows.
</P>
<P>
   So last July 5th was a memorable day for him. He and his
pregnant wife had just bought a futon and frame from Sleep-Rite in
Framingham, Mass. He agreed to buy the floor model of the frame,
because the sales staff said it was the only one available. He also
got a 15 percent discount on the $350 frame, or $52 off.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when the items were delivered at his Boston home, a new
un-assembled frame showed up instead of the already assembled floor
model. The delivery workers said the store had found a new frame in
stock. Kamens braced himself to hear about needing to pay full
price, and perhaps a $15 assembly fee.
</P>
<P>
   But instead the delivery men assembled the bed at no extra
charge. ``I was pleasantly surprised,'' said Kamens, a computer
programmer and father of a 4-month-old.
</P>
<P>
   Amy Farber, the manager at Sleep-Rite, said she remembers her
experience with Kamens very clearly. She said she simply felt the
store should honor the original price given. She said it was also
easier to ``go the extra mile'' for someone like Kamens who was so
kind to everyone at the store. ``It helps when the customer is so
nice,'' she said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
A real guarantee &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fred Liberatore, a father of four, had always heard about the
lifetime guarantee on Cross pens. So when his son found a busted
Cross pen in a library parking lot a couple of months ago,
Liberatore decided to send it to the A.T. Cross company in Lincoln,
R.I., and test the guarantee.
</P>
<P>
   To his amazement, three weeks later, he received a brand-new
grey Cross pen with gold trim, an exact copy of the broken pen he
had sent in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed unreal,'' said Liberatore, a 54-year-old biochemist.
``Here was a company standing behind its product.''
</P>
<P>
   Russell Boss, president of the company, said the 152-year-old
company always honors the lifetime guarantee and generally receives
only 1 percent of its merchandise back for replacement or repair.
He said the guarantee on its pens _ which range from an $18
ball-point pen to a $450 fountain pen _ ``has won us a lot of
friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Boss recalled a time when a Pennsylvania farmer sent them a pen
covered with dark soil in a plastic bag. It turns out he farmer
droped his pen in the fields one day and couldn't find it. Some
months later, he found the pen in the cow manure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cow ate it and got rid of it,'' Boss said.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the pen worked or not, Boss is not sure. He can't say
anyone even tested the digested pen. He said the company gladly
sent the farmer back a new one.
</P>
<P>
   Liberatore said he is amazed that such old-fashioned customer
service exists. After receiving the new pen, he said, he's sure to
give the Cross company a lifetime of loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``You patronize companies that treat customers right,'' he
said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Have it your way &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kathy de Natale pleaded with Roche Bros. to bring back a muffin
recipe she liked. Roche Bros. refused, but did the next best thing.
The supermarket agreed to make her a dozen of the muffins she liked
whenever she wanted.
</P>
<P>
   G. Robert Warren says he had a similar experience with Shaw's
Supermarkets, but with doughnuts instead of muffins.
</P>
<P>
   Warren is a private investigator and self-described doughnut
connoisseur, although he says his wife thinks he's
doughnut-obsessed. Shaw's introduced new items to its bakery
section a year ago and in the process eliminated some items to make
room. One of those eliminated items was the powdered sugar
doughnut, Warren's favorite.
</P>
<P>
   He protested to Shaw's and they restored it to the bakery case,
but they did more than that. Warren liked his powdered sugar
doughnuts greasy and sugared heavily right out of the oven. ``The
greasier the better,'' he said. Shaw's made it that way only about
20 percent of the time, he said. When he inquired, the bakery
department at the Shaw's in Hanover, mass. agreed to make the
doughnuts his way whenever he wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw's spokesman Bernard Rogan said such special requests are
often granted. ``It's called developing customer loyalty,'' he
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (We want your consumer ideas and tips. Please e-mail Mohl at
mohl(at)globe.com or Wen at wen(at)globe.com. Their address is Box
2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
