<HEADLINE>
HOW BEST TO INVEST RETIREMENT ACCOUNT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am 54 and lost my mother earlier this year. I have
inherited $80,000 from her estate that I want to invest, but I'm
not sure in what. Most of my investments _ a total of $740,700 _
are in TIAA/CREF accounts, heavily dominated by equity positions. I
add $1,730 a month to those positions. I have $22,400 in savings
bonds and money markets, and I have been putting $300 a month in a
diversified portfolio of mutual funds. How would you suggest I
invest this inheritance, and do you suggest any changes in my
present investment strategy if my goal is to retire in six to eight
years with an annual income of $75,000 to $80,000?
</P>
<P>
   S.K., Cambridge, Mass. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I suggest you invest it very conservatively, as the first of
a number of steps to reduce the risk level in the overall
portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Let's suppose that over the next seven years your portfolio
achieved only 8 percent average annual total returns. With ongoing
contributions at current levels, you would amass $1,533,154. With
such an accumulation, the portfolio could support withdrawals at
the $80,000-a-year level with a portfolio return of only 5.35
percent. And that's without adding the $80,000 inheritance into the
figures.
</P>
<P>
   The point is that you are already clearly in sight of your
target. That's why I used that presumption of only 8 percent growth
during the next seven years _ because I think you should sharply
reduce portfolio risk.
</P>
<P>
   The lion's share of your money is $491,000 in the CREF stock
fund, and that's also where the biggest part of your ongoing
contributions is going. I know, it's a great account, and it has
done great things for you in the past few years. But as those
lawyers are so fond of saying, past performance should not be
considered an indication of future performance.
</P>
<P>
   I think the bull market is pretty tired. Moreover, at this point
you're only an intermediate-term investor, with a six- to
eight-year time horizon for accumulation.
</P>
<P>
   After that, you will begin to use part of the portfolio to
provide an income stream, with the balance left in stocks as a
hedge against future inflation. But you should move gradually from
the accumulation to the income-producing stage. Now is the time to
begin moving toward more conservative positions.
</P>
<P>
   I suggest you immediately shift your allocations at CREF so that
no more than 65 percent is in stock funds, with the balance in the
TIAA (annuity) and the bond fund accounts. I'd make similar moves
in the mutual fund accounts you are building, which currently are
being divided evenly between stock and fixed-income funds.
</P>
<P>
   Since the $300 a month that's going into these accounts is a
fairly small part of your ongoing savings, I suggest you reallocate
that money, putting all of it on the fixed-income side.
</P>
<P>
   As for the $80,000 inheritance, I'd also put that on the
fixed-income side. My choice would be the Vanguard GNMA fund. If
you reinvested dividends, achieved average 6.5 percent annual
returns there, and used other money to deal with the resulting tax
liabilities, that account would add a further $124,318 after seven
years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am 65 and about to retire. I have $45,000 in my retirement
account. My company proposes to give me $349 a month for the rest
of my life _ and after my death the money would be gone. I think I
can do better myself and save the principal. What do you think,
considering that I do not need the money? I am considering the
following allocation among Vanguard funds: 15 percent in U.S.
Growth, 20 percent in the Index 500 fund, 25 percent in Wellesley
Income, 25 percent in GNMA, and 15 percent in a money market fund.
Would I have to start selling these investments at age 70?
</P>
<P>
   R.M., San Diego &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. You would require a 9.72 percent total return to bring you a
$349 monthly income stream without invading your $45,000 principal.
Since your proposed portfolio works out to 44 percent stocks
(reflecting 36 percent of the Vanguard Wellesley fund portfolio
that's in equities) and the balance is on the fixed-income side,
you are unlikely to come up with such a return.
</P>
<P>
   My guess is that over the long haul, the total return from such
a portfolio would more likely be in the 7 percent to 8 percent
range _ and if you did achieve such results and withdrew $349 every
months, the well would run dry shortly before 21 years have
elapsed.
</P>
<P>
   But from your statement that you don't need the money, and from
your final question about when you would have to begin withdrawals,
I am guessing that what you have in mind is accumulating a pool of
money rather than getting an income stream.
</P>
<P>
   So I would transfer the lump-sum payment to a tax-deferred
account at Vanguard, in which you would not have to make any
withdrawals until after 5 1/2 years _ mandatory withdrawals begin
after age 70 1/2. But if you did achieve average 8 percent
portfolio return and made no withdrawals, at that point the account
would amount to $67,025.
</P>
<P>
   Then you would have enough capital to withdraw $349 a month for
as long as you live _ with the principal gaining modestly to boot.
Theoretically, after 20 years of such a schedule, you would have
accumulated $97,113.
</P>
<P>
   But I say theoretically, since the amount of your required
annual withdrawal would rise steadily. Presuming that the
beneficiary of this tax-deferred account is the same age as you,
for example, for the year in which you turn age 70 1/2, you would
be required to take a mandatory withdrawal of at least $3,318.
</P>
<P>
   That sequence of $349 monthly income checks would more than
cover that.
</P>
<P>
   But as the years elapsed, the escalation in the amount of the
mandatory minimum withdrawal would eventually mean that you would
have to go beyond that $349 monthly figure.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I would like to retire around age 65 with an income of $2,500
to $3,000 a month. I am now 49 and plan to have my home paid for by
the time I retire. I have $25,000 in a bank savings account paying
5 percent, and I will have the opportunity to join my company's
profit sharing and pension plan at the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   O.L., Bedford, Texas &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Let's assume that you'll need $2,750 a month in retirement.
You could achieve such an income stream from a moderately
conservative fixed-income portfolio of about $510,000.
</P>
<P>
   But you'll also want to have additional funds _ money you'll
leave in more aggressive investments such as stock funds to build a
supplementary pool to protect you against inflation in the later
years of your retirement.
</P>
<P>
   So let's (fairly arbitrarily) select $650,000 as a target
accumulation by the time of your retirement. Let's also treat that
$25,000 now in the bank as emergency money _ presuming that you'll
leave it where it is, but not spend it. After 16 years, that
$25,000 would have grown to $54,571 _ meaning that you will need to
save $595,429 more by age 65.
</P>
<P>
   How much will you need to save to get there? If you went with a
fairly aggressive savings program _ investing primarily in stock
investments _ you might aim for a 10 percent average annual return.
If that return were achieved, you'd need to put away $1,319 a
month.
</P>
<P>
   If you went with a more conservative balanced portfolio _
typically divided about 65 percent stocks and the rest bonds _ you
might expect 8 percent average annual returns. That would entail
monthly savings of $1,587.
</P>
<P>
   And if you are truly conservative, you might go for a
fixed-income portfolio, balancing a few bond funds with money
market holdings. But here you should expect only about 6 percent
average returns, and it would thus require savings of $1,881 a
month to achieve the goal.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the best vehicle for these savings is through the
profit sharing and pension plans available through your work. If
these plans don't allow you to save as much as you, need to, you
could add Roth IRA accounts (limited to $2,000 annual
contributions) or variable annuity plans, or even taxable mutual
fund accounts. All of those options are available at most mutual
fund companies.
</P>
<P>
   As for investment vehicles, if you must go beyond your
employer's plans, I'd suggest that the additional savings be done
with the Vanguard Index 500 fund (if you are taking the more
aggressive course), Vanguard Balanced Index fund (for the
middle-of-the-road option), or Vanguard Asset Allocation fund at
the most conservative.
</P>
<P>
   I know that saving $1,300 to $1,800 a month for 16 years might
seem like a pretty daunting task, but my bet is that you'll have
the discipline to do this.
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
