<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 14:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8595 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEATTLE-SLOWDOWN-BOS &LR;      12-28 1573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEATTLE-SLOWDOWN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SEATTLE, A NEW TREND: WAKE   UP, SMELL THE COFFEE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ In the crewmen's shack on Pier 14 of Puget Sound's
Elliott waterway, an engineer in orange slicker and flannel who
identifies himself only as ``Captain'' holds forth at a table of
dock workers clutching cups of oily coffee.
</P>
<P>
   ``This city has become a fraud,'' he said, voicing a common view
on the waterfront, where the city's chic latte-drinking set is
viewed askance. ``It's not what people want you to think it is.
This is no different than anywhere else. Never was.''
</P>
<P>
   After more than a decade of building itself up as the nation's
lifestyle paradise, where Gore-Tex took the place of Armani and the
economy seemed bulletproof, Seattle recently has found reason to
doubt itself.
</P>
<P>
   This month Boeing, by far the city's largest employer, announced
plans to lay off 48,000 workers, a drastic move expected to push
the city into its first recession in 16 years. With Asia in
financial crisis, ships that once departed Seattle docks loaded
with wheat, timber, paper, and aluminum bound for Japan and Korea
are leaving empty. Exports fell 20 percent in the first six months
of the year, decimating some farms and regional manufacturers that
have become dependent on foreign markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see stuff coming in, but there's a lot of empty crates
going out,'' said Bob Dalheim, a tugboat operator.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, some say the much vaunted Pacific Northwest
image that became a virtual trademark for many local companies and
made dozens of them household names is wearing thin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the fascination with that Seattle image, be it
lifestyle or whatever, is probably wearing off,'' said Richard
Conway, a local economist.
</P>
<P>
   All that is a hard fall for a place that was, in the words of
Fortune magazine, the ``capital of the '90s.'' By reputation, at
least, it has everything: urban chic, stunning natural beauty, and
prosperity. The companies it spawned made millions exporting to the
rest of the nation what became known as the Seattle mystique in the
form of designer coffee, microbrewed beer, camping equipment, and
of course, computer software.
</P>
<P>
   But now Microsoft has become a behemoth known these days for its
ongoing battle with the Justice Department, which has accused the
company of widespread anticompetitive practices. Bill Gates is
viewed in many quarters as a corporate Darth Vader, not the Wonder
Boy of a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Starbucks, once an icon of Seattle's homey hipness, is nearly as
common as McDonalds and may be best known as the brand preferred by
Clinton prosecutor Kenneth W. Starr. Eddie Bauer, an L.L.
Bean-style outdoor clothier that relied on homespun simplicity, now
belongs to a mass-market catalog company and has abandoned its
original product line.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, sales at Nike, another Pacific Northwest corporate
giant, have fallen precipitously in the last quarter, as the youth
market continues to eschew athletic shoes. The company's ``Just Do
It'' message, practically a generational motto just a few years
ago, has been trashed in recent marketing surveys and Nike's image
has been tarnished by reports of sweatshop conditions at its
foreign manufacturing facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``They started as symbols of a lifestyle, you might say a pure
lifestyle,'' Conway said. ``But when you get big and make a lot of
money, you lose the personal touch. Then people love to hate you.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle itself seems no longer to possess all the qualities that
helped fuel a dedade of regional hubris. Rampant development has
severely damaged native salmon populations. New subdivisions creep
ever farther up the foothills of the Cascade Mountains. And
rush-hour traffic, once virtually nonexistent, was recently
determined by a Texas consulting firm to be the nation's worst
behind San Francisco and Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the same town it was, that's for sure,'' lamented
Peter Conte, a native and spokesman for Boeing, the company that
more than any other represents what locals now call ``the old
Seattle.''
</P>
<P>
   That time is nostalgically recalled as the era that helped make
Seattle famous in the 1990s. The city was uncrowded, according to
long-time residents, life was simpler, and people hiked and fished
in the unspoiled forests and mountains nearby.
</P>
<P>
   But it was also a one-company town, whose fortunes were tied to
Boeing. During the company's heyday, in the 1960s, two out of every
three of the city's working adults were employed in its cavernous
aircraft assembly plants and administrative offices. When the
company laid off 54,000 in the early 1970s, the city nearly
collapsed. A billboard along the highway near the plant read, ``The
Last Person to Leave, Please Turn Out the Lights.''
</P>
<P>
   City officials embarked on a plan to resurrect Seattle's economy
and build an image as ``the most beautiful city in America.'' Much
was made of the local landscape in recruiting employees and
businesses from other regions of the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to all say that Mount Rainier was worth $10,000 a year
in salary,'' Boeing's Conte said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it helped inspire a mass migration in the 1980s from
cities like Los Angeles and New York, which go-go yuppies fled to
seek a more meaningful life in the outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in California in the '80s,'' said Mary Ann Quarton,
director of the University of Washington's retail management
program. ``I saw what it did to people. Nobody was happy. It was
all about making money and spending it. The values of the Northwest
really caught on. Suddenly everyone wanted to come here.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle was flooded with more than a half-million new residents,
and with the deluge came innovative ideas and marketing savvy. It
is ``interesting to note,'' said Richard Yalch, a University of
Washington marketing professor, ``that some of the most successful
companies selling the Seattle life were started by New Yorkers.''
</P>
<P>
   The newcomers bred deep resentments among established residents,
who responded by forming such groups as the ``Committee for a
Lesser Seattle'' and coining terms like ``Californication'' to
describe what they saw happening to the landscape.
</P>
<P>
   It was the birth of ``the new Seattle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is the old Seattle and there is the new Seattle,'' said
Quarton. ``The new Seattle is Microsoft. That culture is taking
over.''
</P>
<P>
   And very rich. Microsoft's 11,500 Seattle-area employees receive
an average of $250,000 a year, including salary, stock options, and
benefits, according to Conway, the economist.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not talking chump change here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence of that wealth is everywhere, especially on the
city's east side, where subdivisions of sparkling near-mansions
have been carved into the forest. The wooded shores of Lake
Washington, where Gates is finishing his $60 million,
40,000-square-foot mansion, increasingly is fronted by houses
purchased by the new techno class.
</P>
<P>
   Among real estate agents, the vision of a 25-year-old bachelor
Microsoft programmer putting down cash on an $800,000 house has
become a Seattle archetype.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's depressing,'' said Ken Bacon, managing broker for
Windermere Realty in Redmond, the suburb where Microsoft is
headquartered.
</P>
<P>
   Tales of other excesses proliferate. According to the Seattle
Times, a Microsoft employee recently hosted a private dinner for a
group including his tailor, chef, and wine buyer. The tab, after
Chateaubriand, wine, cognac, and cigars: $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   If recession hits Seattle, Microsoft is expected to be one of
the few companies to come out unscathed. While virtually every
other industry has felt the pinch of Asia's financial crisis, the
company is likely to exceed the $2 billion in software it exported
to Pacific Rim countries last year. And when Boeing announced its
layoffs early this month, Microsoft hastily and pointedly announced
it planned to hire thousands.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty clear the message they were sending,'' said
Boeing's Conte. ``They didn't make any bones about it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's virtual reality,'' said economist Conway. ``That's
Seattle.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with its visible presence, Microsoft is not enough to save
Seattle from a likely downturn, economists said. But in the view of
some, the company and its wealthy minions are setting a new tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about money now,'' said Quarton.
</P>
<P>
   The REI mountaineering store offers a view of how things have
changed. Its giant wooden lodge near downtown opened last year and
has become Seattle's most popular tourist attraction except for the
space needle.
</P>
<P>
   Landscaped with native conifers, the site boasts a bike path and
a two-story waterfall. Inside, a stone pinnacle for climbers rises
65 feet. A rain booth simulates mountain thunder showers for
Gore-Tex wearers.
</P>
<P>
   Many visitors never make it to the mountains, admitted William
Chin, REI's special events coordinator. ``The point is they feel
good coming here,'' he said. ``They're happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Of such things, a Seattle resident recently complained in a
letter to the Seattle Times that ``it now appears Seattleites' idea
of a good time has switched from outdoor activities to indoor
shopping.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, that's American life now,'' said Quarton. ``We had an
image of being a different sort of place. But reality is reality.
It always has a way of creeping back in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
