<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUMOR IS OPEN TO INTERPRETATION 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Another year blessed with rewarding travel experiences _ from
the Caribbean to Canada, Arizona to Austria _ is approaching its
conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Though life on the road includes occasional stress and
aggravation, it's nice to find reason to chuckle as the journey
nears home.
</P>
<P>
   So the timing couldn't be better for the arrival in bookstores
of the ninth fun-filled ``do's and taboos'' volume by Roger E.
Axtell. His latest: ``Do's and Taboos of Humo(u)r Around the
World'' (Wiley, $15.95).
</P>
<P>
   ``Laughter has no accent,'' Axtell reminds us in his
introduction. ``And no matter where you travel in our world, there
is one form of communication that is understood _ the smile.''
</P>
<P>
   If only similar understanding through words were guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   Axtell's book, like its predecessors, aims to help American
travelers _ especially business executives _ avoid communication
blunders. Many of his stories and tips have a serious tone.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What did you say? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, humor can be quite unintentional. Among Axtell's
examples:
</P>
<P>
   ``In Belgium, General Motors used a tag line, `Body by Fisher,'
but when that was translated into Flemish it said, `Corpse by
Fisher.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``In China, Kentucky Fried Chicken's famous slogan
`finger-lickin' good' came out as `eat your fingers off.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``When Braniff Airlines translated a slogan about its luxurious
upholstery (`Fly in leather') into Spanish, it came out as `Fly
naked.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Axtell tells about a time when, as an executive with the Parker
Pen Co., he sent a fax to a factory manager in Peru. ``In the
message, I explained that I needed a head count. I said: `I need to
know the number of people in your office, broken down by sex, and I
need the information immediately.'
</P>
<P>
   ``The manager dutifully replied: `Here is your head count. Here
we have 35 in our factory, 10 in the office and five in the
hospital _ none broken down by sex.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Later, in a footnote, he added, `If you must know, our problem
down here is with alcohol.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Think before speaking &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Too often, as Axtell illustrates, travelers don't stop to think
clearly before speaking. He relates the story of an American who
asked an Englishman, ``How do you celebrate Thanksgiving in your
country?'' The Englishman paused, smiled and replied dryly, ``I
suppose you could say in Britain we celebrate Thanksgiving on the
Fourth of July.''
</P>
<P>
   Another American, visiting England as part of a tour group, was
impressed by a lovely church not far from Heathrow Airport. ``When
was it built?'' she asked the guide, who responded, ``About 650
years ago.'' ``It's a pity,'' the woman said, ``they built it so
close to the airport.''
</P>
<P>
   Axtell recalls telephoning the front desk at an Indonesian hotel
to request a wake-up call, only to be informed that alarm clocks
were installed in every room for that purpose. `` `But what happens
if it doesn't work?' I asked. After a pause he replied, `Just call
me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Then there was American baseball pitcher Bill Gullickson, who
signed a lucrative contract to play in Japan and was asked about
daily life in that country. ``He replied that language was the most
difficult and different feature,'' Axtell writes. `` `It's crazy,'
he said. `The only American words I saw were Sony and Mitsubishi.'
''
</P>
<P>
   Other travelers know exactly what they are saying. And why.
Axtell's brother, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Not yet fully recovered from a broken leg but required to travel
overseas, he discovered a sure-fire way to fly in comfort. His
conversation with any person in an adjacent seat:
</P>
<P>
   ``Pardon me, are you going to need that airsick bag?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No. Why?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I normally need more than one.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Invariably, the person would raise a hand, carry on a
whispered conversation with the flight attendant and move to
another seat,'' Axtell writes. And his brother would stretch out
over two seats.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes even accurate translations can lead travelers into
uncomfortable situations. Axtell tells of a woman who discreetly
asked the manager of a restaurant in Peru where she could go to
wash her hands. ``The manager ushered her into a bathroom where
some painters happened to be working. When the painters started to
leave, the manager stopped them, saying: `That's OK. Don't leave.
The lady only wants to wash her hands.' ''
</P>
<P>
   A highlight is Axtell's listing of some of those classic mangled
misinterpretations on signs posted all over the world. Let's usher
out the 1998 travel year with a few gems (and if you want to read
more, bookstores stock or can order Axtell's newest publication and
others in the series):
</P>
<P>
   At a Russian cemetery: ``You are welcome to visit the cemetery
where famous Russian and Soviet composers, artists and writers are
buried daily except Thursday.''
</P>
<P>
   On a Polish hotel menu: ``Salad a firm's own make; limpid red
beet soup with cheesy dumplings in the form of a finger; roasted
duck let loose; beef rashers beaten up in the country people's
fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   In an English bathroom: ``Toilet out of order. You are welcome
to use floor below.''
</P>
<P>
   At a Belgian dry cleaner's: ``Men: For best results, drop
trousers here. Ladies: Leave your clothes here and spend the
afternoon having a good time.''
</P>
<P>
   At a Hong Kong dress shop: ``Ladies have fits upstairs.''
</P>
<P>
   In an Acapulco hotel: ``All the water in this hotel has been
personally passed by the manager.''
</P>
<P>
   And a detour sign in Japan: ``Stop: Drive sideways.''
</P>
<P>
   May all your detours lead to fun-filled adventures. And no
matter what you say or how you say it, keep smiling. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
