<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
START NOW TO GET A JUMP ON WEEDS 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY HUBER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I would like to get a jump on lawn weeds. How can I eliminate
weeds in flower beds?
</P>
<P>
   A: &UR;  &LR; Other gardeners have asked about weeds recently, so while
you plant winter color such as dianthus, snapdragons, pansies,
ornamental kale and cabbage and a round of prechilled tulips, use
the time to remove weeds in your beds. It's a great way to work out
stress. Mulch will improve the appearance of your new plantings,
help retain some soil moisture and warmth for the roots and help
keep weeds down.
</P>
<P>
   Pre-emergent herbicides applied in late winter/early spring can
prevent annual weeds in your beds, and you can spot-treat weeds
that already have sprouted with a herbicide containing glyphosates.
Do not let the latter touch desirable plants. Again, I encourage
you to be as organic as possible.
</P>
<P>
   As you pull and plant, think about your lawn. A healthy lawn
generated by proper fertilizing, watering and mowing is your first
line of defense in controlling weeds. However, if your lawn has
become thin through neglect or weather-related reasons, you may
want to move to another level of weed control. (More on herbicides
in just a minute.) This year's drought, then extra-heavy rains,
have certainly taken a toll on lawns and other plants.
</P>
<P>
   Weeds gain ground through weak spots in a lawn. They thrive
where turfgrass has fallen victim to stress. Bare spots, thin
patches of grass, and diseased or insect-infested areas invite the
seeds of unwanted plants, or weeds.
</P>
<P>
   During the growing season, proper watering, mowing and
fertilizing will promote healthy, thick growth that gives turf a
competing edge over weeds. Don't overwater, as many weeds thrive in
moisture.
</P>
<P>
   Aerate the soil _ either with special aerating shoes or with a
pitchfork.
</P>
<P>
   The recommended mowing height for St. Augustine is 2 { to 3
inches. If you use a mulching mower, the small grass bits will
break down and replenish soil nutrients. Mow {-inch higher during
dry, hot weather to keep roots shaded. Mow high in shaded areas.
That extra bit of leaf surface is needed for photosynthesis to make
up for reduced sunlight. Taller blades block the light needed to
ensure weed seed germination. Mow close and you open up the area to
weeds.
</P>
<P>
   Fertilize the lawn after the grass greens in spring and is
growing and in late October or early November.
</P>
<P>
   A dense turf crowds out weeds, discourages perennial weeds from
spreading and shades the soil, preventing waiting weed seeds from
germinating. When a healthy lawn starts growing in spring,
cool-season weeds become less noticeable.
</P>
<P>
   Each year a long roster of weeds confronts the gardener. It's
helpful to keep in mind that there are warm-season annuals and
perennials and cool-season annuals and perennials. There are
products for each. Use the right product at the right time. The
trick to using a herbicide is to know the type of turfgrass you
have and which weeds you want to eliminate. Labels list target
weeds.
</P>
<P>
   Used improperly, weedkillers can do a lot of harm. Certain
herbicides will kill certain grasses. And don't use them in edible
gardens.
</P>
<P>
   There are two types of weedkillers: pre-emergent and
post-emergent. Pre-emergent herbicides are applied in early spring
to deter warm-season annual weeds and in early fall to prevent
outbreaks of cool-season annual weeds. If you use such products
after the seeds germinate, you've wasted your time and money.
</P>
<P>
   For example, to prevent crabgrass, a warm-season annual, from
emerging, apply a pre-emergent herbicide about two weeks before the
last anticipated frost.
</P>
<P>
   Henbit and chickweed, two cool-season annuals that germinate in
fall, may be deterred with a pre-emergent weedkiller applied in
early fall. Gallery is one pre-emergent product.
</P>
<P>
   Post-emergents attack weeds after they've sprouted and are most
effective when applied to young weeds. The older the weed, the more
difficult it is to control.
</P>
<P>
   According to the research I've done, post-emergents are a more
effective control of perennial weeds. Ortho's Weed-B-Gon for
Southern Lawns is one post-emergent control that can be used on St.
Augustine turf for control of chickweed, dandelions, henbit, oxalis
and other broad-leaved weeds.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia buttonweed is a warm-season perennial that can be a
nuisance in Houston lawns. This matting, fleshy-leafed weed has
small white flowers and green seed pods that resemble green beads.
It spreads underground, so pre-emergents aren't effective. You'll
have to repeat post-emergent applications. Image is said to be
helpful. You can pull it, too, to chisel away at the root network.
</P>
<P>
   Pesky nutsedge (nutgrass) is particularly adept at popping up in
bare spots, but it loses ground in a thick lawn of St. Augustine.
Again, Image is a post-emergent product that helps control
nutsedge.
</P>
<P>
   I hesitate to use product names in this column, but I was asked
to be specific. Ask your certified nurseryman for information
before selecting a herbicide.
</P>
<P>
   Take special note: Only materials recommended for St. Augustine
grass should be used on St. Augustine lawns, as the turf might be
damaged by some chemicals that are safe for Bermuda grass or other
turf. Repeat applications may be necessary for both pre-emergent
and post-emergent herbicides. Follow label recommendations for all
herbicides.
</P>
<P>
   You might consider this, too: It's best to fertilize a lawn
after it has greened and is growing in spring. Pre-emergents for
warm-season lawn weeds must be applied before it's time to apply a
spring fertilizer; therefore weed-and-feed formulas may not be the
answer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
