<HEADER>
A8622 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SOCIAL-SECURI     12-28 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SOCIAL-SECURITY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SAYS SOCIAL SECURITY PROTECTED AGAINST COMPUTER BUG 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDs: FILED in ``w'' and ``f'' categories.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton declared Monday that the
computers controlling the nation's Social Security system are ready
for the Year 2000 computer bug, ensuring that benefits to 48
million older Americans won't be halted in January of that year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This problem won't delay checks a single day,'' Clinton said
at a news conference here.
</P>
<P>
   He said the computer systems that each year make 860 million
payments worth more than $1 billion on behalf of the Social
Security Administration, the Department of Veterans Affairs, the
Internal Revenue Service and other agencies will work on Jan. 1,
2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was truly a stunning achievement,'' he said of the
agencies' work to solve the so-called Y2K problem that threatens to
shut down computers around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that earlier this month an independent contractor
confirmed after testing the system for those agencies that the
computers would work. But the president warned that the computer
glitch continues to threaten the country and that a great deal more
work needs to be done to fix it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This involves everyone who depends on computers, which is
nearly all of us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   According to White House officials, 61 percent of federal
computer systems are now Y2K compliant, up from 27 percent a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Federal agencies face a March deadline to finish their computer
repairs and are required to send status reports on their efforts to
the White House and Congress on a quarterly basis.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the success of the Social Security and other systems,
congressional overseers, such as Sen. Robert Bennett, R-Utah,
chairman of the Senate Special Committee on the Year 2000 Problem,
have said that many other government agencies, including the
Departments of Defense and State, are hopelessly behind.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional reports estimate that the cost to fix the federal
government's computer systems will be $6.4 billion. In addition,
the reports say that many smaller state and local government
agencies are far behind schedule and may not be Y2K compliant in
time.
</P>
<P>
   The problem stems from the fact that many computers originally
programmed to recognize only the last two digits of a year will
fail or give out wrong information on Jan. 1, 2000, when those
machines will assume it is 1900.
</P>
<P>
   The failure could also come when one computer system that thinks
the year is 1900 interacts with another computer system that thinks
the year is 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Some computers can be reprogrammed through tedious review of and
changes to their software code, but many devices have embedded
microchips that must be physically replaced.
</P>
<P>
   Many computer experts warn that the Y2K problem could cause
massive disruptions to everyday life as computers controlling
banks, rail systems, power grids and other essential facilities
shut down or malfunction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to make sure that on Jan. 1, 2000, power comes on,
that water continues to run, that the most vital functions of daily
life are completely safe,'' Bennett said last month.
</P>
<P>
   Some economists also have warned that closed factories and
disabled transportations systems could send the United States,
along with the rest of the world, into recession.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Yardeni, chief economist of the investment firm Deutsche
Morgan Grenfell's North American division, predicted that the
economic disruptions caused by the Year 2000 problem could cause a
recession as severe as the economic downturn of 1974-1975. That
recession was triggered by the Middle East's oil embargo.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's is no doubt that this will be cause some serious
disturbances in the United States,'' he said in a statement Monday.
``The question is how big will they be, and that will depend on
what we do from this point on.''
</P>
<P>
   Yardeni, who gained a large following on Wall Street when he
correctly forecasted the stock market boom of the early 1990s,
currently estimates that there is a 70 percent chance that the Year
2000 computer bug will cause a worldwide recession.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-28-98 1430EST &QL; 
