<SLUG> BC-MONEY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUT FINANCIAL PLAN IN BLACK AND WHITE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PAMELA YIP 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a writer, I know the power of writing your ideas down.
</P>
<P>
   There's something about taking the trouble to put our ideas down
on paper that solidifies them and forces us to weed out the
extraneous stuff.
</P>
<P>
   You can tap this power to help you develop a plan that will help
you achieve your goals for the coming year.
</P>
<P>
   This effort doesn't have to be anything elaborate. The key is to
simply put down your ideas and use them to guide you.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where am I today, where do I want to go and how am I going to
get there?'' said Woody Laywell, a certified financial planner at
Laywell Financial Resources in Houston. ``It does not have to be
rocket science.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Be specific &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Be as specific as possible about your plan so you can estimate
the real costs and benefits of your ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you just say, `I want to take a trip,' you could end up
anywhere,'' said Wynette Stuntz, a partner and certified financial
planner at Allen, Hampton, Stuntz &AMP; Welsh Financial Services in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   After listing your spending and saving goals, prioritize them.
Which ones are the most important? What do you want to accomplish
first?
</P>
<P>
   Write them down in the present tense. That makes them seem more
achievable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does something to your subconscious,'' Stuntz said. ``Your
subconscious mind accepts orders that are in the present tense
better than it does orders that are in the future tense.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, don't just write, ``I want to get rich,'' because
that's too vague.
</P>
<P>
   It would be better to write, ``I have $100,000 on Dec. 31,
2005.'' What you're doing is reinforcing your subconscious on what
you want to achieve.
</P>
<P>
   Being specific and active in your thinking is especially
important in setting retirement goals.
</P>
<P>
   Set an age when you want to have enough money on hand so you
won't have to keep working.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then set a specific dollar amount that you want to have coming
in from all sources in today's dollars at that age _ a gross dollar
amount to make you independent of the need to work,'' Stuntz said.
</P>
<P>
   After you've written down a goal, list ways to achieve it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may mean that I will have to make reasonable sacrifices
today to obtain those future goals,'' Laywell said. ``A person with
a sheet of paper, with a calculator, their checkbook, can determine
what their spending is, where they might be able to conserve.''
</P>
<P>
   Every one of us can cut out some fat in our spending.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever steps you take to achieve your goals, do them
consistently and review what you've done periodically to see if
you're on target.
</P>
<P>
   ``Initially, you should review it monthly until you get on track
and get comfortable with what you're doing,'' Laywell said.
</P>
<P>
   If you're married, it's crucial that you and your spouse work
together as a team to write down a financial plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to talk about it and agree about it, because you
can't do it unilaterally,'' Laywell said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Keep it simple &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Finally, don't write off your effort. Keep your plan simple. If
you set unrealistic goals, you risk getting discouraged and giving
up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason a lot of people fail is because they make it too
complicated,'' Laywell said. ``They say, `I can't do this, so it
won't fit at all.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Don't try to achieve too many goals at once.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will have better success if you focus on one goal at a
time,'' Stuntz said. ``If you diversify too much, you're pulled off
in too many directions and you end up not accomplishing anything at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't get bogged down in picky details.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can make the monitoring of this so much by trying to
evaluate jot and tittle, and you can find yourself doing more
detail and you become frustrated,'' Laywell said. ``That's not
necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't give up if you deviate from your written plan. A big part
of a financial plan will call for your changing behavior that took
years and years to build up. Old habits die hard, and you will trip
up once in a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason people fail is they expect too much, too soon when
they start making changes in their financial management,'' Laywell
said.
</P>
<P>
   So don't rip into yourself too harshly for periodic mistakes.
The trick is to not mess up all the time.
</P>
<P>
   Married couples, don't beat each other up. Putting your plans
down on paper literally calls for you both to be on the same page.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three steps forward and two back are still progress,'' Laywell
said.
</P>
<P>
   Send e-mail to pamela.yip (at) chron.com &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
