<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUN-POWER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOLAR STORMS MAY SHOWER EARTH WITH PROBLEMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The sun goes a little crazy now and then by
hurling million-degree fireballs and star-sized, electrically
charged clouds toward Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Its next celestial fit is likely in mid-2000, possibly even next
summer, and could disrupt the huge electricity grids that link
power systems across the continent, and cause problems with cell
phones and other technologies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're more vulnerable than we used to be because of the
increasing interconnection of society,'' said Don J. Michels, a
solar physicist at the Naval Research Laboratory in Washington,
D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The solar phenomenon has already started.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last two years, you can easily see an increase in solar
activity,'' said Steve Hill, a researcher at NASA's Goddard Space
Flight Center in Greenbelt, Md.
</P>
<P>
   The National Aeronautics and Space Administration and the
Defense Department are scrambling to launch satellites that can
give advance warning of incoming solar storms. The military is
especially concerned because of the possible failure of
reconnaissance satellites during a military engagement.
</P>
<P>
   Other scientists hope to improve their understanding of the
sun's structure and behavior by launching satellites such as HESSI,
the High Energy Solar Spectroscopic Imager, now being designed at
the University of California at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   Planned for launch in mid-2000, HESSI will study X-rays and
gamma rays from solar flares and ``coronal mass ejections,'' vast
clouds of electrically charged particles, said Jay Trimble, the
HESSI integration test manager.
</P>
<P>
   On reaching Earth, the particles warp Earth's magnetic field.
The field gyrations induce electrical currents in power lines that
can short-circuit them. The longer the line, the greater the
electrical surge, making long-distance power lines particularly
vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   Agencies such as NASA, the National Science Foundation, the
Boulder, Colo.-based Space Science Institute and others are trying
to spread the word about the coming threat.
</P>
<P>
   A harbinger of what may come during the disruptions occurred in
May, when a powerful solar storm tripled and quadrupled electrical
currents in the ionosphere, the thick envelope of ionized air
overhead, said researcher Daniel Baker of the University of
Colorado. The greater the electrical current, the greater the risk
to sensitive electronic gear, communications systems, power lines
and other societal infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   The solar breakdown might come sooner than expected, said
Richard C. Altrock, a U.S. Air Force scientist. He expects the
solar storms to peak in mid-1999, a year earlier than other
forecasts, based on his observations of a solar phenomenon
whimsically known as the ``Rush to the Poles.''
</P>
<P>
   At a solar observatory in Arizona, Altrock has observed solar
gases rich in ionized iron steadily flowing toward the sun's north
and south poles. Such flows have preceded the last two solar storms
by an average of 15 to 17 months, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The current rush began in February 1997, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Already we're starting to (detect) quite large flares and mass
ejections that are impacting our Earth.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
