<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 14:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8670 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEEWAX-Y2KCOLUMN-COX     12-28 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEEWAX-Y2KCOLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    As 2000 nears, predictions of doom and delight collide
 &HT;    (Eds: This is the first of weekly columns by Atlanta
Constitution editorial writer Marilyn Geewax on issues raised by
the coming of 2000.)
 &HT;    By Marilyn Geewax
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thursday night, when you start the 10-9-8-etc. ritual and pop
the champagne, yell and kiss everyone, it may be the last fun New
Year's Eve party you'll have for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   At least that is the advice of some experts working on the
computer problem commonly called the Y2K bug. Despite all the
turmoil we're in because of the presidential impeachment process,
1998 soon will be remembered as the good old days. As 1999 unfolds,
awareness of Y2K will grow, and panic will spread as people prepare
for the worst, they predict.
</P>
<P>
   ``By this time next year, there will be rationing at the grocery
store,'' predicts Harrison Fox, staff member of the U.S. House
subcommittee on technology. Speaking in mid-December at a World
Future Society conference on Y2K held in Washington, Fox said it's
``very likely'' next year's 2000 celebrations will be marred by
blackouts and fuel shortages caused by the inability of many
computers to recognize the date 1-1-00.
</P>
<P>
   A few Y2K extremists are even predicting disruptions so severe
that society as we know it will break down.
</P>
<P>
   But wait. Isn't next year's changeover supposed to be the
biggest party ever?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, according to travel agents, party planners and many
economists who insist Y2K worries are overblown. Sure, there may be
a flickering light here or there, but in general, the computer
problem is being fixed and by Dec. 31, 1999, the world will be
bracing only for the biggest party in history.
</P>
<P>
   The optimists note, for example, that although some banks'
automated teller machines might not work after midnight on 1-1-00,
the party will go on. Consumers will be forewarned about ATMs so
they can take out cash in advance. Indeed, the Federal Reserve
System already is preparing for this and has announced that the
financial system will make plenty of cash available leading up to
Dec. 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   So far, most Americans are siding with the optimists. Walt
Disney World's 27 hotels have long been reporting ``no general
availability'' for Dec. 31, 1999. Many cruises are booked solid.
</P>
<P>
   And for many people, the more expensive the party, the better.
Though dinner and a bottle of champagne may do for New Year's Eve
1998, travel agents say affluent Americans are seeking a
``once-in-a-lifetime'' experience for 1999, hoping to be gazing up
at Egypt's Great Pyramid of Cheops or standing on China's Great
Wall when the calendar flips to 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many trend watchers are predicting that productivity
will decline next year between Christmas and New Year's, but not
because of Y2K problems. The atmosphere will be so exuberant, they
predict, most Americans will be unable to concentrate on their
jobs; instead, they'll be staging a weeklong party.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike controversies that never end, the debate over whether
it's best to celebrate New Year's Eve 1999 in a bunker or on a
cruise ship will be settled. By Jan. 1, 2000, we'll know whether
the doomsdayers or the partiers had the right idea.
</P>
<P>
   But many Y2K experts insist theirs is the safer bet. They point
out that older computer programs, as well as the silicon chips
embedded in machinery, were not designed to recognize dates beyond
1999. The pessimists predict that when those date-sensitive
programs and embedded processors hit 1-1-00, computers and chips
will become confused and fail. Such failures will throw off
electric generators, gas pipeline valves, building security systems
and much more, causing a widespread breakdown of equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not wise to plan for big celebrations,'' said Paula
Gordon, a visiting professor at George Washington University and a
Y2K expert. She fears that tipsy partiers will get caught up in a
chaotic night of blackouts and transportation failures after
midnight on Jan. 1, 2000. ``We should postpone celebrations until
2001,'' she said, because that would give computer programmers time
to fix any systems that might fail in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The worst idea for Dec. 31, 1999, would be to travel by air, she
said. ``Next year will be a good time to have a party with friends
who live within walking distance. If nothing goes wrong at
midnight, then all well and good. But it just would not be wise''
to count on any computer-dependent means of transportation.
</P>
<P>
   One interesting suggestion for this year's party: Get a video
camera or audio tape recorder and ask friends to make predictions
for Dec. 31, 1999. Will it be the party of a lifetime? Or the end
of partying as we have known it?
</P>
<P>
   Then start counting down the days ...
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax is an editorial writer for The Atlanta
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
