<HEADER>
A8685 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOG-HNS &LR;      12-28 0388
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOG-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOG CAUSES FLIGHT DELAYS IN BAY AREA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM HERRON ZAMORA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Dense fog envoloped the San Francisco Bay area
Sunday and early Monday, stranding thousands of airline passengers
trying to go home after the Christmas holiday.
</P>
<P>
   All flights were canceled in and out of San Jose and Oakland
Sunday night. Flights that were already in the air when the
airports were shut were diverted to Sacramento and, in some cases,
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco International Airport, where as many as 300
stranded passengers spent Sunday night, faced more delays on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The fog was attributed to a high pressure ridge over the Bay
area that acted as a lid on the cold, damp ground level air, said
Jim Carroll of the National Weather Service.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco International was a sea of confusion Sunday night,
when fog caused delays of up to three hours.
</P>
<P>
   Although the crowds had thinned by early Monday, thousands of
stranded travelers were still waiting outside the terminal for
rides to hotels or to friends' homes. Many people had been waiting
for hours as they waited for flights to resume.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family took me all the way here from Sonoma County, then
they got stuck in (San Francisco 49ers) football game traffic on
the way back,'' said Liddy Chan, who was trying to get to Los
Angeles. ``Now, I'm asking them to come here again and endure more
hell.''
</P>
<P>
   Wally Hartmann of Seattle said he understood it wasn't safe to
fly in heavy fog. ``But the thing that really makes me mad is the
lack of timely information,'' he said. ``If you want to cancel my
flight, cancel it. But they should have a backup plan and tell
everyone ... Right now I feel really lost and clueless. Quote me:
This stinks.''
</P>
<P>
   San Jose International was shut at 7 p.m. Sunday because runway
visibility was down to 1,200 feet. Pilots need at least 1,600 feet
visibility for takeoff, said airport spokesman Egan Schulz.
</P>
<P>
   The same was true at Oakland where heavy fog shut the airport at
7 p.m., stranding several Southwest Airlines passengers, flight
coordinator John Schwammel said. A short while later, some flights
were cleared for takeoff.
</P>
<P>
   The fog also delayed flights at the San Jose airport Monday
morning.
</P>
</TEXT>
