<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 15:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8756 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STITH-QNA-BOS &LR;      12-28 1267
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STITH-QNA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REV. CHARLES STITH: ON THE SPOT IN TANZANIA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Rev. Charles Stith, well known in Boston, must have figured
he was headed for several years of obscurity when he accepted
President Clinton's offer to become ambassador to the African
nation of Tanzania. All that changed on Aug. 7 when terrorists
bombed the US embassy in Dar es Salaam, Tanzania's capital, killing
10 people. The high profile attack put the country and the US role
there in the spotlight in a way in which Stith never could have
imagined.
</P>
<P>
   In his first 100 days as ambassador, Stith has worked to restore
the morale of the embassy staff. He has also focused attention on
his primary mission: boosting trade and investment in the
impoverished nation. It is a task with which he is familiar. As a
minister of the Union United Methodist Church in the South End and
later as head of the Organization For a New Equality, Stith's has
dedicated his career to improving the economy of America's
low-income neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Globe reporter Charles Stein spoke with Stith by telephone last
week about his first few months on the job.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why did you accept this post in the first place?
</P>
<P>
   A: The short answer is the president asked me. It is difficult
to say no when the President asks you to serve your country in some
capacity. Beyond that, I saw a real synergy between what he wanted
and what I had been doing. The President wanted to focus foreign
policy in Africa on investment and trade rather than just foreign
aid. It seemed to me the skills I developed in trying to help
undercapitalized communities in the US could also be used to help
undercapitalized countries.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are there genuine parallels between the two?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are. In both cases it is critical to have access to
capital, it is critical to create confidence in the environment as
a place to invest and it is critical that those involved have a
mindset that approaches development, not as charity, but as an
economic opportunity. You need that mindset if you want to grow in
today's global marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: Tanzania is pretty far afield. Is it realistic to think you
are going to put it on the map of US investors?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think we have to help put Tanzania on investors' map of
potential opportunities. While the characters who bombed the
embassy meant it for evil, one of the upsides of that horrendous
situation was that there were a lot of people who, because of the
daily news coverage, were in a position to look at Tanzania. They
saw that this is a stable country with a viable democracy. The
bombing was an aberration, not the rule.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: Were you surprised by the extent of the damage from the
bombing?
</P>
<P>
   A: When I touched down in Dar es Salaam I went immediately to
the site of the embassy. Seeing the devastation I wondered how the
staff had continued to manage and whether they could continue to
manage. Every way I turned the damage was enormous. There was a car
damaged beyond recognition. The house across the street had one
whole side gone. It reminded me of a doll house we had bought for
our daughter Mimi on one of her first Christmases. You could see
every room and all the rubble from where I stood. It was clear that
the despicable human beings who did this meant to maximize the
death zone. Inside the embassy the damage was unbelievable. We
walked into one room full of fallen debris and I was told, ``Sir,
this is your office or what is left of it. Thank God you weren't
here. There is no way you would have survived.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: Have you had to spend a lot of time keeping morale up in the
wake of the bombing?
</P>
<P>
   A: A big part of my responsibility is making sure the morale of
the staff is high. Having said that, one of the things I take a
great deal of pride in is the level of professionalism and
resilience of the staff here. There were outright acts of heroism
in the aftermath of the bombing. But the staff has made it clear
that they don't want this simply to be known as the embassy which
was assaulted by terrorists. They want an embassy that is actively
engaged in furthering the foreign policy objectives of the United
States. We've got real troopers. They do us all proud as Americans.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: Have all the extra security measures you've had to take made
it difficult for you to do your job?
</P>
<P>
   A: Quite frankly, the day the bomb went off in Dar es Salaam,
the job description changed. It was a clear indication the rules of
the game have changed. The security measures we've taken to make us
less vulnerable are not things that can be looked upon as
inconveniences. They are necessities. They are part and parcel of
what you have to deal with representing American interests abroad.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: I understand you have seen quite a bit of the country since
you arrived. What are your impressions of Tanzania?
</P>
<P>
   A: This is an absolutely beautiful country. It is also huge, the
size of Texas and New Mexico. We took a trip recently from Dar es
Salaam to Arusha, which means we traveled about half the length of
the country. I sat down and calculated that it was the equivalent
of traveling from Boston to Washington DC.
</P>
<P>
   And there is so much diversity. There are pristine beaches on
Zanzibar. In the Tarangire National Park if you wake up before
sunrise you can literally hear the world awaken. You step out of
your tent and as the sun begins to rise you hear birds chirp and
animals rustle in the grass and you see bull elephants jostle.
</P>
<P>
   It is impossible to see this stuff and not be filled with a
childlike sense of awe. In Mwanza we saw boulders placed so
precisely in formation that it seemed as if the work was done by
angels under the direct supervision of God. It is just
breathtakingly beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: In Arusha, you and your children sat in on a trial of a man
charged with genocide in Rwanda. What was that like?
</P>
<P>
   A: We were there for a sentencing hearing for a man named
Jean-Paul Akeyesu. He was the mayor of a one-horse town in Rwanda
no one would have ever heard of had he not personally supervised
the murder of 2000 people.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing was quite dramatic. The man had fired his lawyer and
was representing himself. As he stood up to talk my son leaned over
and whispered, ``Dad, this guy looks so normal.'' I was struck by
the poignancy of what he said. The man was well-dressed. He could
have been a deacon in a church on Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   I think it was important for my kids to appreciate that it is
the demons that lurk in the hearts of normal people that cause them
to do some of the very worst things to others. That is why we have
to be eternally vigilant on issues like justice and mercy and make
sure we are all responsible for making the world a more humane and
better place.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: The news from Africa is generally so depressing: war,
disease, poverty. Do you ever feel you are in a hopeless situation?
</P>
<P>
   A: The answer is no. In part that has to do with my disposition.
But there are other reasons to be hopeful. For 30 years Tanzania
has been one of the most stable countries in Africa. The level of
civility is envied by countries throughout the region. It is a
country that is rich in natural resources. The government is
commited to private sector reform. The president, Benjamim Mkapa,
has some decent honest people around him trying to move that agenda
forward. I believe Tanzania is positioned to be the next economic
success story in Africa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-28-98 1523EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981228.0216 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8757 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONSUMER-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-28 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOMETIMES, THE RIGHT ATTITUDE CAN PAY DIVIDENDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL AND PATRICIA WEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sandy Rodgers of Amherst, N.H., sent us a letter the other day
about Circuit City.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the sort of letter we usually receive here. She didn't
complain about anything. She didn't say she had been ripped off. In
fact, it was just the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   Rodgers was one of a dozen readers who responded to our request
a month ago for tales of exceptionally good consumer experiences.
We thought there would be a lot more positive letters, given that
we get 20 to 30 complaint letters and calls each week. Despite the
low response rate, we still think it's worthwhile talking about the
good as well as the bad out there.
</P>
<P>
   In the sampling of stories that follow, a couple of themes
emerge. The companies in most cases went out of their way to make
sure their customer was satisfied. In some instances, it was
company policy, but in several of the cases another factor was at
work. Store officials said they helped a consumer not because of
any company rule but simply because the customer was so nice.
</P>
<P>
   Rodgers fits the nice category. She went to the Circuit City in
Manchester, N.H., on Nov. 24 to buy a TV for her husband for his
70th birthday. She ended up buying a floor model for $650 that
store officials loaded, unboxed, in the back of her Ford Explorer.
She remembers expressing some concern about the safety of the TV
back there, but says the loader told her it would be fine.
</P>
<P>
   About two blocks away from the store she heard a thud in the
back. She pulled into a Friendly's parking lot, opened the tail
gate and was barely able to get out of the way before the set
tumbled out and crashed to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   A woman at Friendly's helped her load the ruined TV back in her
car. With tears in her eyes, she drove back to Circuit City and
explained what happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without any hassle at all,'' Rodgers said, store manager Sean
McCarthy gave her another TV off the shelf and had it loaded in her
back seat. This time the TV was strapped in with a seat belt and
pinned in with the front seat. ``Friends who know this story are
amazed that a firm as large as this has any compassion. I am very
grateful,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy, who has been with Circuit City six years, stressed
that it is impossible to satisfy every single customer, ``But she
was so nice and I didn't want to disappoint her husband on his
birthday.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
A little less paranoid &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Kamens, 29, describes himself as a ``paranoid''
shopper. He seems to collect stories about bad consumer
experiences, such as the time a tire-maintenance program was not
honored or the day his contractor installed the wrong windows.
</P>
<P>
   So last July 5th was a memorable day for him. He and his
pregnant wife had just bought a futon and frame from Sleep-Rite in
Framingham, Mass. He agreed to buy the floor model of the frame,
because the sales staff said it was the only one available. He also
got a 15 percent discount on the $350 frame, or $52 off.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when the items were delivered at his Boston home, a new
un-assembled frame showed up instead of the already assembled floor
model. The delivery workers said the store had found a new frame in
stock. Kamens braced himself to hear about needing to pay full
price, and perhaps a $15 assembly fee.
</P>
<P>
   But instead the delivery men assembled the bed at no extra
charge. ``I was pleasantly surprised,'' said Kamens, a computer
programmer and father of a 4-month-old.
</P>
<P>
   Amy Farber, the manager at Sleep-Rite, said she remembers her
experience with Kamens very clearly. She said she simply felt the
store should honor the original price given. She said it was also
easier to ``go the extra mile'' for someone like Kamens who was so
kind to everyone at the store. ``It helps when the customer is so
nice,'' she said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
A real guarantee &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fred Liberatore, a father of four, had always heard about the
lifetime guarantee on Cross pens. So when his son found a busted
Cross pen in a library parking lot a couple of months ago,
Liberatore decided to send it to the A.T. Cross company in Lincoln,
R.I., and test the guarantee.
</P>
<P>
   To his amazement, three weeks later, he received a brand-new
grey Cross pen with gold trim, an exact copy of the broken pen he
had sent in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed unreal,'' said Liberatore, a 54-year-old biochemist.
``Here was a company standing behind its product.''
</P>
<P>
   Russell Boss, president of the company, said the 152-year-old
company always honors the lifetime guarantee and generally receives
only 1 percent of its merchandise back for replacement or repair.
He said the guarantee on its pens _ which range from an $18
ball-point pen to a $450 fountain pen _ ``has won us a lot of
friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Boss recalled a time when a Pennsylvania farmer sent them a pen
covered with dark soil in a plastic bag. It turns out he farmer
droped his pen in the fields one day and couldn't find it. Some
months later, he found the pen in the cow manure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cow ate it and got rid of it,'' Boss said.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the pen worked or not, Boss is not sure. He can't say
anyone even tested the digested pen. He said the company gladly
sent the farmer back a new one.
</P>
<P>
   Liberatore said he is amazed that such old-fashioned customer
service exists. After receiving the new pen, he said, he's sure to
give the Cross company a lifetime of loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``You patronize companies that treat customers right,'' he
said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Have it your way &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kathy de Natale pleaded with Roche Bros. to bring back a muffin
recipe she liked. Roche Bros. refused, but did the next best thing.
The supermarket agreed to make her a dozen of the muffins she liked
whenever she wanted.
</P>
<P>
   G. Robert Warren says he had a similar experience with Shaw's
Supermarkets, but with doughnuts instead of muffins.
</P>
<P>
   Warren is a private investigator and self-described doughnut
connoisseur, although he says his wife thinks he's
doughnut-obsessed. Shaw's introduced new items to its bakery
section a year ago and in the process eliminated some items to make
room. One of those eliminated items was the powdered sugar
doughnut, Warren's favorite.
</P>
<P>
   He protested to Shaw's and they restored it to the bakery case,
but they did more than that. Warren liked his powdered sugar
doughnuts greasy and sugared heavily right out of the oven. ``The
greasier the better,'' he said. Shaw's made it that way only about
20 percent of the time, he said. When he inquired, the bakery
department at the Shaw's in Hanover, mass. agreed to make the
doughnuts his way whenever he wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw's spokesman Bernard Rogan said such special requests are
often granted. ``It's called developing customer loyalty,'' he
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (We want your consumer ideas and tips. Please e-mail Mohl at
mohl(at)globe.com or Wen at wen(at)globe.com. Their address is Box
2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-28-98 1524EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981228.0217 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 15:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8760 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PLUNDERED-ARTIFACTS-2     12-28 2269
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLUNDERED-ARTIFACTS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 (a and i coding)  
 BOSTON: ... longtime overseer.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the center of the storm over the museum's ethics is Cornelius
C. Vermeule III, the MFA's longtime curator of classical
antiquities who retired in 1996. A scholar world-renowned for his
connoisseurship, and a beloved figure at the MFA and in the local
art world, Vermeule developed a swashbuckling reputation for his
acquisition habits.
</P>
<P>
   Even in retirement, Vermeule's decisions still preoccupy
lawyers. It was Vermeule who arranged the MFA's questionable
acquisition of the top half of a Heraclean figure the Turkish
government wants reunited with the bottom half that sits in a
Turkish museum. In another case involving the alleged theft of
precious Athenian coins from Turkey, it was Vermeule who had the
MFA authenticate them for the owners, despite evidence they might
be ``hot.''
</P>
<P>
   And like many curators of his generation, who scoured the world
for prized pieces long before the plundering of ancient grave sites
was officially proscribed, Vermeule continued to buy artifacts as
if the rules had never changed, according to McClellan, the BU
archeologist. By many accounts, Vermeule had virtual autonomy
within the MFA.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, with the help of a $30,000 grant from the National
Endowment for the Arts, Vermeule's department published a book
signaling that it was still playing by old rules. The 1993 book,
``Vase Painting in Italy,'' matter-of-factly suggests that three of
the Apulian vases it prizes most highly were newly discovered.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the vases, attributed to the Darius Painter, a name given
by scholars to one of the finest artisans in the Greek civilization
that flourished in Apulia about 2,300 years ago, have been hailed
in one MFA annual report as ``two of the greatest South Italian
vases in America.''
</P>
<P>
   In the museum's book, the MFA's curators wrote: ``Recent years
have seen a host of new vases by the Darius Painter with rare or
unique mythological subjects . . .'' The MFA vases, acquired in
1987, 1989, and 1991, ``are among the most splendid of the new
mythological works,'' according to the book.
</P>
<P>
   The vase acquired in 1991 is jointly owned by the MFA and by
Leon Levy and Shelby White, New York collectors whose collecting
habits have long been controversial.
</P>
<P>
   To archeologists, the language in the book is an unwitting
admission that the MFA knew the prized vases were probably stolen
from grave sites. In his written response to the Globe's questions,
Rogers acknowledged that none of the three vases had any known
owners before the museum acquired them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Museums like the MFA should know better,'' said David W. J.
Gill, an archeologist at the University of Wales at Swansea and an
international authority on antiquities looting. Plainly, Gill said,
the reference in the book ``means the objects were newly surfaced,
and since they had no declared history, any museum curator should
have been highly suspicious of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Gill and a colleague, Christopher Chippindale, have done
pioneering research on undocumented antiquities. For example, after
the New York Metropolitan Museum of Art exhibited Levy and White's
classical collection in 1990, a study by the two men disclosed that
of the 230 objects in the show, 217 had no known history before the
collecting couple acquired them.
</P>
<P>
   Vermeule and White did not respond to requests for interviews.
The MFA said it would not permit Vermeule's successor, John
Herrmann, to be interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   White, in a recent article in the International Journal of
Cultural Property, wrote that she and her husband do not buy
artifacts that are stolen from museums or unearthed from ``known''
archeological excavations.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the wheat-growing region in Apulia, virtually all of the loot
comes from thousands of ``unknown'' grave sites, sealed tombs of
the Greeks' ancient dead that often contain painted vases of the
type favored by Levy and White and the MFA.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult for the Italian government to prove the vases
were stolen since there is no documentation to prove they were in
the ground,'' lamented Marina Mazzei, the Italian archeologist in
charge of government efforts to slow the looting in Apulia. ``So
just like so many vases, they magically appear on the market, as if
they came from nowhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Mazzei, during a visit last spring to the pockmarked wheatfields
with a Globe reporter, said the tombaroli, or tomb robbers, have
taken tens of thousands of vases over the last 15 years, so
brazenly that they often employ mechanical excavators. The dramatic
rise in looting in the early 1980s, Mazzei said, coincided with the
growing popularity of the vases with American and European
collectors and museums.
</P>
<P>
   But with few resources, and vast territory to police, she said,
Italian authorities are almost powerless to stop the looters.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, she said, with unemployment so high in southern Italy,
``there is a high level of crime directed at the living. So to many
laymen, stealing from tombs is not considered criminal, because the
tombaroli disturb the dead, and not the living.''
</P>
<P>
   Organized rings of thieves smuggle much of the plunder into
Switzerland, with its lax statutes and reputation as an
international fencing crossroads. There, the plunder is sold to
collectors and dealers.
</P>
<P>
   Just across the Italian-Swiss border, in scenic vacation towns
like Lugano and Ascona, antiquities shops are ubiquitous, and some
dealers openly admit that their wares have been recently excavated.
In one shop last spring, a score of Apulian vases, some of museum
quality and bearing prices as high as $40,000, were displayed in
glass cases.
</P>
<P>
   Lying on the floor in a corner was a piece of Roman armor
identified by the shop owner as from the 1st century A.D. It was
still caked in mud.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's from a 100-year-old Italian collection,'' the dealer said
with a smile and a wink.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The inexorable link between generous Italian supply and
insatiable collector demand has long raised questions about what
the principals know, or choose to know, about the origin of the
objects they acquire.
</P>
<P>
   Eisenberg, a major figure in the antiquities trade, said he
would not ``knowingly buy a piece that's been smuggled.'' In fact,
he argued in an interview that the vast majority of antiquities are
of no use to archeologists and ought to be traded freely like
modern artworks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ninety-eight percent of items that are excavated offer no new
or useful information for archeologists. So collectors and museums
should be able to acquire these objects,'' said Eisenberg, whose
views anger many archeologists. Strict laws against export, he
added, force the art market to hide information and, sometimes,
prompt museums to doctor provenance information.
</P>
<P>
   As for ``minor pieces'' that most collectors buy, Eisenberg
said, ``We know they come out illegally. But no one bothers about
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the major pieces he has sold, to the MFA and other clients,
he acknowledged: ``There is a likelihood that some material may
have been smuggled. No one knows ultimately where these things come
from.''
</P>
<P>
   The MFA, though it made some of its acquisition records
available to the Globe, refused to disclose the identities of
dealers who have sold classical antiquities to the museum.
</P>
<P>
   But dealers seeking tax deductions often donate artifacts to
curators they sell objects to. The MFA's list of donor-dealers
amounts to a ``who's who'' of dealers, and some collectors, who
have been involved in controversy over the origin of some of their
acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   They include London dealer Robin Symes, Demirjian, White and
Levy, and the late Lawrence Fleischman, a major purchaser of
undocumented antiquities whose collection was acquired in 1995 by
the J. Paul Getty Museum.
</P>
<P>
   Two major collectors who face claims by foreign governments
seeking the recovery of artifacts are also among MFA donors:
Maurice Tempelsman, the New York financier and companion to the
late Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis; and Jonathan H. Kagan, one of the
defendants in Turkey's lawsuit demanding the return of the Athenian
coins.
</P>
<P>
   Kagan has donated numerous undocumented antiquities to the MFA,
including nine ceramic cups from the 7th century B.C. that
McClellan says were probably unearthed from the same tomb complex,
in Latium, the site of an ancient culture near Rome that predated
the Greek colonization of Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Through his lawyer, D. Lloyd Macdonald, Kagan declined a request
for an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Also among the dealers who have sold classical artifacts to the
museum is Robert E. Hecht Jr., a Paris-based antiquities specialist
who was once declared persona non grata by the Italian and Turkish
governments for his alleged role in selling plundered antiquities.
</P>
<P>
   Hecht, the Globe reported in April, played a central role in a
$1.8 million sale to New York's Metropolitan Museum of Art of a 3d
century B.C. silver trove. Italian authorities have an affidavit
from the professional grave robber who helped unearth the objects
from Morgantina, a Greek city-state in Sicily.
</P>
<P>
   During an April telephone interview, Hecht defended the trade in
looted antiquities and ridiculed laws, like Italy's, that seek to
prevent the plundering of grave sites.
</P>
<P>
   The MFA refused to divulge its relationship with Hecht, or even
acknowledge that they had done business with him. But the voluble
Hecht boasted in the interview that in mid-1997 he sold the MFA a
rare silver cup, called a skyphos, at a price reported to exceed
$400,000.
</P>
<P>
   Asked where the silver artifact originated, Hecht replied:
``What does it matter?''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most of the MFA's classical acquisitions examined by the
Globe, the skyphos has a listed provenance. The MFA said Hecht told
them the piece was once in an American collection and provided the
museum with a letter from a third party attesting to the fact that
Hecht has had the skyphos since the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   The museum refused to make the letter public.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If there is no public evidence the MFA has changed its habits,
other institutions have.
</P>
<P>
   Shestack, who is now the deputy director of the National Gallery
of Art in Washington, said that because of the increased
international and public focus on grave robbing, ``Museums are much
more aware of the consequences of this kind of collecting. They are
much more fastidious.''
</P>
<P>
   But during the seven years he ran the MFA, Shestack conceded,
the museum relied on its dealers for written assurance that the
artifacts the MFA bought were clean.
</P>
<P>
   ``The legal counsel, then, was not as sensitive to these issues.
The dealers often didn't want to tell us anything about the prior
ownership,'' Shestack said. ``The lawyers almost always said that
if a dealer signed a guarantee the work was clean, then everything
was OK.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one ever said, `We're not going to buy it if it doesn't
have a clear provenance,' '' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Shestack said, the museum did demand a thorough
legal review of the pre-Columbian collection offered to the MFA by
Landon T. Clay, one of its trustees. The review, at an estimated
cost of $30,000, concluded that there was no reason for the MFA not
to take it. Last December, the lawyer who did the review admitted
in an interview that he knew in 1987 that Guatemalan law forbade
export of the artifacts.
</P>
<P>
   In his 1986 speech calling for higher ethical standards,
Shestack recalled, ``I cried out for stringent laws that would give
museum directors a reason for not doing the evil thing. So then
when the directors encourage you to acquire certain things, you can
say, `No, I can't. I'll go to jail.' ''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``But if there's a gray area in the law, you don't
have an out.'' The gray area, he noted, remains.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, Shestack's candid recollection contradicts Rogers, who in
both the Guatemala and classical areas has insisted there has been
nothing amiss in the museum's behavior. Partly, there are legal
reasons for that: The Guatemalan government has just hired New York
attorneys Lawrence M. Kaye and Howard Spiegler, two aggressive
litigators who handle Turkey's claims, to seek restitution of the
pre-Columbian artifacts.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the legal threat, some lawyers and art historians say
Rogers has a responsibility to assure its public that the museum's
behavior sets a moral standard for the community it serves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The MFA needs to make an unambiguous statement that it will no
longer acquire undocumented antiquities,'' said McClellan, the BU
archeologist. ``This is one more opportunity for the MFA to say,
`Our eyes have been opened. We take responsibility for what's
happened. We've done wrong in the past, but we'll now do better.'
But they seem unwilling to say that publicly.''
</P>
<P>
   Other museums, most notably the once avaricious Getty, no longer
acquire undocumented antiquities. And the Getty has done so
unambiguously.
</P>
<P>
   Marion True, the Getty's curator of ancient art, who now devotes
much of her time to helping countries in the Mediterranean rim
devise strategies to stop looting, told a conference at Rutgers
University last month that the Getty ceased buying undocumented
antiquities because it was not possible to be certain they were
clean.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is because of the all-too-common practices among
so-called reputable dealers of forging provenance documents and
signing false statements on warranties,'' she said. The Getty, True
added, chooses to spend money on other projects, ``rather than
continue to struggle through the mire of deception that pervades
the market.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
