<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 15:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8777 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINDBOGGLING-REI-SEAT     12-28 1249
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINDBOGGLING-REI-SEATTLE-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUGGED CHIC: U.S. CONSUMERS JUST KEEP ON TREKKIN'  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (From Economist's Christmas issue, covering Dec. 19 and 26)   (This excellent 1,025-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 19 Dec. 1998) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from New York Times
Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax her at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1998 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, when Japan's economy first slowed, there was
a popular explanation for its refusal to speed up again. Japanese
consumers, this theory went, had bought so many gadgets during the
go-go years that they now declined to spend a single yen on new
ones.
</P>
<P>
   Late-1990s America presents a gleaming contrast. Despite the
long boom, Americans are pursuing material happiness during this
holiday season with unwavering zeal.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, the notion that they may run out of things to
buy seems laughable _ especially when you visit the mother of 1990s
consumer temples, just off a freeway in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The temple in question is the flagship store of REI, a
camping/sporting/outdoor retailer. You can buy kayaks and snowshoes
and anti-sting kits, indeed everything you might require to master
nature's various elements.
</P>
<P>
   You can buy clips and ropes and ingenious spring-loaded clamps,
all essential for turning sheer rocks into climbing frames for
adults. Upstairs, you may test a hundred types of shoe on a
convenient indoor hiking path. You may choose a waterproof jacket,
and check to see if it really keeps the moisture out by stepping
into a rain room.
</P>
<P>
   The choosing is no simple matter. The clothing at REI features a
bewildering variety of fabrics, lightweight or heavy-duty,
odor-eating or moisture-wicking, Gore-Tex, Spandex and Cordura.
</P>
<P>
   Over in the camping section, even the humble water filter
assumes an intimidating mien. Should you choose the ceramic
micro-strainer or the carbon-core membrane, the iodine resin or the
pleated glass fiber?
</P>
<P>
   To grapple with these issues, you must read a pamphlet, prepared
by REI's thoughtful staff. This describes which microorganisms are
caught by which filtration technology; no single device can be
relied upon to trap all of them.
</P>
<P>
   The prudent course, it seems, is to buy 11 filters and drain
water through each one. But what if a key filter cracks? ``Always
carry spare elements, parts and backup water treatment method,''
intones the pamphlet.
</P>
<P>
   Across America, there are now 51 REI stores, up from 26 in 1990;
and each year 1.5 million visitors flock to the mother temple in
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Some no doubt come to gawp: at the world's highest artificial
climbing spire, laid on for shoppers to test climbing shoes; or at
the cafeteria's bewildering variety of ethnic foods (which come
with another set of instructions, naturally).
</P>
<P>
   But other visitors go to REI with more serious intent. They know
that ambling through the countryside on a weekend afternoon carries
an intolerable opportunity cost: the time could be so much better
spent on greater things, such as whitewater canoeing or off-road
biking.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you choose deliberately not to live life to the full, you
will want to try these sports. Therefore, you realize, you will
need REI's equipment.
</P>
<P>
   And so, for opportunity maximizers at least, shopping at REI
becomes an existential duty.
</P>
<P>
   You must read the medical notes printed on REI's walls,
explaining the risks of exercising without a hydration pack
strapped on to your back, so that you can sip water regularly.
</P>
<P>
   You must master REI's high-tech gadgets, using one computer to
track your whereabouts and another to keep tabs on the weather.
</P>
<P>
   You must feed yourself with intensively nutritious vacuum-packed
objects. After all, with 11 water filters in your bag, there won't
be room for sandwiches.
</P>
<P>
   Some people fret over this ingenious fuelling of materialism.
They see it as evidence of America's darker sides. Americans fret
that, for all their prosperity, life is increasingly stressful; if
buying a water filter has come to involve a chemistry lesson,
perhaps this is not surprising.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Americans worry about a growing class divide; and the
REI attitude to life is spreading mainly among a select group of
richly-compensated high achievers. One in two Americans, after all,
is nowadays classified as overweight; and one in four admits to
being wholly sedentary.
</P>
<P>
   You feel this class divide most sharply in the West, where the
REI way bumps up against a more traditional outdoorsiness.
</P>
<P>
   In the old mining towns of southern Utah, the locals load the
gun racks on their pickups, and rumble off into the wilderness to
hunt; but the taste for shooting at wildlife is being rapidly
displaced by the tourist taste for photographing it.
</P>
<P>
   The locals' pickups are rusting and gnarled; but the tourists
haul themselves up rocks with clips and clamps made out of
aerospace-grade metal.
</P>
<P>
   The locals see no virtue in unnecessary strain. But the tourists
bike up mountains undeterred by desert sun, trusting in health
insurance and helmets to save them from the consequences of their
bravado.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the rich have always sought out nature in ways that
others found bizarre. On a trip out West a century ago, Theodore
Roosevelt was bitten by a snake and pitched from a wagon on to his
head; he declared, in a rehearsal of today's mountain-bike
machismo, that this was ``very good fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, REI does represent a change. For one thing, Roosevelt
did not care what he wore. ``We are dressed about as badly as
mortals could be,'' he wrote of one youthful adventure: ``unshaven
faces, dirty gray shirts, still dirtier yellow trousers.''
</P>
<P>
   And, despite some interest in conservation, Roosevelt was an
environmental lout by modern standards. On a trip to Africa, he
killed nine lions, eight elephants and 13 rhinoceroses.
</P>
<P>
   The patricians of yesteryear resembled, in their approach to
nature at least, today's rougher members of the National Rifle
Association.
</P>
<P>
   The new masters of the information age are different. They want
to preserve the wilderness, but also to look smart in it; they have
taken the fastidious dressing and equipment fetishism of suburban
sports such as golf, and transported them to the great open spaces.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps this makes for new social divisions, and occasionally
for stress; but it is fun, and it fuels the economy.
</P>
<P>
   So long as the boom lasts, America's mild economic anxieties
will pale next to Japan's. As it happens, REI aims to open its
first overseas store in Tokyo, in 2000. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this excellent 1,025-word article, it must be purchased
from New York Times Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS in
New York at 1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax her at
212-499-3382.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
