</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEAM-TRAINS-REBIRTH-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEAM-ENGINE TRAINS: A BLAST FROM THE PAST  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (From Economist's Christmas issue, covering Dec. 19 and 26)   (This 650-word ``separate buy'' article is from the current (week
beginning 19 Dec. 1998) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from New York Times
Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax her at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 c.1998 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once revolutionary, the steam engine is now the epitome of
old-fashioned technology. But the motors of the industrial
revolution have not run out of steam just yet.
</P>
<P>
   This week, in Winterthur, Switzerland, the most advanced large
steam locomotive ever built is being tested at the Swiss Locomotive
and Machine Works (SLM) _ a division of a conglomerate called
Sulzer.
</P>
<P>
   Although it looks like a conventional steam locomotive, SLM's
engine incorporates a host of technological improvements that make
it cleaner and more efficient than the Puffing Billies of old. As a
result, it could give diesel engines a run for their money.
</P>
<P>
   The godfather of the modern steam-engine movement is Livio Dante
Porta, an Argentine engineer who realized, when steam engines
started to be replaced by diesels in the 1950s, that there was
still plenty of room for improvement in steam-engine design.
</P>
<P>
   He spent his career finding new ways to refine the performance
of steam engines. He and his followers, who include Roger Waller,
chief designer of the SLM locomotive, have travelled the world,
restoring and modernizing old engines, and trying to rekindle
support for steam power.
</P>
<P>
   The engine now being tested by SLM was originally built in
Germany in 1942. It has been upgraded according to Porta's
principles, which improve performance in a number of ways.
</P>
<P>
   For a start, unlike conventional coal-fired steam engines, the
new engine burns light oil. It also has an improved draft mechanism
to supply the air for combustion. With coal-fired engines as much
as half the coal is carried away by the air as it passes over the
fuel, so the new engine is far more fuel-efficient.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, there is no need for a stoker to shovel the coal,
and no danger of burning embers causing track-side fires.
</P>
<P>
   Another improvement is the use of modern materials to insulate
the boiler and the steam pipes. One result of this is that the
boiler stays warm overnight and the engine can be brought to its
operating temperature within 15 minutes in the morning, compared
with three hours for a conventional steam engine.
</P>
<P>
   Combined with other improvements, including weight reductions
made possible by the use of welded rather than cast-iron
components, and the replacement of oil-lubricated bearings by
modern roller bearings, the result is an engine 25 percent lighter,
36 percent more powerful, and consuming 41 percent less fuel than
old-fashioned coal-fired engines.
</P>
<P>
   But as well as outperforming conventional steam engines, the new
one compares favorably with diesels, both economically and
environmentally.
</P>
<P>
   According to SLM, modern steam locomotives cost around SFr2
million ($1.5 million) each to build from scratch _ about the same
as a diesel locomotive. Although they consume slightly more fuel,
they are simpler to maintain and repair, making them especially
suitable for use in poor countries. They last longer, too.
</P>
<P>
   And they are also less smelly. Because they rely on external
combustion (the burning of fuel at a constant rate outside the
engine's cylinders, rather than explosively inside them), they
produce only a fifth of the noxious emissions of diesels of
comparable power.
</P>
<P>
   That is especially desirable in such applications as shunting,
when locomotives spend 70 percent of their time idling, often in
built-up areas in which pollution is particularly unwelcome.
</P>
<P>
   The current tests involve measuring the power of a modernized
locomotive by pitting it against two electric engines in a
tug-of-war. Once testing is complete the engine, which belongs to a
German railway company, will be used on the Orient Express.
</P>
<P>
   But according to SLM, tourism is by no means the only market for
new steam locomotives. The company also has its eye on developing
countries with extensive railway networks, such as India and China.
Once the figures from this week's tests are in to prove its case,
SLM hopes it will be full steam ahead. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 650-word article, it must be purchased from New
York Times Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS in New York
at 1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax her at 212-499-3382.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
