<HEADLINE>
D'ESTE'S POETRY OFFERS A FEEL FOR THE ROMANCE OF THE LANGUAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDVINS BEITIKS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The poetry of Jessica d'Este is not well known
except in Britain, on the Continent and in selected places on the
East Coast. It should be.
</P>
<P>
   The author's latest book of poetry, ``Wine, Woman and Song,''
offers a feel for the romance of the English language, for the way
it can fold into everyday living. She has won prizes at poetry
slams and crisscrossed the Continent on reading tours, leaving
entire rooms in silence after working her words into music.
</P>
<P>
   A widow who lives in London, d'Este writes of her father,
biophysicist Leonidas Marinelli, of the death of her husband, of
the delight in childrens' eyes at a simple story, of a life that
has leapt out at her with every passing day.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a sampling, starting with a poem to her father, who
helped in the creation of the atomic bomb. ``My father was a
nuclear physicist involved in the Manhattan project. I grew up with
Bikini,'' said d'Este before one recent reading. ``A strange thing
... a group of intelligent scientists starting a chain reaction
without really knowing how it would end.''
</P>
<P>
   POEM FOR MY FATHER
</P>
<P>
   Often sheltering in Mother's room
</P>
<P>
   I face him, grown faint
</P>
<P>
   in a late photograph: a fathering saint
</P>
<P>
   Of science and its victim. Love
</P>
<P>
   Is better painted
</P>
<P>
   That summons a daughter
</P>
<P>
   To its wisdom
</P>
<P>
   As I was led.
</P>
<P>
   My earliest memory is reason;
</P>
<P>
   Calculations in my head, recited
</P>
<P>
   To boyhood satisfaction 'till thirteen
</P>
<P>
   When seized by female blood
</P>
<P>
   I bled,
</P>
<P>
   altered
</P>
<P>
   From the fun of games with neutral sums
</P>
<P>
   To need protection. I blame
</P>
<P>
   Heroes of the cranium
</P>
<P>
   Slow with solutions
</P>
<P>
   We throw ourselves to and come
</P>
<P>
   Powered like a lesson
</P>
<P>
   In the conversion of a number
</P>
<P>
   Taught by him then, _ a symbol
</P>
<P>
   Among the other
</P>
<P>
   Women.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NOV. 17, 1996 BELGRADE
</P>
<P>
   Silent
</P>
<P>
   Defiant
</P>
<P>
   Sick of Tyrants
</P>
<P>
   By nightfall
</P>
<P>
   Every night
</P>
<P>
   Its disquiet streets
</P>
<P>
   A riot
</P>
<P>
   Of flickering candlelight
</P>
<P>
   Tenous
</P>
<P>
   As each of us
</P>
<P>
   Holding tight
</P>
<P>
   To the life
</P>
<P>
   Of the soul.
</P>
<P>
   If only the whole world's cameras
</P>
<P>
   Could come
</P>
<P>
   Worth it to shoot
</P>
<P>
   A revolution
</P>
<P>
   Without guns.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine what best we'd become _
</P>
<P>
   Changed without rancor
</P>
<P>
   Say: Sri Lanka, Tibet, Rwanda
</P>
<P>
   Think of Baghdad
</P>
<P>
   And wonder.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HIS DREAM
</P>
<P>
   In his dream of love
</P>
<P>
   He dreams of
</P>
<P>
   Singing to her
</P>
<P>
   Above top C, beyond
</P>
<P>
   A sea of faces looking on
</P>
<P>
   Charmed as she is charmed
</P>
<P>
   By clarity
</P>
<P>
   And escalades of tone
</P>
<P>
   That carry the tune and tempo
</P>
<P>
   Of a Renoir afternoon
</P>
<P>
   Into tremulous song;
</P>
<P>
   Mid rise of talent
</P>
<P>
   For her alone:
</P>
<P>
   Sounds and power beyond him _ known
</P>
<P>
   Like a sweet trumpet at Resurrection draws
</P>
<P>
   Or claps of thunder
</P>
<P>
   Or applause.
</P>
<P>
   (``Wine, Woman and Song'' is available only by writing to
Impress, Hill Farm, Nether Westcote, Chipping Norton, Oxon, OX7
65D, England. Include your name, address and phone number, clearly
printed.)
</P>
</TEXT>
