<SLUG> BC-FITTV-SHOWS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S ON THE FIT TUBE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH MARDER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; In addition to ``Fit Resort &AMP; Spa,'' fit tv's
signature show, the network's other initial programming will
include:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Fitting It In'' (60 minutes): A gourmet cooking segment
followed by a predinner workout that can be done at home.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``American Health &AMP; Fitness'' (30 minutes): Offers information
on nutrition and exercise and how they fit into a healthy, balanced
lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Bodies in Motion'' (30 minutes): Former decathlon champion
Gilad Janklowicz teaches easy aerobic routines.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Fitness Adventure'' (30 minutes): A magazine format that
takes viewers across the United States to enjoy outdoor fitness
activities such as mountain climbing, camping, white-water rafting,
bicycling and hiking.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Forever Young With Bill Frank'' (30 minutes): Geared toward
baby boomers, celebrity trainer Bill Frank shares diet, exercise
and grooming tips.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Naturally Fit'' (30 minutes): Will get the viewer outside
with such topics as learning street smarts, becoming familiar with
herbal medicine and practicing emergency first aid.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Yoga Zone'' (30 minutes): Allan Finger of the Yoga Zone Gyms
will start with beginners' workouts and progress to intermediate
and advanced techniques, allowing viewers to improve their skills
from week to week.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Power Living by Jake'' (30 minutes): Jake Steinfeld, in
programs taped at Universal Studios before a live audience, will
offer talk and fitness demonstrations with celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   Designed to debut in February and March are:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Fit on Location'' (30 minutes): Visits with celebrity
guests, who talk about how they relieve stress and stay fit.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Fighting Fit'' (30 minutes): Fat-burning aerobic exercises
that incorporate movements of eight martial arts disciplines,
including tai chi, karate and kick boxing. &QL; 
endit &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-28-98 1629EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981228.0260 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 16:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8876 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-MERGER-2ndTake-     12-28 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-MERGER-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: Christmas Day. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   All this could mean a miserable holiday season for a lot of
people, who know all too well that they may be unemployed within
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's freaked out right now, in the bunker,'' said Kevin
Carter, an editor with the industry publication ``Gavin.'' ``Nobody
can predict how this'll all shake out. People are very nervous, and
being right before the holidays, the timing was terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody is predicting that there will be hard-and-fast sales
figures that determine which bands stay and which go, although
sales will, of course, be a key factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are looking for a return on their investment,'' said
Bannister, who said she ``wouldn't even guess'' at the number of
layoffs or bands facing the ax. ``You aren't going to invest in an
asset that you don't think will pay off down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   But potential and costs will also be a major factor, according
to Philip Walden, an executive with Capricorn Records based in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   A band that sells 750,000 copies but is guaranteed an upfront
multimillion-dollar payment, has lavish tour production needs and
depends on a lot of promotion and expensive videos, may be in more
trouble than a band that sells less but does so through tireless
touring, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may have an inexpensive band with low recording and
production costs,'' said Walden, ``so you can sell 100,000 CDs and
still make money. A band like that is self-sufficient. But any
band's fate at any label is based on the relationship with the
people who work there.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with trimming some bands is the feeling that the Universal
downsizing will mean more caution in signing new ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be harder for bands to get signed,'' said Jerry
Thompson, president of Caravan of Dreams and Promoterline Inc. in
Fort Worth. ``You'll see less and less of the three- to five-album
deals _ it'll be, `Prove it to us.' And I don't think the
developmental dollars for new acts will be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim DeLaughter, lead singer for Dallas' Tripping Daisy, agreed,
saying that the impact on the local music scene could be severe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think bands looking to get signed, well, I just don't see
that happening for a while,'' he said. ``Companies are trying to
regroup and get their company in order before they look for
talent.''
</P>
<P>
   But even this could be a positive in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely an opportunity for the independent music
community in two ways,'' said Sam Paulos, owner of indie Steve
Records based in Dallas. ``First, to possibly pick up bands that
are profitable on an indie level that may not be profitable on a
major. A band that sells 100,000 of a record on an indie is a
success, but a failure on a major.
</P>
<P>
   ``Secondly, the more majors consolidate, the more there's a
reaction for independent labels to renew their efforts, to become
more flexible ...''
</P>
<P>
   DeLaughter said, ``Maybe people will speak out and new little
baby companies will come along. A lot of people out there are
already creating alternative avenues for bands who are into making
good music.''
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, though, nobody knows for sure _ and sometimes
being in limbo is worse than knowing the worst.
</P>
<P>
   Jody Powerchurch, keyboardist for Dallas' Tomorrow People, which
was signed to Geffen last year and recorded a debut CD that isn't
out yet, said nobody knows what will happen to it, or the band, in
the restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've finished the record, but since all this has gone down,
we're just kinda sitting here, waiting,'' he said. ``I mean, we
hired a string section and really put a lot into this record. I
would hate for people not to hear it. Getting dropped isn't the
problem. It's the waiting around to get dropped. We don't really
care if we do. We'd just go to another label. But right now,
because we haven't been told either way, we can't do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman and Malcolm Mayhew are music critics for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. Contact Ferman at dfer(at)star-telegram.com
and Mayhew at (817) 390-7713.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
