A8877 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PILLER-COLUMN-TEX     12-28 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PILLER-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLUT OF CHAMPIONSHIP GAMES IS SOURING THE MARKET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAN PILLER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Christmas carols have been in the air this month, so that means
sports fans are again subjected to what has become an endless
ordeal: championship playoff series.
</P>
<P>
   In pro football, mediocre teams with players whose names you
can't remember will slog through what seems to be an unending
series of games around the turn of the year before we can get to
the denouement of the Super Bowl. That will clear the way for the
NCAA Basketball Tournament, a semi-exclusive event that invites 64
teams so that some outfit that finished third in its conference can
have a chance to win a national title.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA is no sooner out of the way than pro basketball (in
years when it's not on strike) and hockey begin their postseason
marathons that extend into June.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball, the game pickled in tradition, now has a three-step
postseason system that features wild-card teams. Be thankful that
Casey Stengel didn't live long enough to see this.
</P>
<P>
   The pros have an excuse, of course. They have to make a buck,
which they do by putting more ``product,'' as they call it, on the
postseason schedule. But colleges are supposed to be above such
foolishness, or so one would think.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 5, an unbeaten and No. 1-ranked Kansas State team was
required to beat twice-defeated Texas A&AMP;M in the Big 12
``championship'' game in St. Louis. We know what happened: A good
but not great Aggie team suddenly turned into an imitation of the
Denver Broncos in the fourth quarter, and K-State now is headed for
the Alamo Bowl instead of a shot at the national title and a piece
of immortality at the Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad for K-State, you say. It's also too bad for the Big 12.
A national championship in a sport lifts all boats in a conference,
from the winner down to Baylor. But the Big 12 won't get that
chance this year because its furrowed brows succumbed to the lure
of television money and the old saw, ``Let them settle it on the
field.''
</P>
<P>
   Settle what? Wasn't an 11-0 record in the regular season, which
included victories over Texas, Colorado and Nebraska, good enough
to justify calling Kansas State the Big 12 champion? Nothing
against A&AMP;M and its estimable coach, R.C. Slocum, who won the game
in St. Louis fair and square. But the lords of the Big 12 may need
to explain to the math departments at their schools how the
conference ``champion'' can have two defeats and the runner-up just
one.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing that was settled on the field Dec. 5 in St. Louis
was that the conference members got $6.5 million from ABC-TV for a
game that otherwise decided nothing. Meanwhile, K-State quarterback
Michael Bishop, one of the two or three best players in college
football this past season, has to live with erroneous television
replay analyses that his fumble with two minutes left ``cost'' his
school $10 million or so.
</P>
<P>
   What has happened is that sports administrators, both pro and
college, have devalued their regular seasons. Fans are charged
ever-increasing prices for regular games that are decreasingly
meaningful.
</P>
<P>
   Players are asked to put more of their athletic longevity into
extended seasons. For decades, baseball had a 154-game season. It
now is 162 games, and the ultimate winner has to survive three
series and potentially play into cold November weather. If Emmitt
Smith played in the NFL in the 1950s and '60s, he would risk his
body in 12 games and maybe a championship finale. Today, Smith has
a 16-game regular season and the potential for four more games
should the Cowboys keep winning. No wonder his body may be giving
out.
</P>
<P>
   Fans, meanwhile, spend a lot of time talking among one another
about how sports somehow don't seem to be as much fun and as
satisfying as they used to be. Drugs, immature and arrogant jocks,
and greedy owners are listed as the usual suspects.
</P>
<P>
   But the real problem is the old truth: You decrease the value of
something by providing more of it. Just as governments undermine
their economies by printing more money, so do sports undermine
themselves by giving us more and more ``championship games.''
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Piller is a business writer for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram and a loyal alumnus of the University of Nebraska.
Contact him at danpil(at)star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
