<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8879 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YE-TV-MOMENTS-1000(2T     12-28 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YE-TV-MOMENTS-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV'S BIG MOMENTS IN '98, FROM PRESIDENTIAL CONFESSION TO HOME-RUN
HEROICS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton and impeachment. ``ER'' and profits. Dr. Jack
Kevorkian and death. Sooner or later, everything goes through the
tube.
</P>
<P>
   Its best and worst moments often reflect the best and worst
moments of society, period. What with the information overload from
the 24-hours news channels, that's quite a vivid reflection. Here's
a look back at some memorable moments of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. ZipperGate (Aug. 18)
</P>
<P>
   More than 60 million viewers watch a pale, weary President
Clinton admit to an ``improper relationship'' with Monica Lewinsky.
All major broadcast and cable channels carry the announcement,
which lasts no more than six minutes. CNN attracts its largest
audience since that other unifying event, the 1995 verdict in O.J.
Simpson's criminal trial.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2. Camera confessions (March 15)
</P>
<P>
   Jailed suspects in the death of Amy Robinson mug for
KDFW/Channel 4 cameras, telling in detail how they tortured and
killed the 19-year-old grocery store employee. Taking up the first
27 minutes of Channel 4's newscast, Robert Neville and Michael Hall
explain the whys of their deeds, then giggle while suggesting their
own punishment: Death Row.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3. Death TV (Nov. 22)
</P>
<P>
   CBS newsmag ``60 Minutes'' climbs back into the top spot as the
country's most watched TV series _ by showing death. Some stations
refuse to show the segment, which includes a video of Dr. Jack
Kevorkian giving lethal injections to Thomas Youk, who suffered
from Lou Gehrig's disease. More than 23 million people tune in.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4. Texas' killer cadets (Feb. 2)
</P>
<P>
   Court TV's gavel-to-gavel coverage of Diane Zamora's trial in
the murder of Mansfield teen Adrienne Jones opens old wounds.
Earlier, KXAS/Channel 5 in Fort Worth-Dallas had refused to air
``Love's Deadly Triangle: The Texas Cadet Murder'' in order not to
taint the jury. Zamora's trial lasts two weeks, ending in a guilty
verdict. Sobbing, Zamora is escorted away in handcuffs. Former
lover David Graham's trial would end the same way.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   5. Classy departure (Nov. 24)
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Smits' farewell from ``NYPD Blue'' draws 22 million
viewers, the show's largest audience in three years. His character,
Detective Bobby Simone, dies of complications from a heart
condition, opening the gate for Rick Schroder and a rejuvenation of
the cop series.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   6. Unequal blame (July 9)
</P>
<P>
   CNN retracts a report that the U.S. military used nerve gas
during the Vietnam War. CNN News Group chairman Tom Johnson humbly
apologizes for a story claiming that the U.S. military used lethal
nerve gas in a secret 1970 mission in Vietnam aimed at killing
American defectors. The news report costs three CNN producers their
jobs, but correspondent Peter Arnett is merely reprimanded.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   7. Baseball comeback (Sept. 8)
</P>
<P>
   Fox sidelines its entire prime-time lineup _ including the
premiere episode of a new series _ to gamble that Mark McGwire will
hit his 61st homer of the season for the St. Louis Cardinals. It
pays off. McGwire slices a line-drive home run to left field,
breaking Roger Maris' record.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   8. Death Row debate (Nov. 3)
</P>
<P>
   News organizations set up camp in Huntsville, Texas, to witness
Karla Faye Tucker's execution. Tucker's case makes the national
news, reviving debate about a gender double standard when it comes
to the value of life.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   9. On second thought ... (June 23)
</P>
<P>
   Nine months after transforming herself from Republican Party
star to television star, Susan Molinari bows out as co-host of
``CBS News Saturday Morning.'' Molinari expresses dissatisfaction
with the show's fluffy approach; CBS News says she never got over
her stiffness in news reading and interviewing. The show averages a
dismal 1.3 rating. Molinari's next stop? A fellowship at Harvard's
Kennedy School of Government _ no TelePrompter needed.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
.MDBR/.MDNM/
</P>
<P>
   10. How young TV? (April 6)
</P>
<P>
   Not since parents objected to a sedate gentleman with an
affinity for sweaters has there been such skittishness about a new
children's program. PBS presents the American premiere of
``Teletubbies,'' an imaginative program featuring cute, cuddly
creatures with antennas on their heads and TVs in their bellies.
Almost immediately, critics dismiss its educational content to
focus on whether children under age 2 should be targeted by
television producers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   11. The skinny on Ally (Oct. 2)
</P>
<P>
   A New York TV station reports that Calista Flockhart, 33,
entered a clinic for treatment of anorexia, shutting down
production of her Fox TV series, ``Ally McBeal.'' It is never
confirmed. But the story renews water-cooler debate over the
pressures for actresses to remain dangerously thin.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   12. Wagging that dog (Dec. 16)
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the airing of the impeachment debate in the House
of Representatives, President Clinton orders airstrikes on Iraq. TV
news organizations scramble to cover both stories, setting up a day
in which only two things are part of TV programming: war and
politics.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   13. Breaking the bank (Jan. 14)
</P>
<P>
   The medical drama ``ER'' renews its contract with NBC _ at $13
million per episode. It's the highest price paid for any series,
prompting a quick shift in how networks deal with studios. (They'd
rather own their own shows, which means taking a chance on a
mediocre series over a good one.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   14. Sein off (May 14)
</P>
<P>
   ``Seinfeld'' signs off the air with a woeful season finale. It
attracts 76.3 million viewers, but is critically panned as one of
the show's worst efforts. Still, the series proves its power to NBC
when the network slumps badly after its departure.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   15. Heavenly TV (Aug. 31)
</P>
<P>
   Pax TV becomes the seventh broadcast network, airing off-network
reruns like ``Highway to Heaven'' and some original programming in
the form of infotainment programs, game shows and kids' series.
What's interesting is its agenda: ``Positive'' family programming
with a spiritual bent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   16. Yep, she's upset (May 6)
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Degeneres weeps and whines about the cancellation of her
ABC sitcom, ``Ellen,'' during an interview with Diane Sawyer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   17. Yep, she's bitter (May 13)
</P>
<P>
   ``Ellen'' ends on a sour note _ a painful one-hour series finale
that is star-studded but misguided. On the episode, which is shot
as a ``documentary,'' star Ellen Degeneres takes potshots at ABC
that appear more bitter than funny or clever.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   18. About time (Sept. 29)
</P>
<P>
   ``Felicity'' premieres on the WB after being the beneficiary of
the most universal pre-airing hype in years. Starring Keri Russell
as a young woman navigating college life, the series would become
what the network wants: a narrowcast hit. Teen-agers watch
religiously, and advertisers jump aboard.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   19. Skategate II (Feb. 5)
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Kerrigan and Tonya Harding sit through a painful interview
conducted by sportscaster James Brown. The buildup and interview is
nightmarish, something out of a Don King promotional highlight
reel. No one wins this low-rated affair _ not Fox, not viewers. Oh,
except Kerrigan and Harding. They pick up a cool $200,000 and
$100,000, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   20. We like it, but ... (July )
</P>
<P>
   Comedian Dave Chappelle accuses Fox of racism for seeking to add
white cast members to a sitcom he's developing for the network.
Chappelle and producer Peter Tolan air their allegations in the
trade paper ``Variety,'' saying they walked away from the project
after Fox suggested replacing some black supporting characters with
white actors to broaden its appeal. Fox calls the accusation
``disturbing and upsetting.''
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Contact him at kpp(at)Nstar-telegram.com. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
