<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN'S-SOCCER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN JOSE LOOKS TO '99 AS MAJOR YEAR FOR WOMEN IN SPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DWIGHT CHAPIN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ On July 4, 1994, Brandi Chastain sat in the
stands at Stanford Stadium, mesmerized by the spectacle and loving
every historic minute of it as the U.S. men's national soccer team
met Brazil in the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   On July 4, 1999, it could well be Chastain playing on that same
field, soaking up the pageantry and the applause but pinching
herself to make sure she isn't dreaming.
</P>
<P>
   When she's not working as an assistant coach with the women's
soccer team in Santa Clara County, Chastain is a key member of the
U.S. national squad. And if things break right, she and her
teammates will be watching the American flags wave for them next
Independence Day in the semifinals of the Women's World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   That would represent an almost-unbelievable stretch of
imagination for Chastain, who began playing soccer at a San Jose
elementary school more than 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something like this was just not a realistic goal when I
started in soccer,'' she said. ``The opportunity to be involved in
the World Cup, the Olympics or a program like Santa Clara's,
competing on a national level every year, just was not there.
</P>
<P>
   ``So this would be very special to me, not only because my
family and friends could come and watch, but because it would be
such a wonderful day for patriotism and soccer in general and such
great testimony to the growth of women's athletics in our
community.''
</P>
<P>
   And grow it has in San Jose, which will host several major
women's athletic events in 1999 _ including the NCAA Women's
Basketball Final Four at San Jose Arena March 26 and 28 and five
Women's World Cup games, double-headers at San Jose State's Spartan
Stadium June 19 and 30 and the July 4 semifinal at Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the folding of the American Basketball League last week,
wiping out that circuit's All-Star Game, there are more an more
opportunities for women in sports. And professional athletes see
that as a good sign for young women.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will create such good awareness for young girls who are
involved in sports. It will show them they have a lot of options
and opportunities _ a chance to reach the top levels,'' said
Jennifer Azzi, who played at Stanford and was one of the ABL's
founding players.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Cribbs, a founding partner of the ABL, was a swimming
medalist for the U.S. team at the 1960 Olympics in Rome.
</P>
<P>
   ``The women's team members came back not having been allowed to
tour Europe, as the American men did, because we needed a chaperon
and no one was available,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now little girls can dream about going on in athletics. And
there's a real difference in how their role models are viewed, too.
They can go see them play, in many cases.''
</P>
<P>
   Chastain remembers wanting to play football (``My mom wouldn't
let me, because she didn't want me beating up on the boys in the
neighborhood,'' she said), then settling on soccer, which then was
miles from any spotlights.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I loved it, every time I stepped on a field,'' she said.
``No one was going to tell me I had to stop. I'm just grateful my
parents and grandparents gave me the support to keep playing. And
it was crucial that I grew up in the Bay area, where we had a
professional team to watch (the Earthquakes) and there was a
community filled with different cultures, most of which embraced
soccer. Now, it's just wonderful to see people understand and
appreciate how exciting and entertaining soccer and women's sports
can be.''
</P>
<P>
   San Jose Mayor Susan Hammer doesn't have to be sold on that. A
former competitive tennis player whose daughter was a four-sport
star, Hammer is a ``passionate'' fan of the Stanford University
women's basketball team and was a close follower of the ABL San
Jose Lasers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact I was able to play a small part in attracting this
list of things in 1999 is very satisfying,'' she said. ``We've
proven we know how to put on major events.''
</P>
<P>
   Local organizers, spearheaded by Stanford associate athletic
director Cheryl Levick, worked several years to attract the NCAA
Women's Basketball Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe, in bringing this event here, we will show the rest
of the nation that we really are a mecca for women's athletics as
well as women's basketball,'' said Danette Macri, the Final Four's
executive director.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-28-98 1634EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981228.0266 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8898 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPY-NOVELS-ART-2NDTAK     12-28 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPY-NOVELS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: accounting mode.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most affected by the cooler market are the second-tier authors
who were writing in the genre, said Romanos of Simon &AMP; Schuster.
The well-known authors, he said, had a tougher time keeping their
audience, while ``the next level, the up-and-coming spy fiction,
began to shrink dramatically, so there's hardly any more of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Younger thriller writers like Daniel Silva, 37, author of ``The
Unlikely Spy'' and ``The Mark of the Assassin,'' draw inspiration
from World War II, but ``going back to the Cold War would be a
little strange,'' he said. ``Instinctively it doesn't feel right.
There's not enough distance and drama.''
</P>
<P>
   Le Carre, a former British intelligence officer whose real name
is David Cornwell, can be viewed as a case study of shifting to new
themes while tinkering with publishing relationships.
</P>
<P>
   The author left his publisher of 20 years, Alfred A. Knopf,
changed literary agents and is poised to publish a new book,
``Single &AMP; Single,'' that continues his movement away from
espionage themes and the prosaic world of his weary and brooding
spy, George Smiley.
</P>
<P>
   His last book, ``The Tailor of Panama,'' involved an elaborate
plot to void the Panama Canal Treaties. His base of readers has
eroded and his past sales figured into his last advance from Simon
&AMP; Schuster, which dropped to $2.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   At Scribner, where marketing executives have a one-word view of
Cold War spy fiction (``Done'') the publishers are positioning le
Carre to reach a new generation of readers. Scribner is planning to
print 300,000 copies of the novel.
</P>
<P>
   Wesley Wark, a University of Toronto history professor who
specializes in the study of intelligence services and spy fiction,
said the espionage genre still had life but was ``going through a
difficult period when clearly new settings or scenes are
required.''
</P>
<P>
   In Search of a New Lode
</P>
<P>
   Instead of new spy settings, though, writers are switching to
new genres with the intrigue of politics or police work.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to wait for the Cold War to be quaint as a little
Napoleonic war,'' said Charles McCarry, a former CIA intelligence
officer who has moved from novels about spies to books about
political intrigue like his best-selling ``Lucky Bastard.'' ``After
doing this for almost 30 years,'' McCarry said, ``what happens is
that you live your experience and eventually it runs out. So you
find another vein.''
</P>
<P>
   A contrarian view of the Cold War comes from Follett, who with
his departure this month from Crown for Dutton, an imprint of
Penguin Putnam, intends to write a historical novel based on a
failed launching of an American satellite amid Cold War tensions in
1958. He is careful, however, to correct any typecasting of the
book as a Cold War novel.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you say it's a Cold War story,'' Follett said, ``people
will think it has a character like Smiley and involves a KGB person
and an FBI agent who are at loggerheads. And it isn't like that at
all. None of the principal characters are Russian.''
</P>
<P>
   Follett noted that he had avoided the spy genre in his last two
novels, the latter a contemporary thriller called ``The Hammer of
Eden,'' which centers on aging hippie eco-terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, the golden age of the spy story is definitely
over,'' Follett said. ``But that doesn't mean that there aren't
going to be any good ones written. In order to do so, I've had to
set my story in 1958. I don't think it would work in 1998. We're
not afraid of the Russians anymore. You need someone to be afraid
of.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
