r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-MERGER-1400(2Ta     12-28 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-MERGER-1400(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEAGRAM'S BUYOUT OF POLYGRAM HAS BANDS WONDERING WHO'LL GET THE AX
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN and MALCOLM MAYHEW 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Dec. 10 announcement that Seagram Co. had bought Polygram NV
read like just another dry business story: One big company pays a
boatload of money to acquire another, profits are expected, blah de
blah de blah.
</P>
<P>
   But for any music fan it's much, much more.
</P>
<P>
   The merger, which cost the Montreal-based company $10.4 billion,
means that hundreds of bands _ including local heroes such as
Arlington's Slowpoke and Fort Worth's Toadies, Tomorrow People and
Radish _ might be handed their walking papers in the next several
months.
</P>
<P>
   Why? A major facet of the merger is reducing the number of bands
on its now-combined roster, according to analysts and industry
sources.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the consolidation of numerous labels (among them Island,
Mercury, Interscope, Geffen, Motown, Universal and A&AMP;M) into larger
groupings is expected to mean layoffs for a large percentage of the
various labels' 15,500 employees. Analyst Scott Davis with
investment firm Schroder &AMP; Co. was quoted in Bloomberg News as
saying that as many as 20 percent could be fired.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a terrible situation,'' said one A&AMP;M executive, speaking
on condition of anonymity. ``A lot of people are losing their jobs.
Thousands. All across the board. In every department.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosters are expected to be similarly slashed as the labels are
combined into one all-inclusive company. Bands that have not sold
particularly well and/or are expensive to maintain look to be in
trouble as Seagram aims to run a leaner ship.
</P>
<P>
   And that means a time of watching and waiting for thousands of
musicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``The labels aren't letting the bands in on anything,'' said
Lisa Umbarger, bassist for the Toadies. The band's Interscope
debut, ``Rubberneck,'' sold a million copies, but the follow-up is
up in the air because the label won't give the band any more money
to finish mixing it. ``Everyone's just waiting around. From what I
hear, everyone's in danger of being dropped, but we're not worrying
about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rumor is, platinum (million-seller) bands are safe, but I
don't buy into that. The whole industry is downsizing. So it's not
just little bands or bands in the middle. This is affecting
everybody. The record company people have it worse than we do.
There's really no place for them to go. They're gonna be working at
7-Eleven.''
</P>
<P>
   Also facing an ambiguous future is Slowpoke; the Arlington pop
band that signed to Geffen last year and this year released its
label debut, ``Virgin Stripes.'' Now, says lead singer Dave Gibson,
``We're on hold until February or March. Nobody knows what's going
to happen until then. It's the kinda thing where there's hundreds
of bands to review.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure band managers will be busy trying to convince
Interscope to keep their bands on. I think that decision will be
based on a combo of what the bands are currently doing, their sales
history and buzz. It'll be like a talent show, their time to
strut.''
</P>
<P>
   The Polygram purchase means that the new uber-company, Universal
Music Group, is the largest music company in the world, with a
roster that includes U2, Van Morrison, Beck, Erykah Badu, Marilyn
Manson, Hole and Elton John.
</P>
<P>
   UMG won't confirm layoff numbers, said Bob Bernstein, senior
vice president for public relations. He said there will be a
``paring down'' of the label rosters, but declined to be specific.
</P>
<P>
   Announcements of layoffs and roster trims, he said, will come
``early next year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a strategic acquisition,'' said Linda Bannister, an
analyst with investment firm Edward Jones. ``Seventy-five percent
of Polygram's business is international and 75 percent of
Universal's is domestic. This gives Universal an instant market
share internationally _ they're instantly a major player.'' Being a
major player has been harder for Seagram in one of its other major
entertainment ventures: movies. In 1995 Seagram went into the movie
business by buying MCA, which it renamed Universal Studios.
</P>
<P>
   But '98 has been a tough year for the studio, with numerous
mega-hyped movies, among them ``Psycho,'' ``Primary Colors,''
``Babe: Pig in the City'' and ``Meet Joe Black,'' performing poorly
at the box office.
</P>
<P>
   The day before the announcement of the Polygram purchase,
Seagram announced Universal Studios had a loss of $65 million for
the fiscal second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing for them, but it happens to every studio at
some point, and it's to be expected when your films aren't
profitable,'' said Bannister. ``In 1998 Seagram's net income was
$946 million, so obviously this won't break the bank. The Polygram
move was in the works long ago _ it's not a result of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Universal's big hopes for the seasonal movie dollar now rest
with ``Shakespeare in Love'' and Robin Williams' ``Patch Adams,''
both of which opened on Christmas Day.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
