<HEADER>
A8925 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOG-1STLD-WRITETHRU-H     12-28 0324
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOG-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOG CAUSES FLIGHT DELAYS IN BAY AREA 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Updates throughout with latest conditions, forecast.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM HERRON ZAMORA and ERIC BRAZIL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A nearly impenetrable layer of fog clamped down
on the San Francisco Bay area, disrupting holiday travel plans for
thousands of passengers at three airports and turning Monday's
morning commute into an eerie adventure.
</P>
<P>
   The fog was blamed for a fatal traffic accident near Petaluma.
</P>
<P>
   At the San Francisco International Airport, where 200 to 300
stranded travelers spent Sunday night, there were flight delays of
eight hours or more.
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service predicted the fog, caused by a
high-pressure ridge that put a lid on cold, stagnant, ground-level
air, will last through at least Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``People heading to the airport should be prepared for the
worst-case scenario, which means it's possible they won't get out
at all,'' said Ron Wilson, spokesman for the San Francisco
International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some very unhappy passengers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the region usually has its heaviest fog in December and
January, Wilson said he could not recall an occasion when the
airports at San Francisco, Oakland and San Jose had been so badly
socked in.
</P>
<P>
   United Airlines, the largest carrier at the San Francisco
airport, had canceled 130 flights since Sunday night, airline
spokesman Joe Hopkins said.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of incoming flights were diverted to Los Angeles and Las
Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing is going out and nothing is coming in at San Jose,''
an airport spokeswoman said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   However, the fog lifted at Oakland airport around early in the
day and flights were leaving nearly on schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Visibility was reduced to 100 feet on bridges in the Bay area,
and the National Weather Service issued a rare fog warning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-28-98 1655EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
