<DOCNO> NYT19981228.0268 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 16:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8927 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YE-POP-MUSIC-TEX     12-28 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YE-POP-MUSIC-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREAT ALT-COUNTRY, LANDMARK BOXED SETS HIGHLIGHT A HO-HUM YEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (EDS: Accompanied by YE-TOP10CDS) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   How good a year in pop music can it be when Frank Sinatra died?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is, not very _ at least not on the surface, and maybe
even a few layers deeper, too. The loss of Ol' Blue Eyes actually
makes an odd kind of sense _ one could argue that it set the tone
for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Pop music in 1998 was defined by so-so pop acts of every stripe
(from Fastball to 'N Sync to matchbox 20) dominating a barren,
uninteresting landscape. Consider: If swing, a sound and style of
dance first popularized more than 40 years ago, can be the hottest
thing around for most of the year, what does that say about current
artists and contemporary music?
</P>
<P>
   Not much. Techno officially became NOT the next big thing;
Shania Twain used her unremarkable voice and cute figure to fill
arenas. At the same time, a number of acts completely misfired this
year, or found a cooler-than-expected reception: Worthy CDs by
Garbage and Beck, among others, languished on the charts, doing far
less business than one might have expected.
</P>
<P>
   Because there is so much emphasis now on a band having one big
hit and one big CD, audiences don't stay loyal to performers for
very long. More pop music fans seem to follow someone else's lead
and buy what absolutely everybody else is buying _ whether it's the
``Titanic'' soundtrack or matchbox 20's ``Yourself or Someone Like
You.''
</P>
<P>
   And this indicates that building a career is going to become
much harder in the coming years: ``Here today, gone tomorrow'' has
become ``Here today, gone today.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that's why some of the most interesting music released
in 1998 was from alternative-country acts such as Lucinda Williams,
Joe Ely and the Mavericks. As rock continues to water itself down,
alt-country continues to step up to the plate and offer the sort of
passion and strong songwriting that one used to expect from
mainstream rock performers.
</P>
<P>
   Whether mainstream rock will jump on this and realize the wealth
of great performers just waiting for it in this genre is still up
in the air; mainstream country radio has dropped the ball entirely.
</P>
<P>
   The other good news _ besides the Lauryn Hill debut _ was the
fistful of terrific boxed sets and live CDs that came out this
year: Bruce Springsteen's ``Tracks,'' Randy Newman's ``Guilty: 30
Years of Randy Newman,'' the ``Nuggets'' compilation of '60s garage
bands, Bob Dylan's historic and often-bootlegged 1966 show in
Manchester, England.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, looking to the past may be the best option these days.
The year drew to a close with the announcement of the enormous
Seagram Co./Polygram merger. That will mean widespread layoffs at
the labels affected, including A&AMP;M, Interscope and Geffen.
</P>
<P>
   More troubling, though, is the realization that the deal will
mean numerous bands will be dropped in the coming months. Cuts
won't be announced until next year, but one rumor is that bands
that have not yet gone platinum will face the ax.
</P>
<P>
   That's probably too broad, but this much is sure: There will be
even less room for experimentation and freethinking in mainstream
pop music in the coming years. And that will, in turn, lead to more
dumbing-down of the music. As Neil Young once said, if you don't
have the freedom to fail, you don't have any freedom at all.
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman is pop music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Contact him at dfer(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-28-98 1656EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
