A8928 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YE-TOP10CDS-TEX     12-28 0409
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YE-TOP10CDS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP 10 CD RELEASES OF THE YEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (EDS: accompanies BC-YE-POP-MUSIC) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are my favorite 10 CDs of the year, in alphabetical order
by artist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mermaid Avenue,'' Billy Bragg &AMP; Wilco. A terrific English
folkie and an equally terrific American alt-country band team up to
dust off a slew of Woody Guthrie lyrics and render them timeless.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Black Light,'' Calexico. Like a ghost at twilight or the
soundtrack to a movie that exists only in the mind, this noirish
and often instrumental collection of songs drifts from the
honky-tonk to the border cantina and back again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twistin' in the Wind,'' Joe Ely. Ely is one of Texas' leading
bards of the barroom and the highway, and he's never made a better
(or funnier, or more deeply felt) CD than this.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Miseducation of Lauryn Hill,'' Lauryn Hill. This is on
numerous year-end best-ofs for one reason: It's a masterful song
cycle of self-examination and hip-hop and soul grooves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trampoline,'' The Mavericks. This is the Miami-based band's
magnum opus, full of memorable songs, stirring singing from Raul
Malo, and a hybrid country/Latin/soul sound that's unlike anything
any other band is doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deserter's Songs,'' Mercury Rev. Richly textured and darkly
intoxicating, this quiet gem of loss and disappointment can haunt
the mind and the spirit for days after a listen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Philosopher's Stone,'' Van Morrison. More than two dozen
previously unreleased songs by Ireland's greatest musical poet _
many as good as anything he's ever put out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Powertrip,'' Monster Magnet. If metal is on its last artistic
legs, someone forgot to tell Dave Wyndorf and his Jersey homeboys _
this teeth-rattler is the genre's best CD of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Decksandrumsandrockandroll,'' Propellerheads. Best title, best
cover, best cameo (Shirley Bassey on ``History Repeating'') and a
terrific mix of electronic rhythms and R&AMP;B.
</P>
<P>
   ``Car Wheels on a Gravel Road,'' Lucinda Williams. One of the
best CDs of the '90s, this was six years in coming and worth every
minute we had to wait; it's an alt-country benchmark and a simply
amazing collection of bittersweet songs.
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman is pop music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Contact him at dfer(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
