<P>
   &UR; ATTACK OF THE SUPERBUGS! &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ONE COLOR ILLUSTRATION AVAILABLE FREE &QL; 
 &UR; (1,100 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By PETER RADETSKY &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``At least half the human use of antibiotics in the United
States is unnecessary or inappropriate,'' says Stuart Levy, a Tufts
University School of Medicine microbiologist. ``Either antibiotics
are not indicated at all, or the wrong antibiotic is prescribed, or
it's the wrong dosage or the wrong duration.'' The upshot of this
massive exposure is disease-causing bugs that resist the drugs that
once thwarted them. They're superbugs, and their power is
frightening: Superbugs that can withstand not just one but
multitudes of antibiotics. Is it too late to do anything? Peter
Radetsky, who teaches science writing at the University of
California in Santa Cruz, reports.
</P>
<P>
   slugged: BC-SUPERBUGS-NYTSF. Sent to category codes ``a''
general news and ``l'' lifestyle news.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BLOOD OF THE VIKINGS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; FOUR COLOR SLIDES ARE AVAILABLE FREE &QL; 
 &UR; (1,200 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By ROBERT KUNZIG &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Did you know that Icelanders are virtually all descended from a
few thousand people who arrived in the ninth and 10th centuries?
It's true _ and that feature makes them of great interest to
geneticists. In this island nation, tracing family connections even
astonishingly far back into the past is not hard _ and Kari
Stefansson's company deCODE has set about doing it once and for
all. Robert Kunzig, Discover's European editor, reports.
</P>
<P>
   slugged: BC-VIKING-BLOOD-NYTSF. Sent to category codes ``a''
general news and ``l'' lifestyle news.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AIDS: THE CHASM IN CARE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ONE COLOR SLIDE IS AVAILABLE FREE &QL; 
 &UR; (900 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By JOSIE GLAUSIUSZ &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, AIDS deaths dropped 47 percent from 1996
to 1997 _ thanks mostly to expensive drug treatments. Elsewhere the
picture is very bleak. Rates of HIV infection are soaring in
impoverished African and Asian countries. In Zimbabwe, for example,
one-quarter of the adult population is now thought to be infected
with HIV. Worldwide, 16,000 people are newly infected with the
virus every day. Josie Glausiusz, an associate editor at Discover
magazine, reports.
</P>
<P>
   slugged: BC-HIV-INFECTION-SOARS-NYTSF. Sent to category codes
``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle news.
</P>
<P>
   Thank you.
</P>
<P>
   _ The New York Times Syndicate.
