<SLUG> BC-COSMETIC-SURGERY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEATHS SPUR EFFORT TO TOUGHEN STANDARDS IN COSMETIC SURGERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ELIZABETH FERNANDEZ  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In the wake of scores of deaths around the
country linked to cosmetic surgery, legislative reforms targeted to
the boom in ``rejuvenation'' surgery are being considered in
California.
</P>
<P>
   State legislators and medical officials are calling for stricter
standards, ranging from mandatory malpractice insurance for
physicians to tightening qualifications for doctors who perform
cosmetic surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm quite shocked at what I've heard _ that physicians are
essentially taking 16-hour weekend courses, then on Monday putting
themselves out to the public to practice cosmetic surgery,'' says
Democratic Assemblyman Martin Gallegos, chairman of the Assembly
Health Committee. ``There are physicians who are ill-prepared and
put the public at risk with these procedures.''
</P>
<P>
   Gallegos backs the efforts of a special cosmetic surgery
committee formed last year by the state Medical Board in response
to rising alarm over complications stemming from vanity treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doctors are using cosmetic surgery to supplement their income,
it's another outcropping of the explosion of managed care,''
Gallegos says.
</P>
<P>
   However, ``as best as I can tell, there are not uniform and
consistent standards and guidelines pertaining to training, to what
are safe quantities for liposuction removal,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   A San Francisco Examiner investigation published in September
documented escalating peril over cosmetic surgery _ treatment,
promoted as low-risk, that can be performed without additional
training by any medical doctor. In the last five years, the field
has exploded, with baby boomers hoisting sagging jowls, plumping
breasts and dewrinkling middle-age visages.
</P>
<P>
   The series detailed a spate of puzzling deaths of healthy people
who underwent liposuction, the nation's most popular form of
cosmetic surgery. According to one estimate, 60 to 100 fatalities
occurred last year in the United States out of about 100,000
liposuction procedures, a rate doctors term both shocking and
preventable.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Gage, a consultant for the Joint Legislative Sunset Review
Committee, which reviews all consumer boards under the Department
of Consumer Affairs, credits the series with helping to fuel
efforts to initiate regulatory improvements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe the state needs to step in and make sure they (the
boards) are doing a better job of protecting the consumer.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Robert del Junco, head of the cosmetic surgery committee,
says another new liposuction study indicates a fatality rate of 1
in 5,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is completely unacceptable,'' says del Junco, one of the
most outspoken doctors in the state pushing for legislative
remedies. ``In a cosmetic operation that has no health benefit, the
fact that there is one death is unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   A prudent first step, he says, would be mandatory malpractice
insurance for physicians who perform elective cosmetic surgery in
outpatient clinics. Insurance carriers would then require special
training for doctors before they could perform cosmetic surgery, he
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``In California you need malpractice insurance to practice in a
hospital setting,'' says del Junco, an ear, nose and throat
specialist practicing near Los Angeles. ``Now we've turned more to
outpatient settings in medicine and the law is inconsistent.
Doctors are not necessarily held to the same insurance standard.
We're saying we at least should require it for cosmetic surgery
(where) doctors have the freedom of going from internal medicine to
cosmetic surgery over a weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``For patients, it makes sense to be able to get some form of
economic compensation. It doesn't deny doctors the opportunity to
do a career change, but it says before you can practice on the
public, you have to have training before you can be insured. It
becomes a marketplace issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry experts say that only 1 percent or fewer of the state's
physicians are believed to be practicing without insurance
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   But Assemblyman Gallegos says he will likely sponsor legislation
to require it for doctors in outpatient surgical centers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a patient is harmed, there would be recourse for
compensation,'' Gallegos says.
</P>
<P>
   Another concern for the cosmetic surgery committee is false and
misleading advertising.
</P>
<P>
   An October committee report said some ads use different models
for ``before'' and ``after'' photos or use untouched ``befores''
and air-brushed ``afters.'' The report also cited the use of terms
``impossible to support, such as `painless,' `entirely safe,' and
`satisfaction guaranteed.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sadly, consumers seeking cosmetic procedures are increasingly
influenced by these questionable ads ...'' said the report.
``Although it can be argued that current law already prohibits the
very practices the committee would seek to prohibit, the law would
be less problematic to enforce if more defining regulations were
written.''
</P>
<P>
   Accreditation of outpatient surgery centers, where the majority
of cosmetic procedures are performed _ from minor treatments like
collagen injections to major procedures like face lifts _ also
should be reviewed in the coming legislative term, says Julianne
D'Angelo Fellmeth, administrative director of the Center for Public
Interest Law at the University of San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   The law now requires facilities to be accredited if they use
certain levels of anesthesia, but ``it is not working,'' Fellmeth
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Different accrediting agencies apply different criteria to
doctors' settings ... and it's not clear at what point (of
anesthesia) the doctors have to be accredited,'' says Fellmeth.
``Holes need to be filled in. The area of cosmetic surgery seems to
be an area where it is demonstrably not working.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
