A9060 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARY-DONOHUE-HNS &LR;      12-28 1229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARY-DONOHUE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPROBABLE LAWYER GEARS UP FOR NEW YORK'S NO. 2 JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN CAHER  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ With her marriage in disarray and her daughter in
diapers, 33-year-old Mary Kenney rejected her matriarchal mother's
advice and enrolled in law school.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said it would be the biggest mistake I ever made and that
if Sara was able to talk, I'd hear a lot about it from my daughter
as well,'' recalled the native, of Troy, N.Y., who is now Lt.
Gov.-elect Mary Donohue.
</P>
<P>
   Enrolling in Albany Law School in 1980 proved to be a critical
juncture for Donohue, and a springboard into an improbable career
for the bookish, quiet daughter of Thomas and Ruth O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was brought up in a very traditional Irish family,'' Donohue
said.
</P>
<P>
   Donohue's father, ``Whitey O'Connor,'' was a legendary Collar
City lawyer and popular city court judge.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a brilliant lawyer, a very accomplished, interesting
lawyer who, after he stepped down from the bench, devoted his
professional life to defending poor people,'' said Troy attorney
Thomas J. O'Connor, Donohue's brother.
</P>
<P>
   Donohue's mother was ``an old-fashioned Irish mom, a wonderful
mom'' with deep roots in the hardscrabble, industrial city, she
said. And Mary was the dutiful daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Of going to law school, Donohue said: ``You have to make the
decision that is right for you. It was a very big turning point in
my life.''
</P>
<P>
   In May, Donohue made a decision that could very well be another
turning point, and may or may not be right for her.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two years after attaining what could have been the
pinnacle of a legal career, election to a 14-year term as a state
Supreme Court justice, Donohue quit the judiciary to join Gov.
George Pataki on the campaign trail _ opting to run for a less
prestigious job that historically has been a ticket to oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, it could land Donohue in the Executive
Mansion if Pataki leaves to pursue national office. Clearly, the
prospect of becoming chief executive of the nation's third-largest
state does not intimidate Donohue.
</P>
<P>
   ``In deciding whether I would run with the governor for
lieutenant governor, of course I was aware of the potential,''
Donohue said in a recent interview, carefully sidestepping queries
on whether she actually aspires to Pataki's job. ``If that had
given me pause to hesitate, I would have, and I did not.''
</P>
<P>
   Donohue said she signed onto the Pataki team because she was
impressed with the governor's accomplishments, in agreement with
his Republican politics, and enchanted by a philosophy she calls
``empowering the individual.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is reflective of both the governor's and my
philosophy, a belief in the individual ... giving the money and the
power back to the individual, to families, so individuals can
prosper, rather than having the bureaucracy and the state enhancing
itself,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Empowered'' is not a word one would have used to describe Mary
O'Connor until she was in her 30s.
</P>
<P>
   She got a bachelor's degree in English from the College of New
Rochelle, and soon married Troy attorney Tom Kenney.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom I knew since we were kids,'' Donohue said. ``Our families,
our mothers, were best friends. He is still my brother Tom's
closest friend, believe it or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary began teaching, and eventually picked up a master's degree
at Russell Sage College in Troy.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, after years and years of trying to have a baby, Tom
and Mary conceived Sara. But their marriage was crumbling, and Mary
_ more to get it out of her system than anything else _ took the
law boards. She scored in the top 2 percent and, despite her
mother's advice, enrolled, often bringing year-old Sara to school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in class with people who were able to live and breathe
law school every day, every minute, while I was juggling jobs, baby
and other priorities,'' Donohue said. ``Fortunately, I was able to
juggle things.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the things Donohue juggled was an internship at the U.S.
Attorney's office in Albany, where the region's top federal
prosecutor, David R. Homer, tossed a gnarly medical malpractice
case her way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought she was a very hard worker,'' said Homer, now a U.S.
magistrate. ``I gave her a difficult assignment on a civil case,
and she did an exceptional job.''
</P>
<P>
   In law school, Mary met her next husband, Brian Donohue, now a
lawyer in Troy.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first encounter with Mary was at the Supreme Court library
in Troy, where you'd go to study because it was quiet,'' recalled
Brian Donohue. ``The first time she ever said anything to me, she
gave me a dirty look and said, `Please be quiet' _ the first time
of many.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was Mary who first asked Brian out on a date. They went
to an Albany County Bar Association function.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from law school, Donohue took a job with the
Albany law firm of O'Connell &AMP; Aronowitz, where she litigated cases
ranging from Dalkon Shield product liability matters to matrimonial
actions, winning the respect of her colleagues and, just as
importantly, the blessings of her mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was never angry with my mother about her philosophy (about
attending law school), but I never, never expected with her strong
maternal personality that she would understand,'' Donohue said.
``She said: `You know, you were right. You are doing great and your
daughter is doing great and I really respect you for standing up to
me.'''
</P>
<P>
   Donohue left O'Connell &AMP; Aronowitz in 1988, shortly before her
second child, Justin, was born. She was 41, and took a job as an
assistant Rensselaer County attorney, a job that put her in the
political loop. Four years later, Donohue was selected as the
Republican candidate for district attorney, and designated the task
of challenging the incumbent.
</P>
<P>
   Donohue ran to win, and won, but soon attracted criticism when
her office was forced to plea bargain a gang rape case and had to
settle for a manslaughter conviction when it sought a murder
verdict involving a North Greenbush councilman who killed his wife
with chloroform. One former staffer said Donohue was well out of
her league.
</P>
<P>
   Another, however, said Donohue perhaps made mistakes early on,
but never made the same mistake twice.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Donohue was re-elected in 1995 with a landslide 70
percent of the vote. She was viewed in GOP circles as an
exceptional campaigner, and when party leaders went looking for a
Supreme Court candidate in 1996, they knocked on her door.
</P>
<P>
   Donohue easily outpolled five other candidates, and promptly
settled into a 14-year term in robes _ only to ditch it all two
years later.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Pataki announced that he was dumping Lt. Gov. Betsy
McCaughey Ross from his re-election ticket, and suggested Donohue
would be a good replacement. In May, he asked Donohue to join the
team, and she agreed, without hesitation or, so far, regret.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoyed tremendously being a judge,'' Donohue said in a
measured, prudent tone. ``But there is a component in being asked
to be the running mate of a governor whose philosophy I share, who
had done so much already ... to have the opportunity to work with
him and hopefully use my background as a judge to help him be more
effective as governor, was an opportunity I did not want to say no
to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-28-98 1726EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
