<SLUG> BC-NYLITE(SMILE)-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 No. 2880 Mon., Dec. 28: 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (NYLite items can be published if desired; &LR;  please credit the
contributor. Contribute to NYLite and get a NYT rolling-writer
style pen.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BILL'S WORLD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Be patient, children. Another few days and we bet your parents
will have your ``Some Assembly Required'' Christmas toys put
together.
</P>
<P>
   Another way we'll know we've got a serious Y2K problem is if, in
2000, William McKinley gets elected president.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds as if most senators want a speedy impeachment trial.
For one thing, they want to get right back to avoiding the real
issues.
</P>
<P>
   A ``speedy'' Senate trial could mean one that ends by spring.
Senate work has the same relation to speed that most diets have to
losing weight.
</P>
<P>
   Over the Christmas break, Mr. Clinton saw the play ``Twelfth
Night.'' No, it was the Shakespeare production, not a re-enactment
of his twelfth tryst with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   For his planned presidential library in Arkansas, Mr. Clinton
needs to raise about $45 million, it's reported. If his past
girlfriends give just $100 each, it should be easy.
</P>
<P>
   The president wants Congress to pass tougher drunken-driving
laws. Maybe some drunken-legislating laws would help, too.
</P>
<P>
   The Social Security system is so ready for the Y2K computer bug
that no payment will be delayed ``by a single day,'' Mr. Clinton
says. Makes us wonder if there's such a thing as a married day.
</P>
<P>
   Pope John Paul II has thanked Fidel Castro for allowing Cubans
to celebrate Christmas. In return, will Vatican residents get to
celebrate the July 26 anniversary of the Cuban revolution?
</P>
<P>
   Love letters between Queen Victoria and her servant John Brown
have been found in an attic in Scotland, it's reported. Impeach
her, we say.
</P>
<P>
   The violent crime rate has dropped to its lowest level in 25
years. Are all the violent criminals in front of the TV or at the
movies watching violent crimes?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUOTABLES FROM NBC'S 'THE TONIGHT SHOW WITH JAY LENO' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This ice storm is all over the country. In Washington, it was so
cold today Ken Starr had to scrape the ice off people's bedroom
windows to look inside.
</P>
<P>
   Here's some good White House gossip. It seems President Clinton
and Hillary have cancelled their annual family vacation to the
Virgin Islands this year. I wonder what happened?
</P>
<P>
   The American Association for Nude Recreation has come out with a
list of the most popular recreation activities to do whole nude.
Let me tell you something. If you can't figure out what to do for
fun while naked, you don't deserve to be naked in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUOTABLES FROM NBC'S 'LATE NIGHT WITH CONAN O'BRIEN' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Earlier today, President Clinton read Christmas stories to a
bunch of kids at the White House. At one point the president asked
a boy if he's been good this year and the boy said, 'Well, put it
this way, I didn't perjure myself.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dennis Hastert, the Republicans' next choice for Speaker of
the House, came from a small town in Illinois and was once a high
school wrestling coach. When asked to comment about this Hastert
said, 'I resign.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``A new study shows that primetime TV under represents women and
senior citizens. Network executives said they'll hire more women
and seniors as soon as granny gets implants.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At the White House last night, President Clinton read the
story 'A Visit From St. Nick.' The weird part is, in the
President's version it's a conjugal visit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Christmas Ally McBeal has her own line of pajamas and
retailers say they're selling like hotcakes. Actually they're
selling more like low-fat rice cakes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday, Germany accused members of the Three Tenors of tax
evasion. Apparently, they feel that Luciano Pavarotti should claim
Pizza Hut as a second home.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CITY STREETS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   After about 15 minutes of snaking their way along, Mildred Mauer
and other would-be viewers hadn't yet reached the Van Gogh exhibit
at the National Gallery in Washington. An exasperated mother in
front of Mildred addressed her perhaps 8-year-old son. ``We're not
even in yet,'' she said. ``What do you mean you're bored?''
</P>
<P>
   Scene: New York Waterways bus.
</P>
<P>
   Players: Two elderly gentlemen.
</P>
<P>
   Observer: Alfred Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   Conversation in full:
</P>
<P>
   First man: ``You been to Barcelona?''
</P>
<P>
   His friend: ``Nope.''
</P>
<P>
   First man: ``Budapest?''
</P>
<P>
   Friend: ``Nope.''
</P>
<P>
   First man: ``The Grand Canyon?''
</P>
<P>
   Friend: ``Nope.''
</P>
<P>
   First man: ``You ever been to a Wal-Mart?''
</P>
<P>
   Friend: ``Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucille Waldman was busy navigating the holiday crowds on
Madison Avenue in the vicinity of F.A.O. Schwarz. As she waited for
the light to change, she didn't know whether to be pleased to be a
native New Yorker, or whether she was fair game. An intrepid dog
walker was admonishing his dog: ``And don't bite any tourists!''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Walking on the Upper West Side, I saw this tiny lady _ an old
70, I'd guess _ in this incredible dress. It was cotton pique with
large flowers on it in a wonderful range of colors _ and each
covered button was a different color.
</P>
<P>
   I said to her, ``Great dress,'' and she said, ``Thank you.''
Then she came close to me and said: ``A Saks Fifth Avenue dress _ I
got it for $3. At my age, I need to economize. I bought it at a
thrift store. I'm not long for this world.'' She pointed to a woman
wearing a very tight, stretchy dress with a visible panty line
clinging to an enormous behind. ``When I see a dress like that, it
hastens my end,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   I asked her how she found her great dress. ``People ask me for
advice all the time, but I need to keep it to myself,'' she said,
making her hands into fists and placing them on her heart. ``I need
it for me.''
</P>
<P>
   A young man walked by, and she pointed him out to me. ``He held
open the door for me in my building once. I remember people who are
kind to me.'' She then continued as if we had known each other a
long time. ``I can feel my end coming. I'm not myself. I ran into a
friend at the laundromat recently and she said, `Lil, what's
wrong?' I know I don't look like myself. I've been around here long
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   I told her I hoped not, because we needed her to wear great
dresses in New York. She said, ``Thank you for your compliment.'' I
wished her the best of luck, and we parted ways.
</P>
<P>
   _ ANDREA SIEGEL
</P>
<P>
   Chris Boneau was showing Texas relatives the town. When he got
out of a cab with them, he realized he had left behind the
expensive camera he had bought in Tokyo. The cab had driven off,
and he had no receipt.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty minutes later, he was in his apartment bemoaning his loss
when his friend Benedicta Pollock walked in and announced excitedly
that she had taken a cab and found this terrific camera in the back
seat. ``That's my camera!'' Chris cried as he tore it from her
hands.
</P>
<P>
   Now all that remains is to see if his relatives' images are on
the film when it's developed. If not, he said, the camera goes to
the Taxi and Limousine Commission. But in his own mind, he's
certain the pictures will be there and the camera is his. His
relatives believe that these things happen all the time in New
York, but he knows, he said, that ``this is, after all, the season
of miracles.''
</P>
<P>
   The woman pointed to a display of stamps in the post office and
asked the provenance of one particular stamp. ``It's the new
Hanukkah stamp,'' the clerk said. The woman was incredulous. ``They
already have a stamp for Monica?'' she asked. As Arnold Aaron
reported, ``For several laugh-filled minutes, the mail did not go
through.''
</P>
<P>
   A man I know recently found himself doing some lunch-hour
holiday shopping at the Victoria's Secret at South Street Seaport.
His rather conservative selections were carefully packed and placed
in a large shopping bag. To his dismay, the bag was quite the
opposite of the proverbial plain brown bag _ it was brightly
colored, with Victoria's Secret emblazoned across the side. He
shuddered at the idea of returning to the office with it, but was
informed that it was the only style of bag the store carried.
</P>
<P>
   As he emerged, imagining the snickers and titters as he walked
down the long hall to his office, past secretary after secretary,
he noticed a Foot Locker store next door. Inspired, he walked in
and approached a saleswoman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Excuse me,'' he began, ``would you by any chance have ...''
``You want a bag,'' she interrupted, laughing, looking at the
Victoria's Secret bag. ``Exactly,'' he responded, with surprise and
relief. As he thanked her for the bag and turned to leave, she
shook her head and asked, ``Why is it that every guy walks out of
Victoria's Secret and comes in here asking for a Foot Locker bag?''
</P>
<P>
   _ LLOYD S. LOWY
</P>
<P>
   Mark Blackman was at the counter of a Greek coffee shop when a
woman beside him began to lose patience with her tired, unruly
child. ``Jason, try to behave,'' she said. ``Remember, Santa is
right now working on his list of who's naughty and who's nice, and
he's going to release it very soon.''
</P>
<P>
   The Greek waiter behind the counter shook his finger amiably.
``And Ken Starr is going to subpoena it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OLDIE BUT GOODIE (Is This Dirty?) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A father said, `Son, the object of dating is to SCORE! And to do
that, you have to give the woman something. So when you pick up
your date later, make sure you have some flowers or chocolates to
give her. Girls go crazy over that stuff. The more you give, the
more you get!`
</P>
<P>
   So, he showed up with flowers AND chocolates.
</P>
<P>
   She was very flattered and pleased, and she rewarded him with a
long,
</P>
<P>
   passionate kiss.
</P>
<P>
   After the kiss, he turned and bolted for the door.
</P>
<P>
   `Oh! I'm sorry,` she said. `I didn't mean to scare you away.`
</P>
<P>
   `You didn't!` he replied. `I'm going out to get you some
jewelry!`
</P>
<P>
