<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9087 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      12-28 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PREPOSTEROUS PLANNING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE SULPHUR SPRINGS, W.Va. _ The darkling countryside was
eerie and foreboding as it spread before travelers taking a
six-hour train trip from Washington into the chilly, snow-covered
mountains of West Virginia at Christmas time.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of miles of neat, well-kept houses were deserted,
lifeless _ no children played in the yards, no illumination framed
bleak windows, no holiday decorations twinkled with colored lights,
no welcoming smoke rose from chimneys, no cars moved on the roads.
A winter ice storm had downed electric lines and wiped out power to
nearly 300,000 homes, where occupants fled the unpleasant
consequences of several cold days unable to cook, light rooms, use
hot water, heat their homes or generally function normally.
</P>
<P>
   Forty years ago, the nation was awash in grim predictions of a
similar gray and silent landscape on the fringes of an atomic-blast
epicenter, a nuclear winter produced by widespread radioactive
fallout. At the peak of the Cold War with the Soviet Union, the
prime target was expected to be the nation's capital, turning our
historic seat of government to rubble and making neighboring
regions uninhabitable.
</P>
<P>
   A relatively minor nuclear threat still exists today, but few
people worry about it beyond those officials whose duty it is to
anticipate dire possibilities. One place, however, where it is
still taken seriously is the Greenbrier here in the West Virginia
mountains, a fabulous world-class resort.
</P>
<P>
   But the Greenbrier isn't frightened. It is making money off
public curiosity, charging its guests to view a massive concrete
tribute to the folly of bureaucratic efforts to imagine the
unimaginable. Since the once-secret structure's 1995 opening,
85,000 people have had a look.
</P>
<P>
   Underneath the Greenbrier in the late 1950s the federal
government built an enormous bomb-proof bunker meant to house
members of Congress, favored staffers and perhaps the vice
president, while the rest of us were being incinerated. There are
other such bunkers near Washington for the president, the judiciary
and other government officials _ elaborately protected sites whose
existence has never been fully acknowledged and whose current
status is unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Only once, as President John Kennedy and Soviet leader Nikita
Khrushchev engaged in a test of wills during the 1962 Cuban missile
crisis, did the hidden bomb shelters came close to actually being
readied for immediate use. I know this to be true: I was the Hearst
White House correspondent at the time and was told how I would be
alerted to join an exodus to one of the bunkers.
</P>
<P>
   The Greenbrier hideaway has been fully deactivated and restored
to its full 1950s glory. The Dwight Eisenhower administration went
to a lot of trouble and taxpayer expense to develop it. As a stolid
military-style structure, it is impressive. As a practical way for
more than 1,000 of the governing elite to escape nuclear disaster,
it is absurd.
</P>
<P>
   The assumption was that Washington would have plenty of advance
warning of any pending Soviet nuclear strike: The Kremlin leader
was supposed to call the president and announce, ``Ike, my friend,
we bomb in 26 hours. Empty your buildings. Best wishes.''
</P>
<P>
   If the strike were a surprise, nobody in the city would be left
to escape into the mountains, or have the means to do so. At the
airport, the planes would be cinders. The roads would be
impassable, the cars nonexistent or malfunctioning. It's too far to
walk. The mountain air at the Greenbrier might be uncontaminated,
but you still had to get there.
</P>
<P>
   Those to be saved were supposed to be easily rounded up rather
than out of touch at a movie. It was assumed they could manage
through traffic jams to reach a Washington airport where planes
would be available and ready to fly.
</P>
<P>
   And they would have been ordered to leave their families behind.
Imagine any decent father or mother doing that!
</P>
<P>
   Once at the Greenbrier bunker, lawmakers, with all those
inflated congressional egos, were supposed to take their marching
orders from minor civil defense bureaucrats they considered beneath
them in normal life. The legislators were supposed to sleep en
masse in prison-style tin bunkbeds, lined up not by seniority but
by bureaucratic whim. Imagine Sens. Jesse Helms and Paul Wellstone
stretched out side-by-side! Would they punch each other out in
their sleep?
</P>
<P>
   A section was set up for radio communication to whatever was
left of the outside world. A government in exile is no good if no
one knows it exists. But who would be out there to receive a
message?
</P>
<P>
   And how could power lines that break in a cold snap possibly
survive the heat of a nuclear blast, even on the periphery?
</P>
<P>
   The bunker had a self-contained power plant, a 60-day stockpile
of packaged food, a kitchen and dining room, hospital,
message-processing facilities, waste-disposal system, briefing
rooms and a dental operating room. But its functioning was
dependent on a lack of interference from outside conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Relatively comfortable motel-style rooms were meant to
accommodate the Senate majority leader and House speaker, but
there's nothing but the crowded bunk room for the leaders of the
congressional minority or the committee chairs. Bad idea.
</P>
<P>
   There is no prison, but in recognition that these intimate
arrangements might drive some people mad, a supply of straitjackets
was on hand. But who would bell those particular cranky cats?
</P>
<P>
   In those days of Cold War doomsday terror, this unworkable
project was called ``continuity of government.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the Greenbrier wants to turn the exposed bunker into a
peacetime amusement _ a gambling casino. It would be a fitting
adaptation for an installation grounded in fantasy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
