<HEADLINE>
LITERARY PARIS 
RUGBY IN BRITAIN AND FRANCE 
INDONESIAN AIR
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Jan. 3) 
(mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I will be going to Paris and would appreciate information on
the location of the salon that Natalie Clifford Barney had there
earlier in this century. Is the salon or studio a place that can be
visited?
</P>
<P>
   Maria Hopewell, Dallas
</P>
<P>
   A. It was at 20 Rue Jacob, in the sixth arrondissement, that
Barney, an American expatriate and writer, conducted a salon every
Friday, attracting a galaxy of literary and intellectual lights.
Among them were Djuna Barnes, Sylvia Beach, Colette, Hilda
Doolittle, Janet Flanner, Andre Gide, Gertrude Stein and William
Carlos Williams.
</P>
<P>
   The salon met for more than 50 years (except during the two
world wars) until about the early 1960s, according to Karla Jay,
director of Women's and Gender Studies at Pace University in New
York. The Rue Jacob building, near the Place Furstenburg, is
landmarked but not open to the public. In the garden there's a
small temple, with Doric columns, that bears the inscription ``A
l'Amitie'' (``To Friendship'').
</P>
<P>
   Born to an Ohio family of great wealth, Barney moved to Paris as
a student and pursued her interest in French culture, writing
primarily in French. She died in 1972 and is buried in the ninth
division of the Passy cemetery. Also buried at Passy is Renee
Vivien, an expatriate poet from Britain who was among Barney's
loves. Another was Romaine Brooks, whose paintings include some of
Barney.
</P>
<P>
   The sixth arrondissement is rich in literary connections. If you
set out on your own, you will find the maps and descriptions in
Noel Riley Fitch's ``Walks in Hemingway's Paris'' valuable. (It was
reissued by St. Martin's Press in 1997 and is $10.95.) If you
prefer a guided tour, one possibility is Bohemian Paris, run by
Siren's Song Tours, 5 Rue du Parc, 93389 Pierrefitte-sur-Seine,
France; (33-1) 48.26.62.15, fax (33-1) 48.21.41.69. Web site:
www.onecity.com/paris.
</P>
<P>
   The tours, conducted by Gentry Lane, are available daily by
appointment. They take about two and a half hours, cover a mile and
a half on the Left Bank and are limited to six people. On the
itinerary are cafes frequented by Hemingway and Modigliani, the
residences of Modigliani, the composer George Antheil and James
Joyce, and the studios of Man Ray, Picasso and Brassai. Cost: $36
each, at 5.5 francs to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   By way of background, you may want to read Shari Benstock's
``Women of the Left Bank: Paris, 1900-1940'' (University of Texas
Press) and Ms. Jay's book ``The Amazon and the Page: Natalie
Clifford Barney and Renee Vivien'' (Indiana University Press). A
site on the Internet devoted to Barney and her era _ run by Paula
DiTallo, who describes herself as an Atlanta software engineer with
a love for literature _ is
home.sprynet.com/sprynet/ditallop/natalieb.htm.
</P>
<P>
   Rugby World Cup
</P>
<P>
   Q. We would like to attend the Rugby World Cup this year. How
can we get tickets, especially to the championship matches, and do
you have suggestions for lodging? Is there hooliganism as there is
at soccer matches?
</P>
<P>
   _ Andrew Schiavoni, Bronx, N.Y. &QR;
</P>
<P>
   A. Competing in the Rugby World Cup, scheduled to be played in
Britain and France from Oct. 1 to Nov. 6, are 20 teams divided into
five groups. The official source for tour packages is Gullivers
Sports Travel, which takes the minimalist approach: Fans handle
their own air travel.
</P>
<P>
   The closer the date of the final games, the more nights of
accommodation one must buy. So fans who want to follow the initial
progress of a single team, or what is called ``follow the flag,''
get two nights' lodging. The cost, $695 to $895, is based on double
occupancy and includes two breakfasts; a seat at the opening game
and ceremonies on Oct. 1 at the new 72,500-seat Millennium Stadium
in Cardiff, and seats at three games played by a single team.
</P>
<P>
   A package that offers a ticket to the quarterfinal in Paris or
Edinburgh is $699 to $799. It includes three nights at a three-star
hotel and three breakfasts.
</P>
<P>
   Fans who want tickets to the last four games _ the two
semifinals, the playoff and the final _ get nine nights in London
at $3,245 to $4,895. The package covers breakfast daily and, except
for those choosing the economy level lodgings, bus transportation
to and from the games.
</P>
<P>
   Whichever package you choose, there is no guarantee as to the
category of ticket you get. Information: Gullivers Sports Travel,
973 Vale Terrace, Vista, Calif. 92084; (760) 941-7323, fax (760)
941-2997.
</P>
<P>
   A Rugby World Cup spectator's guide is available from the
British Tourist Authority by mail; call (800) 462-2748. It includes
tour suggestions plus a listing of places to stay and agencies
handling accommodations.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about rowdiness, Ed Hagerty, editor and publisher of Rugby
magazine, cited this adage: Rugby is a ruffians' game played by
gentlemen; soccer is a gentlemen's game played by ruffians. He
noted that after a game, competing teams socialized in what is
known as ``the third half.''
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia's Haze
</P>
<P>
   Q. We are considering a tour that will include Indonesia but are
concerned that it could be spoiled by haze from the forest fires.
Can you hazard a guess as to the chances of clear conditions in
February and March? And what about the outlook for Myanmar and
Thailand? _ John Hebard, Sutton, Vt.
</P>
<P>
   A. The drought of El Nino and the haze created by forest fires
are history _ for now, anyway. ``Definitely pack your umbrella,''
says Bill Patzert, a research oceanographer at the Jet Propulsion
Laboratory in Pasadena, Calif. He reports that there are no fires
and no smog over Indonesia or Southeast Asia; in fact, in December,
there were heavy rains. On average, Jakarta, for example, has 11.8
inches of rain in February and 8.6 in March.
</P>
<P>
   The Topex-Poseidon satellite, a French-American project,
measures the height of the sea surface. As the surface heats up,
the sea level rises, which in turn promotes conditions that produce
rainfall. That is exactly what is happening now: At year's end, the
sea level was 7.8 inches above normal in the western Pacific,
Patzert said.
</P>
<P>
   As for Myanmar and Thailand, a National Centers for
Environmental Prediction model suggests that temperatures may be a
bit higher than usual _ it's normally in the low 70s to low 90s in
Bangkok _ and that the precipitation will not differ from the norm,
which is eight-tenths of an inch in February and 1.4 inches in
March.
</P>
<P>
   _Paul Freireich
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
