<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9109 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKUBE-COLUMN29-COX     12-28 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKUBE-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Now as in 1929, Americans are preoccupied with sex
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Mr. Excitement _ that's what my kids call me _ will be
in bed early, as usual. New Year's Eve and I'm sacked out by 10:30,
a paperback Travis McGee mystery beside me on the big down
comforter. Let others ring in the new year; I'll miss the old one.
</P>
<P>
   I'll miss it for many things, but mainly all the sex.
</P>
<P>
   However you look at it, this has been one great year for sex.
Biggest in my lifetime. If it were wine, you could compare it to
the Bordeaux vintage of '47.
</P>
<P>
   Now we've about finished it off and you know what? We're going
to miss it.
</P>
<P>
   We're going to miss Monica and Bill and Ken and Bob Barr _ his
marquee value's not high enough for us to know him on a first-name
basis, with or without the mustache _ and the whole slimy cast. Oh,
there'll be the trial in the Senate, and there'll be testimony that
won't surprise us and sundry exhibits, one of which still hasn't
been sent to the dry cleaners.
</P>
<P>
   But we've seen the best of it. Next year, if not already, we'll
be asking, ``Is this really necessary?''
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, the question's been asked. It was asked almost 70
years ago, just as the good times were crashing down. Whatever else
1999 brings, we can expect edgy replays of the stock market
collapse in October 1929. But the fall of that year was notable in
a smaller way for something else: the publication of E.B. White and
James Thurber's little parody, ``Is Sex Necessary?''
</P>
<P>
   ``When Thurber and I concocted the book,'' White wrote 20 years
later, ``we were riding one of the many small waves that, taken all
together, created the turbulence of the 1920s. Those were unstable
years. The economy was blown up beyond reasonable dimensions, and
nerves were frazzled.''
</P>
<P>
   Sex was in the air, same as now, and it occurred to two young
writers _ unknown to anyone outside the still-infant New Yorker
magazine _ that Americans had a thing about it.
</P>
<P>
   You'll never get them to admit it, but it's the subject
Americans think about most. In a study sponsored by the American
Society of Newspaper Editors, 80 percent of respondents said they
``agree'' or ``strongly agree'' with the statement ``Journalists
chase sensational stories because they think it'll sell papers, not
because they think it's important news.''
</P>
<P>
   Fine, blame the messenger. But someone will have to explain a
federally appointed special prosecutor's spending tens of millions
of dollars investigating an Arkansas real estate deal and coming to
court with boxes and boxes of evidence having to do mostly with
oral sex.
</P>
<P>
   Blame the movies, blame television, blame Cosmo and every other
magazine with a bare-breasted woman on its cover. There's plenty to
go around. But when everyone has his full share, the fact remains
that Americans don't know what to do about sex. The Puritan side of
their makeup looks upon it with a cold eye, while their prurient
side privately wonders what it is.
</P>
<P>
   It was no different in White and Thurber's day. ``I think we
somehow managed, simultaneously, to arrive at the conclusion that
(to borrow a phrase from Wolcott Gibbs) the heavy writers had got
sex down and were breaking its arms. We were determined that sex
should retain its high spirits.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Is Sex Necessary?'' was reissued in paperback this year, with
Thurber's inimitable line drawings still fresh and funny and a
subtitle that retains its parodic point: ``Or, Why You Feel the Way
You Do.''
</P>
<P>
   It was meant as a spoof on medical books of the day, with their
basso profundo omniscience, but now the joke's on us. We know more
and more about the biological aspects of sex, and less and less
about love. We explain more than we experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Understanding the principles of passion,'' White and Thurber
wrote, ``is like knowing how to drive a car; once mastered, all is
smoothed out; no more does one experience the feeling of perilous
adventure, the misgivings, the diverting little hesitancies, the
wrong turns, the false starts, the glorious insecurity. All is
smoothed out, and all, so to speak, is lost.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's where we are as one year folds into another, lost in
a quagmire we neither understand nor enjoy. We'd like to believe
it's only about an adulterous president and a frisky intern, and so
limit it in time and space. We'd like to believe it's about a
voyeuristic prosecutor, a Peeping Tom with power to subpoena.
</P>
<P>
   We'd like to believe it's about anyone but us. Here's a bet:
This time next year, we'll still be talking about sex. Not in the
White House, maybe, but somewhere. The stock market may have
crashed, or at least taken a bad fall, but sex will still sell. We
buy it and buy it, and wonder later why we bought so much.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: mskube(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
