<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9154 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GA-RURALHOSPITALS-COX     12-28 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-RURALHOSPITALS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rural facilities plagued by deteriorating financial stability
 &HT;    By Andy Miller
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Bacon County Hospital in Alma, Ga., is living on the
financial edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we are operating on three days' cash flow,'' says
Cindy Turner, who doubles as the chief financial officer and chief
operating officer for the 50-bed rural hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital, with annual revenue of about $10 million, has lost
money the last three years. A prime factor: cuts in hospital
payments by the Medicare and Medicaid programs, which account for
about 80 percent of Bacon County Hospital's care. And for the few
patients with private insurance, their employers are demanding big
discounts from the hospital, Turner says.
</P>
<P>
   Now another threat looms. The agency that runs the federal-state
Medicaid program has proposed lowering payments to hospital-based
nursing homes. Bacon County Hospital has such a facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any cut in reimbursement would impact us tremendously,''
Turner says wearily.
</P>
<P>
   In dealing with red ink, though, Bacon County has plenty of
company. Statistics compiled by HomeTown Health, a rural hospital
association, show that 21 rural facilities have lost money in three
straight years.
</P>
<P>
   Another 17 have been unprofitable two of the three years,
according to HomeTown Health, which bases its figures on state
hospital survey data. Thirteen more lost money in one of the three
years.
</P>
<P>
   The main financial damage lies south of metro Atlanta,
particularly in the southeastern part of the state.
</P>
<P>
   The plight of rural hospitals erupted as a major issue in the
1998 General Assembly. Lawmakers pushed to equalize rates paid by
Medicaid to both urban and rural hospitals for the same medical
procedure. And they passed a bill to help rural facilities join
managed-care networks.
</P>
<P>
   Still, rural hospitals again are expected to take a high profile
in the upcoming Legislature. Besides the proposed nursing-home cut,
measures likely will surface to give rural facilities more
financial flexibility. And Gov.-elect Roy Barnes has urged that the
state's $4.8 billion tobacco settlement create a fund that targets
rural hospitals, along with Medicaid reimbursement.
</P>
<P>
   But for the 21 hospitals on the critical list, more help is
needed, says Jimmy Lewis, chief executive officer of HomeTown
Health.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have no reserves; they have no cash,'' Lewis says. ``Many
of these hospitals have a (daily patient) census of two, four, six
or 10.''
</P>
<P>
   A hospital shutdown would devastate a local community, experts
insist. The presence of health care services is a crucial
ingredient to a rural community's ability to attract and keep
industry. If a hospital shuts down, tax bases, jobs and even
populations can evaporate. Many rural areas that lack up-to-date
facilities often struggle to recruit doctors.
</P>
<P>
   ``These little hospitals are needed out here,'' says Buck
Benton, CEO of the struggling Minnie G. Boswell Memorial Hospital
in Greensboro. ``When you lose your hospital, you lose your ability
to (attract) industry and create jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a hospital is the leading employer in many
counties, or, as in Bacon County, the No. 2 employer.
</P>
<P>
   Problems in access to care can produce disturbing health
statistics. South Georgia, in fact, suffers from alarming rates of
infant mortality, low-birthweight babies, and cardiovascular and
cancer deaths.
</P>
<P>
   If the negative trends continue, ``We can write a health care
scenario in southeast Georgia that would resemble that of a Third
World country,'' Lewis says.
</P>
<P>
   With rural areas having a high level of Medicare and Medicaid
patients, recent government cost-cutting has left scars. The
federal Medicare program for the elderly, for example, is
delivering $1 billion in cuts to Georgia hospitals over five years,
according to GHA, an association of Georgia hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   And reductions in the Medicaid program, which serves low-income
residents, have amounted to $100 million for Georgia hospitals over
the past three years, GHA adds.
</P>
<P>
   If hospital cuts continue, says state Sen. Jack Hill
(D-Reidsville), who has chaired several legislative hearings on
rural hospitals this year: ``We could be looking at the demise of
20 to 40 hospitals. There's almost no tomorrow for them.''
</P>
<P>
   The common ingredients in their financial predicaments, Hill
says, include:
</P>
<P>
   _ A high percentage of Medicare and Medicaid patients.
</P>
<P>
   _ Low numbers of privately insured patients.
</P>
<P>
   _ An inability to modernize equipment.
</P>
<P>
   _ Difficulty in recruiting physicians.
</P>
<P>
   _ Losing hundreds of thousands of dollars on patients who can't
or don't pay.
</P>
<P>
   Another setback, Hill says, could be the proposed Medicaid
reduction in the rates for hospital-based nursing homes, to the
level of free-standing nursing facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Many rural facilities have such nursing homes. Holly Snow of GHA
notes that hospital-based facilities treat sicker patients than
other nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   The nursing home at Effingham Hospital is one of the few nursing
homes in the area that take ventilator patients, says Scott
Burnette, CEO of the Springfield, Ga., hospital.
</P>
<P>
   A cut, he said, ''would eliminate our ability to take that type
of patient.''
</P>
<P>
   The hospital has lost money three straight years, but its
financial health is improving this year, Burnette says. Still, the
facility constantly fights a patient exodus to Savannah hospitals,
a 45-minute drive away.
</P>
<P>
   With costs rising and fewer patients requiring hospital care,
Monroe County Hospital finds itself in the same unprofitable
predicament. Its administrator, Buzz Tanner, concludes:
</P>
<P>
   ``If the state is unable to help small hospitals somehow, I'd
guess that 50 percent of them will go belly up in the next five
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Andy Miller writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
