</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBAFEAT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NBA lockout pits some players on other side of strike line
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Outside, Monday morning has come wet and nasty, but
inside the gymnasium at Life University the pace is slow, relaxed
and easy as a summer's day for small groups of athletes who have
little to do, no place to go and are in no hurry to get there.
</P>
<P>
   While young Hawks guard Ed Gray shoots at the near end of the
court and his father, Ed Sr., of Riverside, Calif., records with a
video camera, Toronto's Kevin Willis demonstrates his hook shot 80
feet away.
</P>
<P>
   Track athletes work on wind sprints under a coach's supervision
at the far side, while a high school freshman, Alexander Stevenson,
works on his free throws.
</P>
<P>
   Life varsity player Ron Glover watches from a chair, his right
hand in a cast.
</P>
<P>
   And the Hawks' Dikembe Mutombo becomes engaged in passionate
discussion with NBA free agent Ivano Newbill, his ex-teammate,
about the stalled negotiations that have the NBA season on hold.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the scene at Life, where many NBA players are fearing
a season-long death.
</P>
<P>
   Mutombo, a member of the NBA Players Association's negotiating
committee, is angry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am also making a sacrifice,'' he tells Newbill. ``We (all
the board members) are making this sacrifice for the next
generation of players. We've made our money. We've saved our money.
Now we must help those players to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Newbill, a former Georgia Tech player, doesn't buy it. He's
agitated. ``I'm a three-year guy,'' he said. ``I haven't made my
money. I need to play. A lot of guys need to play. But I read in
the paper you're giving up on the season, and I can't believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mutombo argues that David Stern has given the players no choice
in the matter. He disputes Stern's ``final offer,'' and argues that
the NBA commissioner's Jan. 7 ``drop-dead'' date is disingenuous.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Mutombo will miss his fourth scheduled pay check
of the season, at a cost to date of more than $4 million. He says
he is aware that that money, and any money lost this season, never
can be recouped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day, I sit down with my wife (Rose) and I tell her,
'Honey this is how much money we've lost today,''' Mutombo says.
This accounting is instructive, ``because that way we know exactly
how much we have.''
</P>
<P>
   Newbill, a minimum-salary player, has taken a beating at his own
level. A third of a season is lost, and it's probably too late to
play in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be 20 jobs over there, and how many guys will want
them if the season's over?'' he asks. ``If I had any idea this was
going to go this long, I would have enrolled in graduate school. I
could have completed the first quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   Mutombo pulls out a sheaf of pages bound in plastic. It is the
NBA's ``final'' offer from a few weeks ago. He holds up a list of
improvements the league presented to the union at a Sunday meeting
in Denver. He tells Newbill there will be another final offer from
the league.
</P>
<P>
   Newbill, lips pursed, shakes his head in frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Mutombo begins getting ready for play. ``I came here to play
some basketball,'' he says while walking onto the court where
Willis embraces him, then tugs him over to a couple of folding
chairs for another impassioned discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Willis has broken ranks publicly with union leadership, calling
for a secret vote of membership on the NBA's new offers.
</P>
<P>
   There is word that agent Norman Blass is urging a players'
revolt. Blass, the agent for Hawks guard Mookie Blaylock, said
Monday that he has sent letters league-wide asking players to vote
their pocketbooks.
</P>
<P>
   Newbill wants to speak to Blaylock, but he doesn't have his
telephone number.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wouldn't do you no good to have it; he don't answer the
phone,'' the younger Gray says. Newbill is aggravated. ``I been
here since 8,'' he says, glancing at a clock that reads 11:45 a.m.
``Ty (Corbin) is in South Carolina, Steve (Smith) took his wife to
Michigan. . . . Hey, we need to play.''
</P>
<P>
   At the far end, Mutombo and Willis end their intense labor
discussion and finally take the court for a game.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Newbill is sour. ``Nobody had their heart in it,'' he
said. ``We're 10 days away from the end of the season. This is
terrible, and nobody's doing anything about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Denberg writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
