<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reeves to be involved in pre-playoff planning
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta Falcons coach Dan Reeves, who went to team
headquarters Monday, said he will participate part-time this week
in preparation for a home playoff game Jan. 9, and he plans to be
at that game.
</P>
<P>
   However, Reeves and the team internist, Dr. Charlie Harrison,
are not sure whether the 54-year-old coach will return to the
sideline that quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves, 54, had quadruple heart bypass surgery Dec. 14. After
being released Dec. 18, he was re-admitted Dec. 20 with an
irregular heartbeat but was released again Dec. 24.
</P>
<P>
   He arrived at the team workout facility in Suwanee on Monday
just before regularly scheduled 2 p.m. meetings. The coach quickly
congratulated players and coaches, and headed for his first workout
_ a date with a treadmill _ since surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel better,'' he said. ``I got my physical this morning,
and everything so far looks good. I'll probably be out here every
day this week, seeing what my energy level allows me to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be at the stadium somewhere (for the playoff game). I
don't want to get in the way of our football team; they're doing a
great job without me.''
</P>
<P>
   Rich Brooks, the assistant head coach and defensive coordinator
who has served as interim coach in Reeves' absence, will continue
setting practice schedules and running meetings this week.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves will be around, however. He planned on Monday to review
film of Dallas (10-6), Green Bay (11-5) and San Francisco (12-4),
all potential playoff opponents for the Falcons (14-2) on Jan. 9.
He also will attend practice Wednesday and Thursday, unless he's
too tired.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, Reeves seems likely to be back in charge, but he
won't put in the typical 60-plus hours at work.
</P>
<P>
   One concern about being on the sideline for the game would be
that if Reeves got hit and cut, the blood-thinning medication he's
taking could lead to excessive bleeding.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not the safest place to be,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison said Reeves is back on track for a normal recuperation,
after a setback experienced by 10 percent to 30 percent of all
bypass patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``This week, he'll gain strength (by working out),'' Harrison
said. ``He's looking great. It's a good thing the team has (a bye).
They'll . . . be off Friday, Saturday and Sunday. He can help with
the game plan. We'll make the decision about what he can do (on
game day) when I see him next Monday.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
