<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUMMER-RESOLUTIONS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Finally, easy-to-keep resolutions
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Instead of plunging into impossible vows that can't be
kept, a few easy resolutions for 1999. This annual ritual doesn't
have to be a chore, if you pick your promises carefully.
</P>
<P>
   I hereby resolve:
</P>
<P>
   _ Not to watch any sport described as extreme, ultra or radical.
As soon as they break out a ramp or a board of any kind, I'm outta
there.
</P>
<P>
   _ Never to do the ''Dirty Bird'' in public, no matter how
well-served I've been. Regardless of how a middle-aged white guy
may try, it's still going to look like he just mistook flaming
sterno for his roll-on deodorant.
</P>
<P>
   _ Never to fall into SportsCenter speak and refer to a home run
as ''Booo-Yeahhh,'' or ''Gyot-It,'' or ''I am the king of the
diamond. Let there be a postgame feast in my honor. Me and my
followers will feast on the finest of wines and cheeses.'' It is
just a home run.
</P>
<P>
   _ Not to take up mahjong.
</P>
<P>
   _ Not to buy a used Maserati from an NBA player.
</P>
<P>
   _ Never to ask Bobby Cremins to be my investment broker. One day
flush, the next day flat broke _ who could stomach the ride?
</P>
<P>
   _ Never to use the ATM at a casino. That is one small step away
from borrowing the money from some guy nicknamed ''Mako.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Always to have at least one less demand than Roger Clemens and
one more friend than Albert Belle.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sometimes to overlook ego. It can be a good thing, too. Take
for example Jamal Anderson. On his touchdown run against Miami
Sunday, he began to celebrate 10 yards before the end zone,
dangling the ball in his left hand. Had he not been watching
himself run on the Georgia Dome video screen, he wouldn't have
noted the Dolphin defender who was closing fast, ready to slap the
ball free. But Anderson did see the big picture and switched the
ball to his right hand at the last second. He was actually saved by
narcissism.
</P>
<P>
   _ Occasionally to watch an NHL highlight or read a hockey story.
They keep insisting that it's coming to town next season and I've
really got to start caring. Put this in the same file with such
duties as flossing and getting an oil change.
</P>
<P>
   _ Never to confuse my son's Pony League baseball game with a
turning point in history.
</P>
<P>
   _ Never to spend more to play golf than the cost of a nice meal
out. Never to spend more to take the family to a professional
sporting event than to take them to the beach.
</P>
<P>
   _ Not to be named in a paternity suit.
</P>
<P>
   _ Not to refer to myself in the third person. Steve really hates
that. Steve thinks it very pretentious.
</P>
<P>
   _ Not to hang on the rim. Nor to show up the pitcher. Nor to
excessively celebrate a touchdown catch.
</P>
<P>
   _ Never to use androstenedione. I prefer to get my bulk the
old-fashioned way, one super-sized value meal at a time.
</P>
<P>
   _ Not to invite Bobby Knight over for an evening of
''Pictionary.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Not to pay any more attention to college football recruiting
than I do to soybean futures.
</P>
<P>
   _ Not to sign a deal with Nike to put a swoosh on my word
processor.
</P>
<P>
   _ Never to go anywhere without my restrictor plate securely
bolted in place.
</P>
<P>
   _ Not to ask any athlete after a crushing defeat, ''How does it
feel?''
</P>
<P>
   _ Never to forget that the good guys still outnumber the bad and
that sport is supposed to be more limerick than sermon.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Hummer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
