<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9162 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FREAKNIK-COX     12-28 1217
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREAKNIK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Return of Freaknik? Neither Atlanta nor celebrants making plans
yet
 &HT;    (ATTN: Florida, Texas editors.)
 &HT;    By Jennifer Ffrench-Parker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Freaknik, the street party Atlanta loves to hate, cost
the city more than $1 million in overtime pay to public safety
employees this year and next Spring's price tag for the event could
be as high.
</P>
<P>
   Early next month, Mayor Bill Campbell's office will name a 1999
Black College Spring Break Planning Committee, which in is expected
to try again to rein in the raucous celebration the city has been
trying to discourage for years.
</P>
<P>
   But controlling the event is expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Freaknik annually lures thousands of black college students to
Atlanta during the third weekend in April. According to figures
recently obtained from the city under the state Open Records Act,
last spring's Freaknik cost Atlanta more than $1.2 million in
overtime pay to police officers, firefighters and corrections
officers.
</P>
<P>
   Though costly, the city's efforts _ which include tough
enforcement of traffic offenses and more serious violations _ have
succeeded in reducing the crowds. Officials estimated last April's
attendance at a paltry 50,000, down from the peak of 200,000 in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of the overtime pay, about $1.1 million, went to police
officers. That's more than double the $497,000 paid for Freaknik in
1995, when the city paid fewer police officers, and took a gentler
approach to enforcing traffic and other violations. This year, the
city paid 1,624 officers, firefighters and corrections officers
overtime for 43,361 hours of extra work during the event. The
city's overtime Freaknik tab for police officers in 1996 was $944,
312, Atlanta police reported. In 1997, it was $956,057, according
to police. The mayor's office said, however, the city paid from
$650,000 to $720,000 in overtime to police officers both years.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 payments, authorized by special legislation passed by
City Council in May, were made instead of granting compensatory
time so that officers would stay on the job instead of taking time
off from work. Civilian employees who also worked overtime were
offered compensatory time instead.
</P>
<P>
   Next April 16-18, public safety employees will no doubt again
work thousands of hours of overtime for Freaknik, which routinely
generates complaints of loud music, public lewdness, drunkenness
and traffic gridlock.
</P>
<P>
   Early indications are that if they are paid overtime, it will
again be by way of special legislation. The mayor's budget,
currently before City Council, does not mention the event.
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Lee Morris, who heads the council's Finance
Committee, said no decision has been made, but the council's
preference is to again pay overtime to public safety employees
rather than have them take comp time.
</P>
<P>
   ``As shorthanded as we are, I would rather have police officers
working,'' Morris said.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Police Department has said it is at least 300
officers short of its authorized force of 1,874.
</P>
<P>
   Lee said funds to pay the workers would come from ``salary
savings'' built into the budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``We budget 100 percent of salaries for 100 percent of
authorized positions and we never fill all the vacancies,'' he
said. ``That's really where we get the salary savings that can pay
overtime.''
</P>
<P>
   DeWayne Martin, the mayor's chief of staff, said informal
conversations have started with some of the organizations and
people who served on the mayor's 1998 Black College Spring Break
Planning Committee.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of this year's Freaknik, the 1998 committee
recommended that the city discourage next year's Freaknik with
tough law enforcement and by not issuing permits for
Freaknik-related events or offering its support of any private
functions. However, an annual national job fair, sponsored by a
private company during Freaknik weekend, will continue to get city
support.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the official Freaknik website has not been
updated since last April and the Atlanta University Center's campus
buzz about Freaknik is that there is no buzz yet. Zaret Akande,
president of Spelman College student government, said students have
been preoccupied with the holidays. ``It just hasn't been an action
item yet,'' said Akande, a senior.
</P>
<P>
   But with Freaknik's adverse effect on the city's convention
business and other special events, hopes are high in Atlanta that
Florida's Daytona Beach and Galveston Island, Texas, will continue
to siphon off some of the throngs that normally descend on Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Daytona's Black College Reunion crowds swelled to
110,000, from the usual 50,000. On Galveston Island, last spring's
revelers numbered ``well over 200,000,'' up by 25 percent over
1997. Beach parties in both cities coincide with Atlanta's
Freaknik.
</P>
<P>
   On Galveston Island, 50 miles south of Houston, a committee that
includes the African-American Chamber of Commerce and a group of
black ministers is deep into planning for the 1999 Kappa Beach
Party Weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The 14-year-old event is organized by the Kappa Alpha Psi
Fraternity, but Robert Warren, director of the Galveston Island
Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau, said most who visit for the event
don't belong to the fraternity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Kappas have 6,000 to 8,000 members,'' Warren said. ``The
other 50,000 are followers.''
</P>
<P>
   The city was forced two years ago to begin controlling the event
as growing crowds of cruisers clogged the only two causeways to and
from the 32-mile long island.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very difficult event but we are trying to bring some
control to it and have a quality event,'' Warren said.
</P>
<P>
   Galveston Police Chief Kim Schoolcraft said last spring's event
was akin to ``semi-organized chaos,'' with nudity, alcohol
consumption and numerous arrests for disorderly conduct.
</P>
<P>
   But it was ``thankfully violence-free,'' she said. ``There were
no shootings, stabbings or assaults.''
</P>
<P>
   Daytona Beach's decade-old event was finally recognized by that
city this year, but was marred by the death of a black youth in a
gunfight and the shooting of four police officers. It also drew
widespread complaints, similar to those commonly made in Atlanta,
of traffic tie-ups, sex in public, and littering.
</P>
<P>
   In its aftermath, angry Daytona residents have been pressing the
city to discourage the event.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, no promoters have come forward seeking support
from the bureau, said Susan McLain, director of communications for
the Daytona Beach Area Convention and Visitors Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   ``We operate on applications, and we haven't received an
application yet, so there is nothing for us to act on,'' McLain
said. ``At this time, we are not doing anything to help it or
hinder it.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, Daytona Beach officials will have to soon join
Atlanta and Galveston in bracing for the massive parties headed to
their towns. ``We all seem to suffer the same with these events,''
said Warren, of the Galveston Island Convention and Visitors
Bureau. ``We have got to have some control. You can't just allow
people to come in an operate your city for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Ffrench-Parker writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
