<HEADER>
A9163 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OAK-COX     12-28 0380
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OAK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Legendary oak tree felled by storm
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Its branches created 100 feet of leafy canopy, its trunk was 65
inches wide. It was a century older than the United States, and
provided shade and a place to think for the likes of John D.
Rockefeller Jr. and Japanese Emperor Hirohito.
</P>
<P>
   But the Greak Oak at Colonial Williamsburg in Virginia succumbed
to the Christmas ice storm that hit portions of the South last
week. The 300-year-old tree was declared dead after its branches,
unable to support layers of heavy ice, came crashing to the ground.
All that remains is the trunk, which even before the storm was
mostly hollow and lifeless.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tree had not been doing well for years,'' said Jim
Bradley, public relations manager for Colonial Williamsburg. ``This
storm was essentially the death knell for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Virginia and other parts of the South continued to recover from
the storm Monday, which mostly meant waiting for the lights to come
on. At one point over the holidays, more than 600,000 customers in
Virginia, Alabama, Tennessee and Louisiana were without power.
Thousands still had no power Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Great Oak was older than Williamsburg, whose charter dates
back to 1699. So well-known and beloved was the oak that the staff
at Williamsburg is preparing an obituary for it.
</P>
<P>
   The tree became famous in 1926 when Rockefeller and the Rev.
William A. R. Goodwin sat under it and mapped out plans to restore
Williamsburg to its 18th-century appearance. Rockefeller spent part
of each year with his wife at Bassett Hall, a plantation on the
edge of Williamsburg and home to the Great Oak.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Rockefeller died in 1960, the citizens of Williamsburg
gathered under the oak for a memorial service,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   When Emperor Hirohito of Japan visited the U.S. in the 1970s, he
wanted to see the tree, and when he got there, he sat for a while
on a bench under the huge branches.
</P>
<P>
   What's left of the tree will live on in the form of seedlings
that have sprouted from its acorns, Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Rochell Konigsmark writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
