<DOCNO> NYT19981228.0333 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9165 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LLOYD-COLUMN-LADN     12-28 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LLOYD-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATEST BIZ BUZZWORD MORE THAN HYPE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Ken Lloyd _ a specialist in organizational behavior _ is a
columnist for the Los Angeles Daily News. His column moves Mondays
in the ``f'' financial news file. Send your questions to P.O. Box
260057, Encino, C A 91426 or by electronic mail to
LloydOnJobaol.com. Names will be withheld upon request.) 
By KEN LLOYD  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Question: At a recent meeting, the company
president said he is fully committed to implementing something
called ``knowledge management'' during the coming year. I'm not
sure what this means. Is it another buzzword, or is there something
to it? _ M.R.
</P>
<P>
   Answer: Knowledge management is not a buzzword, but it certainly
has been creating a great deal of buzz recently. Knowledge
management (often abbreviated as KM) means using today's computer
and online technologies to gather, track and, most importantly,
share a broad range of knowledge and information to help make an
organization and its employees more effective.
</P>
<P>
   KM can be used to monitor and document employee skills,
competencies and growth, and help a company carry out near- and
long-term planning. When employees have questions about projects,
programs, plans or just about any other work-related matter,
particularly those that call for some real expertise, KM can
provide the forum in which ideas can be shared and questions can be
answered.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, KM implies that employees are willing to share
their expertise. However, in some organizations, employees are
reluctant to do so. It is also not uncommon to find employees who
would rather work out a problem on their own, rather than seek help
from others. These are the kinds of matters that point to the
importance of addressing a company's culture as part of the
implementation of any KM plan.
</P>
<P>
   In order to have a knowledge management program that actually
manages to succeed, it should be accompanied by a healthy dose of
communication, training and incentives.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Every time I give one particular employee some positive
feedback, he responds with a wisecrack. I find this to be very
annoying. The obvious step is for me to stop praising him, but
that's not being fair. How can I deal with this? _ T.O.
</P>
<P>
   A: When a particular employee responds to a compliment with a
wisecrack, this is not a particularly wise thing to do. But you are
correct in assuming that it would be unfair for you to eliminate
positive feedback altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Your employee's reaction indicates that he is one of those
people who have a hard time accepting compliments. The underlying
reasons behind this type of reaction can range from basic modesty
and humility, to issues related to self-esteem, self-image and
self-confidence. You are not going to be able to change any of
these deep-seated factors. However, you may be able to change his
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Since this issue revolves around the issue of providing him with
feedback, the next time he responds to a compliment with a
wisecrack, give him some immediate feedback on this behavior. Ask
him if he is aware of what he is actually doing and let him know
that it is becoming increasingly difficult to praise him. Ask him
if there is anything he can do to change this behavior and follow
this by asking if he can make a commitment to do so.
</P>
<P>
   In the future, whenever you give him a compliment that is not
met with a wisecrack, be sure to compliment him on this as well.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We are getting a new manager in our department and I was
wondering about the kinds of things I can do to make a good
impression and start things on a positive note. _ G.B.
</P>
<P>
   A: First impressions are important, but ultimately your
manager's impression of you is going to be based on who you really
are and what you really can do.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most important first step in dealing with the new
manager is to be highly observant. Try to obtain a clear picture of
this manager's style, objectives, standards, expectations and
general mode of operations. With this in mind, try to make sure
that your behavior is in sync with his or hers. It can be very
helpful for the new manager to see that the two of you have a good
deal in common.
</P>
<P>
   You should also seek opportunities through which you can help
the new manager. It may be in terms of providing some needed
information, or it could be carrying out a project that he or she
would like to delegate. Let this manager see by your actions that
you are a person with high levels of energy, initiative, commitment
and drive.
</P>
<P>
   It is also important to avoid complaining, criticizing or making
negative comments about the company. If there are issues that are
causing dissatisfaction, try to present some suggestions as to the
ways to correct them.
</P>
<P>
   As time goes by, first impressions tend to become vague
impressions. It is far more important for you to be sure that the
quality and quantity of your work are excellent, as this will form
your manager's lasting impression of you.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
