<SLUG> BC-OCTUPLETS-UPDATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEVEN SURVIVING BABIES OF OCTUPLETS REMAIN IN CRITICAL CONDITION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CAROL CHRISTIAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The seven surviving babies of the octuplets born
earlier this month remained in critical condition Monday at Texas
Children's Hospital, doctors said.
</P>
<P>
   Their mother, Nkem Chukwu, was still resting at St. Luke's
Episcopal Hospital where she gave birth to children. Hospital
officials have not said when Chukwu might be released.
</P>
<P>
   The first baby, a girl, was born naturally Dec. 8 and the others
were born Dec. 20 by Caesarean section.
</P>
<P>
   The smallest baby _ a girl who was born fifth and whose name,
Chijindu Chidera, means ``God has my life'' _ died of heart and
lung failure at 3:23 a.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Of the surviving seven, four were breathing on their own and
were in stable condition at 9 a.m. Monday, the hospital reported.
No further update on the babies' condition was expected until this
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Breathing on their own Monday were, by nickname: Chidi, a girl,
born second; Echerem, a girl, born third; Chima, a girl, born
fourth, and Jioke, a boy, born seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Still on ventilators are Ebuka, a girl, born first; Ikem, a boy,
born sixth, and Gorom, a girl, born eighth, who had abdominal
surgery Saturday to repair an intestinal perforation.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Leonard Weisman, chief of Texas Children's Hospital's
Newborn Center, said Thursday that the babies would remain in
critical condition for many weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Chukwu and her husband, Iyke Louis Odobe, are naturalized
citizens from Nigeria. Each comes from families of eight children.
The names they chose for the octuplets reflect their heritage from
the Ibo people, one of the major ethnic groups in Nigeria. Each
child was given a formal name as well as a nickname. Chijindu
Chidera's nickname was Odera.
</P>
<P>
   The octuplets' parents, along with Chukwu's mother, visited the
babies for the first time Saturday evening about the time Odera's
condition began to deteriorate, according to a statement from Texas
Children's Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   As updates in the babies' condition are announced, they are
posted on Texas Children's Hospital's Worldwide Web site, which was
set up Dec. 20. The web site address is http://www.txchildrens.org
</P>
<P>
   The family has asked that donations be sent only to the
following address: The Chukwu Family Fund, c/o St. Luke's Episcopal
Hospital, 6900 Fannin, Suite 440, Houston, TX 77030. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-28-98 1848EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
