<HEADLINE>
3-D SPACE TRIPS AT CHICAGO MUSEUM 
VAN GOGH PACKAGES IN LOS ANGELES 
MAKING TIME IN COPENHAGEN
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Jan. 3) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the return to space by John Glenn and the start of
construction of the international space station has put you in the
mood for space travel, a new exhibition opening on Friday in
Chicago may be a good first stop. The Adler Planetarium and
Astronomy Museum's Sky Pavilion, a 60,000-square-foot wing,
contains four galleries, including an interactive 3-D theater that
simulates space travel.
</P>
<P>
   The first show, ``Journey to Infinity,'' will take visitors on a
trip to places they choose using keypads on each of the theater's
193 seats. Three computer systems are used to project
three-dimensional graphics on a 55-foot-diameter dome, giving the
sensation of flying past planets and stars.
</P>
<P>
   The system can vary with each show, as the visitors choose to go
to Jupiter, say, instead of Mars. When the audience decides what
the destination is (by ``voting'' on the keypad), one or more
members get to ``steer'' the spaceship for the group, again using
the keypads.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the theater, the Sky Pavilion offers a 3-D fly-through
of the Milky Way in the Ameritech Gallery; a computerized animated
look at the birth of the solar system in the Formations Theater;
and ``From the Night Sky to the Big Bang,'' a presentation that
deals with the history of cosmology and current theory in the
Pritzker Cosmology Gallery.
</P>
<P>
   The new wing also contains the Galileo cafe and the Shooting
Star gift shop. With the opening of the Sky Pavilion, the museum's
original 1930 building is being closed for renovation. It is
scheduled to reopen in October.
</P>
<P>
   The Adler Planetarium and Astronomy Museum is on the Museum
Campus on Lake Shore Drive, with the Field Museum and Shedd
Aquarium. The Adler is open from 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. Monday to
Thursday, until 9 p.m. on Friday and 6 p.m. on weekends. Admission:
$5, $4 for ages 65 and older and 17 and under. The Star Rider show
costs an additional $5. Through Jan. 12, there will be free
admission to the building, but not to the Star Rider show.
</P>
<P>
   Information: (312) 922-7827, fax (312) 322-2257 or
www.adlerplanetarium.org.
</P>
<P>
   Hotel Plus Van Gogh in Los Angeles
</P>
<P>
   Eight hotels in the Los Angeles area are offering packages with
passes to the exhibition ``Van Gogh's Van Goghs: Masterpieces from
the Van Gogh Museum, Amsterdam'' at the Los Angeles County Museum
of Art, on Wilshire Boulevard in West Los Angeles, between downtown
and the coast. The show of 70 paintings, now at the National
Gallery of Art in Washington, will be in Los Angeles from Jan. 17
through April 4 _ on a rare tour outside the Netherlands during the
expansion of the Van Gogh Museum.
</P>
<P>
   Admission to the exhibition is usually for a reserved date and
time of entry, but the passes that come with the packages may be
used at any hour of any day.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the museum passes, the packages include
accommodations for two for one night and a copy of the exhibition
catalog. Individual hotels may offer other features, such as
breakfast, dining room credits, half-price tickets for the Los
Angeles Philharmonic at the Los Angeles Music Center, or admission
to other museums; most offer reductions for additional nights.
</P>
<P>
   Packages are available at the Renaissance Los Angeles, $165 on
weekdays and $150 on weekends, (310) 337-2800; Westin Bonaventure,
$195, (213) 624-1000; Doubletree Santa Monica, $210, (310)
395-3332; Inter-Continental, $215 on weekdays, $185 weekends, (213)
617-3300; Sheraton Universal, $235 on weekdays, $220 weekends,
(818) 509-0888; Summit Hotel Bel-Air, $259, (310) 476-6571; Park
Hyatt Los Angeles, $289 on weekdays, $249 weekends, (310) 277-1234;
and Regent Beverly Wilshire, $350, (800) 427-4354. Weekday tickets
for the public are $17.50, $10 for students and anyone over 61, and
$5 ages 6 to 17; the corresponding weekend prices are $20, $15 and
$5.
</P>
<P>
   Information: (323) 857-6000 and on the Internet at
www.vangogh-la.com. Tickets can be bought through Ticketmaster,
(213) 462-2787, or at the museum after Jan. 10.
</P>
<P>
   New in Copenhagen: Train From the Plane
</P>
<P>
   There is now a faster and cheaper way to get to downtown
Copenhagen, Denmark, from the airport. Three times an hour, the Air
Rail train departs from its new terminal beneath Copenhagen
International Airport for the 10-minute ride to the Central Railway
Station. The trip costs about $2.50, at 6.8 kroner to $1. The same
ride in a taxi would cost about $18.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Rail Terminal is part of a project that includes the
Oresund bridge and tunnel for cars and trains, expected to open in
2000, linking Copenhagen with Malmo, Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the underground railway station, the airport
expansion includes a new Hilton hotel, also scheduled to open in
2000. Information is available from the Danish Tourist Board, (212)
885-9700.
</P>
</TEXT>
