<HEADLINE>
CLINTON DEFENDS MILITARY FORCE IN IRAQ 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton Monday staunchly defended the
latest American show of military force in Iraq, saying U.S.
warplanes fired back after being attacked by Iraqi missiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our pilots have the authority to protect themselves if they're
threatened or attacked. They took appropriate action today in
responding to Iraq's actions,'' said Clinton, speaking about the
incident before a Social Security event. ``They attacked because
they were attacked.''
</P>
<P>
   The incident occurred at about 1:30 p.m. Iraq time, or 5:30 a.m
EST in the skies near Mosul, more than 200 miles north of Baghdad,
according to Pentagon officials. After being targeted by radar and
attacked with surface-to-air missiles, the U.S. crews responded by
firing missiles of their own at the Iraqi air defense site.
</P>
<P>
   The president said that U.S. and British air crews were flying
over northern Iraq as part of their routine duties to enforce
no-fly zones in the northern and southern sectors of the country,
when they were fired upon.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon spokesmen said that all planes involved in the
operation and their crews returned to base safely.
</P>
<P>
   Iraqi spokesmen said that the U.S. missiles killed four soldiers
and injured seven others. The Iraqi News Agency reported that
defense forces ``almost certainly shot down an enemy plane.''
</P>
<P>
   Iraq's ambassador to the United Nations dismissed U.S. arguments
that the pilots were acting in self-defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (the U.S.) said they acted in their own defense as if
Texas or Florida was attacked,'' said Ambassador Nizar Hamdoon.
``Iraq has always said that there is no way that it could recognize
the no-fly zones. They are illegal and they have not been
established by United Nations resolutions.''
</P>
<P>
   The military skirmish is the first since the United States and
Britain engaged in an air assault on Iraq from Dec. 16-20 in an
effort to destroy sites suspect of containing weapons of mass
destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Since the bombings, Iraqi dictator Saddam Hussein has made
increasingly belligerent comments aimed at the United States and
has refused to let U.N. weapons inspectors back into the country.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that enforcing the no-fly zones was essential to
the U.S. policy of containing Saddam.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we effectively control the skies over much of a Iraq,
Saddam has been unable to use air power to repress his own people
or to lash out again at his neighbors,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   The northern no-fly zone, extending above the 36th parallel, has
been in effect since the end of the Gulf War in 1991, and was
designed to protect Kurdish rebels from attacks by Saddam's forces.
</P>
<P>
   Details of Monday's incidents were sketchy and the Pentagon did
not hold any official briefings on the engagement.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press reported that at least three SAMs were
fired at U.S. aircraft and that the pilots retaliated by firing
HARM anti-radar missiles at the air defense site.
</P>
<P>
   One report indicated that additional aircraft may have been sent
to the target for bombing runs, and U.S. officials told AP there
were at least two direct hits on Iraqi air defense sites.
</P>
<P>
   A Pentagon spokesman said there was no damage to the U.S.
aircraft, which included F-15s and EA-6B planes, or to two British
tankers that were along to refuel the warplanes.
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman said the damage to Iraqi military installations
was still being assessed. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
