<TEXT>
<P>
   (pr) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Tuesday, Dec. 29. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   CAMBODIA-DEFECTORS (Phnom Penh, Cambodia) _ Defying
international pressure to put top leaders of the Khmer Rouge on
trial, Prime Minister Hun Sen says that they should be welcomed
``with bouquets of flowers, not with prisons and handcuffs.'' By
Seth Mydans. 1,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   TV-RACE (Undated) _ Prime-time television has rarely been as
racially divided as it is today, both in terms of casts and
audiences, a fact most striking in network television's dominant
form of entertainment, comedy. Networks, under enormous pressure to
maximize dwindling profits, have been focusing on the more numerous
and generally more affluent white households that advertisers
prefer. By James Sterngold. With graphic and sidebar,
TV-RACE-HISTORY. 2,600 words.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-U.S. (Washington) _ U.S. fighter jets patrolling northern
Iraq attack an Iraqi missile battery after coming under fire in
what appeared to be an attempt to provoke a new confrontation with
the United States, the Clinton administration said. By Steven Lee
Myers.
</P>
<P>
   With: IRAQ-U.N.
</P>
<P>
   HOLIDAY-SHOPPING (New York) _ When the first reports on holiday
season sales for Internet retailers were released, the results were
huge. The increases came despite glitches that forced consumers to
suffer indignities like being denied access to retailers' Web sites
and holiday gifts that did not arrive on time. The most optimistic
estimates of holiday sales came from a subsidiary of InterPublic
Group of Cos., whose survey of 1,000 consumers suggested that
online sales would reach $5 billion. By Leslie Kaufman and Saul
Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-MINISTER-PROFILE (Bonn) _ From the neck down, the German
interior minister, Otto Schily, is very much the bourgeois
gentleman. But look up at the mischievous eyes and unruly hair, and
some of the contradictions of the man and his country begin to come
into focus. The official who represents law and order in this most
ordered of nations, is an iconoclast: a defender of the
revolutionary Red Army Faction during the 1960s, celebrated lawyer
in the 1970s, founder of the environmentalist Green Party in the
1980s, tough Social Democrat in the 1990s and bon vivant with a
love for Tuscany throughout. By Roger Cohen. 1,500 words.
</P>
<P>
   ADOPTION-SIBLINGS (Boston) _ Lawyers in a Massachusetts adoption
case have asked the Supreme Court to use it to declare a new
national rule that brothers and sisters have a constitutional right
to be together. Their argument, family law experts say, is at the
forefront of a growing legal movement that is pressing to change
the focus in custody disputes from the rights of adults to the
rights of children. By William Glaberson. With photo. 1,800 words.
</P>
<P>
   DENVER-DOWNTOWN (Denver) _ The return to downtown living in
eastern cities is well-known but that it is happening in the
automobile-loving cities of the West is part of a new trend that is
expected to take hold over the next few years. One of the cities
viewed by experts as a model is Denver, where a burst of downtown
development is aimed at the returning residents, largely baby
boomers whose kids have grown and left home. By James Brooke. With
map and photo. 1,800 words.
</P>
<P>
   Reefer:
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH (Washington) _ He has the impeachment vote he sought
from the House. Now Rep. Henry Hyde is in search of a strategy for
an impeachment trial in the Senate. On Tuesday, Hyde and the 12
Republican congressmen he picked to manage President Clinton's
Senate trial will meet for the first time since the historic House
vote on Dec. 19 to begin mapping out the prosecution's game plan.
By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
