<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-YEAR-2TAKES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM `NYPD BLUE' TO `SIN CITY,' THE YEAR'S BEST 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1998, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Picking the best of 1998 is a little like reliving the laughs in
``Our American Cousin,'' the play the Lincolns attended on (set
ital)that(end ital) night.
</P>
<P>
   I mean, the central point of the year in television is that it
was a lousy year for television. But good work still got done, and
there's no sense penalizing those who did it for the sins of the
real culprits.
</P>
<P>
   Most Top 10 lists for 1998 include, and maybe even begin with,
Tom Hanks' Emmy champion, ``From the Earth to the Moon,'' which ran
on HBO. Mine doesn't. I thought there was plenty to admire about
Hanks' space saga, but it was a stupefyingly slow creep skyward.
</P>
<P>
   Also missing is the year's most hyped entertainment event, the
``Seinfeld'' finale. I liked the way ``Seinfeld'' bowed out by
putting itself on trial. But Top 10? Huh-uh.
</P>
<P>
   Here's my own Top 10 list, in no particular order. And remember,
there's no point doing the conniption thing. It's only TV.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Lateline.'' For some reason, television viewers never have
liked television spoofs of television itself, unless you count the
old SCTV cult. This NBC series didn't spring to the front of the
Nielsen ratings, either, though it has earned a second shot
beginning January 6.
</P>
<P>
   Series creator Al Franken stars as the schlemiel Al Freundlich,
a spectacularly uncharismatic correspondent for a
``Nightline''-type news program. Word is, Franken's character will
be de-emphasized when ``Lateline'' returns.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Sports Night.'' For some reason, television viewers never
have liked television spoofs of tel ... Oops, sorry.
</P>
<P>
   But this fall series from ABC, no better than so-so when it
premiered, gathered steam through the fall and is now regarded as a
potential classic, if only it can survive for a second season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sports Night'' mocks ESPN's signature show ``SportsCenter,''
but it's not just for laughs. The show is the latest incarnation of
the TV dramedy _ half comedy, half drama and all risky.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Africans in America: America's Journey Through Slavery.''
The six-hour PBS series showed how indentured servitude evolved
into race-based slavery and haunted a nation ... well, forever.
Executive producer Orlando Bagwell amply documented his primary
point and never strayed far from it. Slavery was barbaric and, from
the beginning, was accompanied by tension and resistance.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``An Evening With the Rat Pack.'' Frank Sinatra died this
year, amid a flurry of nostalgia for his Rat Pack's boozy high
times. For one thing, there was a failed HBO movie. But the TV Land
cable channel, a kid brother in the MTV and Nickelodeon family,
found the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   Never before seen nationally, ``An Evening With the Rat Pack''
was a 1965 charity concert from St. Louis with Sinatra, Dean
Martin, Sammy Davis Jr. and, filling in as host, a young Johnny
Carson. It was the legends in perfect form. Sinatra, swinging
through ``I've Got You Under My Skin,'' ``Luck Be a Lady'' and
``You Make Me Feel So Young.'' Martin, treating his own hit songs
like yesterday's refuse. Davis, talented but helplessly over the
top.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Penn &AMP; Teller's Sin City Spectacular.'' Admittedly, my
oddball choice. But this FX cable series from Las Vegas is more
(set ital)alive(end ital) than 98 percent of the filler material on
network prime time.
</P>
<P>
   A sly mixture of smarts and tacky excess, the show also was a
refreshing throwback to TV's supposedly extinct variety format. The
genre has been dead so long that Penn and Teller make it seem
newborn. Maybe when you get right down to it, though, I was won
over by the appearance of Irving, the talking dog, in the show's
premiere.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Shot Through the Heart.'' This HBO movie was the astonishing
true story of best friends who found themselves on opposite sides
of the deadly sniper war in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Unfettered by advertisers and almost totally immune from the
tyranny of ratings, HBO is free to make its movies right. Often
enough, it does.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, actors Linus Roache and Vincent Perez were cast
because they were right for the roles, not because of any inherent
box office appeal. And ``Shot Through the Heart'' was a grim movie
about a war few Americans understood. An uncompromising, humanistic
experience.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The American Experience: Ronald Reagan.'' Documentary
producers Austin Hoyt and Adriana Bosch found their defining
metaphor in one of Reagan's first jobs. He was a summer lifeguard
in Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Already the future president saw himself as a rescue artist, a
frame of mind he'd later apply to the Screen Actors Guild, the
state of California, the United States and, ultimately, the
non-communist world.
</P>
<P>
   The riveting profile of the 40th president also caught the great
dichotomy in Reagan: the friendly, straightforward charmer who is
utterly unknowable. ``You're not going to figure him out,'' his son
Ron Reagan said on camera. ``That's the first thing you need to
know. ... I haven't figured him out. I don't know anybody who's
figured him out.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Cold War.'' CNN's 24-hour history of the Cold War began
in September and continues into April. That's a lot of heft. But
executive producer Jeremy Isaacs (``World at War'') has crafted an
old-fashioned historical documentary that's just as brisk as it is
informative.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (MORE) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Isaacs doesn't believe in heavy analysis; he prefers anecdotes
with a human touch. But hour after hour, the program demonstrates
that the Cold War was scorchingly real, &LR;  and hardly bloodless.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``P.O.V.: Kelly Loves Tony.'' Bay Area filmmaker Spencer
Nakasako has something in common with the novelist Tom Wolfe.
Wolfe, in ``A Man in Full,'' and Nakasako, in this installment from
PBS' ``P.O.V.'' documentary series, bottled rough truths about the
working class deep in the East Bay.
</P>
<P>
   A young Laotian couple, Kelly Saeteurn and Tony Saelio, used a
camcorder from Nakasako to document their own lives for a year and
a half. Saeteurn emerged strongly on videotape as a woman stretched
almost to breaking between two cultures.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``NYPD Blue: Hearts and Souls.'' Bobby Simone (Jimmy Smits)
went gently in a stunner of an episode that might have been TV's
finest hour of power all year.
</P>
<P>
   In lesser hands, this sensitive episode could have been _
probably would have been _ unbearably maudlin. But abetted by
wonderful performances all around, the ``NYPD Blue'' team proved
that there's such a thing as death with dignity, even in the midst
of the November sweeps.
</P>
<P>
   A week later, Rick Schroder joined the cast as Smits'
replacement, and ``NYPD Blue'' strode toward new directions. But an
afterglow remains from the ``Hearts and Souls'' episode. In death,
something was regained.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
