<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-REPORTER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO HUICHOL INDIAN MEN CHARGED WITH KILLING SAN ANTONIO REPORTER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DUDLEY ALTHAUS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GUADALAJARA, Mexico _ Two Huichol Indian men were formally
charged Monday with the slaying of San Antonio Express-News
reporter Philip True, whose body was found Dec. 16 in the rugged
central Mexico mountains where he was on a 10-day hike.
</P>
<P>
   The two men, Miguel Hernandez and Juan Chivarra, were accused of
strangling True because they were angry he had entered land sacred
to the Huichol without permission and was taking pictures of
people, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say they have had a lot of outsiders come and take
pictures and make money from them,'' Horacio Vega, the 28-year-old
chief of the Jalisco state prosecutor's homicide division, said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Officials say the two attacked True as they hiked together on a
stretch of trail near the village of San Miguel Huastita on Dec. 6.
After tripping the backpack-wearing reporter from behind, Vega
said, one of the suspects pinned True's legs while the other
strangled him with a kerchief.
</P>
<P>
   Vega said the arrested men said True, an avid jogger in good
physical condition, offered no resistance during the attack,
although he was conscious.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez and Chibarra were paraded before reporters on a back
patio of the police investigator's offices in downtown Guadalajara,
the capital of Jalisco.
</P>
<P>
   Both men, slightly built and shabbily dressed, were forced to
stand alongside True's recovered backpack and 35-millimeter camera,
which investigators said they recovered near the suspects' houses,
while television cameras whirred and newspaper photographers
clicked.
</P>
<P>
   Neither suspect made eye contact with reporters nor answered
their questions. After a few minutes, officials escorted the men
away for a crosstown trip to prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not accustomed to speaking,'' Vega said in response
to a Mexican journalist's question whether the men had been ordered
not to say anything to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Although he said officials were still looking for some of True's
belongings and were investigating the pregnant wife of one of the
suspects, who authorities say was present at the time True was
killed, Vega declared the crime largely solved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have (the coroner's) finding (of murder) and the confessions
of two people,'' Vega said Monday. ``That's proof enough for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, as often happens with police investigations in Mexico,
the True case has taken several baffling turns in the 13 days since
his body was found by relatives, friends and colleagues who had
launched a frantic search for him.
</P>
<P>
   The coroner who performed autopsies on True's remains in
Guadalajara announced on Dec. 17 that he had been murdered, then
refused to elaborate. The coroner, Mario Rivas Souza, was quoted in
the Mexican press as saying he was told by superiors to keep quiet.
</P>
<P>
   Results of a second autopsy, performed Dec. 20 in Mexico City by
forensic specialists from the federal attorney general's office and
attended by an expert from the FBI, were promised by last weekend
but have not yet been released.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI's forensic expert, Emma Lew, referred questions Monday
to her superior, who referred them to an FBI spokesperson, who
didn't return calls for comment.
</P>
<P>
   A high-level official in the Jalisco state attorney general's
office said off the record last week that True had died
accidentally, falling down in a drunken stupor and freezing to
death. And other officials in Mexico City gave similar accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the state prosecutor's office arrested the Huichol
suspects for the reporter's murder. Although the San Antonio
Express-News was told of the arrests on Christmas Day, Vega said
that Hernandez and Chibarra were arrested the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Vega says he has no knowledge of what he called ``rumors'' of
True's accidental death. And he said that the conflict in the
reported times of the Huichols' arrests is explained because they
were only ``formally'' detained on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Vega said that the original autopsy report found a high level of
alcohol in True's body and the presence of a drug, which he did not
name. He said he could not explain how True would be heavily
intoxicated at 8 a.m., the time which authorities say he was killed
on Dec. 6.
</P>
<P>
   True was known by friends to be a moderate social drinker.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know what happened that night, because he didn't have
any companions with him,'' Vega said.
</P>
<P>
   An experienced hiker, True had often taken solo treks through
Mexico and elsewhere over the years. The walls of True's Mexico
City home are filled with photographs of peasants, many of them
Indians, that he had photographed. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
