<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9261 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-NOFLY-BOS &LR;      12-28 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-NOFLY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US WARPLANES HIT MISSILE BATTERY; FOUR IRAQIS DIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLUM LYNCH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ US warplanes fired on an air defense battery in
northern Iraq Monday, killing four soldiers, injuring seven and
possibly setting the stage for a new phase of low intensity
skirmishes between the United States and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton defended the air strike _ which produced the
first Iraqi casualties since a four-day US-British bombing campaign
ended December 19 _ as an ``appropriate'' response after
surface-to-air missiles were fired at US jets patrolling the
northern a ``no-fly zone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They attacked because they were attacked,'' Clinton said of
the US pilots. The White House denied Iraqi reports that an
American pilot was shot down during the operation, insisting that
all Americans involved in the attack returned safely to their base
at Incirlik, Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   The Iraqi action underscores Saddam Hussein's willingness to
endure further air strikes as he tests US resolve in the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could very well be that we are entering a new phase of low
intensity exchanges,'' said a State Department official who has
been involved in Iraq policy for years. ``But we have demonstrated
that we can strike very, very quickly and that should be enough to
keep Saddam worried.''
</P>
<P>
   In another challenge to Washington's containment policy, Baghdad
restarted a massive oil smuggling operation from Basra through Iran
less than two weeks after US missiles struck the city's refineries,
according to an administration official.
</P>
<P>
   Baghdad claimed it was justified in firing on the US plane
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Iraq has always said that there is no way that it could
respond to the no-fly zones,'' said Iraq's UN ambassador, Nizar
Hamdoon. ``Why should there be such a breach of Iraq's sovereignty?
Why should Iraq stand idle.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Iraqi military added later that an ``enemy''
US warplane was struck by Iraqi surface-to-air missiles.
</P>
<P>
   He suggested Washington was trying to cover up the loss ``in
order to provide its pilot an opportunity to infiltrate if he is
alive or give its agents an opportunity to bring back his body if
he is dead.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not true,'' White House national security spokesman David
Leavy said in response to the Iraqi allegations. ``Our air crews
returned to their bases safely. This is just more propaganda from
Saddam Hussein.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If Saddam's motives are to break out of his box, then he got
his answer today,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Britain have maintained a no-fly zone over
northern Iraq since 1991 to shield the country's minority Kurds
from Iraqi aggression. A second no-fly zone that stretches from the
southern suburbs of Baghdad to the Kuwaiti border was established
in 1992 to protect Iraq's Shiite minority.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we effectively control the skies over Iraq, Saddam has
been unable to use air power against his own people or lash out
against his neighbors.'' Clinton said Monday. ``We will continue to
enforce the no-fly policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the US halted its bombardment of Iraq, Baghdad has
repeatedly sought to test Washington's willingness to defend the
no-fly zones.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Iraq directed anti-aircraft fire near two British
Tornado fighter jets conducting patrols in southern Iraq, according
to the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   And on Sunday Iraqi Vice President Taha Yassin Ramadan said Iraq
would target British and US planes patrolling the zones.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday's exchange was by far the most significant incident.
</P>
<P>
   The Iraqi government said ``several enemy formations'' entered
Iraqi airspace at 10:25 a.m from US military bases at Incirlik. A
second wave of US jets entered the country at 1:37 p.m. and ``fired
criminal missiles against one of our sites'' outside the town of
Mosul.
</P>
<P>
   US officials said the Iraqis fired first.
</P>
<P>
   A White House source said that a team of F-16 and F-15 fighters
jets ``came across a SAM (surface-to-air missile) battery that
illuminated our F-16s'' with their radar.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a hostile Iraqi action, an act of aggression against
US aircraft,'' said a Pentagon spokesman, Col. Richard Bridges.
``The US took appropriate action under their rules of engagement.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The aircraft acted in self-defense and attacked the
ground-based missile launch site with HARM (High-Speed Anti
Radiation) missiles and precision-guided munitions,'' added Major
Tony Kemper, a spokeswoman for the US-European Command based near
Stuttgart, Germany. ``There was no damage to coalition aircraft and
all crew returned safely to Incirlik airbase.''
</P>
<P>
   As Iraq raised the military stakes in its confrontation with the
United States, it backed off from a threat to eject 400 UN
humanitarian aid workers and end the so-called oil-for-food deal.
</P>
<P>
   But Iraq's trade minister, Mohammed Mehdi Saleh, said the
agreement must end soon along with eight years of crippling
economic sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Iraq will not live with the oil-for-food program forever,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The two-year-old deal _ conceived by the United States and
Britain as a humanitarian exception to the UN embargo _ allows Iraq
to sell $10.4 billion worth of oil each year to purchase food and
medicine and to repair basic infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   US officials say Iraq has intensified its efforts to circumvent
the UN sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Baghdad has called on Arab leaders preparing for a summit in
Cairo next month to trade with Iraq in violation of the embargo.
And Iraq has re-established a smuggling route along the Shatta al
Arab Persian Gulf waterway that straddles the coasts of Iraq and
Iran.
</P>
<P>
   A State Department official that tracks Iraq's smuggling
activities said the illicit trade -- suspended during the
US-British air campaign -- has resumed with one to two oil tankers
traveling in and out of the port of Basra each day.
</P>
<P>
   Before the strikes, the official said, between two to three
tankers ferried oil out of Basra each day en route to Iran,
accounting for some 250,000 metric tons of oil during the month of
November.
</P>
<P>
   The source said it is too early to determine whether the renewed
smuggling indicates that American bombardment failed to erode
Iraq's capacity to circumvent an eight-year-old oil embargo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can see the ships go in an out,'' the official said. ``But
it's still too early to say what the long-term impact will be. We
have struck at the source and I would expect a greatly reduced
amount of smuggling over the long haul.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
