<SLUG> BC-MA-AUTO-INSURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE AUTO INSURANCE RATES MAY RISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Auto insurance rates will rise next year for the first
time in five years, with the increase in the average premium of
$835 expected to be in the 1 to 4 percent range, sources said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   An increase, even a small one, would represent a victory for the
auto insurance industry in one of the most contentious rate fights
in state history. The industry had requested a 15.5 percent rate
hike, but Attorney General Scott Harshbarger and the Division of
Insurance's own State Rating Bureau said rate cuts of as much as 12
percent were warranted.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance Commissioner Linda Ruthardt is expected to issue her
formal decision later this week, but administration sources decided
to release news of the rate hike early. One source said Governor
Paul Cellucci, who held a press conference to announce the 1998
rate cut, won't have anything to do with this announcement.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the auto insurance industry said he would have
no comment until the actual decision is released, although he did
point out that rates this year are at the same level they were in
1988.
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger's office had no comment, but other auto insurance
watchdogs were critical of the reported rate increase.
</P>
<P>
   Deirdre Cummings, consumer program director for the
Massachusetts Public Interest Research Group, said a solid case had
been made during this year's rate hearings for holding 1999 rates
stable or cutting them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that they're talking about a rate increase is a
disappointment for consumers,'' she said. But she added that a 1
percent increase _ about $8 on an average premium _ wouldn't be
that big of a blow.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen J. D'Amato, the former head of the State Rating Bureau,
said any increase is unwarranted. ``Insurers are currently giving
large discounts off of 1998 rates and the commissioner's own State
Rating Bureau recommended decreasing rates next year by more than
10 percent. In this context, any rate increase at all is
unreasonable and may well be appealed,'' D'Amato said.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato resigned his post earlier this year, sending a letter to
Cellucci in which he warned that Ruthardt was too cozy with the
insurance industry. Harshbarger subsequently asked Ruthardt to
recuse herself from the hearings because of a private meeting she
held with an industry official.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts is the only state that sets all aspects of auto
insurance rates, although insurers here have competed for customers
in recent years by offering discounts off the state-set rates.
</P>
<P>
   For consumers, the real impact of Ruthardt's decision may not be
the decision itself, but what effect it has on the appetite of the
insurance industry to continue offering the discounts.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last several years, group and safe driver discounts
have been plentiful. Discounts have run as high as 20 percent at
some companies, offering savings far in excess of what Ruthardt has
ordered with her rate cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials have said they would have to see whether
Ruthardt offered any rate relief to the industry before announcing
whether the discounts would continue in 1999 and at what size.
</P>
<P>
   But industry watchdogs say the fact that auto insurers have been
offering hefty discounts off the state-set rates means Ruthardt has
set rates too high in the past. ``There's fluff in the system
somewhere,'' Cummings said.
</P>
<P>
   Industry officials say the ``fluff'' has been company reserves
that have been tapped to remain competitive with other companies
offering discounts.
</P>
<P>
   State officials were tight-lipped about key elements of
Ruthardt's decision. For example, they declined to say how she
ruled on a Harshbarger request for financial sanctions against the
industry for failing to provide accurate data on executive
salaries. They also declined to say whether Ruthardt went along
with an industry proposal to begin dismantling the subsidies that
benefit urban drivers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-28-98 1933EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
