</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARCH-MOBILEMEDIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARCH-MOBILEMEDIA DEAL UNDER A CLOUD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arch Communications Group's planned acquisition of troubled
pager giant MobileMedia Corp. could run afoul of a group of the
company's bondholders, who say they may have enough votes to
scuttle the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly looks like we are very close,'' said George
Putnum III, president of New Generation Advisers, a Boston
investment firm representing the bondholders.
</P>
<P>
   Putnum said some bondholders have rebelled against Arch's
proposal, which followed MobileMedia's bankruptcy filing in early
1997, because it is ``grossly unfair.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It just seems that a number of other viable options have not
been considered,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A merger with Arch, based in Westborough, Mass., would create
the No. 2 US paging company with more than 7 million subscribers
and $800 million in annual revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Arch deal, MobileMedia's unsecured creditors including
bondholders would be paid with Arch stock and stock options. But
the options to buy Arch stock at $2 a share are ``essentially
worthless,'' Putnam said. Arch shares have been trading well below
$2, which means it would cost less to purchase the shares outright
than to exercise the options. Arch planned to use the money paid by
bondholders to help finance the takeover.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't make a bit of economic sense,'' for the
bondholders, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Putnam said the $479 million acquisition plan was favored by a
small group of creditors who own Arch securities. ``They are sort
of calling the shots right now,'' but their desires ``are not
consistent with the desires of the creditor group as a whole.''
</P>
<P>
   While some bondholders are balking, four major creditors agreed
to support the deal by promising to step in and buy shares not
purchased by other bondholders. They are Credit Suisse First Boston
Corp. of New York; Whipoorwill Associates Inc. of White Plains, New
York; Northwestern Mutual Life Insurance Co. of Milwaukee; and W.R.
Huff Asset Management Co. of Morristown, New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   MobileMedia _ one of the nation's largest electronic paging
companies and a chief rival of Arch _ filed a petition for Chapter
11 bankruptcy protection Jan. 30, 1997, following large
acquisitions that plunged the company into debt. In October, the
company reported a $5.72 million loss, according to public filings.
</P>
<P>
   But the Fort Lee, N.J. company has done a good job in turning
its business around, Putnum said, and could find ``more favorable
terms'' in another buyer or as a standalone company.
</P>
<P>
   Arch shares closed at 1 5/32, down 9/32, on Nasdaq. Shares have
declined about 71 percent since the merger was announced Aug. 20.
MobileMedia shares were delisted by the Nasdaq in June 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
