<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS PLAYERS, COACH LOOKING AHEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ It's the spineless season, when some players
point fingers at game plans and coaching staffs when things go bad,
overlooking the fact that it is they _ not the balding, middle-aged
men dressed in Patriots garb _ who play the games.
</P>
<P>
   After a decisive loss to the Jets in the Meadowlands Sunday,
there were comments from New England players about being
``outplayed'' and ``outcoached,'' and references to the Jets having
what the Patriots used to have. So with the playoffs arriving this
weekend, maybe it did take a Steve Sidwell or an Ernie Zampese or a
Pete Carroll to take players aside Monday and tell them that they
should watch what they say and keep any problems they have
in-house.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like Sidwell said (Monday),'' offered defensive end Willie
McGinest, ``this league is made up of people pointing fingers. When
things aren't going well, coaches point fingers at players and
players point fingers at coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this organization and team, that's something we try and
stay away from. We try to stay together as a family and a team. And
pointing fingers at each other is something that happens. Sometimes
a guy can be having a normal conversation and someone hears it and
it gets out.''
</P>
<P>
   Such was not the case after this loss. Players were speaking
loudly and clearly.
</P>
<P>
   And so defensive end Ferric Collons, a quiet, bright man of 6
feet 7 inches and 310 pounds, was the one who sprinkled a dose of
reality on his teammates Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's the deal,'' Collons said. ``Nobody wants to lose.
Nobody wants to lose in that fashion. But the goal of any season is
to get into the dance, and we're in the dance. Everything that's
happened in the last 17 weeks is gone and done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hated the way we played. I hated the outcome of Sunday's
game, but it's over and done with and now we have to concentrate on
beating Jacksonville there.''
</P>
<P>
   Regarding comments that the Patriots were flat and didn't come
to play, Collons said, ``You're a professional and you come to play
every week if you're a good team. And we're a good team who got
beat on that given day and they were a better team on that day. But
don't say you didn't come to play. You come to play. We lined up
and got beat. We took a bad situation and made it worse. We didn't
adjust properly as players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't speak for everybody, but all of that `flat'
(expletive) is (expletive).
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a (expletive) excuse is what that is. We're a very good
football team. You know how it goes on any given day in the NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   Concerning a supposed lack of preparedness, Collons said, ``If
you get beat deep or you miss a tackle or you get knocked off the
(expletive) ball, that has nothing to do with your (expletive)
coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Line up, be a man, look in the (expletive) mirror and say you
were outplayed Monday. You might not like some of the situations
you were put in, but it's your job. You make the most of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to cover for anyone in this (expletive)
building, but that's (expletive). We got outplayed Monday. It's not
a matter of I don't like this or I don't like that. Line up, buckle
up your chinstrap, and be a man about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The moral of this story is don't tell Ferric Collons that
coaching is the issue. There are many other Patriots who feel the
same way. And those who don't feel that way won't be blurting it
out after tough losses anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't heard anything about players criticizing game plans
or confidence in the game plan,'' said wide receiver Shawn
Jefferson. ``Every week it's good. It's up to the players to
execute it.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if any players were looking over to the Jets' sideline,
longing for what they once had, Jefferson said, ``No. I don't think
the players are saying that. If they are, they should look deep
down within themselves and see what they're doing wrong. I think
we're a close team and we stick together in all situations. We're
going to go out and have a great game this week.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll, still standing after his weekly bludgeoning by the
media and fans, was asked again what happened. Why couldn't the
Patriots have given it more of an effort?
</P>
<P>
   ``When the plays don't happen and you're taking it, taking it,
and taking it, there's nothing to get excited about,'' said
Carroll. ``It's the old chicken and the egg. Is it the plays that
create the excitement or the excitement that creates the plays?
When you play this many games, you have to play well to create the
excitement. When we don't get the sack when we're free on the rush
. . . there were too many plays that we didn't take advantage of.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots did not view film of the New York game Monday;
instead they began studying Jacksonville, their first-round playoff
opponent Sunday. McGinest said the team has put the Jets game
behind it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to use that game as a steppingstone,'' said McGinest.
``We have to turn it positive heading for the playoffs. Nobody's
record matters anymore. If you lose, you go home. And if you play
well, you go on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
