<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-SHULMAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE SADIE SHULMAN, AT 107; FIRST WOMAN ON A MASS. BENCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Judge Sadie Lipner Shulman, the first woman judge
commissioned in Massachusetts, died Wednesday in Johnson City,
Tenn. She was 107.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Shulman was sworn in as an associate justice of the
Municipal Court of the Dorchester District of Boston by Governor
Frank G. Allen on Dec. 17, 1930. Emma Fall Schofield was named a
judge at Malden District Court the same day. To settle the delicate
matter of who would have the honor of being the first woman judge,
Mrs. Schofield signed the appropriate papers first and Judge
Shulman was given the first commission, as special justice at the
Dorchester District Court.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to being the first woman to preside over a court in
Boston, she was the first woman named assistant corporation counsel
of the City of Boston, a post she held from 1926 to 1930. She was
also the first woman president of the Boston University Law School
Alumni Association.
</P>
<P>
   Born in New York City, she graduated cum laude from Boston
University Law School in 1911, when she was 20. She was admitted to
the bar the following year.
</P>
<P>
   She endowed a scholarship for women at Boston University Law
School, where the women's lounge is named in her honor.
</P>
<P>
   In a profile published in the Globe on Dec. 17, 1965, when she
was observing her 35th year on the bench, she was described as ``a
motherly woman who looks more suited to bouncing grandchildren on
her knee than meting out justice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not what is called a `tough' judge,'' Judge Shulman said,
``but I'm severe when I need to be severe. I pride myself in
thinking I'm a pretty jood judge of human nature and I think I've
developed that over the years. You base your decisions on the
evidence and not on being `tough' or `soft.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Shulman received widespread publicity in April 1964, when
she directed that five juveniles, ages 13 to 15, be taken to a
Dorchester funeral home to view the body of a woman the 13-year-old
was charged with killing when they were joyriding in a stolen car.
</P>
<P>
   ``It occurred to me,'' Judge Shulman said at the time, ``that
these boys take a look at this women, 48 years old, whose life had
been nipped out, that it would make a lasting impression on then,
that they never again would take a car or get behind the wheel
without thinking of the consequences, that they had to be shocked
into the realization of what they had caused to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Six years later, when she was observing her 40th year on the
bench, she said her shock therapy worked. ``To the best of my
knowledge none ever became a repeater,'' she said in a story
published in the Globe on Dec. 17, 1970.
</P>
<P>
   She leaves seven grandchildren and 12 great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
