<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-SCHOOLS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia teachers don't fare well in skills tests, report shows
 &HT;    By Doug Cumming
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia is among a majority of Southern states
certifying new teachers who score as low as the bottom quarter on a
national basic-skills teacher test, according to a new report on
raising standards for middle schools in the South.
</P>
<P>
   The report, focusing on the relationship between teacher quality
and the South's low 8th-grade student achievement in math and
science on a prominent national test, found that Georgia is one of
eight Southern states allowing students to be admitted with scores
that are lower than 75 percent of test-takers' scores nationally in
reading and writing on a basic-skills entrance exam used by teacher
programs in 11 states in the region. The required minimum scores in
Georgia are above only 16 percent of the test-takers' scores
nationally in reading, 20 percent in writing and 29 percent in
math. Among states studied by the Southern Regional Education Board
(SREB) for the report, only Virginia, North Carolina and Delaware
set all three minimum scores on the test above the 25th percentile.
The highest is Virginia, which requires a minimum passing score
that is higher than 54 percent of scores nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia will raise its minimums on the test, called Praxis I, in
two years to levels at least as high as those in North Carolina and
Delaware. States in other parts of the country using the test set
standards no higher than the South, overall.
</P>
<P>
   Because the test began in Georgia in mid-1997, virtually none of
the 10,000 middle school teachers already in Georgia's classrooms
took it. Improving teacher-education programs, as the Board of
Regents and the Professional Standards Commission are both
attempting to do, only affects about 5 percent of the teachers
coming into the system each year.
</P>
<P>
   To raise standards for current teachers, the report recommended
that middle school teachers lacking a subject-matter major or
minor, such as in math or science, go back to college to earn its
equivalent within five years. It also recommended that every middle
school develop a staff-development plan built around the school's
student-achievement scores.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia, at least, gets a gold star for not allowing
elementary-education certificates to cover beyond the fifth grade,
according to the SREB, an Atlanta-based board that advises 16
governors from Delaware to Texas on education policy. Across most
of the South, elementary education certificates cover or overlap
the middle grades, allowing at least a third of all middle-grade
teachers in SREB states to have only elementary-education
background.
</P>
<P>
   Still, middle schools are not rigorous enough, both in the
teachers' subject knowledge and in the way teachers are assigned
outside their academic specialty, said Lynn Cornett, an SREB senior
vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Middle schools ``do a lot of team teaching, block schedules, all
those newfangled ideas, but they don't use them to focus on
academic content, and improving the academic achievement of
students,'' Cornett said.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Cumming writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
