<SLUG> BC-FBC-FIESTA-FSU-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kickers may be ace in hole for Tennessee, FSU
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ As their teams prepare for the Fiesta Bowl,
Tennessee's Phillip Fulmer and Florida State's Bobby Bowden face a
million uncertainties. But they both are sure of one thing: If the
game comes down to a field goal, they like their chances.
</P>
<P>
   The game for the national championship features two of the
nation's best kickers, Tennessee's Jeff Hall and Florida State's
Sebastian Janikowski. They are opposites in personality, but in
sticking the ball between the two yellow posts when the pressure is
on, they are dead, solid identical.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Florida State likes their guy, and they should,'' said
Fulmer, Tennessee's coach. ``But when the game's on the line, there
is nobody I would rather have out there than Jeff Hall. He's proven
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall, from Fulmer's hometown of Winchester, Tenn., is the
definitive clean-cut boy. A devout Christian, Hall leads the team's
Bible study and does not sample the abundant night life along
Knoxville's Cumberland Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   But he makes the kicks with the game on the line. On Sept. 5 he
made a 27-yarder as time expired to beat Syracuse 34-33.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 19, he made one of the biggest field goals of his life,
a 41-yarder in overtime to beat Florida 20-17. After the game, his
teammates went out and celebrated breaking a five-year drought
against the Gators. Hall celebrated in his own way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went home, had a bowl of Wheaties and went to bed,'' said
Hall, who still wears his junior-high T-shirt under his game
jersey. ``I was exhausted.''
</P>
<P>
   But don't let Hall's Dudley-Do-Right image fool you, his
teammates say. There is nothing laid-back about him when it comes
to winning. He is not above getting in another guy's face if he
sees them dogging it. That is one reason why the Tennessee players
voted Hall one of their co-captains.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very unusual for a kicker to be a captain, but in Jeff's
case, he earned it,'' said linebacker Al Wilson, who is also a
captain. ``Captains should be leaders, and Jeff is a leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Janikowski, however, is a horse of a different color. He's not
built like a kicker (6 feet 2, 255 pounds), and he didn't grow up,
as Hall did, kicking footballs and dreaming of playing in college.
An outstanding soccer player, he came to the United States from
Poland in 1994 and enrolled at Seabreeze High in Daytona Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take long for Janikowski to get the knack of kicking a
football, and it didn't take long for word to filter out about the
kid with a cannon for a left leg.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike Hall, Janikowski has proved to be a more fun-loving
sort in his two years at Florida State. On Nov. 22, the fun got out
of hand when he was charged with battery after an altercation with
a male cheerleader at a local bar. The two men gave different
versions of the event, and eventually the assistant state attorney
decided not to prosecute the case.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 4, Janikowski was asked to leave a Tallahassee night
club, and when he refused, police were called. He pleaded no
contest and paid $295 in court costs. Bowden did not suspend
Janikowski but forced him to do extra running after practice, along
with other undisclosed punishments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a stupid thing,'' said Janikowski, who turned down
a lucrative offer to play soccer in Argentina. ``But everybody
makes mistakes, and now I've got to pay for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Janikowski might have some growing up to do in his personal
life, but as a kicker he's as solid as a rock. This season he made
27 of 32 field goals, including 10 of 13 from 40 yards or more. He
has a career long of 56, but observers say he once nailed one from
77 yards in practice.
</P>
<P>
   But his greatest value to Florida State could be as a kickoff
specialist. Forty-seven of his 79 kickoffs this season have gone
for touchbacks. That means that 59.5 percent of the time after a
kickoff, the other team has taken possession on the 20-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   ``A great weapon,'' said Mickey Andrews, Florida State's
defensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   And what if the game, and the national championship, did come
down to a last-second field goal?
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love it,'' Hall said. ``When I was a little boy
kicking in my back yard, I used to pretend I was making kicks to
win the national championship for Tennessee. I've prepared all my
life to be in this kind of situation. I'd love to have the chance
to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Janikowski is taking a more pragmatic approach. Unlike Hall, he
does not have fantasies of making the winning kick.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, because if you miss it you're going to be in the
newspapers all over the United States, and I don't want that,'' he
said. ``I'd rather score a touchdown.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Hall File
</P>
<P>
   _ Born: July 30, 1976, in Winchester, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   _ Class: Senior.
</P>
<P>
   _ Career highlights: Four-time All-SEC pick and academic
All-SEC. . . . SEC's all-time leading scorer with 371 points. . . .
Made 27-yard field goal as time expired to beat Syracuse 34-33. . .
Made 41-yard field goal in overtime to beat Florida 20-17. . . Made
13 of 14 field goals this season inside 40 yards. . . . For career,
has made 61 of 89 field goals and 188 of 194 extra points.
</P>
<P>
   Sebastian Janikowski File
</P>
<P>
   _ Born: March 2, 1978, in Walbrzych, Poland.
</P>
<P>
   _ Class: Sophomore.
</P>
<P>
   _ Career highlights: Winner of the 1998 Lou Groza award as the
nation's best placekicker. . . . Football Writers Association of
America All-America team. . . . Made 27 of 32 field goal attempts
and 42 of 43 extra points. . . . Set Florida State and ACC records
for a kicker with 123 points. . . . Forty-seven of his 79 kickoffs
(59.5 percent) were not returned. . . . Has made 43 of 53 field
goals, including 15 of 21 from more than 40 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
