<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rogers' first school was hard knocks
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jacksonville, Fla. _ Charlie Rogers was 19 years old and a
target in the summer of 1995. Lucky for him, he was a moving one.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow a man's threats toward his sister, and his mother's
warning that her son would protect them, brought a dozen men
holding guns to the door of Rogers's home in Cliffwood, N.J. The
police came to the rescue, but the men returned the next night to
the alley behind the home and fired a shot intended for Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it hit Rogers' cousin in the back as Rogers ran
alongside him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard them say, 'What's up now?' `` Rogers recalled Monday.
``I guess they thought they'd shot me.''
</P>
<P>
   What's up now is that Rogers is a senior star for the Georgia
Tech Yellow Jackets preparing to play his final college game Friday
in the Gator Bowl. He shows no signs of a heavy history, of friends
and family members being carted off to jail.
</P>
<P>
   He's a warm-hearted, positive guy off the field, and on the
field he's one of the main reasons behind Tech's 9-2 season and its
berth in the New Year's Day game against Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever he saw an adult (while growing up), it was always,
'Yes, ma'am,' and, 'No, sir,' `` said Kim Rogers, Charlie's mother.
``He never raised his voice.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time Rogers was in the 10th grade, his mother was in
jail. He moved in with his aunt, looked after his younger brother
and sister and kept going to school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody actually made me go to school,'' Rogers said. ``But I
was determined to make it to college.''
</P>
<P>
   His mother got out when Rogers was in his senior year, and by
then, he had turned poor grades into good ones and had college
recruiters knocking on his door. Rogers chose Georgia Tech because
coach George O'Leary wanted him as a runnng back and most schools
wanted to convert the 5-foot-9, 175-pounder into a defensive back.
</P>
<P>
   While playing running back for Tech, Rogers also has returned
kickoffs and, this season, punts. When the Yellow Jackets needed
help at wide receiver this year, he moved into the slot and learned
a new position.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's probably pound for pound one of our toughest players,''
O'Leary said. ``He's a great competitor, and what he does is very
contagious. . . . He's done a magnificent job, what he's done with
himself, his maturity. I've been happy to see him grow.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers was elected a team captain for the season by his
teammates, receiving the most votes of the three. Defensive end
Jesse Tarplin describes Rogers as an ``inspiration;'' he was
talking about his size, not his background, which is something his
teammates might not even know.
</P>
<P>
   For Rogers, however, getting here from there is what his success
has been all about. Just ask his mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been so determined,'' Kim Rogers said. ``I'm so proud of
him I don't know which way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the future, Rogers is hoping for a shot at the NFL,
probably returning kicks, where his speed and elusiveness help and
his size doesn't hurt. Otherwise, he plans to finish school and
live in Atlanta. His mother wants to move the family wherever
Charlie is, eventually.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the city,'' Rogers said. ``People down here are
friendly, not like home, where people are in a race to go places.
It's not as hostile as home.''
</P>
<P>
   And for his finale as a Yellow Jacket, Rogers said he wants to
go out with a bang _ the kind that widens eyes and gives hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to be remembered as a good player,'' he said. ``A
tough guy who made plays when plays needed to be made. Somebody who
worked hard, and, I guess, a positive guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
