<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COACHES-FIRED-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Bloody Monday' in NFL as 5 coaches lose jobs
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   During a quiet moment in training camp last summer, Seattle
Seahawks coach Dennis Erickson acknowledged that he was one of
several NFL sideline bosses entering the 1998 campaign with the
``sword of (Damocles) hanging over our heads.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Erickson and four others discovered that
disconcerting threat to security actually was a guillotine, as the
heads of head coaches rolled in record numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Owners moved swiftly to demonstrate to disgruntled fans that
losing would not be tolerated _ and to establish an early pecking
order in the shallow pool of possible replacements. In addition to
Erickson, the casualties were Dom Capers of Carolina, Baltimore's
Ted Marchibroda, Ray Rhodes of Philadelphia and Dave Wannstedt of
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The last four all were dumped within an hour of the start of the
business day Monday. Only his West Coast location bought Erickson a
temporary reprieve of a few hours. The decisiveness of owners on
what one suddenly unemployed assistant coach described as ``Bloody
Monday'' was unprecedented.
</P>
<P>
   Five coaches had not been fired on one day since the NFL and AFL
merged, in 1970. Although the wholesale purge might have been an
aberration, it magnified a disturbing trend. Over the last two
decades, the average NFL coaching tenure has been reduced by about
40 percent, from five seasons to roughly three years. Only six
coaches have been with their current teams since before 1995.
Kansas City's Marty Schottenheimer is the lone NFL coach who has 10
years tenure with his current franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like they trotted out the firing squad,'' former NFL
coach Chuck Knox said about the Monday massacre, ``and the blood
started running. Everybody in the business knows it's a job with no
security, but you don't expect something like this.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, however, the only dismissal that rated as even mildly
surprising was that of Wannstedt, whose Bears were competitive for
much of the season. ``It's a tough job in a tough city,'' said
Wannstedt, who appeared stressed the past month and confided to a
friend last week that the uncertainty of his status was an
increasing strain.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT'S NEXT?
</P>
<P>
   _ Dom Capers: Among the leading contenders to replace Ray Rhodes
in Philadelphia, or could possibly return to Pittsburgh as
defensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dennis Erickson: College background and limited NFL contacts
will make it difficult for him to find work in the league in '99,
even as an assistant coach.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ted Marchibroda: At age 67, his coaching days are over, and
he's likely to be offered _ and accept _ some sort of front-office
position with the Ravens.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ray Rhodes: Despite a poor record the last two seasons, could
be a candidate in Green Bay and won't have problem landing a
coordinator's job.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dave Wannstedt: Respected long-time defensive coordinator will
catch on as assistant, maybe in Miami, and get the opportunity to
start rebuilding his reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Len Pasquarelli writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
