<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BATTERIES29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Those rechargeable batteries eventually pose a disposal problem
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Look closely at the owner's manual that came with that
new rechargeable Christmas gizmo _ cell phone, electric razor,
cordless drill, whatever _ and you'll see an unobtrusive, but firm
warning: The battery inside is an environmental hazard, and it must
never be thrown in the trash, even after it wears out.
</P>
<P>
   Many people, probably, never notice the warning in the first
place. Those who do, depending on how the manual reads, may be left
wondering: How do you get rid of the things? And what's the hazard,
anyway?
</P>
<P>
   The answers, briefly: See the last paragraph in this story to
find out where to toss the batteries. And the hazard is that
chemicals from old batteries can leach from landfills, polluting
the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, says Stanley Carpenter, a public policy professor
at Georgia Tech, companies that sell such rechargeable gadgets
aren't doing a good job of letting people know these facts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if you read in the manuals that you need to dispose of
these batteries, nobody knows what that means, where to take it,
what to do,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Government statistics seem to bear him out. About 335 million
rechargeables are purchased annually, but only 23 percent are
disposed of properly, the Environmental Protection Agency
estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter tried to get information on batteries from a
manufacturer recently, to no avail. ``It's upsetting,'' he says.
``I was literally screaming into the phone, because all I got was
menus with options, and nothing worked.''
</P>
<P>
   Some retailers and instruction manuals do offer ways to dispose
of the batteries. Kristie Madara, a spokeswoman for Atlanta-based
BellSouth Cellular, says the company tells customers to return
batteries to stores, where they'll be picked up for recycling.
</P>
<P>
   ``These batteries are not going to explode or catch on fire,''
she says. ``But if you get enough in a landfill, it's bad from an
environmental standpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   Problem is, most people don't read owner's manuals, says Julie
Vandersea of the Gainesville, Fla.-based Rechargeable Battery
Recycle Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The RBRC has launched a drive to make the public more aware of
the issue. And it's encouraging retailers to make it clearer that
consumers shouldn't just chuck the batteries into the garbage.
</P>
<P>
   To find out where to drop off old batteries, call
</P>
<P>
   1-800-822-8837, or go to http://www.rbrc.com/cgi-local/zip.pl on
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bill Hendrick writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
