<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOLEN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSEUM DEFENDS ARTIFACT ACQUISITION PRACTICES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a, i and e coding; Vermeule is cq)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WALTER V. ROBINSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Museum of Fine Arts, responding to a Boston Globe
report that it has acquired scores of classical antiquities in
recent years that may have been plundered from grave sites, Monday
said it exercises ``appropriate diligence'' when it acquires
artworks.
</P>
<P>
   But Cornelius C. Vermeule III, the retired curator who oversaw
most of the acquisitions, said Monday that he does not know whether
some of the objects might have been freshly looted from grave sites
when the museum acquired them.
</P>
<P>
   In the report, a former MFA director said the museum seldom
raised questions about the origin of antiquities it acquired. And
two antiquities dealers who have sold objects to the museum said
they cannot always say that objects they sell have not been
recently looted.
</P>
<P>
   With assistance from 11 archeologists, the Globe studied 71
classical artifacts the museum acquired, by donation or purchase,
between mid-1984 and mid-1987. Only 10 had a history of any prior
owner. The remaining 61 had no history at all, strong
circumstantial evidence, the scholars said, that they had recently
been looted by grave robbers, mostly in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   In a two-paragraph statement, the MFA said that when it
considers acquiring objects for its collection, the artifacts are
reviewed ``to ensure that their addition to the Museum's collection
is both legal and appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   In the brief statement, the MFA chose not to take issue with
what the Globe reported. Asked about that late Monday, Dawn
Griffin, the MFA spokeswoman, said the museum does not agree that
it acquired the artifacts without exercising due diligence.
</P>
<P>
   Vermeule, the MFA's classical curator for four decades until his
retirement in 1996, did not return telephone calls before the Globe
report. But in a brief telephone interview Monday, Vermeule said
the MFA ``tried to do due diligence'' before acquiring artifacts.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether it was possible that some of the 61 undocumented
artifacts might have been freshly looted, Vermeule replied, ``I
don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Vermeule took issue with MFA director Malcolm Rogers for
consistently refusing to discuss the acquisitions, even though his
predecessor, Alan Shestack, acknowledged in an interview last week
that the MFA had been less than rigorous in ensuring that artifacts
it acquired were not recently plundered. Shestack was director from
1987 to 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``The museum and Malcolm Rogers should talk about these things.
Otherwise it will look like we've been bounding through the
marketplace picking up everything in sight,'' Vermeule said.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe reported that the museum acquired the undocumented
objects after it committed itself in 1983 to observe international
standards designed to slow the plunder of antiquities.
</P>
<P>
   Mario Bondioli Osio, the president of Italy's Interministerial
Commission for the Recovery of Art, expressed frustration Monday at
cases like that involving the MFA, saying his government cannot
mount a successful legal claim without having evidence of where and
when an artifact was looted.
</P>
<P>
   As one way to minimize the demand for looted artifacts, Italy
recently began making year-long loans to US museums of classical
antiquities that are much more important and valuable than most
museums could afford to purchase, according to Bondioli Osio.
</P>
<P>
   The MFA now faces a likely lawsuit from the government of
Guatemala, seeking the return of a collection of pre-Columbian
artifacts the MFA acquired in 1988. The museum's lawyer has
acknowledged that he knew the objects were illegally exported from
Guatemala. But the MFA has insisted that they were legally imported
into the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe also reported that Turkey's government is pressing for
the return of the top half of a ``Weary Herakles'' statue whose
bottom half is in a Turkish museum in Antalya.
</P>
<P>
   Murray C. McClellan, a Boston University classical archeologist,
said he views the fact that the MFA did not take issue with the
Globe's story as an indication that the museum might take greater
precautions in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we'll see whether they really do exercise due diligence,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   McClellan said the potential lawsuits, by Turkey and Guatemala,
would amount to a tragic waste of resources. But given the museum's
statement, he said, ``I would be shocked if they would make a major
blunder, like Guatemala or the Herakles, again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-28-98 2005EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981228.0398 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9311 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-FOREIGN-JOURNAL     12-28 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-FOREIGN-JOURNAL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JOURNAL: MISSILE COMPONENTS AND IRAQI RESILIENCE LEGACIES OF
TRIP TO IRAQ
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (k) Commentary
categories.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAGHDAD _ I'll be coming home from Iraq with a charred and
twisted piece of U.S. federal property.
</P>
<P>
   It's a flat, grooved ring about three inches across. I found it
in a deep muddy crater where a cruise missile had landed a couple
hours earlier.
</P>
<P>
   This scrap is just a minuscule portion of the more than 400
missiles that slammed into this country over four days this month.
Maybe it's the part I paid for with my tax dollars.
</P>
<P>
   It will remind me of how strange it feels to stand in the rubble
of someone's house, or by somebody's grimy hospital bed, and ask
him what he thinks about the United States of America.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, they say that they were in bed or walking down the
street when the missile hit. They say that America is evil and will
some day be vanquished. What else can they say?
</P>
<P>
   There are a lot American journalists here and Iraqis generally
feel that they can talk to the American people through us.
</P>
<P>
   Only two people refused to talk to me. One eventually opened up
and we shook hands. The other was headed to pray at a mosque. He
warned his fellow worshipers that we were trying to figure out
their prayer time so we could bomb them. His friends apologized to
us for his rudeness.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, there are a lot of infuriating things about working in
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   People know the government line and generally toe it
vociferously. Just in case they might not, the Ministry of Culture
and Information tries to assign ``guides'' to each of us. You can
get away from them, but most of our drivers are also part of the
network and, if they are not, you could get them in trouble by
ordering them any place too risky.
</P>
<P>
   Our hotel, the Al Rasheed, is watched at all hours by men in
blazers who stand in the lobby and parking lot. During the
bombings, I twice needed special permission before they would open
the gates and let me leave the building.
</P>
<P>
   And, the government of Iraq has not always been a gracious host.
Remember the ``human shields'' of the Gulf War?
</P>
<P>
   But, if America were attacked, would we let a bunch of people
from the attacking country, many of them with satellite telephones
that can call home easily, wander around and assess the damage to
targets?
</P>
<P>
   And, I wonder how we would treat our enemies.
</P>
<P>
   Here, a family invited me to dinner even as so-called ``smart''
bombs rumbled in the distance. They offered to let me sleep there
if my hotel lost power.
</P>
<P>
   A bride and groom took time to tell a group of us why they would
get married amid all of this. Then, they invited us to the wedding.
</P>
<P>
   I made the 11-hour car trip from Amman, Jordan to Baghdad with a
couple of other reporters and a wealthy Iraqi businessman. He
offered his contacts and advice to smooth our border crossing.
</P>
<P>
   Noticing that we had brought three cases of Pepsi Cola, known to
be popular with Iraqi border authorities, he gave us an approving
fatherly grin, ``Ahh, Pepsi. That is very important.''
</P>
<P>
   On the road, he asked us why Americans were attacking Iraq and
surmised for himself that they want to control the Persian Gulf. As
for Saddam Hussein, Iraqis could not oust him even if they wanted
to, he said. And, ``they don't want to,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   He had decided to return to his family because, he explained,
Iraqis would rather die together than separately.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, we were crossing the barren Iraqi desert, lined
with patches of short brush and the occasional large picture of
Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   When the Jordanian driver of our big GMC slapped a cassette into
the tape deck, pop singer Meredith Brooks opened our travels in
beleaguered Iraq with the line, ``I hate the world today.''
</P>
<P>
   We did not know that the casualties would be relatively low and
that these cruise missiles could demolish one building while barely
scarring the one next door.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, I never felt in danger during the attacks. Watching the
explosions from my hotel window or with crowds on the sidewalk,
they always seemed isolated, even when shock waves blew my hair
back.
</P>
<P>
   I just tried to follow the Iraqis' lead. In good times, they
live under a severely restrictive regime and crippling economic
sanctions. In the bad times, they have all that and missile
attacks, too.
</P>
<P>
   So, in helplessness or resilience, they go on buying their ice
cream, playing billiards, getting married and treating their guests
well.
</P>
<P>
   This past week, Iraqis were busy buying Christmas trees. I have
this missile part I found. After all, it brought me here. Maybe it
will make me think about the Iraqis even after I leave them behind
in the desert.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
