<SLUG> BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHION NOTES AND NEWS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By MARYLOU LUTHER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _
</P>
<P>
   &UR; New Koos Boutique Planned &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Koos van den Akker says his fashion business has been
resuscitated and he will be able to open a new Madison Avenue
boutique, thanks to his earnings from QVC, the television shopping
channel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The QVC tie-in also saved me from poverty,'' said van den
Akker, the Dutch-born designer whose artistic patchwork jackets and
coats are worn by clients like Ellen Burstyn, Sherry Bronfman and
Julie Belafonte.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six years ago,'' he said, ``my partner died. I had tax
problems. I lost the boutique I'd had for 20 years at 68th and
Madison because the building was sold and I couldn't afford the new
owners' rent. I couldn't even afford the rent on my apartment. I
ate pizza for a year. I was literally on the street.''
</P>
<P>
   Van den Akker credits Veronica Vickers for his re-entry into the
fashion world he entered so propitiously in 1963 as a Christian
Dior apprentice in Paris. First his money manager, now his partner,
Ms. Vickers helped him open a store at 215 West 10th St., near
Bleecker Street, three and a half years ago.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, along came QVC with a proposition to create a
secondary line, Koos, translating his costly fabric collages into
printed fabrics, thereby transforming a $1,400 jacket into an
$87.50 made-in-China copy.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first TV collection appeared on Halloween,'' he said, ``and
I had to sell $500,000 worth in an hour in order to fulfill their
projections. The 10 styles sold out in 27 minutes, so they want me
back in April.''
</P>
<P>
   Van den Akker said the less expensive designs have not
jeopardized his regular collection. He said that customers who pay
$900 to $1,400 for jackets and up to $2,500 for coats do not object
to seeing copies. ``If they can buy one of my scarfs on QVC for $30
and it's $235 in my store, they buy both,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; No Squinting for Barbie Fans &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The marketers at Mattel have a new idea: They are offering
Barbie sunglasses by Alain Mikli _ not for Barbie, whose 40th
birthday will be celebrated March 9, but for all the adults who
have ever owned one of the more than a billion Barbie dolls sold
since 1959. At least that's the goal of Adrienne Fontanella,
Mattel's general manager of worldwide licensing, who sees the new
glasses as ``capturing the essence of Barbie: chic, glamorous and
playful.''
</P>
<P>
   That means glasses with Barbie elements like pink lenses and
frames with side pieces modeled after Barbie's legs. The
sunglasses, at $165, will be at Saks Fifth Avenue, Neiman Marcus
and Barneys New York in time for the birthday hoopla.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; In Love With Pretty &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Josh Patner and Bryan Bradley, designers and owners of Tuleh,
believe in the selling power of pretty. They say they have doubled
their business since March and that they owe it all to clothes that
are ``heartbreakingly romantic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Women from Boston to Beverly Hills are responding to things
that make them look pretty,'' said Patner, who likens the clothes
(suits at $1,800, evening dresses to $3,000) to wearable flowers.
Many Tuleh florals are in motifs reprinted by Ascher in London from
original screens once used in haute couture. Best sellers include a
rose chiffon printed with green roses, a pink gardenia and a bird
print.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've struck a chord with many women,'' Patner said, citing
customers as diverse as those who patronize Bergdorf Goodman and
Liberty of London; the singers Monica and Deborah Cox, who wore the
clothes in a Vibe magazine spread; Cameron Diaz, who wore them in
Entertainment Weekly, and Marisa Tomei, ``who wears our clothes all
the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Patner, a former magazine stylist and women's fashion director
at Bergdorf Goodman, and Bradley, a former freelance designer for
Calvin Klein and Anne Klein, say their latest look at pretty will
be seen at the Golden Globe Awards on Jan. 24. On whom? ``We're not
supposed to reveal that,'' Patner said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
