<HEADLINE>
SEAHAWKS FIRE COACH DENNIS ERICKSON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND, Wash. _ He was the hometown guy, working for local
ownership, a combination Seahawk fans seemed to favor. But Monday,
Dennis Erickson was told to get a new address.
</P>
<P>
   Erickson, 51, was fired as head coach of Seattle's National
Football League team, a day after the Seahawks lost 28-21 to Denver
and finished out of the playoffs for the 10th consecutive season _
the league's longest such streak.
</P>
<P>
   The Everett, Wash., native was hired four years ago because he
seemingly won big wherever he went. He had coached the University
of Miami to two national championships. He was let go because he
didn't win enough in four seasons in the NFL. His Seahawk teams
finished 8-8, 7-9, 8-8 and 8-8.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're kind of stuck at this 8-8 hurdle,'' Seahawks president
Bob Whitsitt said.
</P>
<P>
   While there had been month-long speculation suggesting that
Erickson would lose his job, Whitsitt said the decision regarding a
coaching change was his alone and was made Sunday night, with input
from owner Paul Allen.
</P>
<P>
   Whitsitt said Erickson's firing was ``based on a three-year
evaluation,'' a time period that covers Allen's two-year ownership
and negotiation to purchase the team.
</P>
<P>
   The club executive declined to give specifics over the move,
though he seemed to agree there was a lack of quality Seahawk
victories during the Erickson regime.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to see continual improvement,'' Whitsitt said.
</P>
<P>
   Erickson was informed of the decision by Whitsitt in a
mid-morning meeting at the team's headquarters. The silver-haired
coach then met with his assistant coaches, spoke with a few players
and somberly attended a press conference just before 2 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm from Seattle,'' Erickson said. ``I came here for a reason.
I came to get this thing turned around. And to a point, we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Erickson said he wants to coach again. He planned to take a few
days off at his Redmond home before starting a job search.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-28-98 2038EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
