<DOCNO> NYT19981228.0417 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9353 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMUGGLED-ALIENS-NYT &LR;      12-28 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMUGGLED-ALIENS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
82 DETAINED IN HUMAN-SMUGGLING OPERATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)  (mk) 
 By MIREYA NAVARRO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Eighty-two illegal immigrants from Cuba, Haiti and
Jamaica were dropped off at eight locations between Key West and
West Palm Beach over the last three days in a flurry of smuggling
that takes a page from the drug trafficking in the seas off South
Florida, federal officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 82 illegal immigrants detained over the weekend were
46 Cubans, 30 Haitians and six Jamaicans, including 12 minors,
officials said. One group of 18 Cubans landed on the shore in Miami
Beach's trendy South Beach section.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Border Patrol officials said organized alien smugglers
using high-powered speedboats were believed to be involved in all
but one of the incidents, the highest number of landings the Border
Patrol has seen in a 72-hour period. They said the boats, which
have been used increasingly in the past year, take smaller groups
of people and require more landings than larger vessels, but can go
faster and blend in better to elude law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest benefit is that they can more or less disguise
themselves in the general boating population,'' said Keith Roberts,
a Border Patrol spokesman here.
</P>
<P>
   Speedboats are a staple of cocaine smuggling _ they rendezvous
with airplanes for drug airdrops, and also make delivery runs
between Bahamian islands like Bimini to ports and marinas along
Florida's east coast.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials said some of the alien smugglers, who
sometimes also use the Bahamas by having their human cargo dropped
off there by larger boats for pickup by a speedboat, use drug
trafficking methods because they often smuggle drugs too. Of 21
pending federal prosecutions of alien smugglers in South Florida,
Roberts said, at least six cases involve defendants also connected
to drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Border Patrol, which handles the illegal immigrants
who make it to shore, had no year-end figures available, the U.S.
Coast Guard, which handles those caught at sea, reports a doubling
in the number of immigrant interceptions from last year. So far in
1998, 998 Cubans and 1,345 Haitians have been intercepted at sea,
compared with 406 Cubans and 587 Haitians in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   A Coast Guard spokesman, Petty Officer Jeff Murphy, said one
theory for the rise, which was registered mostly in the second half
of the year, was that because of hurricane destruction in the
Caribbean, ``more and more people might be willing to risk it all''
and leave for the United States. Still, the numbers are far below
their crisis proportions in 1994, when more than 37,000 Cubans and
24,000 Haitians crossed the Florida Straits.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the United States, which used to indiscriminately
welcome those escaping Fidel Castro's Cuba, repatriates Cubans
found at sea, just as it does Haitians and others. Those who make
it to land, however, are less likely to be deported, and many
Cubans still attempt the crossing. Increasingly, they have resorted
to smugglers with boats better equipped for the journey.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1994, it was anything that would float,'' Murphy said.
``We're seeing more and more sophistication in their approach.''
</P>
<P>
   But the smuggling fee _ which Border Patrol officials said
averages about $1,500 but can reach $8,000 or higher _ does not
guarantee a safe passage. Earlier this month a speedboat carrying
21 Cuban immigrants capsized near the Florida Keys and 14 people
drowned. Two men, both of Cuban descent, have been charged with
alien smuggling.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts of the Border Patrol said one factor contributing to the
high number of incidents this month was that organized smugglers
``traditionally'' _ and erroneously _ assume that U.S. borders are
lightly staffed during the holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that better coordination with local law enforcement
offices has led to more reports of suspicious activity from boaters
and people walking along the beaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``There seems to be an overall heightened awareness,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
