<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: BARYSHNIKOV IN THE VILLAGE; NEW FRENCH MUSEUM; FILM
TALK IN BROOKLYN; GREGORY PECK HONORED; `ARMAGEDDON' WINS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Pa., France)  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mikhail Baryshnikov will perform the American
premiere of ``Dance With Three Drums and Flute,'' choreographed by
the Japanese Kabuki dancer-actor Tamasaburo Bando, when he appears
in an evening of new, mostly solo works on Jan. 12 at St. Mark's
Danspace, at St. Mark's Church at Second Avenue and 10th Street in
the East Village. The event, a benefit for Dancers Responding to
AIDS, will feature previews of works by Mark Morris and Neil
Greenberg, whose ``MacGuffin or How Meanings Get Lost (Revisited)''
is set to sections of Bernard Herrmann's score for ``Psycho.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming Attraction
</P>
<P>
   The French government has approved plans for a $200 million
Museum of Arts and Civilization, dedicated to Africa, Asia, the
Americas and Oceania. Scheduled to open in 2004 near the Eiffel
Tower, the museum will incorporate the collections of the current
Museum of African and Oceanic Arts and the Museum of Mankind.
</P>
<P>
   Advance Words
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With participants like the filmmaker Spike Lee, the
composer-musician Toshi Reagon, the New York Times cultural critic
Margo Jefferson and an NPR senior editor, Sharon Green, a
discussion and preview screening of segments of a new six-part film
documentary about the contributions of African-American artists
will take place at 8 p.m. Monday, Jan. 11, under the auspices of
651, An Arts Center, at the Brooklyn Academy of Music Opera House.
</P>
<P>
   The documentary, ``I'll Make Me a World,'' by Blackside Inc., is
to be broadcast in February on PBS. It is narrated by Vanessa
Williams and features commentary and analysis from artists, critics
and scholars like Amiri Baraka, Alice Walker, Wynton Marsalis, Bill
T. Jones and August Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Select Company
</P>
<P>
   Gregory Peck is to receive the Marian Anderson Award for
humanitarian efforts. In announcing the accolade, Mayor Edward
Rendell of Philadelphia said, ``At a time when it took great
personal and professional courage to take public stands in
denouncing anti-Semitism and racism, Gregory Peck made brave
choices about the film roles he accepted.'' The mayor cited
``Gentleman's Agreement'' (1947) and ``To Kill a Mockingbird''
(1962). Peck, 82, is to receive the honor at a ceremony on June 27.
</P>
<P>
   Wicket Ways
</P>
<P>
   On the basis of attendance through Dec. 20, Exhibitor Relations,
which keeps an eye on movie house box offices, has named the
top-grossing films of 1998 in North America. The leading five are:
``Armageddon'' ($201.6 million); ``Saving Private Ryan'' ($190.4
million); ``There's Something About Mary'' ($173.7 million);
``Doctor Dolittle'' ($144.1 million), and ``The Waterboy'' ($140.9)
million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
