<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRELIMINARY REPORTS SHOW BRISK ONLINE SALES
</P>
<P>
   The first reports on holiday sales for Internet retailers showed
results that surpassed even what earlier this month had seemed to
be hyped-up preseason predictions. The increases came despite
glitches that forced consumers to suffer indignities like access
denial to Web sites and despite holiday gifts that did not arrive
on time as promised.
</P>
<P>
   The figures are preliminary, and even the most optimistic
prediction would be far less than 1 percent of the $2.6 trillion in
retail sales in the United States for the year, leading many
analysts to remain skeptical about the wave of euphoria generated
by the data.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET STOCKS SURGE, TOO
</P>
<P>
   The burgeoning use of the World Wide Web for shopping and stock
trading lifted shares of Internet-related companies. The Nasdaq
composite index, which is heavily weighted toward technology
stocks, rose 17.27 points, or 0.8 percent, to 2,180.30, its fourth
record in six sessions. The Dow Jones industrial average rose 8.76
points, to 9,226.75, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index fell
eight-tenths of a point, to 1,225.49.
</P>
<P>
   PRICES OF TREASURIES REBOUND
</P>
<P>
   Bond prices posted their biggest gain in four weeks as
month-high yields and expectations for low inflation in 1999
attracted buyers. The yield of the benchmark 30-year bond fell to
5.15 percent from 5.21 percent on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   SOCIAL SECURITY CLEARED FOR 2000
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton called the year 2000 challenge ``a stunning
problem'' for computer programmers but said the Social Security
Administration had fixed its computers so that elderly people would
receive their monthly benefits without interruption in 2000. He did
not address the situation at other agencies judged by the White
House to be inadequately prepared for the year 2000, including the
Pentagon, the Energy Department and the agency that runs Medicare
and Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   SICK CALLS COST TWA MILLIONS
</P>
<P>
   Trans World Airlines flight attendants who called in sick over
the holiday weekend caused widespread flight cancellations, the
airline said, which cost the company millions of dollars. TWA said
Monday that service was returning to normal.
</P>
<P>
   RCN TO COMBINE ONLINE OPERATIONS
</P>
<P>
   RCN, which provides telecommunications services in the
northeastern United States, said it would combine its four Internet
service operations into a single concern under the common brand
name RCN.com. Shares of the company rose $7.25, or 54 percent, to
$20.625 on the Nasdaq market.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH KOREA PUNISHES LG SEMICON
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring its determination to reorganize the nation's
biggest conglomerates, the South Korean government stopped banks
from extending new loans to LG Semicon, punishing it for rejecting
a proposal to give Hyundai Electronics control of their merged
computer-chip businesses. South Korea's president, Kim Dae-jung,
will watch closely to see whether LG Semicon lives up to its
promise, a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   GROUP MAKES PITCH FOR LOCAL TV
</P>
<P>
   The Television Bureau of Advertising, which represents local
television broadcasters, is undertaking what is being described as
its first large-scale effort aimed at marketers and agencies to
promote the benefits of running commercials locally rather than
nationally.
</P>
<P>
   RAYTHEON EXPECTS DEAL WITH GREECE
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon, the aerospace and military concern, said that it
expected to complete a $1.1 billion order with Greece for its
Patriot Air Defense System by the end of the year. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
