<SLUG> BC-SYNCOR-FALL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYNCOR'S SHARES DIP 4.5 PERCENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DEBORAH ADAMSON  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Syncor International Corp. lost 4.5 percent of its
stock value Monday on news that it expects a revenue drop of up to
$15 million after losing a contract to a smaller rival.
</P>
<P>
   Syncor closed at $24, down $1.125.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst L. Mitra Ramgopal of Schroder &AMP; Co. in New York said
Syncor didn't go after the contract aggressively because it didn't
want to slash prices to gain market share at the expense of
profitability.
</P>
<P>
   Syncor, a provider of radioactive isotopes used in illuminating
body organs for diagnosis, lost the Novation contract to
Nycomed/Amersham. The $15 million revenue loss is equivalent to 4
percent of Syncor's annual sales.
</P>
<P>
   Novation is the purchasing organization representing the
hospital members of VHA Inc. and University Health Consortium.
</P>
<P>
   Syncor currently has $112 million in business from VHA as a
group, and from the individual members of VHA and University
Health.
</P>
<P>
   Syncor moved quickly to assure investors that it expects to
retain much of that business. Brad Nutter, Syncor's chief operating
officer, said Syncor is confident of keeping the majority of the
business because many of these hospitals currently use Syncor's
management software system and Syncor is more convenient for
hospitals to use on account of its much larger distribution system.
</P>
<P>
   Syncor has 118 pharmacy centers nationwide compared with 26 for
Nycomed. Also, Syncor has the exclusive distribution rights to
Cardiolite, a popular cardiac-imaging agent that represents 40
percent of its sales to VHA and UHC.
</P>
<P>
   And in 1996, when Syncor lost a similar contract, it still
managed to retain 80 percent of the business, Nutter said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
