<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARINE-RAPE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASE'S FORMER MARINE OF THE YEAR CHARGED WITH HAVING SEX WITH
MINOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ED OFFLEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A veteran Marine sergeant at Whidbey Island (Wash.) Naval Air
Station who was named the base's outstanding Marine of the year for
1996 faces a general court-martial on charges he had sexual
relations with a 14-year-old family friend.
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Kenneth Poppy, 28, was charged under four counts of the
Uniform Code of Military Justice after a five-month investigation
by the Naval Criminal Investigative Service and Marine officials,
said Marine spokesman Maj. Stephen Kay.
</P>
<P>
   The charges were filed in October, but not confirmed until
Monday after a formal request by the Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
<P>
   Poppy, an eight-year career Marine, is assigned to the Marine
Air Training Support Group at the Oak Harbor base and works at the
aircraft intermediate maintenance department.
</P>
<P>
   Poppy received the Oak Harbor Rotary Club's Marine of the Year
award on Oct. 11, 1996, after a selection process to evaluate
outstanding military performance and civic contributions among the
base's military personnel.
</P>
<P>
   A native of California, Poppy graduated from boot camp and
combat training in 1990 before receiving advanced training in
aircraft maintenance. He served as a maintenance technician for a
Marine F/A-18 squadron before coming to Oak Harbor in 1995. He was
cited by the Rotary Club as top Marine for participating in the
annual Toys for Tots drive and for volunteer work with the
Washington Trails Association helping maintain hiking trails at
state parks.
</P>
<P>
   Poppy is charged with one specification of Article 120 of the
military code, for having carnal knowledge of a person under the
age of 16; one specification of Article 125, for an act of sodomy;
and 2 specifications of Article 134 of the military code for
indecent acts.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted on all four counts, Poppy could receive a maximum
sentence of 49 years in prison, reduction in rank to private,
forfeiture of all pay and allowances, and a dishonorable discharge,
Kay said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having an affair with a child is not right,'' Poppy's
estranged wife, Corrine Caulfield, said in a phone interview. ``I
hope the military system works the way it is supposed to work.''
</P>
<P>
   The proceeding against Poppy stems from an alleged relationship
between the sergeant and a 14-year-old family friend in the summer
of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Caulfield said she and Poppy separated last January after she
learned her husband had been having an affair with another adult
female. Several months later the other woman approached Caulfield
with allegations of relationships with a third adult and the
14-year-old. Both women then took the information to Marine Corps
officials at Whidbey Island, who in turn requested a probe by naval
criminal investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Poppy remains assigned to Whidbey Island and is not being
confined pending the court-martial, which is scheduled to open Jan.
8 at Camp Pendleton, Calif., Kay said.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Don King, Kay's military lawyer, declined comment Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
