<P>
   (NYT11) KONYA, Turkey -- Dec. 28, 1998 -- TURKEY-RUMI, 12-28
--Every year around this time, the streets of Konya are decorated
with images of whirling dervishes, the Islamic mystics who seek to
commune with the infinite through ecstatic dance. These images mark
the annual festival commemorating Jalaluddin Rumi, who conceived
the dervish dance as part of his lifelong quest for religious
rapture. (Burhan Ozbilici/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) UNDATED -- Dec. 28, 1998 -- MIGRANE-DRUGS, 12-28 --
After going for decades with few available migraine drugs, the 25
million Americans who suffer these monster headaches now have a
wide choice of new remedies including Glaxo Wellcome's Amerge. (New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- Dec. 28, 1998 -- WANAMAKER-ELECTRA, 12-28 --
Zoe Wanamaker, seen recently in New York, plays ``Electra'' in
Frank McGuinness's adaptation of Sophocles' play. It is the role of
Wanamaker's career, and despite the exhaustion of eight shows a
week, she says she is exhilarated. (Librado Romero/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) BOSTON, Mass. -- Dec. 28, 1998 -- ADOPTION-SIBLINGS,
12-28 -- Hugo P., the pseudonym given to the five-year old boy at
right by the Massachusetts courts, plays with his six-year-old
sister, Gloria, a name also given by the courts. Hugo's lawyers,
who have worked to keep Hugo and Gloria together in the foster
mother's house, have asked the Supreme Court to review the case and
use it to declare a new national rule that brothers and sisters
have a constitutional right to be together. (Kirsten Elstner/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) DENVER -- Dec. 28, 1998 -- DENVER-DOWNTOWN-2, 12-28 --
Visitors look at the view from a newly constructed loft in DenverUs
historic downtown. Within a one-mile radius of the station,
Denver's beaux arts historic core, the city is halfway through a
decade-long downtown investment of $2 billion. In addition to a
sports complex, an aquarium and urban shopping complexes, over
1,000 apartments are now being built or converted downtown, more
than the total of the last four years. (Kevin Moloney/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) DENVER -- Dec. 28, 1998 -- DENVER-DOWNTOWN, 12-28 -- A
bustling scene near Denver's Union station. Within a one-mile
radius of the station, Denver's beaux arts historic core, the city
is halfway through a decade-long downtown investment of $2 billion.
In addition to a sports complex, an aquarium and urban shopping
complexes, over 1,000 apartments are now being built or converted
downtown, more than the total of the last four years. (Kevin
Moloney/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Dec. 28, 1998 -- BIJAN-FASHION-2, 12-28 -- By
his own staunch admission, fashion designer Bijan does not
subscribe to trends in men's wear, sticking instead with classics
like windowpane wool suits and cashmere sweaters and jackets in a
plethora of colors. (Susan Farley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Dec. 28, 1998 -- BIJAN-FASHION, 12-28 --
Fashion designer Bijan Pakzad will not discuss who his customers
are, however this wall at his opulent Fifth Avenue store is covered
with clocks, each bearing the name of one of his most loyal
shoppers. (Susan Farley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 28, 1998 --SOCSEC-Y2K, 12-28 --
President Clinton walks to the podium after being introduced by
Pauline Johnson, 90, a Social Security recipient, at the White
House on Monday. Clinton assured Americans there would be no delay
in payment of Social Security checks in the year 2000 because the
responsible federal computers have been certified free of the
millennium bug. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) SAUSALITO, Calif. -- Dec. 28, 1998 -- SCI-ORNISH-DIET,
12-28 --Dr. Dean Ornish, developer of a program that promises to
reverse heart disease and help people live better, in his office.
Cut the fat, eliminate the caffeine and learn to love vegetables,
says Ornish, whose rigid regimen for a healthy- heart regimen also
involves yoga, exercise and cultivating close relationships.
(Terrence McCarthy/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) BOSTON -- Dec. 28, 1998 -- PLUNDERED-ARTIFACTS-BOS, 12-28
-- Cornelius Vermeule III, the Boston Museum of Fine Arts' longtime
curator of classical antiquities who retired in 1996, is at the
center of the storm over the museum's ethics. Like curators of his
generation, who scoured the world for prized pieces long before the
plundering of ancient grave sites was officially proscribed, he
continued to buy artifacts as if the rules had never changed. (Bill
Greene/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
