<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9394 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMBODIA-U.S.-NYT &LR;      12-28 0223
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMBODIA-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. SEEKS ACCOUNTABILITY FOR KHMER ROUGE DEFECTORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: With CAMBODIA-DEFECTORS) 
(rl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The State Department said on Monday it hoped that
the ``apparent surrender'' of two former Khmer Rouge to the
Cambodian government would lead to some form of justice.
</P>
<P>
   A statement released by the department said the United States
would work to try to ensure that there would be ``accountability
for Nuon Chea and Kheiu Samphan, as well as for the other, most
senior, Khmer Rouge leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We trust that no actions will be taken by any party that could
preclude achieving this goal,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Hun Sen of Cambodia forswore vengeance against
the two men Monday, saying he would welcome them at a meeting in
his home on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In April, only days before the death of Pol Pot, the senior
leader of the Khmer Rouge, the United States began trying to plan
to capture him and his associates. After his death, the United
States asked the U.N. Security Council to set up a tribunal to try
surviving Khmer Rouge leaders on charges of genocide.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a panel appointed by U.N. Secretary General Kofi
Annan traveled to Cambodia to research how best to create such a
tribunal. Its report is expected next month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-28-98 2133EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
