<HEADER>
A9411 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BANKSTOX-SFCHRON &LR;      12-28 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKSTOX-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Bank Stock Believer  &HT;       
 By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michael Stead has two traits rare among mutual fund managers:
the shrewdness to sense when stocks could fall and the bluntness to
say so.
</P>
<P>
   Stead manages SIFE Trust Fund, the 37-year-old Walnut Creek fund
that specializes in bank stocks. Six months ago, when bank shares
were near the end of a three-year run that had seen some stocks
triple in value, he Stead  &LR; sounded the alarm.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with Bloomberg News in June, Stead warned that
global financial turmoil threatened to trigger an across-the-board
plunge in equities that could hit bank stocks especially hard.
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly what happened. From the end of July to the middle
of October, as economic collapse in Asia and Russia spilled over
into U.S. markets, major bank stock indexes lost more than a
quarter of their value, significantly worse than the fall in the
broader U.S. stocks indexes.
</P>
<P>
   Stead's fund didn't escape the mayhem. It dropped about 23
percent during the period.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, bank stocks have climbed back as investors' fears
about global financial panic receded. That's helped SIFE regain
more than half the ground it lost.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Stead says, bank stocks could continue to gain.
</P>
<P>
   The British-born fund manager still casts a skeptical eye on the
stock market as a whole. The global economy remains shaky, Stead
stressed in a recent interview. Problems around the world are
likely to take a toll on the profits of U.S. companies, he
believes.
</P>
<P>
   But even after the recent rebound from the steep drop, some
banks still represent decent values, he said. With interest rates
at low levels and exposure to global problems limited, bank
earnings should grow in the high single digits in 1999, Stead
he &LR; predicted, far above profit growth projected for the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have to be invested, you want to be over-weighted in
the financial sector,'' he said. ``There are still some good buys
available.
</P>
<P>
   Stead said the fall in bank stocks ``was absolutely necessary.''
But, he added, ``as time goes by, investors will come to realize
that the sell-off was overdone.''
</P>
<P>
   He also thinks that the bank merger juggernaut will continue,
boosting share prices as institutions look to cut costs and build
sprawling networks.
</P>
<P>
   Amid a roller-coaster market for bank stocks, SIFE's total
return for the first 11 months of 1998 was positive, though barely
so. The fund eked out a 0.25 percent return when dividends and
capital gains are added in. That's a big comedown from the heady
annual returns of 27.7 percent or more from 1995 through 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Some 40 mutual funds specialize in financial stocks, according
to Morningstar, the Chicago company that tracks funds. So far this
year, they have gained 4.40 percent, less than the average 7.38
percent rise of all stock mutual funds and way below the 24.12
percent rise in the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500.
</P>
<P>
   But, over a longer period, financial funds have excelled. In
recent years, as banks benefited from a healthy economy, low
interest rates and improved efficiency in their own operations,
their stocks soared.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past three years, the average annual 24.86 jump in
financial sector funds handily beat the average 11.07 rise of all
mutual funds and nearly matched the increase rise &LR; in the S&AMP;P 500.
</P>
<P>
   With a little more than $1 billion in assets, SIFE is now a big
player in the bank stock market, though it's still dwarfed by
mutual funds operated by groups such as Fidelity Investments and
John Hancock.
</P>
<P>
   Stead, who is in his mid-40s, joined SIFE in 1995 after a
17-year career as a banker with Citibank and Bank of America in
Latin America and Asia. SIFE's manager picks stocks with the help
of Scott Edgar, his research director, and analyst/ trader Laurie
Buntain.
</P>
<P>
   Working out of a low-slung brick building in a Walnut Creek
office park, the three look for banks that are both profitable and
safe _ meaning they provide a 15 percent return on equity and have
plenty of funds set aside to cover potential loan problems.
</P>
<P>
   Using those criteria, Stead and his team have put together a
list of 100 banks they would like to own. Then they look at price.
Of the 100, about 42 are trading below their real value based on
earnings potential.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest positions in SIFE's portfolio are giant regional
banks focused on consumers plus small- and medium-size businesses.
His favorites include Fleet Financial Group, which operates in New
England and the Northeast; and North Carolina's Wachovia Corp.,
based in the Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   Other big holdings include Bank of New York Corp. and State
Street Corp., both of which occupy specialty niches as fund
custodians and administrators for other institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Of the giant New York banks with extensive foreign operations,
Chase Manhattan Corp. is the only institution in which SIFE
maintains a big position. Chase, Stead said, is more in the
regional than money-center banking mold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conservative and cautious is what we want,'' Stead said.
</P>
<P>
   While Stead believes bank stocks still have a little more
mileage in them, he's quick to acknowledge their vulnerability to
the business cycle. Sometime in the not too distant future, he
warned, the economy will slow, causing loans to go sour and making
revenue hard to find.
</P>
<P>
   When times are good, bankers claim they've got all potential
risks under control. Stead thinks that's nonsense, and he points to
the loans some banks made to speculative investment funds or to
borrowers in such trouble spots as Russia and Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   Said Stead: ``Time and again, there are those who try to
convince others, `This time, it's different.' Well, it's never
different.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-28-98 2153EST &QL; 
