r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONEYBAG-SFCHRON &LR;      12-28 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Scholarships May Be Taxable  &HT;       
 By Arthur M. Louis  
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; QUESTION: &LR;  I recently completed graduate school. I was fortunate
enough to receive scholarships and grants this year totaling more
than $15,000. I've been told that I might owe taxes on some of the
money. Please say it isn't so. But if it is, what is taxable and
what isn't?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ANSWER: &LR;  Internal Revenue Service spokesman Jesse Weller says
you won't be taxed as long as you were a candidate for a degree and
all the money you received was used strictly to pay tuition, fees
and other required school expenses. That includes money spent on
books, supplies and equipment necessary to complete your course of
study.
</P>
<P>
   Any money used to pay what the IRS considers ``incidental''
expenses is taxable. That includes room and board _ even in a
university-operated dormitory. It also includes travel expenses
between home and school.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, if you got any money with a quid pro quo attached _
for example, a stipulation that you perform research or laboratory
work in the future _ that money is taxable.
</P>
<P>
   Getting a Late Start
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am 57 years old and live from paycheck to paycheck. Aside
from an investment fund in which my employer sets aside $480 per
year for my retirement, I have no investments, assets, savings or
anything. Is it too late for me to think about accumulating the
money I'll need for retirement?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: It's not too late _ but at this point you can't expect
spectacular results. You indicate that you have trouble saving
money _ but to build a substantial retirement fund you must save as
much as you can as early as you can. Age 57 is not the ideal time
to start.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco financial planner Norm Boone suggests that you
continue working beyond age 65 _ even beyond 75, if you are up to
it. The longer you wait for Social Security, the larger your
monthly payments will be. In the meantime you will continue to
receive a salary that might allow you to build other sources of
retirement income.
</P>
<P>
   For example, you ought to divert some of your salary to a Roth
Individual Retirement Account, which you can set up at a bank or
other financial institution. You can contribute up to $2,000 a year
to a Roth, and any money you earn from your investments will be
tax-free.
</P>
<P>
   Also, ask your employer to increase his retirement
contributions. It's nice that he has a retirement fund _ many
companies don't _ but the $480 a year he sets aside for you each
year is peanuts. If he won't increase the payments, perhaps he will
let you contribute part of your paycheck to a tax-deferred savings
account. It won't hurt to ask.
</P>
<P>
   Medical Savings
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am self-employed. I would like to set up a Medical Savings
Account to help cover medical expenses for myself and my family. My
broker said they don't offer this kind of account. Can you tell me
how to proceed?
</P>
<P>
   A: You can set up a Medical Savings Account through Merrill
Lynch _ to name just one broker _ or through an insurance company.
Ask an insurance agent to find a provider for you. Or, if you would
rather deal directly with an insurer, you might want to check out
the offerings of Medical Savings Insurance Co., of Indianapolis,
which appears to be the leading MSA vendor in California. Its
toll-free telephone number is (888) 696-9663.
</P>
<P>
   Medical Savings Accounts, created by Congress in 1996, are a
great deal for consumers. They allow self-employed individuals or
employees of small companies _ those with fewer than 50 workers _
to set aside tax-exempt funds to pay medical expenses.
</P>
<P>
   To qualify for an MSA, you must be covered by high-deductible
health insurance. Congress specified high-deductible insurance
because it wanted to encourage small businesses to start these
programs. High-deductible insurance costs less than low-deductible
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   As of January 1, the minimum deductible that qualifies for the
MSA program will be $1,550 per year for single individuals and
$3,050 for families. The maximum amount a family may deposit in a
MSA each year is 75 percent of the amount of the deductible. For
singles, the limit is 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   You can use the funds in your MSA to pay your deductible
expenses. Once you exceed the deductible, the insurance kicks in.
</P>
<P>
   The money you deposit in an MSA is exempt from taxes, and any
earnings in your account accumulate tax-free _ just as they do in a
Roth Individual Retirement Account. You can invest the money in
stocks, mutual funds, bonds, money-market funds _ whatever suits
you.
</P>
<P>
   Another neat feature, if you are self-employed, is that you can
deduct a portion of the premiums you pay for health insurance. For
the 1998 tax year, the deduction is 45 percent, and for 1999 it
rises to 60 percent. This deduction is not available to members of
group MSA plans.
</P>
<P>
   There is no time limit for using the money in your MSA. If you
are lucky enough to enjoy good health, the money can remain in your
account year after year.
</P>
<P>
   If you wish, you may withdraw funds to pay nonmedical expenses.
However, you must pay taxes on these withdrawals at your regular
tax rate. If you are less than 65 years old, you also must pay a 15
percent penalty.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send questions about how to manage your money to moneybag(at
sign)sfgate.com, or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, Calif., 94103
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
