<SLUG> BC-MA-AREA-CODES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EASTERN MASSACHUSETTS MAY GET FOUR NEW AREA CODES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Less than a year after consumers endured the cost and
confusion of adding two new area codes in eastern Massachusetts,
state officials are now laying the groundwork for adding four more.
</P>
<P>
   Officials confirmed Monday that hearings will begin next month
on the best way to increase the number of area codes in eastern
Massachusetts from four to eight. The area-code expansion could
take place in a little over a year.
</P>
<P>
   The officials portrayed the planning process as a safeguard in
case efforts to conserve phone numbers and avoid the need for new
codes are not sufficient, but other sources familiar with the
process say the odds are strong that new area codes will be needed
by the end of 1999 or early 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The battle over how the new area codes should be created is
likely to be even more controversial than it was with the 781 and
978 codes. The problem is particularly acute in Boston, since
carving a new area code out of 617 would probably require the city
to be split between two different area codes.
</P>
<P>
   Janet Besser, head of the state Department of Telecommunicatons
and Energy, said she is still hopeful that conservation measures
and new technologies will significantly delay the need for new area
codes. But she said it was prudent to lay the groundwork now so
that if the conservation measures fail to work the state is ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be prepared. We don't want to be scrambling late
next year,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Two other sources said the conservation picture is bleaker than
Besser is admitting and the likelihood that the new area codes will
be needed is strong. The sources said the Federal Communications
Commission has limited what states can do to ease the phone number
crunch and technological solutions to the problem are still only
theoretical.
</P>
<P>
   The number crunch is not easy to understand. There is strong
consumer demand for second phone lines, faxes, pagers, and cellular
phones, but not enough to exhaust the supply of numbers in the
existing area codes.
</P>
<P>
   The real problem is the way phone numbers are distributed to
companies competing in the local phone market. A company needs at
least one exchange code _ the first three digits of a seven-digit
phone number _ in each rate center in which it is competing. A rate
center is the geographic area on which rates are based.
</P>
<P>
   Numbers are released in blocks of 10,000. So a company wishing
to compete in each of the 202 rate centers in eastern Massachusetts
would draw more than 2 million numbers, even if it needed only a
couple hundred.
</P>
<P>
   The system of distributing numbers originated when AT&AMP;T was the
only phone company in existence and could parcel out numbers to
consumers as needed. Now that there are hundreds of
telecommunication companies competing for customers, numbers are
being gobbled up in a wasteful manner. The system is in overload.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts' dilemma is not unique. California has more than
20 area codes and nearly all of them are in jeopardy of running out
of numbers. Over the last five years, 82 new area codes have been
added nationally.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not using numbers as efficiently as we should, but it's
really nobody's fault,'' said James Deak, the Lockheed Martin IMS
official in charge of area code relief planning for the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   All four eastern Massachusetts area codes _ 617, 781, 508 and
978 _ have been declared in jeopardy of running out of numbers, and
rationing of numbers has been in place since last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Last May, Besser said she wanted her agency to investigate ways
to conserve numbers and issue corrective orders by midsummer. But
the problem has proven more difficult than she initially thought,
both because the agency lacks the resources and expertise to
evaluate conservation measures and because the FCC is trying to
address the problem on a national level.
</P>
<P>
   Besser said her agency will continue to explore number
conservation measures, particularly issuing numbers in smaller
increments and reducing the number of rate centers so companies
would need fewer numbers to compete. The problem with rate center
consolidation is that it would require a revamping of local calling
areas and a restructuring of the entire rate system for local
calls.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, next month the agency will start hearings on
how to create four additional area codes. Last year, the state
decided to split 617 and 508 to create 781 and 978. It could do
that again, thus creating eight relatively small area codes and
allowing people to continue dialing calls as they do currently.
</P>
<P>
   The other approach, and one that is slowly gaining favor around
the country, is to overlay the new area codes over the existing
ones. That would mean any new number issued would be in the new
area code but existing customers would keep their old numbers and
area codes.
</P>
<P>
   The disadvantage to this approach is that consumers would have
to dial at least 10 numbers on every call and neighbors on the same
street could have phone numbers with different area codes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
