<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KAISER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 California to Rule On Kaiser's Viagra Policy  &HT;       
 By Tom Abate 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The State Department of Corporations will announce by the end of
the week whether the Kaiser Foundation Health Plan can exclude
Viagra and other sexual dysfunction remedies from the list of drugs
it normally covers.
</P>
<P>
   The decision will be closely watched by six other California
health insurers that have similar applications pending. Like many
insurers nationwide, they fear that Viagra and other so-called
lifestyle-enhancing drugs will add millions in new expenses at a
time when the whole system is under pressure to reduce costs.
</P>
<P>
   In what amounts to the bureaucratic equivalent of a tease,
Corporations Commissioner Dale E. Bonner said yesterday he has made
up his mind on the issue, but was keeping his counsel for the next
few days while he makes sure his reasoning is defensible.
</P>
<P>
   ``This department has never allowed a (health) plan to exclude
coverage for a prescription drug that is deemed medically
necessary,'' Bonner said. ``On the other hand, we have to look at
the reality we live in, with wonder drug after wonder drug coming
onto the market, creating a lot of concern for the health plans and
for the enrollees, who expect a cure for everything they get.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonner's tantalizing comments came during an interview on a more
mundane but related issue.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, he announced that the Department of Corporations had
ended an investigation into whether Kaiser management had pressured
its doctors not to prescribe Viagra between April, when the drug
came on the market, and September, when Kaiser agreed to put it on
the list of drugs it routinely pays for.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser admitted no wrongdoing but agreed to pay the state
$250,000 to cover the cost of the investigation. Kaiser also agreed
to notify any members who had to pay for their Viagra prescriptions
during the five-month period in question that they can ask the
health plan to consider reimbursing them for the pills, which cost
about $64 for an eight-pill monthly dose.
</P>
<P>
   ``At no time in the past or in the future will the health plan
interfere with doctors' discretion to prescribe Viagra,'' Kaiser
spokesman Tom Debley said yesterday in response to the settlement
with the state.
</P>
<P>
   But the question of what Kaiser did or didn't do between April
and September clearly pales before the issue of whether insurers in
California will routinely have to pay for Viagra and similar drugs
in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser was the first California health plan to ask the state for
permission to stop paying for Viagra which, it has estimated, could
add a dollar to the monthly cost of each of the 5.5 million people
it insures in the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are asking whether the cost of these drugs should be borne
by the user or spread across the entire member base,'' said Debley.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser has put the same question to other states in which it
operates. So far, Debley said, 12 states, including Massachusetts,
Colorado and Oregon, as well as the District of Columbia, have
allowed it to stop paying for Viagra. Two states, New York and
Connecticut, have ordered it to keep paying for the potency pill.
And California and Washington are still mulling the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Bonner, whose role as commissioner of corporations gives him the
authority to make the decision for California insurers, said he
would not be influenced by what other states have done. But a
source close to the issue said Kaiser is expecting Bonner to rule
that it must pay for Viagra.
</P>
<P>
   Six other insurers have similar requests pending before the
Department of Corporations. They are: Blue Cross of California,
PacifiCare, Cigna, HealthNet, Aetna and Greater Pacific.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
