<HEADLINE>
BRUINS STAY ON THE ROAD TO RUIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Bruins are only halfway through this four-game
swing, but so far it has all the earmarks of the road trip from
hell.
</P>
<P>
   After a less-than-stellar performance in a loss to the Islanders
Saturday night, followed by logistical nightmares during the
journey here, the Bruins' fortunes got even worse Monday night as
they were clobbered by the Capitals, 5-1, at the MCI Center.
</P>
<P>
   Boston's third straight loss matched its longest losing streak
of the season (Oct. 19-24 to Phoenix, Anaheim, and New Jersey), and
it was just the third time this season that the Bruins have given
up five goals (they're 0-2-1 when they do so).
</P>
<P>
   For the second straight game, the Bruins dug themselves a hole
in the first period. In the 4-2 loss to the Islanders Saturday
night, Boston had to fight back after falling behind, 2-0. Monday
night, the hole was even deeper as the Bruins trailed, 3-0, heading
into the first intermission as Washington outshot Boston by a
whopping 18-8.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's first goal came less than half a minute into the
contest, with Peter Bondra benefiting from a fortuitous bounce.
</P>
<P>
   Michal Pivonka, down in the left corner with Jason Allison,
attempted to throw the puck out to Bondra. His pass went off Ray
Bourque before finding its mark on Bondra's stick. Bondra, off to
the right of goalie Byron Dafoe, fired a shot that went off the
netminder's shoulder, bounced up high, then glanced off Dafoe's
back before falling into the net at the 24-second mark.
</P>
<P>
   The Capitals boosted the advantage to two at 11:28 on a goal by
Ken Klee. James Black set up the score with a pass to Klee at the
right point that the defenseman one-timed into the net for his
fourth of the season.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared the momentum would swing Boston's way despite the
score. After fending off a superb Washington power play that
yielded five shots but no goals, the Bruins thought they had pulled
within a goal at 15:32. Anson Carter won a battle along the boards
in the neutral zone and skated the puck down the right side into
the circle. He saw Steve Heinze heading for the net so he gunned
the pass there.
</P>
<P>
   Heinze beat goalie Rick Tabaracci with a forehander inside the
right post, but a replay overturned the score, as Heinze was ruled
in the crease before the puck's arrival.
</P>
<P>
   The Capitals made it 3-0 when they scored just 39 seconds after
the disallowed goal. Andrei Nikolishin, in the right corner, dished
the puck between the legs of linemate Brian Bellows to Sergei
Gonchar, who was alone in front and banged in a forehand shot at
16:11.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to find a spark, coach Pat Burns scrambled his
lines, putting Joe Thornton with Dmitri Khristich and Sergei
Samsonov. That combination resulted in a goal, with Thornton
setting up Khristich at 10:50 of the second period.
</P>
<P>
   Khristich took Thornton's pass and tried a backhander that
Tabaracci stopped but couldn't contain. Khristich kept whacking
away, and on his fourth try, he finally got it underneath the
goalie and across the line for Boston's first goal.
</P>
<P>
   But less than four minutes later, the Capitals made it a
three-goal lead again, with Steve Konowalchuk beating Dafoe from
the left post. Bondra, in the right circle, dished the puck down
low to Pivonka behind the net to Dafoe's left. Pivonka fired the
puck through the crease to Konowalchuk for the 4-1 lead at 14:40.
</P>
<P>
   Black made it 5-1 at 11:34 of the third. Klee fired the puck out
from the right corner and Black stuck his stick out, deflecting it
under the crossbar and over Dafoe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
