<HEADLINE>
POWER HOUSE: ARIZONA NUCLEAR PLANT'S OUTPUT IS TOPS IN NATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL MULLER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINTERSBURG, Ariz. _ The reactor is shut down, but it glows
brightly anyway, filling the water with a shimmering blue
incadescence.
</P>
<P>
   It's called the Cerenkov effect _ particles moving faster than
the speed of light, escaping from uranium-laden fuel rods.
</P>
<P>
   Physics 101, but spooky.
</P>
<P>
   Nervous glances are exchanged on a catwalk just 30 feet above
the containment pool. Below the visitors, workers on a movable
platform are refueling the core, gently lowering fresh rods into
the reactor's dark heart.
</P>
<P>
   Not many have ventured this far. The containment building at
Unit 3 of the Palo Verde Nuclear Generating Station has 7-foot
concrete walls, reinforced with steel rods as thick as a man's
forearm.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors enter through a bank-vault style air lock, after
donning protective clothing _ smocks, rubber gloves and booties,
hoods and hard hats. Radiation detectors dangle from their necks. A
technician tells them in flat tones not to touch anything, or
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the reactor building, security is tight. To enter the
compound, visitors pass through three checkpoints, supersensitive
metal detectors and a bomb sniffer. Armed guards roam the halls.
</P>
<P>
   It all sends an incontrovertible message: This is the real deal.
Mother Nature's laws are being bent here, and nobody's fooling
around.
</P>
<P>
   Here at Palo Verde, they sell fission and fission accessories.
</P>
<P>
   And business is booming.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Palo Verde's three units generated more electricity
than any power plant of any kind in the United States _ 29.5
billion kilowatt &UR; hours. That's 2 billion kilowatt hours more than
the Grand Coulee Dam.
</P>
<P>
   Palo Verde should produce 30 billion kilowatt hours in 1998, a
first for any U.S. power plant.
</P>
<P>
   Production costs at Palo Verde have dropped almost in half, from
2.49 cents per kilowatt hour in 1990 to 1.33 cents in 1997. A
kilowatt hour is the amount of electricity it takes to light 10
100-watt light bulbs for an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Operation and maintenance costs also have plummeted, to $325
million in 1997 from a high of $422 million in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Palo Verde _ 50 miles west of downtown Phoenix _ promises to be
productive until its 2026 decommissioning date, and perhaps beyond,
but other plants aren't having the same success.
</P>
<P>
   As the electricity industry is deregulated, the nation's nuclear
power industry is shrinking. The harsh economics that come from
competition won't leave room for plants that are poorly run or
don't generate enough power to cover their costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think there will be some plants that shut down,'' said
Bill Stewart, who is widely credited with turning
middle-of-the-road and underachieving Palo Verde into an industry
star. Stewart ran Palo Verde from 1994 through 1996 and now heads
generation for Arizona Public Service Co., which owns 29.1 percent
of the plant.
</P>
<P>
   ``The single biggest (factor) is the economics,'' Stewart said.
``Smaller plants tend to have more difficulty.''
</P>
<P>
   The numbers bear him out. Although more than 100 nuclear power
plants are operating across the nation, no new plant has been built
since the Three Mile Island accident in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Half the nation's nuclear plants are scheduled to be
decommissioned by 2020, and there are no new plants on the drawing
boards. About 27 units will be closed before their time, mainly
because of economics, &UR; according to projections by the Energy
Information Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Although two nuclear plants have been acquired by new owners
(one was Three Mile Island's undamaged twin), they were sold for a
fraction of their original value. The sale prices also were
inflated because they included the price of fuel contracts.
</P>
<P>
   So what does this mean for the future of nuclear power?
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who claims to have a crystal ball on this one is a
charlatan,'' said Alan Nogee, energy program director for the Union
of Concerned Scientists.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very uncertain, and the reason is you have a huge range
in performance in the U.S. nuclear fleet, and you also have plants
that have changed very quickly, from good performers into poor
performers, and a few that have gone the other way.''
</P>
<P>
   Nogee said plants can be goosed into better production over the
short term at the cost of long-term health.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really need to demonstrate that kind of improvement for a
period of years, before we're willing to take it to the bank,''
Nogee said, ``especially in a deregulated environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Before more plants can be built, Stewart points out, the
public's perception of nuclear power must be changed.
</P>
<P>
   The industry got off to a good start in the early 1970s, with
promises of cheap, clean energy for generations to come. But then
came accidents at Three Mile Island in 1979 and at Chernobyl in
1986. The public lost faith in nuclear power, if not the
willingness to gobble electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Although nations like France, Japan and China have accepted
nuclear power as a necessity, Americans are still wary, and have
the luxury of abundant fossil fuels.
</P>
<P>
   But there is hope for the nuclear industry, especially with
growing pressure to reduce greenhouse gases and protect the
environment, said Leighann Marshall, a Nuclear Energy Institute
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nuclear power plants are the largest source of emission-free
energy we have in this country,'' Marshall said. ``They also happen
to be the second-cheapest source of energy we have.'' Coal is the
cheapest.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists have been slow to embrace nuclear power plants
as an alternative, mostly because of the high-level radioactive
waste they produce in the form of spent fuel rods. Many aren't
willing to trade one environmental problem for another.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, experts say, is that the Department of Energy has
dragged its feet in building a permanent storage facility for
high-level radioactive waste at Yucca Mountain, Nev. The issue also
has turned into a political quagmire, as Nevada's elected officials
have battled against the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a technical problem, it's a political problem,''
Marshall said. ``Other countries are (storing waste), and they're
doing it very successfully.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the industry is changing. Companies with
expertise and purchasing clout are expected to acquire nuclear
plants with an eye toward turning a profit. And a breed of newer,
cheaper, smaller nuclear plants could spring up after deregulation
shakes out.
</P>
<P>
   ``In about 10 years, I wouldn't be surprised, for example, to
see someone, somewhere, propose building a new plant on the same
site of an old plant,'' Nogee said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Palo Verde is producing at record power levels.
Refueling outages are shorter than ever, and the plant is running
more efficiently with fewer people.
</P>
<P>
   That's a far cry from the 1980s, when the plant was being
criticized for cost overruns and its $9.3 billion price tag, and
APS was raising electric rates to cover the cost.
</P>
<P>
   Though he likes to spread the credit around, insiders attribute
much of Palo Verde's success to Stewart, who was brought in from
Virginia Power in 1994 to pull Palo Verde out of the doldrums.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, APS was doing a corporate ``re-engineering,'' a
politically correct term for layoffs. Stewart, a no-nonsense
executive who learned the trade on nuclear submarines in the 1960s,
convinced top management to end the layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Palo Verde was kind of semi in the ditch, both operationally
and regulatory wise,'' Stewart said, ``and people were being lined
up to be let go. My initial efforts were just to stop all that, you
know, let's take stock of where we are and what the heck we are
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, said he ended all the ``sidebar circus stuff'' and told
workers, ``We all know we have to get the units up, we all know we
have to do a good job. And you're free to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the way, I'm not bringing in a bunch of my buddies to help
me. I'm going with you. You guys, you know you have your jobs, and
if you want 'em you got 'em and just help make this thing work.''
</P>
<P>
   The results have been impressive.
</P>
<P>
   While Palo Verde's production has gone up, costs have gone down.
Since 1994, when Stewart joined APS, the utility's rates have
decreased 8.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The plant has received two straight top rankings from the
Institute of Nuclear Power Operations, and has fallen off the
Nuclear Regulatory Commission's radar screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Stewart) is one of those rare individuals,'' said Jim Rhodes,
who worked with Stewart at Virginia Power and now serves as chief
of the institute.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the ability to really have knowledge of the details . .
. but also can keep (the) big picture in mind at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is hard to do.'' &QL; 
Bill Muller can be reached at 444-8178 or at bill.muller(at)pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
