<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`INSIDE STUFF' SUCCUMBS TO THE OLD STUFF
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On pre-lockout nights at NBA Entertainment in
Secaucus, N.J., satellite dishes and fiber-optic links used to pull
in every game. ``Loggers'' charted each dunk, 3-point shot, rebound
and no-look pass to help producers create features for NBC, TNT and
TBS's studio shows and programs like ``Inside Stuff,'' highlights
and repackaged versions of the games for more than 100 global
markets and home videos such as the annual National Basketball
Association championship tape.
</P>
<P>
   Not much of that is happening now, as NBA Entertainment has
shifted to feeding oldies footage and classic games to hungry
international markets (and the new NBA Store on Fifth Avenue) and
Women's NBA features to ``Inside Stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   The league's video arm is also developing an IMAX film shot
during last season's finals, an animated series and an all-NBA
channel for DirecTV (which would probably carry fresh sitcoms like
``Honey, My Cell Phone's Stuck to My Ear,'' starring Patrick Ewing,
if it were in operation today).
</P>
<P>
   And the troupe of loggers remains employed, dipping into history
by charting plays from games played during Commissioner Larry
O'Brien's reign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not as busy as we'd like to be, but we're not sitting
around,'' said Adam Silver, senior president of NBA Entertainment.
``We're also developing a potential promotional plan to restart the
season.''
</P>
<P>
   The flood of NBA highlights that was a reliable element of local
and national sportscasts has evaporated, forcing producers to show
more college basketball, National Football League and National
Hockey League clips. The bank-busting free-agent signings in
baseball filled time for a while, and the American Basketball
League got more highlight play until it died last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an hourlong `SportsCenter,' there were 10, 12, 14 minutes
of NBA highlights, so it's a good chunk,'' said Norby Williamson, a
senior coordinating producer of ESPN. ``We're not sitting around
saying, `How are we going to fill the time?' This has forced us to
reinvent ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the time devoted to the NBA is taken up with lockout
news, but there are few negotiation visuals and not much news. So
besides adding highlights from other sports, ``Sportscenter'' has
filled time with a five-part interview with Bob Knight, the Indiana
basketball coach; a series on the greatest NFL wild-card playoff
games, and more player features.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've turned up the burners on college basketball,'' said John
Terenzio, executive producer of Fox Sports News. ``Normally, we're
not that intense on college basketball until after Jan. 1.''
</P>
<P>
   FSN has chosen not to add more hockey highlights, but has
shifted to weeknight NFL analysis, up from three nights last year.
It also landed a coup last week _ a rare interview with
Commissioner David Stern.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lockout forced us to be a better news organization,''
Terenzio said.
</P>
<P>
   The 24-hour CNN/SI has survived the lockout, despite being a
giant maw for highlights. ``I think this gives us an opportunity to
do more storytelling,'' said Steve Robinson, the managing editor.
Losing NBA clips has let the cable service add more feature
packages and highlights from other sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in spite of all the polls and surveys that show people
couldn't care less about the lockout, I'm sure people miss seeing
the highlights,'' Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   If the season is canceled _ the NBA Board of Governors could
vote to do so on Jan. 7 _ producers may have to be at their most
creative in February, when the NFL dries up, and baseball spring
training games have not yet begun.
</P>
<P>
   ``With no NBA, February will be as slow as can be,'' Terenzio
said.
</P>
<P>
   This has also been a slow time for NBA announcers. After a
year's hiatus, Marv Albert has been awaiting his return to
basketball ``I can't wait,'' he said. ``I'm very anxious. I really
miss it. It looks like there's finally a sense of urgency.''
</P>
<P>
   Memories of '58
</P>
<P>
   Forty years ago Tuesday, Bob Wolff provided one of the radio
calls of Baltimore's 23-17 overtime victory over the New York
Giants in the NFL title game. ``My seat was low and on the 20-yard
line, so I couldn't see the yard lines too well,'' Wolff, the
sports anchor of Long Island's News 12 station, said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end, all the action took place at the other end of the
field,'' Wolff said. ``But what jumped out was Johnny Unitas'
pinpoint passing. It looked like he'd never miss. His confidence
and authority grew and grew.''
</P>
<P>
   David Plaut, producer of a terrific NFL Films documentary on the
game (which has been seen on ESPN and ESPN2), said: ``I was only 5
in 1958, and all I cared about was Superman and Zorro. But a game
like this is an epic.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC's TV feed was unavailable, but the documentary used film
shot by two companies from opposite sides of the stadium, allowing
Plaut to show plays from reverse angles. The vintage film was
accompanied by the verbal passion of players like Sam Huff, the
candor of Frank Gifford and the wit of Art Donovan, who recalled
telling Gino Marchetti, his Colts teammate, ``If we lose this, what
a mistravesty of justice.'' Marchetti said, ``You're right,
fatso.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
