<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-TIGERS-D-BACKS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D-BACKS GIVE UP ON GARCIA  
 OUTFIELDER TRADED FOR TIGERS' GONZALEZ 
</HEADLINE>
  TRADE-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Their thirst for improvement still unsatisfied, the Diamondbacks
continue to drink from the cask of experience, not the fountain of
youth.
</P>
<P>
   The team added another veteran presence on Monday with the
acquisition of 31-year-old corner outfielder Luis Gonzalez in a
trade with the Detroit Tigers for Karim Garcia, a 23-year-old
outfielder who was taken in the expansion draft but whose world of
promise appeared to be shrinking.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona also will receive cash considerations from the Tigers,
presumably to help with the $2.2 million
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez is scheduled to receive as part of a two-year free
agent deal signed with Detroit in December 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, who throws right-handed but hits from the left side,
had a .267 average with a career-high 23 home runs and 71 RBIs as
Detroit's primary left fielder in 1998. But he saw increasing
evidence that he would be the odd man out in Detroit, with Bobby
Higginson moving from right to left and 23-year-old Juan
Encarnacion taking over in right.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez heard rumors he might be headed to Seattle, then
Arizona stepped in ``and caught me by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really happy to be going to a contending team, one that
has taken a lot of steps forward in the off-season, particularly
with its pitching staff.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, who began his career in the National League with
Houston in 1990 and spent two seasons with the Chicago Cubs,
returns to the NL on a club full of senior citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Pitchers Andy Benes, Randy Johnson, Gregg Olson, Armando
Reynoso, Todd Stottlemyre and Greg Swindell, infielders Jay Bell
and Matt Williams and outfielders Steve Finley and Bernard Gilkey
all are older than 30.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez is looking forward to a reunion with Finley, with whom
he played in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The question remains: When Finley takes his spot in center, will
Gonzalez be in left or in right?
</P>
<P>
   Gilkey remains a strong candidate for left field. Or he could be
part of a trade before spring training begins, or move to right if
Manager Buck Showalter decides to put Gonzalez in left.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks apparently still have interest in San Diego
left fielder Greg Vaughn, who hit a career-high 50 homers last
season to help the Padres win the NL pennant. If Vaughn joins the
club, Gonzalez could move to right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every deal we make, people ask, `Are you through yet?' '' said
Sandy Johnson, Diamondbacks assistant general manager. ``You can't
really say that we are. We're still dealing from strength.''
</P>
<P>
   In Arizona's case, strength means pitching. Left-hander Brian
Anderson and/or left-hander Omar Daal could be part of future
transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez's immediate future involves returning to a league in
which he feels the most comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing bad against the American League, but the pace of the
game is different in the National League and there appears to be
more strategy involved,'' Gonzalez said. ``It's more of a
scratch-and-claw, move-the-runner-over, more fundamental type of
game. I'm more of that style player.''
</P>
<P>
   Showalter's evaluation of Gonzalez: ``The best way you can
describe him is that he's a baseball player, very fundamentally
sound. In terms of strikeouts and walks, he is low in strikeouts
and high in walks. He had career highs in homers and doubles last
year, and we think he is in the middle of his prime.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the departed Garcia, the question is whether he will ever
reach his prime in the big leagues? He hit .222 with nine homers
and 43 RBIs in 113 games with the Diamondbacks in 1998 and .311
with 10 homers and 27 homers with Triple-A Tucson. The left-handed
hitting Garcia was particularly vulnerable to off-speed pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Karim is a young player with skills. Hopefully, things will
work out for him and the Tigers,'' Showalter said. ``Karim played
hard for us. I don't know if you can say that you're disappointed
in a guy who's only 23 years old. In some people, the light goes on
at different stages of their career than others.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-28-98 2245EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
