<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9470 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FIESTASUPER-AZR &LR;      12-28 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIESTASUPER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO'S NO. 1 IN INTEREST? CARDINALS BEAT TOP COLLEGE TEAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 Note: Story moving in sports and news categories  
  
 By CHRIS FISCUS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ Sometimes, it seems, the Fiesta Bowl can't catch
a break.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's big game will produce a national champion _ but the
game is being overshadowed in metropolitan Phoenix by the Arizona
Cardinals' dramatic and improbable playoff run.
</P>
<P>
   The talk Monday _ whether on sports radio shows or the lunchtime
chatter at Sam's Cafe _ was not the Fiesta Bowl battle a week away.
The topic? The Cardinals finally ending the NFL's longest playoff
drought.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the Cardinals dominated the discussion on the
three major sports radio shows. The scene was the same on at least
one prominent talk radio show.
</P>
<P>
   At Sportsfan, a Tempe sports apparel shop near Sun Devil
Stadium, the Cardinals also had the edge, with sales of wild-card
playoff T-shirts and sweat shirts going faster than Fiesta Bowl
garb. ``It's more favoring the Cardinals,'' an employee said.
</P>
<P>
   There's no question the Fiesta Bowl is taking a back seat
locally this year, said John Cannon, a Phoenix sports radio host.
</P>
<P>
   The Fiesta Bowl is non-existent when it comes to callers to his
show, he added. ``I've gotten two phone calls since the pairings
were announced,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There's no Nebraska playing in the game. No Pac-10 team, which
could spark more local interest. And the losses by key unbeaten
teams late in the season hurt the game's impact, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then in the last two weeks with what the Cardinals have
accomplished, it has really wiped them off the map,'' Cannon said
of the Fiesta.
</P>
<P>
   It all should be a familiar feeling for the Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The game produced a national champion in 1996 _ but was
overshadowed some locally because of the upcoming Super Bowl, which
arrived in Tempe a few weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   The Fiesta Bowl produced another title game in 1987 _ the day
after Arizona State upset Michigan to win its first Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   But don't look for Fiesta Bowl leaders in their yellow blazers
to publicly fret.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Shover, one of three original organizers of the bowl game,
pooh-poohs any such idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was never our intention to make it the No. 1 thing in
town,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He remembers when Fiesta Bowl Executive Director John Junker
asked him if the bowl should pick another year, besides when the
Super Bowl was coming to town, to host a national title game. ``I
said, `Are you kidding?'
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got your different audiences for the different
events,'' Shover said. ``There's never been any kind of envy . . .
there's plenty of room for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Fiesta Bowl spokesman Shawn Schoeffler agreed and added, ``if it
is being overshadowed, the only place in the world it is (being
overshadowed) is in Phoenix, Arizona.''
</P>
<P>
   Pro football fans aren't necessarily college football fans, he
said. ``We don't feel like the first unified college football
championship is going to be overshadowed, really, by anything.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, Monday's Fiesta Bowl will be a flashback to when
Tempe hosted Super Bowl XXX.
</P>
<P>
   There's the pageantry of two teams fighting for a football
championship. A stadium packed with more than 70,000 screaming
fans. A game attracting international attention and plenty of hype.
It's a present for many Valley hotels, restaurants, bars and
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   While there are similarities between the two events, though,
there's a huge difference between the Fiesta Bowl _ even when it
produces a national champion _ and the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect Diana Ross to climb out of a helicopter during the
Fiesta Bowl's halftime. And the level of national recognition
differs, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It brought attention to Arizona like we've never seen
before,'' Shover said of the Super Bowl. ``Nothing can match the
NFL and the Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to being an original organizer of the Fiesta Bowl,
Shover played a key role in helping bring the NFL's championship
game to the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a college spirit around the Fiesta Bowl. It's a
different spirit,'' he said. When the Valley hosted the Super Bowl,
it was the NFL's game. But with the Fiesta Bowl, ``it's our game.''
</P>
<P>
   Tempe Mayor Neil Giuliano agreed. He said the two events are
``like night and day for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fiesta Bowl is a breeze compared to dealing with the NFL for
the Super Bowl, he said. And the emphasis is different: ``The NFL's
motivation is profit . . . the Fiesta Bowl is much more
community-oriented. It's hometown,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another difference: the estimated economic impact of the two
events. Fiesta Bowl officials project that this year's game will
have an economic impact of about $100 million. Super Bowl XXX had
an economic impact of about $306 million.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest difference between the two games, though, is
the people who attend. It is corporate America compared with
collegiate America.
</P>
<P>
   The Super Bowl is an international event, and fans are a who's
who of corporate leaders lucky enough to get tickets. Most Valley
residents didn't have a prayer of attending Super Bowl XXX.
</P>
<P>
   But the Fiesta Bowl is driven by the fans of the two
universities. Each of the participating schools receives 16,000
tickets. Another 35,000 go to Fiesta Bowl annual ticket-holders,
which includes local residents.
</P>
<P>
   While Monday's Fiesta Bowl may not be the most pressing thing on
the minds of Valley sports fans, it may not matter to Fiesta Bowl
organizers, said Cannon, the radio host.
</P>
<P>
   The tickets are sold. People will be in from out of town. The TV
ratings should be high. There will be plenty of national media
exposure.
</P>
<P>
   Local interest could climb this week with the bowl teams in
town. But with the Cards' playoff berth, it will be a tough go, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Fiesta Bowl spokesman Schoeffler downplayed the impact of the
Cardinals' playoff run on the bowl game. And Fiesta organizers
realize a lot of people in the Valley are excited about the NFL
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're excited for them, too,'' he said. &QL; 
Chris Fiscus can be reached at at chris.fiscus(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-28-98 2250EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
