<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9593 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-ISLANDERS-PANTHER     12-28 0511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-ISLANDERS-PANTHERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITHOUT SALO IN THE NET, ISLANDERS ARE POROUS
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUNRISE, Fla. _ There are two players the Islanders cannot seem
to win without. Defenseman Kenny Jonsson, as they found out earlier
this month, is one of them, but after Monday night's game it was
clear that goalie Tommy Salo is the other. And until Salo returns
from a broken finger in two weeks, victories could be few and far
between for the Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   Salo's replacement, Wade Flaherty, has allowed a few soft goals
the last two games, and Monday night he was pulled after allowing
two first-period goals in a 5-1 loss to the Florida Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   Flaherty got the Islanders off to a bad start, allowing a
stoppable Terry Carkner shot between his pads to give Florida an
early 1-0 lead. After giving up another goal, Flaherty (1-4-1 with
a 3.48 goals against average) was banished to the bench, replaced
by Marcel Cousineau, who had not appeared in an National Hockey
League game since 1997. Cousineau allowed three goals.
</P>
<P>
   The Panthers dominated the Islanders on both ends of the ice in
the first period and took a 2-0 lead on goals by Carkner and Oleg
Kvasha. Paul Laus stretched the lead to 3-0 early in the second.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps embarrassed by Laus' goal, his first in 188 games, the
Islanders began showing signs of life, getting a goal two minutes
later from Mark Lawrence. Then came a pivotal point in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Mariusz Czerkawski appeared to bring the Islanders within a goal
at 11 minutes 33 seconds of the period. But the goal was waved off
by Referee Lance Roberts, who ruled that the whistle had been blown
before the puck trickled between Sean Burke's pads.
</P>
<P>
   Carkner scored Florida's first goal at 4:53. Skating over the
blue line unmarked, he took a cross-ice pass from Ray Whitney and
unleashed a rocket that beat Flaherty between the pads.
</P>
<P>
   Kvasha, a 6-foot-5-inch wing whom the Islanders are said to
covet, scored the second goal on a power play at 17:49. He crashed
the net and whacked the puck away from Jonsson and into the goal.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders got a scare in the first period when Trevor
Linden, their captain, was cut above his right eye by the high
stick of Bill Lindsay, who drew a penalty. The game had to be
stopped for several minutes as the linesmen cleared off a stream of
blood. Linden, who missed five minutes in the period while the gash
was stitched up, threw a punch at Lindsay on his first shift after
the incident, and then, moments later, confronted Lindsay. They
were quickly separated.
</P>
<P>
   Laus extended the Panthers' lead to 3-0 at 4:40 of the second
period. He chipped a rebound over Cousineau for his first goal
since April 6, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence, who was recently called up by the Islanders, scored at
6:16 of the second period, stretching his scoring streak to four
games. He persistently poked at the puck until it dribbled into the
goal.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Whitney scored the Panthers' fourth goal and Bill Lindsay
scored the fifth in the final seconds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
