<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOCH LOSES RADIO SHOW; PARTYING ON ST. BARTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Koch Replaced by Dr. Laura
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's certainly not as if Ed Koch is out of a job, as
the former mayor reminded everyone who called him Monday.
</P>
<P>
   He is still gainfully employed as, among other things, a lawyer,
a newspaper columnist, a movie reviewer, a television commentator,
a university lecturer, a public speaker, an author, an advertising
pitchman and the sometimes irascible, sometimes avuncular judge of
``The People's Court,'' the daily television program.
</P>
<P>
   But on Thursday, Koch will no longer be a radio host.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at WABC-AM radio told his agent that they had decided
to cancel his talk show, over which Koch had presided five days a
week for about eight years.
</P>
<P>
   ``My ratings are good, so I don't think it has anything to do
with ratings,'' Koch said Monday. But his ratings have not been as
good as they once were, and the station said it planned to move Dr.
Laura Schlessinger, the host of the syndicated pop-psychology talk
show, into his 11 a.m. slot.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're doing what they think is in the best interest of the
station,'' Koch said, ``and there are no hard feelings. That's
America, and that's free enterprise.''
</P>
<P>
   The program director for WABC-AM said it was the station's
policy not to comment on the reasons why shows are canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Losing the radio show means Koch loses a bully pulpit, which he
has often used for the last several years to excoriate Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani. But when informed of the show's cancellation,
Giuliani seemed almost wistful. ``You know,'' he said, ``I always
look forward to his criticisms because then I have something to
talk about at a news conference.''
</P>
<P>
   They're All There, And You're Not
</P>
<P>
   On St.-Barthelemy, nothing seems different this year, except
that the tiny island in the French West Indies is more crowded than
ever.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurants are overbooked, Jeeps are overrunning Gustavia, the
island's port, and, once again, it seems as if no one is waiting
around for New Year's Eve for parties to begin.
</P>
<P>
   More than 2,000 invitations went out from Ocean Drive magazine
in Miami for its party held Saturday night at Le Feeling, the hot
mountaintop disco in St. Bart's, where last year's party went on
till 6 a.m. This year, the line formed at 10:45 p.m. and by
midnight no one could move on the dance floor.
</P>
<P>
   Sean ``Puffy'' Combs, the rap impresario, who is staying in a
villa by night and a boat by day (because of the partying on his
boat last year, he could not rent a boat this year), danced to his
own music. So did Ronald Perelman, the chairman of Revlon, who
uncharacteristically was wearing jeans and a T-shirt. Perelman took
his own boat, the Ultima III, to the island. Penny Marshall and
Martha Stewart are said to be staying on it.
</P>
<P>
   Two of Ralph Lauren's children, Dylan and David, were dancing
the night away along with Chris Barish, the son of the Planet
Hollywood owner, Keith Barish. A party on the Barish boat (called
The Indian Achiever) is planned for Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Mottola, chairman of Sony Music Entertainment, is on a
boat called The Pegasus, but hasn't been spotted, and Clive Davis,
head of Arista Records, is planning his yearly party at his own
villa. Mick Jagger, is said to be on the yacht of Jean Pigozzi, an
Italian investor, and Ted Field, chairman of Interscope
Communications, is keeping it low until his New Year's Eve bash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone keeps saying, `I'm so over it,''' said Jacquelynn
Powers, senior editor of Ocean Drive magazine. ``They say: `I don't
want to see the same people. Let's just go to dinner and go home,'
and two seconds later they say, `Where's the party?'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
