<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEX-SLAYING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tearful admission: Killer was invited in for sex
 &HT;    By Bill Montgomery
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JONESBORO, Ga. _ The weekend slaying of a 72-year-old
grandfather took a strange twist Monday as police announced Chester
Smith's widow tearfully admitted the killer was a hitchhiker the
couple invited to their home for sex.
</P>
<P>
   Clayton County police Maj. Jerry Robinson said Evelyn Smith, 76,
changed her story late Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   She originally told police the ponytailed, bearded man who slit
her husband's throat with a switch-blade had come to their door
asking for a glass of water and then had burst in and attempted to
rob them.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators grew suspicious after they determined Evelyn Smith
had purchased a six-pack of ``pony sized'' beer bottles that she
had claimed the man brought to their home.
</P>
<P>
   Police discovered her purchase when they reviewed a videotape
from a surveillance camera at a convenience store near the couple's
home. They expected to see the suspect buying the beer, Robinson
said, but ``the tape showed Mrs. Smith buying the beer instead.''
</P>
<P>
   The widow originally claimed the intruder forced his way into
their home and demanded money. He cut a telephone cord in the
bedroom and was about to tie them up with the cord and bedsheets
when Chester Smith bolted for safety, yelling for help, she told
police.
</P>
<P>
   The man chased Smith, knocked him down and cut his throat,
police said. Police said Smith managed to run outside. He made his
way into the kitchen through a side entrance and got a towel.
Neighbors who heard the couple's cries called 911. Arriving medics
found the mortally wounded man sitting on the kitchen stoop holding
a bloody towel to his throat, police said. Chester Smith died
undergoing surgery at Southern Regional Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The killer fled in the Smiths' 1994 light blue Mercury Sable,
Georgia license tag 385GRB; the car has grey primer paint on the
right rear panel and two large pillows in the rear seat, Robinson
said.
</P>
<P>
   The killer is described as 30 to 40 years old, slender and about
5 feet 6 six inches tall.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said Evelyn Smith broke down when confronted with the
store's videotape and told investigators that she and her husband
picked up the man at an exit off I-75. ``They told him they would
take him home for the purpose of having sex with Mrs. Smith,''
Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving the man at their home, Evelyn Smith went to the
convenenience store and bought beer for him, returning home shortly
after 3 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``The man drank some beer, and in the bedroom told them he
wasn't interested (in sex), he wanted money and their car. The
motive was robbery, we believe, but this was not a home invasion as
it first appeared,'' Robinson .added.
</P>
<P>
   The widow could not be located Monday night for comment. Family
members said Monday afternoon they had heard nothing from police
about the suspect or details of Chester Smith's murder.
</P>
<P>
   Daughter Linda Brown, when told by a reporter police said the
killer was a hitch-hiker, said ``I don't care who he is, he had no
reason to kill my father.''
</P>
<P>
   She and other family members declined further comment.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, several home invasions in the Atlanta area have
made headlines, including a particularly violent one Dec. 12; in
that crime, a couple was beaten and robbed in their home and their
Jeep Grand Cherokee stolen; the woman also was raped.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said the public needed to know the details of the Smith
case, despite their embarrassing nature, because ``we receive many
calls from people concerned that some one was walking door to door
commiting horrible, random crimes of violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not a random crime after all, it appears, and the
public needed to know that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said police had not decided whether Evelyn Smith would be
charged with making false statements. ``We're concerned with
apprehending this killer more than anything else,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Montgomery writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
