A9596 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PARTY-SWITCH-COX     12-28 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARTY-SWITCH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Impeachment backlash includes voters wishing to switch parties
 &HT;    By Dan Moffett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The political rancor over impeachment is
spreading from Washington to the voter registration offices of
South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Elections supervisors in Palm Beach County and the Treasure
Coast report being surprised by high numbers of requests for party
changes, with Republican defections being a discernible trend.
</P>
<P>
   In an apparent backlash against the move to impeach President
Clinton that culminated in a House vote on Dec. 19, Democrats are
adding to their ranks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We usually see requests for changes die down when we get into
the holidays,'' said Theresa LePore, the Palm Beach County
elections supervisor. ``But this year has been unusually active,
and most of the changing has been from Republican to Democrat.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the most recent figures available, from Oct. 1 to
Dec. 16 in Palm Beach County, 452 Republicans defected to the
Democratic Party and 321 Democrats turned Republican; overall, if
new residents and those who switched from other parties are
included, 867 voters joined the Democratic Party and 562 became
Republicans. The county has about 614,000 voters.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's problems have inspired movement in both directions,
election officials say, as voters make statements of affiliation to
express their unhappiness with either the president or Congress.
Since the November elections, 234 Palm Beach County voters have
left the Republican Party and 185 have quit the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``The viciousness with which the Republicans have behaved is
nauseating to most people,'' said Monte Friedkin, the chairman of
the Palm Beach County Democratic Party. ``There's no question
they've motivated a lot of lifelong members of their own party to
support us.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank DeMario, chairman of the Palm Beach County Republican
Party, said the data is too preliminary to be alarming.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's this way six months from now, maybe there will be
cause for concern,'' DeMario said. ``But there are a bunch of
dissatisfied people on both sides. Republicans who changed sides so
rapidly probably weren't loyal anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   The trend is apparent also in Martin County, which has about
80,000 registered voters. From Dec. 1 to Dec. 18, 13 Republicans
changed affiliations, five to Democrat and eight to non-partisan,
officials said. And since Dec. 21, 17 Republicans have become
Democrats and six others became non-partisan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started to get a run on changes after the House
(impeachment) vote,'' Martin elections official Emma Smith said.
``And we've had several more come in this morning in the mail.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans jumping ship may not be a surprise, but Martin
officials also reported a few Democrats turning to the GOP. Since
Dec. 1, nine Democrats have changed to Republicans; seven more
became non-partisan.
</P>
<P>
   In St. Lucie County, which has about 131,800 voters, 130 people
switched party affiliations within the past month _ 48 more than
this time last year. Of those, 41 became Democrats, 31 became
Republicans and 58 became either independent or nonpartisan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think the Clinton deal has accounted for some, but I do
think some of the local politics have accounted for some,'' said
Wesley Wilcox, systems administrator for the St. Lucie elections
office.
</P>
<P>
   Small but telling samplings from elections officials around the
state and nation point to a busy season of political upheaval.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is significant for this time of year,'' said Deborah Clark,
deputy elections administrator in Pinellas County, of her workload.
``During the holidays our file is usually pretty static. So this is
different from previous years.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark said her office recorded 75 people dropping Republican
registration between Dec. 7 and Dec. 21, at the height of the
impeachment action. Of those, 55 registered as Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had about 100 people change from Republican to Democrat
in the last week to week and a half,'' said an elections official
in Polk County, Iowa, which includes Des Moines. ``Some of these
guys have been Republican for a long time. It's very unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   In California, officials have been caught off guard by the high
volume of requests for party changes since the state has gone to an
open primary system and affiliation is less important.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's highly unusual for us to get any requests for party
change,'' said Steve Weir, a Santa Clara elections administrator.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Moffett writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. Palm Beach Post staff writers Howie Paul Hartnett and Lady
Hereford and The New York Times wire service contributed to this
story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
