<HEADLINE>
PRINCE, WARNER BROS. COMPETING OVER `1999' 
</HEADLINE>
   By NEVA CHONIN  
 c.1998, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   He was dreamin' when he wrote it, forgive him if he goes astray.
</P>
<P>
   Just in time for the new year, the Artist Formerly Known as the
Unpronounceable Glyph Formerly Known as Prince plans to release
seven new mixes of his landmark 1982 single ``1999'' on his NPG
label.
</P>
<P>
   But the Prince of Paisley Park has competition. Warner Bros.,
which holds the copyright to the original ``1999'' master, has sent
new copies of the single to radio stations and has plastered
promotional stickers on the original ``1999'' album and ``Prince's
Greatest Hits Volume One.'' DJ remixes of the song by Roger Sanchez
and others are also expected.
</P>
<P>
   Why the dueling ``1999'' releases? Because the song _ written,
recorded and produced by a 23-year-old Prince _ is the property of
Warner Bros. No longer affiliated with the label, an older and
wiser Artist can release new versions of ``1999'' _ the EP will
have reggae and hip-hop remakes _ as long as he steers clear of the
1982 master tape.
</P>
<P>
   The Artist is peeved at Warner Bros. for what he views as an
exploitative 18-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was The Artist (or any artist 4 that matter) ever in4med that
it was in his best interest 2 sign this agreement only if he had
ownership of the master recordings, seeing that this is where the
majority of ALL future earnings would come from??'' demands a post
on the Artist's Love 4 One Another Web site
(www.love4oneanother.com). ``NO, NO, and thrice, NO!''
</P>
<P>
   But according to Warner Bros. executive Bob Merlis, the reality
is closer to yes, yes and thrice yes. ``(Prince) signed a lucrative
contract, and he had legal counsel,'' he says. ``He's our partner
in this, and he's getting royalties.''
</P>
<P>
   Why the outrage, then? ``I can't theorize about how he thinks,''
sighs Merlis. ``But we don't begrudge him anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Except, perhaps, the coveted master to the original ``1999.'' Ad
agencies are reportedly in a frenzy of high-priced bidding for the
song _ though it's anybody's guess why they would want to peddle
products with lyrics such as ``Mommy, why does everybody have a
bomb?'' and ``We could all die any day.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reasoning, Merlis says no commercial deals will be
struck without the Artist's permission. In the meantime, he
insists, ``We're simply letting people know the song is available.
Because if not now, when? It's logical.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Logic and music seldom mix, though, and the Artist's ``1999 _
The New Master'' EP is probably only the opening salvo in the War
of ``1999.'' The Artist, according to copyright law, is entitled to
tweak his enduring song with stratagems ranging from creating an
exact replica of the original ``1999'' album using digitized sound
to supplying new lyrics to the tune.
</P>
<P>
   The Artist's immediate plans are more staid. He will preview his
new EP on January 1 and 2 at MGM Grand's Studio 54 in Las Vegas,
with Morris Day and the Time guesting on the first night and label
mates Larry Graham and the New Power Generation on the second.
Tickets for both shows are available at MGM ticket outlets.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
