<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-SABRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS' SCORING RUSH SENDS HASEK TO THE BENCH
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ Midway through the first period Monday night,
the fans at Marine Midland Arena let out a chorus of mock cheers
when the New Jersey Devils dumped the puck softly toward the net,
where the Buffalo Sabres goaltender Dominik Hasek cradled the
slow-moving puck. Just 22 seconds into the second period, there
were no cheers, mock or otherwise, as the Sabres' coach, Lindy
Ruff, benched Hasek.
</P>
<P>
   Hasek hardly lived up to his name, the Dominator, on this rare
occasion, surrendering goals on each of the Devils' first three
shots, then another 22 seconds into the second period. After the
fourth goal, the little-used backup Dwayne Roloson skated on as the
crowd watched silently, too shocked to critique Hasek.
</P>
<P>
   The benching did little to change what was happening. The Devils
scored on almost every opportunity and built a five-goal lead
before hanging on for a 7-4 victory. That countered a 2-0 loss on
Saturday night in New Jersey and gave Hasek and the Sabres
something to think about should these teams, the two best in the
Eastern Conference, meet in the post-season.
</P>
<P>
   While the Devils have improved their offense this season, it
would be hard to describe Monday night's splurge as anything more
than an oddity. The Devils' four goals came on only six shots, a
confounding statistic against Hasek, who stopped 34 New Jersey
shots two nights ago and entered the game with consecutive shutouts
and only one goal allowed in the last three games.
</P>
<P>
   Brendan Morrison had a goal and two assists, all in the first
period, as Hasek surrendered three goals in a period for the first
time since Oct. 31. Dave Andreychuk had a goal and an assist, Brian
Rolston two goals, and Bobby Holik and Sasha Lakovic each had two
assists.
</P>
<P>
   Hasek's early departure was just the third of the season for the
National Hockey League's premier goalie. Hasek has played in every
game for the Sabres this season, leaving early on Nov. 14 with a
5-1 lead and then getting pulled while trailing by 2-0 on Nov. 28
in a game at Florida. On this night, it was the Devils' Martin
Brodeur who made one acrobatic save after another as the Devils
were badly outshot by 40-18.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Devils beat Hasek both times they faced him last
season, they were wary entering Monday night's game. ``Against any
team you have to beat six guys,'' Coach Robbie Ftorek said at the
morning skate. ``Against this team the sixth man is tougher than
most.''
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur, who is 6-3-1 in head-to-head meetings, had said,
``We've got to go through him to get a win. It's a mental block,
but somebody has got to pass through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Some players had theories on how they would change that Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some traffic will be good,'' Ftorek said with a smirk. ``I
don't know about more because there wasn't any last time.''
</P>
<P>
   Krzysztof Oliwa struck first, exactly as the players planned.
Just 2:50 into the game, Scott Stevens kept the puck in at the blue
line and then Lakovic slipped the puck to Morrison behind the net.
Morrison fed Oliwa, who was parked in front of the net. With
surprising ease, Oliwa poked the puck by Hasek for his third goal
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Four minutes later, Morrison picked up the puck near center ice
after the Devils repelled a Sabres threat and skated alone along
the right side as defenseman Richard Smehlik retreated to cover
Oliwa, who was racing in from the left side. Morrison flicked the
puck low and to the right of Hasek.
</P>
<P>
   Just 1:31 later, Patrick Elias fed Petr Sykora on the left side
of the net and from an impossible angle. Sykora banged the puck off
Hasek's right skate and into the net.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
