r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NHL-COLUMN-LADN     12-28 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS RED WINGS' REIGN NEARING AN END?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Six months can be a long time in the NHL. Just ask the Detroit
Red Wings.
</P>
<P>
   In June the Red Wings were skating around with the Stanley Cup
for the second straight year. This season, they have been terrible
against the better teams in the league, and if not for beating up
on the NHL's weaklings, the Red Wings would be in real trouble in
the mediocre Central Division.
</P>
<P>
   ``People read the paper and know what we're doing and they want
to know why,'' the Red Wings' Kris Draper said. ``With as much
talent as we have, why can't we beat Dallas? Look at our record
against teams above .500. You go home and people want to know
what's going on with your team. It's a pride factor.''
</P>
<P>
   How bad are things? Before Monday's 4-4 tie with St. Louis, the
Red Wings had lost five consecutive games. In eight losses to five
of the NHL's top teams _ Phoenix, Dallas, Boston, Toronto and
Carolina _ the Wings have been outscored 34-12. And their power
play had produced three goals in their previous 33 chances before
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Changes could be coming, mainly because Detroit management
believes complacency has set in. There even is some thought the
Wings could become involved as late bidders in the sweepstakes for
Calgary'sTheoren Fleury.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit will make the playoffs, and has to be considered a Cup
favorite until proven otherwise. But the Red Wings don't want to
wait until April to find their game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still the regular season, but you can't just all of a
sudden turn it on come April 1 and find your `A' game,'' general
manager Ken Holland said. ``You need to get it going at some point
in the regular season and play your `A' game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only Christmas, but at the same it is Christmas _ we've
played three months and it's three months before crunch time. We
haven't played poorly but we haven't played anything near how we
have to play to be competitive against the elite teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleury update: The Calgary Herald reported that Fleury has
rejected a $5-million-a-year offer to remain with the Flames.
Fleury had seven points as the Flames went 3-1-1 on a recent trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how to put it,'' he said, ``but I think I made a
pretty good pitch for myself on this trip _ that if you want me,
here I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Fighting friends: Fighting and hockey are not exactly mutually
exclusive. But the recent wrestling match between Nashville's Mike
Dunham and Vancouver's Garth Snow was unique.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, both are goalies. For another, they were
roommates when they played at the University of Maine.
</P>
<P>
   The scrap began when Dunham went after the Canucks' Brad May.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to go down there when Dunham went at it with May,'' Snow
said. ``You've got to protect your teammate.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a scene reminiscent of a Washington-Boston fight earlier
this season, when goalies (and former roommates) Olaf Kolzig and
Byron Dafoe went at it. The Bruins' Dafoe, a former King, was best
man at Kolzig's wedding over the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Garden party: When Dallas visited Toronto last week, Stars
goalie Ed Belfour rented Maple Leaf Gardens and invited 26 friends
to join him there for a pickup game. Belfour skated as a forward
and scored two goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a joke almost, when you think about it,'' said David
O'Connor, a building contractor from Chicago who was one of
Belfour's guests. ``I mean, we're going to skate on the ice at
Maple Leaf Gardens. I'll tell you this about Eddie Belfour: He's as
loyal a friend as you'll ever find. He's a stand-up guy, and a real
gentleman.''
</P>
<P>
   Loose pucks: Why were the Kings able to acquire skilled right
wing Donald Audette from Buffalo for the meager price of a 1999
second-round draft choice? Apparently, Buffalo was trying to make
an example of Audette, who missed the first two months of the
season in a contract dispute with the Sabres.
</P>
<P>
   According to Sabres general manager Darcy Regier, the Kings'
offer typified the offers he received _ strange, considering
Audette scored a team-high 24 goals last year playing in Buffalo's
defense-oriented system. Tampa Bay was another team interested in
acquiring Audette, but refused to give up a second-round pick to
get him. Audette's history of knee problems is believed to have
driven his value down....
</P>
<P>
   When Mighty Ducks goalie Dominic Roussel beat Colorado 1-0, last
week, it was his first NHL victory in nearly three years. Teammate
Jim McKenzie was impressed: ``He stopped 45 point-blank shots. He
gets down in that butterfly and his legs look like the bumpers of a
pinball machine.'' The Ducks have been involved in five 1-0 games
this season, going 3-2....
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of goalies, Stars backup goalie Roman Turek unveiled a
new mask featuring artwork from the heavy metal band Iron Maiden,
complete with an eye dripping down a skull.... The president of
Belarus reportedly offered Vancouver holdout Pavel Bure $4 million
to play at home next season. Vancouver general manager Brian Burke
reacted angrily to the report, because Bure remains under contract
to the Canucks....
</P>
<P>
   Sabres winger Matthew Barnaby missed a recent game with a
sprained ankle. Barnaby was injured when he wrestled with teammate
Rob Ray in the Buffalo dressing room while wearing only one skate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
