A9609 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-UTEXAS-BROWN-COX     12-28 0511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UTEXAS-BROWN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UT sets up 10-year deal for head football coach
 &HT;    By Kirk Bohls
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The University of Texas is taking steps to lock up head
football coach Mack Brown for the long term by arranging a contract
extension that will in effect give him a 10-year deal and a raise
of $100,000, for an annual total package of $850,000.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Athletic Director DeLoss Dodds said Monday that he is
briefing members of the UT Men's Athletic Council and has already
gained the verbal approval of President Larry Faulkner on the new
contract. Ultimately, the measure would have to be approved by the
Board of Regents, but that is expected to be approved without
delay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we ought to make a statement,'' Dodds said. ``We've
had a great season, and this is the right time to do this. They are
recruiting well, and things are in really good shape. They're the
answer that we're looking for, and we need to keep them happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the extension, which would take effect
Friday, Brown would have a five-year contract that adds an extra
year each year through 2004. After the fifth extension, the
contract could be allowed to expire in a natural progression,
ending in 2008.
</P>
<P>
   Brown originally had a five-year package that rolled over for
two years _ the equivalent of a seven-year deal.
</P>
<P>
   A buyout of his contract by UT would cost the school $1 million
at most, Dodds said, because it would be obligated to pay only the
base annual salary of $200,000 over a maximum of five years.
</P>
<P>
   That would be less than what the school still owes former Coach
John Mackovic, who is entitled to payments of more than $1.2
million over the next two years. Since being reassigned in December
of 1997, Mackovic has already been paid more than $600,000.
</P>
<P>
   Were Brown to want out of his contract, he would not have to pay
any buyout.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Brown's pay, UT will raise the salaries of
offensive coordinator Greg Davis and defensive coordinator Carl
Reese by $35,000 apiece to put them at $150,000. The seven other
assistant football coaches, as well as assistant athletic directors
Cleve Bryant and Jeff Madden, will each get $15,000 increases.
</P>
<P>
   Dodds said the school wanted to reward Brown and his staff for
the Longhorns' outstanding 8-3 season and Cotton Bowl berth as well
as to ward off offers from potential suitors. But Dodds said he
doesn't expect Brown to look hard at any of the seven vacant head
coaching positions in the National Football League, five of which
came open Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he is interested in an NFL job,'' Dodds said.
``I'm not worried about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he wouldn't be surprised if some NFL teams came
calling this week, but he would tell them all the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy here, and I'm not going anywhere,'' Brown said. ``We
feel good about what we have going here.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Bohls writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
