game against Florida.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE IMES (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GRAVITY-LENS (Undated) _ Far away in the cosmos, where
everything is separated by distances measured in hundreds and
billions of light-years, sometimes a galaxy or cluster of galaxies
in the foreground intersects the light from a more distant object.
The conjunction plays visual tricks, producing mirages that are
becoming a practical tool of astronomy, a kind of natural
telescope. Aided by more sensitive cameras and advanced computer
technologies, systematic searches of the heavens are yielding an
increasing number of examples of such celestial phenomena, known as
gravitational lenses. Scientists are learning to interpret these
distorting and magnifying lensing events for revealing clues in the
most intractable mysteries of the universe. By John Noble Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BABERUTH-CANCER (Undated) _ The Doctor's World column: This
year, the 50th anniversary of Babe Ruth's death, his sports legacy
has been extolled again as baseball heroes of newer generations
breezed past the home-run record the Babe held for 34 years, until
1961. But unknown to many, Ruth also left a legacy in the annals of
medical history. In fact, he was among the first patients anywhere
to receive experimental chemotherapy, and some researchers say he
was the first ever to receive a combination treatment of
chemotherapy and radiation for his type of cancer. By Lawrence K.
Altman Jr.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-IMMORTAL-CELLS (Undated) _ Life and death lie nowhere so
close together as in the human cell's counting device for limiting
how often it can divide. The device is a sort of tally stick that
gets shorter at each division. When it runs out, the cell dies. New
research on cell division demonstrates the potential to overrule
the counter and ``provide therapeutic opportunities for age-related
diseases.'' according to one team of researchers. Researchers are
pleased now that even after multiple divisions of cells, far beyond
their normal life of 50 divisions of so, the cells show no
cancerous tendencies. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PRAIRIE-CHICKENS (Urbana, Ill.) _ For six decades,
conservationists in Illinois tried to save the greater prairie
chickens that once covered the state like its sea of grass.
Nonetheless, the showy little birds, beloved for their flamboyant
mating rituals, began a headlong population collapse to fewer than
50. Now a team of geneticists and ecologists from state agencies
and the University of Illinois has reversed that decline and, for
one of the first times in a wild population, documented how
inbreeding and loss of habitat reinforced each other to create what
an ``extinction vortex.'' By Jo Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ISOTOPES-BUTTERFLIES (Undated) _ Every winter, after flying
south from the Eastern United States, millions of monarch
butterflies festoon fir trees in the mountains of Mexico, creating
one of the world's most dazzling and famous biological spectacles.
But in spite of interest in these insects, details of their travels
have largely remained a mystery. Now, three new studies herald the
arrival of a powerful new technique that can identify, sometimes to
within a few miles, where migrating animals have been. The new
technique takes advantage of different forms, known as isotopes, of
chemical elements. Biologists have begun discovering that these
isotopes, present in different amounts in different regions, can
leave a distinctive chemical signature written in the feather of a
bird or the wing of a butterfly living in that region. By Carol
Kasek Yoon.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CERNETTES (Undated) _ The language of physics is not exactly
the stuff of song lyrics, but the Cernettes, billed as the world's
first particle physics rock band, have hit the Internet. Even if
nonphysicists fail to get their musical jokes, the Cernettes count
on an audience of admiring scientists. By Malcolm W. Browne.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ORNISH-DIET (Undated) _ Dr. Dean Ornish advocated a diet of
virtually no fat, no sugar, no caffeine and minimal sodium and
claims it helps patients' cardiovascular systems. While he has some
supporters in the medical profession, others say this his studies
involve so few patients over such a short time that no conclusions
about benefits can be drawn from his tightly regulated and highly
promoted program. By Gina Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT2) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FITNESS-EXERCISE (Undated) _ An essay: a vow to exercise
less. It's time to stop and smell the roses, or at least something
other than the guy sweating on the next treadmill. By Andrea
Higbie.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DRUG-SAFETY (Undated) _ When a drug harms patients, there is
no independent agency to find out what went wrong. Instead, the
government relies on doctors to report problems voluntarily, and
the job of investigating then falls to the same people who put the
drug on the market in the first place: the FDA, which approved the
drug, and the pharmaceutical company that manufactured it. In a
recent issue of The New England Journal of Medicine, three doctors
compared airplane safety and drug safety, noting that drug
reactions kill 100,000 Americans a year, vastly more than plane
crashes. They suggested that the United States needed an
independent drug safety agency, analogous to the transportation
board. By Denise Grady.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NYT News Service &LR;  &QL;
</P>
