<HEADER>
A9629 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-COL-SECURITY-NYT &LR;      12-28 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-SECURITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEHIND A SENSE OF SECURITY LIES A PERMANENT CAUTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By CLYDE HABERMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A post-midnight subway ride from Greenwich Village to
the Upper West Side was as good a sign as any of the growing sense
of personal security in the city. There were maybe 15 people in the
car, not one of them obviously homeless and planning an all-nighter
on the No. 1 train. They were ordinary New Yorkers on the way home.
And about half of them were napping.
</P>
<P>
   That's when it hit how remarkable a scene this was.
</P>
<P>
   Would it have been likely, only a few years ago, for so many
people to let down their guard to sleep on the subway at 12:30
a.m., unconcerned about lowlifes snatching their purses or ripping
chains from their necks?
</P>
<P>
   You know the answer is no.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel a change,'' said Peter Ryan, 20, a student at St.
Francis College in Brooklyn. ``You used to have to watch your back
on the subway. Now I frequently doze off. I never have any
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems that more New Yorkers are also reading on trains than a
few years ago, again because they can indulge in the luxury of
normal behavior that was denied them during the high-crime siege.
</P>
<P>
   You see them on the sidewalks at later hours than before. You
don't see them crossing the street quite as much because a fellow
walking their way looks wrong. You don't hear them talking so often
about how it wasn't worth the risk to make a late-night run to the
corner grocery.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I noticed the change was seeing women with
Macy's bags going to Brooklyn on the subway,'' the writer Pete
Hamill said. ``They didn't used to think they could have a bag that
screamed `Just Bought' and get it home.''
</P>
<P>
   All this is the tangible, human side of the statistics showing a
sustained and spectacular decline in crime across the city. You
could also throw in, as the mayor does, all the lives that will
continue to be led because homicides are way down from the wretched
1990 high of 2,262.
</P>
<P>
   Barring a blood bath as 1998 gasps its last, New York will end
the year with fewer murders than at any point since 1963. As of
Monday afternoon, the homicide count stood at 616, tolerably below
the 636 recorded in 1964. (The 1963 figure was 549.)
</P>
<P>
   Yet, despite the numbers, it is hard not to ask if New Yorkers
feel transported back to 1964 when it comes to crime. Do they think
they are as relatively safe now as then?
</P>
<P>
   You know that on this score, too, the answer is no.
</P>
<P>
   To begin with, some people do not feel better off than even a
couple of years ago, especially outside Manhattan, despite police
statistics showing crime down in every borough.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as Brooklyn is concerned, I don't feel any safer,''
said a woman who gave only her first name, Julie, as she bought
Christmas presents for her four children at the Fulton Mall in
downtown Brooklyn. ``I'm wary even talking to you, because I don't
know who'll be coming up behind me to grab my purse.''
</P>
<P>
   Ask parents if they would allow their 9- or 10- or 11-year-old
children to ride the subways alone, as New York youngsters that age
(boys in particular) routinely did on odysseys of discovery in
1964. Unanimously, parents interviewed said no. Some could not have
looked more startled if asked about possibly hurling their children
down a well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't dare put my boy on the bus alone,'' the father of a
10-year-old said at the Fulton Mall.
</P>
<P>
   Mind you, 1964 itself was not such a thrill in terms of crime.
</P>
<P>
   A realization that New York was coming unglued had begun to kick
in after years of middle-class flight, a growing neglect of basic
city services, an influx of poor people from the South and the
Caribbean, and a steady rise in the welfare rolls. It was in 1964,
in Harlem, that the urban riots of that decade got rolling.
</P>
<P>
   And crime had already set out on its inexorable march. In four
short years, from 1960 to 1964, the number of homicides rose to 636
from 390 _ a staggering 63 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
   But back then, the memory of a more tranquil city was still
keen, and that affected New Yorkers' sense of well-being. ``These
days, people who feel safe in Manhattan may not feel safe in the
Bronx, but in the 50s you felt safe everywhere,'' said Fred Siegel,
an urban-affairs specialist and history professor at Cooper Union.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the murder rate is not necessarily the best gauge of a
city's feelings of security. Even in the darkest days of 1990, your
chances of being killed were slim if you were middle class and
uninvolved in the crack wars. Most New Yorkers probably worry more
about being mugged, and the numbers are discouraging compared with
those of years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Forget 1964 for a moment. The police department's record keeping
in those days made a joke of its statistics on nonlethal crimes. In
1966, the system was changed to reflect reality better. Reported
robberies that year totaled 23,539. The 1998 tally is at least 61
percent higher _ 37,902 and counting. There were 23,205 reported
assaults in 1966, and 28,181 thus far this year.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: compared with 1964, you are far more likely to look
over your shoulder when you hear footsteps while walking home at 1
a.m. And you are far more likely to seek protection in ways that
were unheard of 34 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, you did not pass through metal detectors to enter
school buildings. You did not have the vast army of private
security guards that now occupies buildings throughout the city.
You did not have the many surveillance cameras, and not nearly as
many steel gates on store windows (not to mention the graffiti that
scars them).
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference is that in 1964 you counted on your neighbors
and your immediate community to provide a sense of security, and
now you count on all kinds of electronic devices and the police
department,'' said Mitchell Moss, director of New York University's
Urban Research Center.
</P>
<P>
   True, New Yorkers are breathing easier than they did in the
early 1990s. But Hamill said: ``Anybody who came through the last
35 years will have permanent caution. I don't think anybody is
throwing out the Fox locks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
