<DOCNO> NYT19981228.0484 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 23:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9632 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-CLEMENCY-COX     12-28 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-CLEMENCY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clemency rules to face open meetings challenge
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A federal judge who couldn't find much good
about the state's clandestine clemency system ruled Monday that it
is good enough to meet minimum standards set by the U.S. Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is abundantly clear that the Texas clemency procedure is
extremely poor and certainly minimal,'' U.S. District Judge Sam
Sparks of Austin said in his order.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks rescinded stays of execution granted to Joseph Stanley
Faulder, a Canadian who had been scheduled for execution on Dec. 10
for the 1975 slaying of an East Texas woman, and Danny Lee Barber,
sentenced to die Dec. 9 for the 1979 slaying of a Balch Springs
woman. Their cases now go back to state district courts to set new
execution dates.
</P>
<P>
   Despite page after page of criticism of the system, Sparks said
the only phrase that mattered was ``minimal procedural
safeguards,'' the low hurdle set by the U.S. Supreme Court in a
case challenging Ohio's clemency process.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks said state officials could open up the process and
silence its critics in ways that ``would not threaten the
employment of the Huntsville executioner.''
</P>
<P>
   Victor Rodriguez, chairman of the Texas Board of Pardons and
Paroles, called Sparks' ruling fair.
</P>
<P>
   ``His criticisms are well-taken and we will study those and look
at those and do the best we can with those,'' he said. ``We owe
everybody that. If there are things we can do better to more firmly
establish that we are extending minimum due process we would
obviously look at those.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rodriguez seemed uninterested in a major overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ruling attests to what we have been saying. We felt we
were extending minimal due process and apparently he agrees,''
Rodriguez said of Sparks.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Attorney General Dan Morales, who had his staff defend the
system despite his concerns about it, hopes the Sparks ruling leads
to serious consideration of changes, according to spokesman Ron
Dusek.
</P>
<P>
   ``The clemency procedure is a separate procedure and the
attorney general believes, and Judge Sparks believes, based on his
opinion, that that separate procedure should also provide a greater
degree of due process rather than simply meeting the minimal
standards,'' Dusek said.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Elliott Naishtat, D-Austin, has filed a bill that
would require the board to conduct open meetings and give reasons
for its clemency decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is still clear to me that the clemency process in Texas
does not comply with either the Texas Open Meetings Act or the
explicit language in the Texas Constitution,'' Naishtat said after
Sparks' ruling. ``I look forward to proceeding with my
legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   Austin lawyer Rita Radostitz, who represented one of the inmates
who brought the case, found solace in Sparks' words if not his
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm certainly heartened by the court's criticism of the
process, and I hope that it leads to changes in the clemency
process,'' she said, adding that she may ask the 5th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals in New Orleans to decide if Sparks correctly
interpreted the Supreme Court's use of the word ``minimal.''
</P>
<P>
   Austin lawyer Curt Sauer, representing death row inmates
mounting a state court challenge of the clemency system, was
encouraged by Sparks' suggestion that there are important issues
for state courts to decide.
</P>
<P>
   A hearing is scheduled for Monday in a Travis County state
district court to consider death row inmates' claim that the
clemency process violates the Texas Open Meetings Act.
</P>
<P>
   Both condemned men com- plained that the system of deciding
whether to change death sentences to life in prison doesn't give
death row inmates a fair shot.
</P>
<P>
   Under the current process, clemency requests are reviewed by the
18-member Board of Pardons and Paroles, which does so without
conducting a public hearing, convening a meeting or guaranteeing
that all members see all the documentation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is apparent none of the members read every word on every
line of every piece of paper in the clemency application,'' Sparks
said in one of his many criticisms of the process. ``Only Rodriguez
testified that he reads every bit of every file, and his
credibility is suspect.''
</P>
<P>
   If the board recommends against clemency, the request dies
shortly before the inmate does. If the board recommends clemency,
the decision is up to the governor.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-six clemency petitions have been submitted since George
W. Bush became governor in January 1995. The board has recommended
clemency only once, in the case of serial killer Henry Lee Lucas,
whose punishment was changed to life in prison by Bush.
</P>
<P>
   It is, Sparks said many times in many ways, not much of a
clemency system.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is elemental a flip of the coin would be more merciful than
these votes,'' he said in a footnote.
</P>
<P>
   The footnote was a reference to the 1998 ruling in which the
U.S. Supreme Court said, in a 5-4 decision, that clemency systems
must meet only ``minimal procedural safeguards'' that place them
somewhere between a coin toss and complete denial of access to the
process.
</P>
<P>
   Texas' system meets the ``minimal procedural safeguards''
criteria by affording inmates the right to submit their requests
and a guarantee that they will be considered, Sparks ruled.
</P>
<P>
   ``This process may not meet normal due process standards, but it
does meet `minimal procedural safeguards,''' he said, adding that
Faulder and Barber failed to show that the board's decisions not to
recommend clemency were ``arbitrary, capricious, whimsical or based
on improper factors.''
</P>
<P>
   Sparks then took the liberty of telling state officials they
could ``render frivolous any future cases'' attacking the process
by revising the system to add a hearing or, at least, require board
members to state reasons for decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Herman writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. Juan B. Elizondo Jr. contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
