<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BICKLEY_COLUMN-CARDS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDS' ONLY CHANCE IS TO REMAIN HUNGRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Texas Stadium is nothing special. A dome with a hole in its roof
and a giant Nike swoosh plastered on one wall. A place for pin-up
cheerleaders, love-struck fans and theme music that blares after
every first down.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing special except for the mystique. The invisible,
two-stepping dragon.
</P>
<P>
   If the Cardinals are content, they're cooked, available on the
menu of appetizers. If they're happy, they're history, and the only
thing left is the degree of embarrassment. Which, in the past, has
been nothing short of well done.
</P>
<P>
   But if they're still hungry and properly humiliated, they have a
chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we're going to be intimidated by a) the
playoffs; b) the star on the side of their helmets; or c) the sight
of Texas Stadium,'' Lomas Brown said. ``I think we're going to be
ready.''
</P>
<P>
   It is true that every team is given a clean slate in the
postseason, but the differences in perspective can be staggering.
Failure in Minnesota is not reaching the Super Bowl; the standard
in Arizona is slightly above showing up.
</P>
<P>
   Here is the buffet of excuses: The Cardinals are on the rise.
They finally finished in the black, finally made the playoffs. They
have nothing to lose, a young team that needs to jump in the pool
before crossing the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Here is the reality: At some point, the Cardinals need to beat a
good team. And at some point, they need to beat the Cowboys in a
game that means something.
</P>
<P>
   You might be lost in the euphoria, but across the country, the
Cardinals are still considered gangly outsiders. A team that has
yet to beat anyone with a winning record, for whom four of nine
victories came against teams searching for a new coach. The worst
of 12 playoff entries.
</P>
<P>
   And, yee haw, you know they are relieved in Dallas. Thankful the
Cowboys are not playing Tampa Bay or the New York Giants. Welcoming
an opponent they have beaten 15 of the past 16 times, including
nine straight at home. Fully expecting to put another bird on the
grill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope they are relieved,'' Brown said. ``I hope they do feel
that way. Then you set someone up for a big letdown because we are
coming to play.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be up to Vince Tobin and Dave McGinnis to find a way to
slow the Cowboys running attack, to put a helmet on Troy Aikman, to
keep the game from becoming a ball-control farce. It will be up to
the offense to step up to the table, recognize the stakes and find
a way to match and raise.
</P>
<P>
   But more than anything, the Cardinals must look at the Cowboys
in the same way the Cowboys look at them. A team that stands in
their way. A team they deserve to beat, even on enemy turf.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team has shown the ability to break through any type of
psychological barriers,'' McGinnis said. ``We've just about run the
gamut, and I think we've been steeled by the whole process.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, anything is possible. In 1994, McGinnis was a coach
with the Bears, a team that went 9-7, losing twice to the Vikings
in the regular season. Somehow, they walked into the Metrodome and
put a playoff pasting on their rivals.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, in 1996, the Vikings talked very much like
the Cardinals of today. About maturity, toughness and revenge. They
entered Texas Stadium as a wild card and got bombed, 40-15.
</P>
<P>
   So it's not what you say you believe. It's believing what you
say and proving it.
</P>
<P>
   After losing to the Cowboys in November, a day when all thoughts
turned to the wild card, Andre Wadsworth talked the talk. He
predicted they would meet again in the postseason, and when it
happened, he offered a bit of advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``They better come correct,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, that tasks belongs to the Cardinals. A team that surely
realizes it won seven games by three or fewer points playing a
last-place schedule.
</P>
<P>
   A team that doesn't have to apologize for where it is _ as long
as it isn't apologizing after another 60 minutes in Dallas. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at dan.bickley(at)pni.com. via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
