<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-28 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9638 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDINALSVSCOWBOY     12-28 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINALS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDS HOPE TO ROLL A 3  
 ODDS DON'T FAVOR COWBOYS 
</HEADLINE>
 VS COWBOYS-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Theoretically, the better team should always win. Shouldn't
matter where it's played. Shouldn't matter how many times the teams
have met.
</P>
<P>
   In an emotional game like football, though, talent isn't always
the determining factor. Over a four-month season, players are lost
to injuries and young teams grow up.
</P>
<P>
   Or at least that's what the Cardinals are banking on when their
postseason begins Saturday where their regular season began, at
Texas Stadium against the Dallas Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals, at 9-7, enter the playoffs as neophytes who
didn't beat a winning team. Two of their setbacks came against the
Cowboys, including a blowout loss in the opener at Texas Stadium,
where the Cardinals have not won since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals aren't for a moment predicting a victory in their
third meeting with the Cowboys. But they like their chances. It is
difficult for a team to beat another three times in one season. It
has been done only seven times in the NFL since 1970.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something that was said in the locker room among the
players,'' center Aaron Graham said Monday, the day after a
last-second, 52-yard field goal by Chris Jacke gave the Cardinals a
16-13 win over San Diego and sent them to a 17th game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's no prediction, but anybody in the league will tell you
it's tough to beat a team three times in one year.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Vince Tobin is glad his players have confidence in what is
unfamiliar territory for a young roster. But he's a proponent of
talent being the determining factor, and he points out that Dallas
(10-6) has ``probably seven or eight guys who are among the best,
or are the best, at their positions in the league. We don't have
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It probably works both ways,'' Tobin said of the third
meeting. ``Being divisional foes, we're familiar with each other.
Where Dallas might have an advantage is they've beaten us
consistently through the years.''
</P>
<P>
   During the 1990s, the Cowboys have won 16 of 17 games against
the Cardinals, including a 13-game streak that ended last season
with the Cardinals' 25-22 win in overtime at Sun Devil Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Graham is typical of the young players on the roster who have
come from college programs that played regularly in high-stakes
bowl games. Twenty-eight players were not yet in the league when
Tobin became coach in 1996, and 45 have been added during the Tobin
regime.
</P>
<P>
   There are few ties to a not-too-storied past.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was at Nebraska,'' Graham said, ``the first time we got
to a national championship game, we knew what was on the line, what
was at stake, but we walked away with a loss on a last-second field
goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also came away thinking that if we ever got that
opportunity again, we were not going to lose. If I could say one
thing to my team this week, it would be to have that attitude. This
shouldn't be `I hope we win,' or `it would be great if we win.' We
have to go in with the attitude that we are going to win and keep
this going. If we do that, we'll be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1970, of the 36 games matching foes for the third time in
a season, 11 involved regular season sweeps. Seven of those became
3-0 sweeps.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals were dominated in the opener, 38-10, distracted
somewhat by first-round draft pick Andre Wadsworth's ending his
holdout the night before, and then by defensive tackle Eric Swann's
being ejected in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   They believe they should have won the second, a 35-28 loss at
home on Nov. 15 that ended with a no-call in the end zone. The
Cardinals contended that receiver Rob Moore was interfered with by
Cowboys cornerback Kevin Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Had the Cardinals won that game, they would be hosting this one.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a new season and anything can happen,'' Tobin said.
``Dallas has been in the playoffs many years. We're trying to get
where they have been. A team that's been to the mountaintop doesn't
like to give it up to a team that hasn't been there.''
</P>
<P>
   The playoffs are new, but winning close, pivotal games is not.
The Cardinals' seven wins in games decided by three or fewer points
set an NFL record. Their last three were won by a field goal on the
final play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pressure is when you are unprepared,'' said Aeneas Williams, a
five-time Pro Bowl cornerback who in the last game against Dallas
ended Michael Irvin's consecutive-game receiving streak at 117. ``I
think we have done a good job over and over in the face of
adversity. Whenever you go down to the wire, you learn something
every time. Now, instead of finding ways to lose games, we are
finding ways to win them. I think that is going to help us make a
quantum leap to the next level.''
</P>
<P>
   To do that, the Cardinals have to get better in the basic
elements that swing football games: running the ball and stopping
the run. They did neither well in their regular season finale, nor
in the last game against Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure they're not quaking in their boots that they have to
play the Cardinals,'' Tobin said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rule of Threes suggests the Cowboys better not take it
for granted. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
